P_HTM[1177]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sīlaṃ nissāya sīle patiṭṭhāya ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bhāveti ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bahulīkaroti?* **";
P_HTM[1178]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sammādiṭṭhiṃ bhāveti nibbānaninnaṃ nibbānapoṇaṃ nibbānapabbhāraṃ … pe … sammāsamādhiṃ bhāveti nibbānaninnaṃ nibbānapoṇaṃ nibbānapabbhāraṃ.**“… slants, slopes, and inclines to extinguishment …”*";
P_HTM[1179]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sīlaṃ nissāya sīle patiṭṭhāya ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bhāveti ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bahulīkarotī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[1180]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1181]="*2. Bījasuttaṃ**Seeds*";
P_HTM[1182]="*“Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, ye kecime bījagāmabhūtagāmā vuḍḍhiṃ virūḷhiṃ vepullaṃ āpajjanti, sabbe te pathaviṃ nissāya pathaviyaṃ patiṭṭhāya evamete bījagāmabhūtagāmā vuḍḍhiṃ virūḷhiṃ vepullaṃ āpajjanti;**“All the plants and seeds that achieve growth, increase, and maturity do so depending on the earth and grounded on the earth.*";
P_HTM[1183]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sīlaṃ nissāya sīle patiṭṭhāya ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bhāvento ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bahulīkaronto vuḍḍhiṃ virūḷhiṃ vepullaṃ pāpuṇāti dhammesu.**In the same way, a mendicant develops and cultivates the noble eightfold path depending on and grounded on ethics, achieving growth, increase, and maturity in good qualities.*";
P_HTM[1184]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sīlaṃ nissāya sīle patiṭṭhāya ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bhāvento ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bahulīkaronto vuḍḍhiṃ virūḷhiṃ vepullaṃ pāpuṇāti dhammesu?**And how does a mendicant develop the noble eightfold path depending on and grounded on ethics, achieving growth, increase, and maturity in good qualities?*";
P_HTM[1185]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sammādiṭṭhiṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ … pe … sammāsamādhiṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ virāganissitaṃ nirodhanissitaṃ vossaggapariṇāmiṃ … pe …**It’s when a mendicant develops right view, right thought, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, and right immersion, which rely on seclusion, fading away, and cessation, and ripen as letting go.*";
P_HTM[1186]="*evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sīlaṃ nissāya sīle patiṭṭhāya ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bhāvento ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bahulīkaronto vuḍḍhiṃ virūḷhiṃ vepullaṃ pāpuṇāti dhammesū”ti.**That’s how a mendicant develops and cultivates the noble eightfold path depending on and grounded on ethics, achieving growth, increase, and maturity in good qualities.”*";
P_HTM[1187]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1188]="*3. Nāgasuttaṃ**Dragons*";
P_HTM[1189]="*“Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, himavantaṃ pabbatarājaṃ nissāya nāgā kāyaṃ vaḍḍhenti, balaṃ gāhenti;**“Mendicants, dragons grow and wax strong supported by the Himalayas, the king of mountains.*";
P_HTM[1190]="*te tattha kāyaṃ vaḍḍhetvā balaṃ gāhetvā kusobbhe otaranti, kusobbhe otaritvā mahāsobbhe otaranti, mahāsobbhe otaritvā kunnadiyo otaranti, kunnadiyo otaritvā mahānadiyo otaranti, mahānadiyo otaritvā mahāsamuddaṃ otaranti, te tattha mahantattaṃ vepullattaṃ āpajjanti kāyena;**When they’re strong they dive into the pools. Then they dive into the lakes, the streams, the rivers, and finally the ocean. There they acquire a great and abundant body.*";
P_HTM[1191]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sīlaṃ nissāya sīle patiṭṭhāya ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bhāvento ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bahulīkaronto mahantattaṃ vepullattaṃ pāpuṇāti dhammesu.**In the same way, a mendicant develops and cultivates the noble eightfold path depending on and grounded on ethics, acquiring great and abundant good qualities.*";
P_HTM[1192]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sīlaṃ nissāya sīle patiṭṭhāya ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bhāvento ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bahulīkaronto mahantattaṃ vepullattaṃ pāpuṇāti dhammesu?**And how does a mendicant develop the noble eightfold path depending on and grounded on ethics, acquiring great and abundant good qualities?*";
P_HTM[1193]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sammādiṭṭhiṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ virāganissitaṃ nirodhanissitaṃ vossaggapariṇāmiṃ … pe … sammāsamādhiṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ virāganissitaṃ nirodhanissitaṃ vossaggapariṇāmiṃ …**It’s when a mendicant develops right view, right thought, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, and right immersion, which rely on seclusion, fading away, and cessation, and ripen as letting go.*";
P_HTM[1194]="*evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sīlaṃ nissāya sīle patiṭṭhāya ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bhāvento ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bahulīkaronto mahantattaṃ vepullattaṃ pāpuṇāti dhammesū”ti.**That’s how a mendicant develops and cultivates the noble eightfold path depending on and grounded on ethics, acquiring great and abundant good qualities.”*";
P_HTM[1195]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1196]="*4. Rukkhasuttaṃ**Trees*";
P_HTM[1197]="*“Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, rukkho pācīnaninno pācīnapoṇo pācīnapabbhāro.**“Mendicants, suppose a tree slants, slopes, and inclines to the east.*";
P_HTM[1198]="*So mūlacchinno katamena papateyyā”ti?**If it was cut off at the root, where would it fall?”*";
P_HTM[1199]="*“Yena, bhante, ninno yena poṇo yena pabbhāro”ti.**“Sir, it would fall in the direction that it slants, slopes, and inclines.”*";
P_HTM[1200]="*“Evameva kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bhāvento ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bahulīkaronto nibbānaninno hoti nibbānapoṇo nibbānapabbhāro.**“In the same way, a mendicant who develops and cultivates the noble eightfold path slants, slopes, and inclines to extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[1201]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhu ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bhāvento ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bahulīkaronto nibbānaninno hoti nibbānapoṇo nibbānapabbhāro?**And how does a mendicant who develops the noble eightfold path slant, slope, and incline to extinguishment?*";
P_HTM[1202]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sammādiṭṭhiṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ virāganissitaṃ nirodhanissitaṃ vossaggapariṇāmiṃ … pe … sammāsamādhiṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ virāganissitaṃ nirodhanissitaṃ vossaggapariṇāmiṃ …**It’s when a mendicant develops right view, right thought, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, and right immersion, which rely on seclusion, fading away, and cessation, and ripen as letting go.*";
P_HTM[1203]="*evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bhāvento ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bahulīkaronto nibbānaninno hoti nibbānapoṇo nibbānapabbhāro”ti.**That’s how a mendicant who develops and cultivates the noble eightfold path slants, slopes, and inclines to extinguishment.”*";
P_HTM[1204]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1205]="*5. Kumbhasuttaṃ**Pots*";
P_HTM[1206]="*“Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, kumbho nikkujjo vamateva udakaṃ, no paccāvamati;**“Mendicants, suppose a pot full of water is tipped over, so the water drains out and doesn’t go back in.*";
P_HTM[1207]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bhāvento ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bahulīkaronto vamateva pāpake akusale dhamme, no paccāvamati.**In the same way, a mendicant who develops and cultivates the noble eightfold path expels bad, unskillful qualities and doesn’t let them back in.*";
P_HTM[1208]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhu ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bhāvento ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bahulīkaronto vamateva pāpake akusale dhamme, no paccāvamati?**And how does a mendicant who develops the noble eightfold path expel bad, unskillful qualities and not let them back in?*";
P_HTM[1209]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sammādiṭṭhiṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ virāganissitaṃ nirodhanissitaṃ vossaggapariṇāmiṃ … pe … sammāsamādhiṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ virāganissitaṃ nirodhanissitaṃ vossaggapariṇāmiṃ …**It’s when a mendicant develops right view, right thought, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, and right immersion, which rely on seclusion, fading away, and cessation, and ripen as letting go.*";
P_HTM[1210]="*evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bhāvento ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bahulīkaronto vamateva pāpake akusale dhamme, no paccāvamatī”ti.**That’s how a mendicant who develops and cultivates the noble eightfold path expels bad, unskillful qualities and doesn’t let them back in.”*";
P_HTM[1211]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1212]="*6. Sūkasuttaṃ**A Spike*";
P_HTM[1213]="*“Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, sālisūkaṃ vā yavasūkaṃ vā sammāpaṇihitaṃ hatthena vā pādena vā akkantaṃ hatthaṃ vā pādaṃ vā bhindissati lohitaṃ vā uppādessatīti—ṭhānametaṃ vijjati.**“Mendicants, suppose a spike of rice or barley was pointing the right way. If you trod on it with hand or foot, it may well break the skin and produce blood.*";
P_HTM[1214]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[1215]="*Sammāpaṇihitattā, bhikkhave, sūkassa.**Because the spike is pointing the right way.*";
P_HTM[1216]="*Evameva kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sammāpaṇihitāya diṭṭhiyā sammāpaṇihitāya maggabhāvanāya avijjaṃ bhindissati, vijjaṃ uppādessati, nibbānaṃ sacchikarissatīti—ṭhānametaṃ vijjati.**In the same way, a mendicant whose view and development of the path is pointing the right way may well break ignorance, produce knowledge, and realize extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[1217]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[1218]="*Sammāpaṇihitattā, bhikkhave, diṭṭhiyā.**Because their view is pointing the right way.*";
P_HTM[1219]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sammāpaṇihitāya diṭṭhiyā sammāpaṇihitāya maggabhāvanāya avijjaṃ bhindati, vijjaṃ uppādeti, nibbānaṃ sacchikaroti?**And how does a mendicant whose view and development of the path is pointing the right way break ignorance, give rise to knowledge, and realize extinguishment?*";
P_HTM[1220]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sammādiṭṭhiṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ … pe … sammāsamādhiṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ virāganissitaṃ nirodhanissitaṃ vossaggapariṇāmiṃ …**It’s when a mendicant develops right view, right thought, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, and right immersion, which rely on seclusion, fading away, and cessation, and ripen as letting go.*";
P_HTM[1221]="*evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sammāpaṇihitāya diṭṭhiyā sammāpaṇihitāya maggabhāvanāya avijjaṃ bhindati, vijjaṃ uppādeti, nibbānaṃ sacchikarotī”ti.**That’s how a mendicant whose view and development of the path is pointing the right way breaks ignorance, gives rise to knowledge, and realizes extinguishment.”*";
P_HTM[1222]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1223]="*7. Ākāsasuttaṃ**The Sky*";
P_HTM[1224]="*“Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, ākāse vividhā vātā vāyanti—**“Mendicants, various winds blow in the sky.*";
P_HTM[1225]="*puratthimāpi vātā vāyanti, pacchimāpi vātā vāyanti, uttarāpi vātā vāyanti, dakkhiṇāpi vātā vāyanti, sarajāpi vātā vāyanti, arajāpi vātā vāyanti, sītāpi vātā vāyanti, uṇhāpi vātā vāyanti, parittāpi vātā vāyanti, adhimattāpi vātā vāyanti;**Winds blow from the east, the west, the north, and the south. There are winds that are dusty and dustless, cool and warm, weak and strong.*";
P_HTM[1226]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bhāvayato ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bahulīkaroto cattāropi satipaṭṭhānā bhāvanāpāripūriṃ gacchanti, cattāropi sammappadhānā bhāvanāpāripūriṃ gacchanti, cattāropi iddhipādā bhāvanāpāripūriṃ gacchanti, pañcapi indriyāni bhāvanāpāripūriṃ gacchanti, pañcapi balāni bhāvanāpāripūriṃ gacchanti, sattapi bojjhaṅgā bhāvanāpāripūriṃ gacchanti.**In the same way, when the noble eightfold path is developed and cultivated the following are fully developed: the four kinds of mindfulness meditation, the four right efforts, the four bases of psychic power, the five faculties, the five powers, and the seven awakening factors.*";
P_HTM[1227]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bhāvayato ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bahulīkaroto cattāropi satipaṭṭhānā bhāvanāpāripūriṃ gacchanti, cattāropi sammappadhānā bhāvanāpāripūriṃ gacchanti, cattāropi iddhipādā bhāvanāpāripūriṃ gacchanti, pañcapi indriyāni bhāvanāpāripūriṃ gacchanti, pañcapi balāni bhāvanāpāripūriṃ gacchanti, sattapi bojjhaṅgā bhāvanāpāripūriṃ gacchanti?**And how are they fully developed?*";
P_HTM[1228]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sammādiṭṭhiṃ bhāveti … pe … sammāsamādhiṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ virāganissitaṃ nirodhanissitaṃ vossaggapariṇāmiṃ …**It’s when a mendicant develops right view, right thought, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, and right immersion, which rely on seclusion, fading away, and cessation, and ripen as letting go.*";
P_HTM[1229]="*evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bhāvayato ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bahulīkaroto cattāropi satipaṭṭhānā bhāvanāpāripūriṃ gacchanti, cattāropi sammappadhānā bhāvanāpāripūriṃ gacchanti, cattāropi iddhipādā bhāvanāpāripūriṃ gacchanti, pañcapi indriyāni bhāvanāpāripūriṃ gacchanti, pañcapi balāni bhāvanāpāripūriṃ gacchanti, sattapi bojjhaṅgā bhāvanāpāripūriṃ gacchantī”ti.**That’s how they’re fully developed.”*";
P_HTM[1230]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1231]="*8. Paṭhamameghasuttaṃ**Storms (1st)*";
P_HTM[1232]="*“Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, gimhānaṃ pacchime māse ūhataṃ rajojallaṃ, tamenaṃ mahāakālamegho ṭhānaso antaradhāpeti vūpasameti;**“Mendicants, in the last month of summer, when the dust and dirt is stirred up, a large sudden storm disperses and settles it on the spot.*";
P_HTM[1233]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bhāvento ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bahulīkaronto uppannuppanne pāpake akusale dhamme ṭhānaso antaradhāpeti vūpasameti.**In the same way, a mendicant who develops and cultivates the noble eightfold path disperses and stills bad, unskillful qualities on the spot.*";
P_HTM[1234]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhu ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bhāvento ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bahulīkaronto uppannuppanne pāpake akusale dhamme ṭhānaso antaradhāpeti vūpasameti?**How does a mendicant who develops the noble eightfold path disperse and still bad, unskillful qualities on the spot?*";
P_HTM[1235]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sammādiṭṭhiṃ bhāveti … pe … sammāsamādhiṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ virāganissitaṃ nirodhanissitaṃ vossaggapariṇāmiṃ …**It’s when a mendicant develops right view, right thought, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, and right immersion, which rely on seclusion, fading away, and cessation, and ripen as letting go.*";
P_HTM[1236]="*evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bhāvento ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bahulīkaronto uppannuppanne pāpake akusale dhamme ṭhānaso antaradhāpeti vūpasametī”ti.**That’s how a mendicant who develops and cultivates the noble eightfold path disperses and stills bad, unskillful qualities on the spot.”*";
P_HTM[1237]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1238]="*9. Dutiyameghasuttaṃ**Storms (2nd)*";
P_HTM[1239]="*“Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, uppannaṃ mahāmeghaṃ, tamenaṃ mahāvāto antarāyeva antaradhāpeti vūpasameti;**“Mendicants, when a large storm has arisen, a strong wind disperses and settles it as it proceeds.*";
P_HTM[1240]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bhāvento ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bahulīkaronto uppannuppanne pāpake akusale dhamme antarāyeva antaradhāpeti vūpasameti.**In the same way, a mendicant who develops and cultivates the noble eightfold path disperses and stills bad, unskillful qualities as they proceed.*";
P_HTM[1241]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhu ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bhāvento ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bahulīkaronto uppannuppanne pāpake akusale dhamme antarāyeva antaradhāpeti vūpasameti?**And how does a mendicant who develops the noble eightfold path disperse and still bad, unskillful qualities as they proceed?*";
P_HTM[1242]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sammādiṭṭhiṃ bhāveti … pe … sammāsamādhiṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ virāganissitaṃ nirodhanissitaṃ vossaggapariṇāmiṃ …**It’s when a mendicant develops right view, right thought, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, and right immersion, which rely on seclusion, fading away, and cessation, and ripen as letting go.*";
P_HTM[1243]="*evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bhāvento ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bahulīkaronto uppannuppanne pāpake akusale dhamme antarāyeva antaradhāpeti vūpasametī”ti.**That’s how a mendicant who develops and cultivates the noble eightfold path disperses and stills bad, unskillful qualities as they proceed.”*";
P_HTM[1244]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1245]="*10. Nāvāsuttaṃ**A Ship*";
P_HTM[1246]="*“Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, sāmuddikāya nāvāya vettabandhanabandhāya cha māsāni udake pariyādāya hemantikena thalaṃ ukkhittāya vātātapaparetāni bandhanāni tāni pāvussakena meghena abhippavuṭṭhāni appakasireneva paṭippassambhanti, pūtikāni bhavanti;**“Mendicants, suppose there was a sea-faring ship bound together with ropes. For six months they deteriorated in the water. Then in the cold season it was hauled up on dry land, where the ropes were weathered by wind and sun. When the clouds soaked it with rain, the ropes would readily collapse and rot away.*";
P_HTM[1247]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bhāvayato ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bahulīkaroto appakasireneva saṃyojanāni paṭippassambhanti, pūtikāni bhavanti.**In the same way, when a mendicant develops and cultivates the noble eightfold path their fetters readily collapse and rot away.*";
P_HTM[1248]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bhāvayato ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bahulīkaroto appakasireneva saṃyojanāni paṭippassambhanti, pūtikāni bhavanti?**And how do they develop and cultivate the noble eightfold path so that their fetters readily collapse and rot away?*";
P_HTM[1249]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sammādiṭṭhiṃ bhāveti … pe … sammāsamādhiṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ virāganissitaṃ nirodhanissitaṃ vossaggapariṇāmiṃ …**It’s when a mendicant develops right view, right thought, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, and right immersion, which rely on seclusion, fading away, and cessation, and ripen as letting go.*";
P_HTM[1250]="*evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bhāvayato ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bahulīkaroto appakasireneva saṃyojanāni paṭippassambhanti, pūtikāni bhavantī”ti.**That’s how they develop and cultivate the noble eightfold path so that their fetters readily collapse and rot away.”*";
P_HTM[1251]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1252]="*11. Āgantukasuttaṃ**A Guest House*";
P_HTM[1253]="*“Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, āgantukāgāraṃ. Tattha puratthimāyapi disāya āgantvā vāsaṃ kappenti, pacchimāyapi disāya āgantvā vāsaṃ kappenti, uttarāyapi disāya āgantvā vāsaṃ kappenti, dakkhiṇāyapi disāya āgantvā vāsaṃ kappenti, khattiyāpi āgantvā vāsaṃ kappenti, brāhmaṇāpi āgantvā vāsaṃ kappenti, vessāpi āgantvā vāsaṃ kappenti, suddāpi āgantvā vāsaṃ kappenti;**“Mendicants, suppose there was a guest house. Lodgers come from the east, west, north, and south. Aristocrats, brahmins, merchants, and workers all stay there.*";
P_HTM[1254]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bhāvento ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bahulīkaronto ye dhammā abhiññā pariññeyyā, te dhamme abhiññā parijānāti … pe …**In the same way, a mendicant who develops and cultivates the noble eightfold path completely understands by direct knowledge the things that should be completely understood by direct knowledge.*";
P_HTM[1255]="*ye dhammā abhiññā pahātabbā, te dhamme abhiññā pajahati, ye dhammā abhiññā sacchikātabbā, te dhamme abhiññā sacchikaroti, ye dhammā abhiññā bhāvetabbā, te dhamme abhiññā bhāveti.**They give up by direct knowledge the things that should be given up by direct knowledge. They realize by direct knowledge the things that should be realized by direct knowledge. They develop by direct knowledge the things that should be developed by direct knowledge.*";
P_HTM[1256]="*Katame ca, bhikkhave, dhammā abhiññā pariññeyyā?**And what are the things that should be completely understood by direct knowledge?*";
P_HTM[1257]="*Pañcupādānakkhandhātissa vacanīyaṃ.**It should be said: the five grasping aggregates.*";
P_HTM[1258]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1259]="*Seyyathidaṃ—rūpupādānakkhandho … pe … viññāṇupādānakkhandho.**That is: form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness.*";
P_HTM[1260]="*Ime, bhikkhave, dhammā abhiññā pariññeyyā.**These are the things that should be completely understood by direct knowledge.*";
P_HTM[1261]="*Katame ca, bhikkhave, dhammā abhiññā pahātabbā?**And what are the things that should be given up by direct knowledge?*";
P_HTM[1262]="*Avijjā ca bhavataṇhā ca—**Ignorance and craving for continued existence.*";
P_HTM[1263]="*ime, bhikkhave, dhammā abhiññā pahātabbā.**These are the things that should be given up by direct knowledge.*";
P_HTM[1264]="*Katame ca, bhikkhave, dhammā abhiññā sacchikātabbā?**And what are the things that should be realized by direct knowledge?*";
P_HTM[1265]="*Vijjā ca vimutti ca—**Knowledge and freedom.*";
P_HTM[1266]="*ime, bhikkhave, dhammā abhiññā sacchikātabbā.**These are the things that should be realized by direct knowledge.*";
P_HTM[1267]="*Katame ca, bhikkhave, dhammā abhiññā bhāvetabbā?**And what are the things that should be developed by direct knowledge?*";
P_HTM[1268]="*Samatho ca vipassanā ca—**Serenity and discernment.*";
P_HTM[1269]="*ime, bhikkhave, dhammā abhiññā bhāvetabbā.**These are the things that should be developed by direct knowledge.*";
P_HTM[1270]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhu ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bhāvento ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bahulīkaronto, ye dhammā abhiññā pariññeyyā te dhamme abhiññā parijānāti … pe … ye dhammā abhiññā bhāvetabbā, te dhamme abhiññā bhāveti?**And how does a mendicant develop the noble eightfold path in this way?*";
P_HTM[1271]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sammādiṭṭhiṃ bhāveti … pe … sammāsamādhiṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ virāganissitaṃ nirodhanissitaṃ vossaggapariṇāmiṃ …**It’s when a mendicant develops right view, right thought, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, and right immersion, which rely on seclusion, fading away, and cessation, and ripen as letting go.*";
P_HTM[1272]="*evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bhāvento ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bahulīkaronto ye dhammā abhiññā pariññeyyā, te dhamme abhiññā parijānāti, ye dhammā abhiññā pahātabbā, te dhamme abhiññā pajahati, ye dhammā abhiññā sacchikātabbā, te dhamme abhiññā sacchikaroti, ye dhammā abhiññā bhāvetabbā, te dhamme abhiññā bhāvetī”ti.**That’s how a mendicant develops and cultivates the eightfold path in this way.”*";
P_HTM[1273]="*Ekādasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1274]="*12. Nadīsuttaṃ**A River*";
P_HTM[1275]="*“Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, gaṅgā nadī pācīnaninnā pācīnapoṇā pācīnapabbhārā.**“Mendicants, suppose that, although the Ganges river slants, slopes, and inclines to the east,*";
P_HTM[1276]="*Atha mahājanakāyo āgaccheyya kuddālapiṭakaṃ ādāya:**a large crowd were to come along with a spade and basket, saying:*";
P_HTM[1277]="*‘mayaṃ imaṃ gaṅgaṃ nadiṃ pacchāninnaṃ karissāma pacchāpoṇaṃ pacchāpabbhāran’ti.**‘We’ll make this Ganges river slant, slope, and incline to the west!’*";
P_HTM[1278]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhikkhave,**What do you think, mendicants?*";
P_HTM[1279]="*api nu so mahājanakāyo gaṅgaṃ nadiṃ pacchāninnaṃ kareyya pacchāpoṇaṃ pacchāpabbhāran”ti?**Would they succeed?”*";
P_HTM[1280]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.*";
P_HTM[1281]="*“Taṃ kissa hetu”?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[1282]="*“Gaṅgā, bhante, nadī pācīnaninnā pācīnapoṇā pācīnapabbhārā.**The Ganges river slants, slopes, and inclines to the east.*";
P_HTM[1283]="*Sā na sukarā pacchāninnaṃ kātuṃ pacchāpoṇaṃ pacchāpabbhāraṃ.**It’s not easy to make it slant, slope, and incline to the west.*";
P_HTM[1284]="*Yāvadeva pana so mahājanakāyo kilamathassa vighātassa bhāgī assā”ti.**That large crowd will eventually get weary and frustrated.”*";
P_HTM[1285]="*“Evameva kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhuṃ ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bhāventaṃ ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bahulīkarontaṃ rājāno vā rājamahāmattā vā mittā vā amaccā vā ñātī vā ñātisālohitā vā bhogehi abhihaṭṭhuṃ pavāreyyuṃ:**“In the same way, while a mendicant develops and cultivates the noble eightfold path, if rulers or their ministers, friends or colleagues, relatives or family should invite them to accept wealth, saying:*";
P_HTM[1286]="*‘ehambho purisa, kiṃ te ime kāsāvā anudahanti, kiṃ muṇḍo kapālamanusaṃcarasi. Ehi, hīnāyāvattitvā bhoge ca bhuñjassu, puññāni ca karohī’ti.**‘Please, mister, why let these ocher robes torment you? Why follow the practice of shaving your head and carrying an alms bowl? Come, return to a lesser life, enjoy wealth, and make merit!’*";
P_HTM[1287]="*So vata, bhikkhave, bhikkhu ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bhāvento ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bahulīkaronto sikkhaṃ paccakkhāya hīnāyāvattissatīti—netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**It’s simply impossible for a mendicant who develops and cultivates the noble eightfold path to reject the training and return to a lesser life.*";
P_HTM[1288]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[1289]="*Yañhi taṃ, bhikkhave, cittaṃ dīgharattaṃ vivekaninnaṃ vivekapoṇaṃ vivekapabbhāraṃ taṃ vata hīnāyāvattissatīti—netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**Because for a long time that mendicant’s mind has slanted, sloped, and inclined to seclusion. So it’s impossible for them to return to a lesser life.*";
P_HTM[1290]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhu ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bhāveti ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bahulīkaroti?**And how does a mendicant develop the noble eightfold path?*";
P_HTM[1291]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sammādiṭṭhiṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ … pe … sammāsamādhiṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ virāganissitaṃ nirodhanissitaṃ vossaggapariṇāmiṃ …**It’s when a mendicant develops right view, right thought, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, and right immersion, which rely on seclusion, fading away, and cessation, and ripen as letting go.*";
P_HTM[1292]="*evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bhāveti, ariyaṃ aṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ bahulīkarotī”ti.**That’s how a mendicant develops and cultivates the noble eightfold path.”*";
P_HTM[1293]="*(Yadapi balakaraṇīyaṃ, tadapi vitthāretabbaṃ.)* **";
P_HTM[1294]="*Dvādasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1295]="*Balakaraṇīyavaggo chaṭṭho.* **";
P_HTM[1296]="*Balaṃ bījañca nāgo ca,* **";
P_HTM[1297]="*rukkho kumbhena sūkiyā;* **";
P_HTM[1298]="*Ākāsena ca dve meghā,* **";
P_HTM[1299]="*nāvā āgantukā nadīti.* **";
P_HTM[1300]="*8. Nirodhavaggo**Searches*";
P_HTM[1301]="*1. Esanāsuttaṃ**Searches*";
P_HTM[1302]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[1303]="*“Tisso imā, bhikkhave, esanā.**“Mendicants, there are these three searches.*";
P_HTM[1304]="*Katamā tisso?**What three?*";
P_HTM[1305]="*Kāmesanā, bhavesanā, brahmacariyesanā—**The search for sensual pleasures, the search for continued existence, and the search for a spiritual path.*";
P_HTM[1306]="*imā kho, bhikkhave, tisso esanā.**These are the three searches.*";
P_HTM[1307]="*Imāsaṃ kho, bhikkhave, tissannaṃ esanānaṃ abhiññāya ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo bhāvetabbo.**The noble eightfold path should be developed to directly know these three searches.*";
P_HTM[1308]="*Katamo ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo?**What is the noble eightfold path?*";
P_HTM[1309]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sammādiṭṭhiṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ … pe … sammāsamādhiṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ virāganissitaṃ nirodhanissitaṃ vossaggapariṇāmiṃ.**It’s when a mendicant develops right view, right thought, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, and right immersion, which rely on seclusion, fading away, and cessation, and ripen as letting go.*";
P_HTM[1310]="*Imāsaṃ kho, bhikkhave, tissannaṃ esanānaṃ abhiññāya ayaṃ ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo bhāvetabboti.**This is the noble eightfold path that should be developed to directly know these three searches.”*";
P_HTM[1311]="*Tisso imā kho, bhikkhave, esanā.**“Mendicants, there are these three searches.*";
P_HTM[1312]="*Katamā tisso?**What three?*";
P_HTM[1313]="*Kāmesanā, bhavesanā, brahmacariyesanā—**The search for sensual pleasures, the search for continued existence, and the search for a spiritual path.*";
P_HTM[1314]="*imā kho, bhikkhave, tisso esanā.**These are the three searches.*";
P_HTM[1315]="*Imāsaṃ kho, bhikkhave, tissannaṃ esanānaṃ abhiññāya ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo bhāvetabbo.**The noble eightfold path should be developed to directly know these three searches.*";
P_HTM[1316]="*Katamo ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo?**What is the noble eightfold path?*";
P_HTM[1317]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sammādiṭṭhiṃ bhāveti … pe … sammāsamādhiṃ bhāveti rāgavinayapariyosānaṃ dosavinayapariyosānaṃ mohavinayapariyosānaṃ.**It’s when a mendicant develops right view, right thought, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, and right immersion, which culminate in the removal of greed, hate, and delusion.*";
P_HTM[1318]="*Imāsaṃ kho, bhikkhave, tissannaṃ esanānaṃ abhiññāya ayaṃ ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo bhāvetabboti.**This is the noble eightfold path that should be developed to directly know these three searches.”*";
P_HTM[1319]="*Tisso imā kho, bhikkhave, esanā.**“Mendicants, there are these three searches.*";
P_HTM[1320]="*Katamā tisso?**What three?*";
P_HTM[1321]="*Kāmesanā, bhavesanā, brahmacariyesanā—**The search for sensual pleasures, the search for continued existence, and the search for a spiritual path.*";
P_HTM[1322]="*imā kho, bhikkhave, tisso esanā.**These are the three searches.*";
P_HTM[1323]="*Imāsaṃ kho, bhikkhave, tissannaṃ esanānaṃ abhiññāya ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo bhāvetabbo.**The noble eightfold path should be developed to directly know these three searches.*";
P_HTM[1324]="*Katamo ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo?**What is the noble eightfold path?*";
P_HTM[1325]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sammādiṭṭhiṃ bhāveti … pe … sammāsamādhiṃ bhāveti amatogadhaṃ amataparāyanaṃ amatapariyosānaṃ.**It’s when a mendicant develops right view, right thought, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, and right immersion, which culminate, finish, and end in the deathless.*";
P_HTM[1326]="*Imāsaṃ kho, bhikkhave, tissannaṃ esanānaṃ abhiññāya ayaṃ ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo bhāvetabboti.**This is the noble eightfold path that should be developed to directly know these three searches.”*";
P_HTM[1327]="*Tisso imā kho, bhikkhave, esanā.**“Mendicants, there are these three searches.*";
P_HTM[1328]="*Katamā tisso?**What three?*";
P_HTM[1329]="*Kāmesanā, bhavesanā, brahmacariyesanā—**The search for sensual pleasures, the search for continued existence, and the search for a spiritual path.*";
P_HTM[1330]="*imā kho, bhikkhave, tisso esanā.**These are the three searches.*";
P_HTM[1331]="*Imāsaṃ kho, bhikkhave, tissannaṃ esanānaṃ abhiññāya ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo bhāvetabbo.**The noble eightfold path should be developed to directly know these three searches.*";
P_HTM[1332]="*Katamo ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo?**What is the noble eightfold path?*";
P_HTM[1333]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sammādiṭṭhiṃ bhāveti … pe … sammāsamādhiṃ bhāveti nibbānaninnaṃ nibbānapoṇaṃ nibbānapabbhāraṃ.**It’s when a mendicant develops right view, right thought, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, and right immersion, which slants, slopes, and inclines to extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[1334]="*Imāsaṃ kho, bhikkhave, tissannaṃ esanānaṃ abhiññāya ayaṃ ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo bhāvetabboti.**This is the noble eightfold path that should be developed to directly know these three searches.”*";
P_HTM[1335]="*Tisso imā, bhikkhave, esanā.**“Mendicants, there are these three searches.*";
P_HTM[1336]="*Katamā tisso?**What three?*";
P_HTM[1337]="*Kāmesanā, bhavesanā, brahmacariyesanā—**The search for sensual pleasures, the search for continued existence, and the search for a spiritual path.*";
P_HTM[1338]="*imā kho, bhikkhave, tisso esanā.**These are the three searches.*";
P_HTM[1339]="*Imāsaṃ kho, bhikkhave, tissannaṃ esanānaṃ pariññāya … pe … ayaṃ ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo bhāvetabboti.**The noble eightfold path should be developed to completely understand …”*";
P_HTM[1340]="*(Yadapi abhiññā, tadapi pariññāya vitthāretabbaṃ.)**(This should be expanded with “completely understand” instead of “directly know”.)*";
P_HTM[1341]="*Tisso imā, bhikkhave, esanā.**“Mendicants, there are these three searches.*";
P_HTM[1342]="*Katamā tisso?**What three?*";
P_HTM[1343]="*Kāmesanā, bhavesanā, brahmacariyesanā—**The search for sensual pleasures, the search for continued existence, and the search for a spiritual path.*";
P_HTM[1344]="*imā kho, bhikkhave, tisso esanā.**These are the three searches.*";
P_HTM[1345]="*Imāsaṃ kho, bhikkhave, tissannaṃ esanānaṃ parikkhayāya … pe … ayaṃ ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo bhāvetabboti.**The noble eightfold path should be developed to finish …”*";
P_HTM[1346]="*(Yadapi abhiññā, tadapi parikkhayāya vitthāretabbaṃ.)**(This should be expanded with “finish” instead of “directly know”.)*";
P_HTM[1347]="*Tisso imā, bhikkhave, esanā.**“Mendicants, there are these three searches.*";
P_HTM[1348]="*Katamā tisso?**What three?*";
P_HTM[1349]="*Kāmesanā, bhavesanā, brahmacariyesanā—**The search for sensual pleasures, the search for continued existence, and the search for a spiritual path.*";
P_HTM[1350]="*imā kho, bhikkhave, tisso esanā.**These are the three searches.*";
P_HTM[1351]="*Imāsaṃ kho, bhikkhave, tissannaṃ esanānaṃ pahānāya ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo bhāvetabbo.**The noble eightfold path should be developed to give up …”*";
P_HTM[1352]="*Katamo ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo?* **";
P_HTM[1353]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sammādiṭṭhiṃ bhāveti … pe … sammāsamādhiṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ virāganissitaṃ nirodhanissitaṃ vossaggapariṇāmiṃ …* **";
P_HTM[1354]="*Imāsaṃ kho, bhikkhave, tissannaṃ esanānaṃ pahānāya ayaṃ ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo bhāvetabbo”ti.* **";
P_HTM[1355]="*(Yadapi abhiññā, tadapi pahānāya vitthāretabbaṃ.)**(This should be expanded with “give up” instead of “directly know”.)*";
P_HTM[1356]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1357]="*2. Vidhāsuttaṃ**Discriminations*";
P_HTM[1358]="*“Tisso imā, bhikkhave, vidhā.**“Mendicants, there are three kinds of discrimination.*";
P_HTM[1359]="*Katamā tisso?**What three?*";
P_HTM[1360]="*‘Seyyohamasmī’ti vidhā, ‘sadisohamasmī’ti vidhā, ‘hīnohamasmī’ti vidhā—**One discriminates, thinking that ‘I’m better’ or ‘I’m equal’ or ‘I’m worse’.*";
P_HTM[1361]="*imā kho, bhikkhave, tisso vidhā.**These are the three kinds of discrimination.*";
P_HTM[1362]="*Imāsaṃ kho, bhikkhave, tissannaṃ vidhānaṃ abhiññāya pariññāya parikkhayāya pahānāya ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo bhāvetabbo.**The noble eightfold path should be developed for the direct knowledge, complete understanding, finishing, and giving up of these three kinds of discrimination.*";
P_HTM[1363]="*Katamo ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo?**What is the noble eightfold path?*";
P_HTM[1364]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sammādiṭṭhiṃ bhāveti … pe … sammāsamādhiṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ virāganissitaṃ nirodhanissitaṃ vossaggapariṇāmiṃ …**It’s when a mendicant develops right view, right thought, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, and right immersion, which rely on seclusion, fading away, and cessation, and ripen as letting go.*";
P_HTM[1365]="*imāsaṃ kho, bhikkhave tissannaṃ vidhānaṃ abhiññāya pariññāya parikkhayāya pahānāya ayaṃ ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo bhāvetabbo”ti.**This is the noble eightfold path that should be developed for the direct knowledge, complete understanding, finishing, and giving up of these three kinds of discrimination.”*";
P_HTM[1366]="*(Yathā esanā, evaṃ vitthāretabbaṃ.)**(This should be expanded as in the section on searches.)*";
P_HTM[1367]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1368]="*3. Āsavasuttaṃ**Defilements*";
P_HTM[1369]="*“Tayome, bhikkhave, āsavā.**“Mendicants, there are these three defilements.*";
P_HTM[1370]="*Katame tayo?**What three?*";
P_HTM[1371]="*Kāmāsavo, bhavāsavo, avijjāsavo—**The defilements of sensuality, desire to be reborn, and ignorance.*";
P_HTM[1372]="*ime kho, bhikkhave, tayo āsavā.**These are the three defilements.*";
P_HTM[1373]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, tiṇṇannaṃ āsavānaṃ abhiññāya pariññāya parikkhayāya pahānāya … pe … ayaṃ ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo bhāvetabbo”ti.**The noble eightfold path should be developed for the direct knowledge, complete understanding, finishing, and giving up of these three defilements.”*";
P_HTM[1374]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1375]="*4. Bhavasuttaṃ**States of Existence*";
P_HTM[1376]="*“Tayome, bhikkhave, bhavā.**“There are these three states of existence.*";
P_HTM[1377]="*Katame tayo?**What three?*";
P_HTM[1378]="*Kāmabhavo, rūpabhavo, arūpabhavo—**Existence in the sensual realm, the realm of luminous form, and the formless realm.*";
P_HTM[1379]="*ime kho, bhikkhave, tayo bhavā.**These are the three states of existence.*";
P_HTM[1380]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, tiṇṇannaṃ bhavānaṃ abhiññāya pariññāya parikkhayāya pahānāya … pe … ayaṃ ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo bhāvetabbo”ti.**The noble eightfold path should be developed for the direct knowledge, complete understanding, finishing, and giving up of these three states of existence.”*";
P_HTM[1381]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1382]="*5. Dukkhatāsuttaṃ**Forms of Suffering*";
P_HTM[1383]="*“Tisso imā, bhikkhave, dukkhatā.**“Mendicants, there are these three forms of suffering.*";
P_HTM[1384]="*Katamā tisso?**What three?*";
P_HTM[1385]="*Dukkhadukkhatā, saṅkhāradukkhatā, vipariṇāmadukkhatā—**The suffering inherent in painful feeling; the suffering inherent in conditions; and the suffering inherent in perishing.*";
P_HTM[1386]="*imā kho, bhikkhave, tisso dukkhatā.**These are the three forms of suffering.*";
P_HTM[1387]="*Imāsaṃ kho, bhikkhave, tissannaṃ dukkhatānaṃ abhiññāya pariññāya parikkhayāya pahānāya … pe … ayaṃ ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo bhāvetabbo”ti.**The noble eightfold path should be developed for the direct knowledge, complete understanding, finishing, and giving up of these three forms of suffering.”*";
P_HTM[1388]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1389]="*6. Khilasuttaṃ**Kinds of Barrenness*";
P_HTM[1390]="*“Tayome, bhikkhave, khilā.**“Mendicants, there are these three kinds of barrenness.*";
P_HTM[1391]="*Katame tayo?**What three?*";
P_HTM[1392]="*Rāgo khilo, doso khilo, moho khilo—**Greed, hate, and delusion.*";
P_HTM[1393]="*ime kho, bhikkhave, tayo khilā.**These are the three kinds of barrenness.*";
P_HTM[1394]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, tiṇṇannaṃ khilānaṃ abhiññāya pariññāya parikkhayāya pahānāya … pe … ayaṃ ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo bhāvetabbo”ti.**The noble eightfold path should be developed for the direct knowledge, complete understanding, finishing, and giving up of these three kinds of barrenness.”*";
P_HTM[1395]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1396]="*7. Malasuttaṃ**Stains*";
P_HTM[1397]="*“Tīṇimāni, bhikkhave, malāni.**“Mendicants, there are these three stains.*";
P_HTM[1398]="*Katamāni tīṇi?**What three?*";
P_HTM[1399]="*Rāgo malaṃ, doso malaṃ, moho malaṃ—**Greed, hate, and delusion.*";
P_HTM[1400]="*imāni kho, bhikkhave, tīṇi malāni.**These are the three stains.*";
P_HTM[1401]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, tiṇṇannaṃ malānaṃ abhiññāya pariññāya parikkhayāya pahānāya … pe … ayaṃ ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo bhāvetabbo”ti.**The noble eightfold path should be developed for the direct knowledge, complete understanding, finishing, and giving up of these three stains.”*";
P_HTM[1402]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1403]="*8. Nīghasuttaṃ**Troubles*";
P_HTM[1404]="*“Tayome, bhikkhave, nīghā.**“Mendicants, there are these three troubles.*";
P_HTM[1405]="*Katame tayo?**What three?*";
P_HTM[1406]="*Rāgo nīgho, doso nīgho, moho nīgho—**Greed, hate, and delusion.*";
P_HTM[1407]="*ime kho, bhikkhave, tayo nīghā.**These are the three troubles.*";
P_HTM[1408]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, tiṇṇannaṃ nīghānaṃ abhiññāya pariññāya parikkhayāya pahānāya … pe … ayaṃ ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo bhāvetabbo”ti.**The noble eightfold path should be developed for the direct knowledge, complete understanding, finishing, and giving up of these three troubles.”*";
P_HTM[1409]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1410]="*9. Vedanāsuttaṃ**Feelings*";
P_HTM[1411]="*“Tisso imā, bhikkhave, vedanā.**“Mendicants, there are these three feelings:*";
P_HTM[1412]="*Katamā tisso?**What three?*";
P_HTM[1413]="*Sukhā vedanā, dukkhā vedanā, adukkhamasukhā vedanā—**Pleasant, painful, and neutral feeling.*";
P_HTM[1414]="*imā kho, bhikkhave, tisso vedanā.**These are the three feelings.*";
P_HTM[1415]="*Imāsaṃ kho, bhikkhave, tissannaṃ vedanānaṃ abhiññāya pariññāya parikkhayāya pahānāya … pe … ayaṃ ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo bhāvetabbo”ti.**The noble eightfold path should be developed for the direct knowledge, complete understanding, finishing, and giving up of these three feelings.”*";
P_HTM[1416]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1417]="*10. Taṇhāsuttaṃ**Craving*";
P_HTM[1418]="*“Tisso imā, bhikkhave, taṇhā.**“Mendicants, there are these three cravings.*";
P_HTM[1419]="*Katamā tisso?**What three?*";
P_HTM[1420]="*Kāmataṇhā, bhavataṇhā, vibhavataṇhā—**Craving for sensual pleasures, craving to continue existence, and craving to end existence.*";
P_HTM[1421]="*imā kho, bhikkhave, tisso taṇhā.**These are the three cravings.*";
P_HTM[1422]="*Imāsaṃ kho, bhikkhave, tissannaṃ taṇhānaṃ abhiññāya pariññāya parikkhayāya pahānāya … pe … ayaṃ ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo bhāvetabbo.**The noble eightfold path should be developed for the direct knowledge, complete understanding, finishing, and giving up of these three cravings.*";
P_HTM[1423]="*Katamo ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo?**What is the noble eightfold path?*";
P_HTM[1424]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sammādiṭṭhiṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ virāganissitaṃ nirodhanissitaṃ vossaggapariṇāmiṃ … pe … sammāsamādhiṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ virāganissitaṃ nirodhanissitaṃ vossaggapariṇāmiṃ.**It’s when a mendicant develops right view, right thought, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, and right immersion, which rely on seclusion, fading away, and cessation, and ripen as letting go.*";
P_HTM[1425]="*Imāsaṃ kho, bhikkhave, tissannaṃ taṇhānaṃ abhiññāya pariññāya parikkhayāya pahānāya … pe … ayaṃ ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo bhāvetabbo”ti.**This is the noble eightfold path that should be developed for the direct knowledge, complete understanding, finishing, and giving up of these three cravings.”*";
P_HTM[1426]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1427]="*Tasināsutta**Thirst*";
P_HTM[1428]="*“Tisso imā, bhikkhave, tasinā.**“Mendicants, there are these three thirsts.*";
P_HTM[1429]="*Katamā tisso?**What three?*";
P_HTM[1430]="*Kāmatasinā, bhavatasinā, vibhavatasinā.**Thirst for sensual pleasures, thirst to continue existence, and thirst to end existence.*";
P_HTM[1431]="*Imāsaṃ kho, bhikkhave, tissannaṃ tasinānaṃ abhiññāya pariññāya parikkhayāya pahānāya … pe ….**For the direct knowledge, complete understanding, finishing, and giving up of these three thirsts …*";
P_HTM[1432]="*rāgavinayapariyosānaṃ dosavinayapariyosānaṃ mohavinayapariyosānaṃ…pe…**… which culminates in the removal of greed, hate, and delusion.*";
P_HTM[1433]="*amatogadhaṃ amataparāyanaṃ amatapariyosānaṃ…pe…**… which culminates, finishes, and ends in the deathless.*";
P_HTM[1434]="*nibbānaninnaṃ nibbānapoṇaṃ nibbānapabbhāraṃ.**… which slants, slopes, and inclines to extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[1435]="*Imāsaṃ kho, bhikkhave, tissannaṃ tasinānaṃ abhiññāya pariññāya parikkhayāya pahānāya …pe…  ayaṃ ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo bhāvetabbo”ti.**The noble eightfold path should be developed for the direct knowledge, complete understanding, finishing, and giving up of these three thirsts.”*";
P_HTM[1436]="*Ekādasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1437]="*Esanāvaggo sattamo.* **";
P_HTM[1438]="*Tassuddānaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1439]="*Esanā vidhā āsavo,* **";
P_HTM[1440]="*bhavo ca dukkhatā khilā;* **";
P_HTM[1441]="*Malaṃ nīgho ca vedanā,* **";
P_HTM[1442]="*dve taṇhā tasināya cāti.* **";
P_HTM[1443]="*11. Tasināsuttaṃ**Floods*";
P_HTM[1444]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[1445]="*“Cattārome, bhikkhave, oghā.**“Mendicants, there are these four floods.*";
P_HTM[1446]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[1447]="*Kāmogho, bhavogho, diṭṭhogho, avijjogho—**The floods of sensuality, desire to be reborn, views, and ignorance.*";
P_HTM[1448]="*ime kho, bhikkhave, cattāro oghā.**These are the four floods.*";
P_HTM[1449]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, catunnaṃ oghānaṃ abhiññāya pariññāya parikkhayāya pahānāya … pe … ayaṃ ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo bhāvetabbo”ti.**The noble eightfold path should be developed for the direct knowledge, complete understanding, finishing, and giving up of these four floods.”*";
P_HTM[1450]="*(Yathā esanā, evaṃ vitthāretabbaṃ.)**(This should be expanded as in the section on searches.)*";
P_HTM[1451]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1452]="*9. Gaṅgāpeyyālavaggo**Floods*";
P_HTM[1453]="*1. Oghasuttaṃ**Attachments*";
P_HTM[1454]="*“Cattārome, bhikkhave, yogā.**“Mendicants, there are these four attachments.*";
P_HTM[1455]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[1456]="*Kāmayogo, bhavayogo, diṭṭhiyogo avijjāyogo—**The attachment to sensual pleasures, future lives, views, and ignorance.*";
P_HTM[1457]="*ime kho, bhikkhave, cattāro yogā.**These are the four attachments.*";
P_HTM[1458]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, catunnaṃ yogānaṃ abhiññāya pariññāya parikkhayāya pahānāya … pe … ayaṃ ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo bhāvetabbo”ti.**The noble eightfold path should be developed for the direct knowledge, complete understanding, finishing, and giving up of these four attachments.”*";
P_HTM[1459]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1460]="*2. Yogasuttaṃ**Grasping*";
P_HTM[1461]="*“Cattārimāni, bhikkhave, upādānāni.**“Mendicants, there are these four kinds of grasping.*";
P_HTM[1462]="*Katamāni cattāri?**What four?*";
P_HTM[1463]="*Kāmupādānaṃ, diṭṭhupādānaṃ, sīlabbatupādānaṃ, attavādupādānaṃ—**Grasping at sensual pleasures, views, precepts and observances, and theories of a self.*";
P_HTM[1464]="*imāni kho, bhikkhave, cattāri upādānāni.**These are the four kinds of grasping.*";
P_HTM[1465]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, catunnaṃ upādānānaṃ abhiññāya pariññāya parikkhayāya pahānāya … pe … ayaṃ ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo bhāvetabbo”ti.**The noble eightfold path should be developed for the direct knowledge, complete understanding, finishing, and giving up of these four kinds of grasping.”*";
P_HTM[1466]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1467]="*3. Upādānasuttaṃ**Personal Ties*";
P_HTM[1468]="*“Cattārome, bhikkhave, ganthā.**“Mendicants, there are these four ties.*";
P_HTM[1469]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[1470]="*Abhijjhā kāyagantho, byāpādo kāyagantho, sīlabbataparāmāso kāyagantho, idaṃsaccābhiniveso kāyagantho—**The personal ties to covetousness, ill will, misapprehension of precepts and observances, and the insistence that this is the only truth.*";
P_HTM[1471]="*ime kho, bhikkhave, cattāro ganthā.**These are the four ties.*";
P_HTM[1472]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, catunnaṃ ganthānaṃ abhiññāya pariññāya parikkhayāya pahānāya … pe … ayaṃ ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo bhāvetabbo”ti.**The noble eightfold path should be developed for the direct knowledge, complete understanding, finishing, and giving up of these four ties.”*";
P_HTM[1473]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1474]="*4. Ganthasuttaṃ**Tendencies*";
P_HTM[1475]="*“Sattime, bhikkhave, anusayā.**“Mendicants, there are these seven underlying tendencies.*";
P_HTM[1476]="*Katame satta?**What seven?*";
P_HTM[1477]="*Kāmarāgānusayo, paṭighānusayo, diṭṭhānusayo, vicikicchānusayo, mānānusayo, bhavarāgānusayo, avijjānusayo—**The underlying tendencies of sensual desire, repulsion, views, doubt, conceit, desire to be reborn, and ignorance.*";
P_HTM[1478]="*ime kho, bhikkhave, sattānusayā.**These are the seven underlying tendencies.*";
P_HTM[1479]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, sattannaṃ anusayānaṃ abhiññāya pariññāya parikkhayāya pahānāya … pe … ayaṃ ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo bhāvetabbo”ti.**The noble eightfold path should be developed for the direct knowledge, complete understanding, finishing, and giving up of these seven underlying tendencies.”*";
P_HTM[1480]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1481]="*5. Anusayasuttaṃ**Kinds of Sensual Stimulation*";
P_HTM[1482]="*“Pañcime, bhikkhave, kāmaguṇā.**“Mendicants, there are these five kinds of sensual stimulation.*";
P_HTM[1483]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1484]="*Cakkhuviññeyyā rūpā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā piyarūpā kāmūpasaṃhitā rajanīyā,**Sights known by the eye that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasant, sensual, and arousing.*";
P_HTM[1485]="*sotaviññeyyā saddā … pe … ghānaviññeyyā gandhā … pe …**Sounds known by the ear … Smells known by the nose …*";
P_HTM[1486]="*jivhāviññeyyā rasā … pe …**Tastes known by the tongue …*";
P_HTM[1487]="*kāyaviññeyyā phoṭṭhabbā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā piyarūpā kāmūpasaṃhitā rajanīyā—**Touches known by the body that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasant, sensual, and arousing.*";
P_HTM[1488]="*ime kho, bhikkhave, pañca kāmaguṇā.**These are the five kinds of sensual stimulation.*";
P_HTM[1489]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, pañcannaṃ kāmaguṇānaṃ abhiññāya pariññāya parikkhayāya pahānāya … pe … ayaṃ ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo bhāvetabbo”ti.**The noble eightfold path should be developed for the direct knowledge, complete understanding, finishing, and giving up of these five kinds of sensual stimulation.”*";
P_HTM[1490]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1491]="*6. Kāmaguṇasuttaṃ**Hindrances*";
P_HTM[1492]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, nīvaraṇāni.**“Mendicants, there are these five hindrances.*";
P_HTM[1493]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1494]="*Kāmacchandanīvaraṇaṃ, byāpādanīvaraṇaṃ, thinamiddhanīvaraṇaṃ, uddhaccakukkuccanīvaraṇaṃ, vicikicchānīvaraṇaṃ—**The hindrances of sensual desire, ill will, dullness and drowsiness, restlessness and remorse, and doubt.*";
P_HTM[1495]="*imāni kho, bhikkhave, pañca nīvaraṇāni.**These are the five hindrances.*";
P_HTM[1496]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, pañcannaṃ nīvaraṇānaṃ abhiññāya pariññāya parikkhayāya pahānāya … pe … ayaṃ ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo bhāvetabbo”ti.**The noble eightfold path should be developed for the direct knowledge, complete understanding, finishing, and giving up of these five hindrances.”*";
P_HTM[1497]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1498]="*7. Nīvaraṇasuttaṃ**Grasping Aggregates*";
P_HTM[1499]="*“Pañcime, bhikkhave, upādānakkhandhā.**“Mendicants, there are these five grasping aggregates.*";
P_HTM[1500]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1501]="*Seyyathidaṃ—rūpupādānakkhandho, vedanupādānakkhandho, saññupādānakkhandho, saṅkhārupādānakkhandho, viññāṇupādānakkhandho.**The grasping aggregates of form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness.*";
P_HTM[1502]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, pañcupādānakkhandhā.**These are the five grasping aggregates.*";
P_HTM[1503]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, pañcannaṃ upādānakkhandhānaṃ abhiññāya pariññāya parikkhayāya pahānāya … pe … ayaṃ ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo bhāvetabbo”ti.**The noble eightfold path should be developed for the direct knowledge, complete understanding, finishing, and giving up of these five grasping aggregates.”*";
P_HTM[1504]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1505]="*8. Upādānakkhandhasuttaṃ**Lower Fetters*";
P_HTM[1506]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, orambhāgiyāni saṃyojanāni.**“Mendicants, there are five lower fetters.*";
P_HTM[1507]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1508]="*Sakkāyadiṭṭhi, vicikicchā, sīlabbataparāmāso, kāmacchando, byāpādo—**Identity view, doubt, misapprehension of precepts and observances, sensual desire, and ill will.*";
P_HTM[1509]="*imāni kho, bhikkhave, pañcorambhāgiyāni saṃyojanāni.**These are the five lower fetters.*";
P_HTM[1510]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, pañcannaṃ orambhāgiyānaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ abhiññāya pariññāya parikkhayāya pahānāya … pe … ayaṃ ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo bhāvetabbo”ti.**The noble eightfold path should be developed for the direct knowledge, complete understanding, finishing, and giving up of these five lowers fetters.”*";
P_HTM[1511]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1512]="*9. Orambhāgiyasuttaṃ**Higher Fetters*";
P_HTM[1513]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, uddhambhāgiyāni saṃyojanāni.**“Mendicants, there are five higher fetters.*";
P_HTM[1514]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1515]="*Rūparāgo, arūparāgo, māno, uddhaccaṃ, avijjā—**Desire for rebirth in the realm of luminous form, desire for rebirth in the formless realm, conceit, restlessness, and ignorance.*";
P_HTM[1516]="*imāni kho, bhikkhave, pañcuddhambhāgiyāni saṃyojanāni.**These are the five higher fetters.*";
P_HTM[1517]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, pañcannaṃ uddhambhāgiyānaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ abhiññāya pariññāya parikkhayāya pahānāya ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo bhāvetabbo.**The noble eightfold path should be developed for the direct knowledge, complete understanding, finishing, and giving up of these five higher fetters.*";
P_HTM[1518]="*Katamo ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo?**What is the noble eightfold path?*";
P_HTM[1519]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sammādiṭṭhiṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ … pe … sammāsamādhiṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ virāganissitaṃ nirodhanissitaṃ vossaggapariṇāmiṃ.**It’s when a mendicant develops right view, right thought, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, and right immersion, which rely on seclusion, fading away, and cessation, and ripen as letting go.*";
P_HTM[1520]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, pañcannaṃ uddhambhāgiyānaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ abhiññāya pariññāya parikkhayāya pahānāya ayaṃ ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo bhāvetabboti.**This is the noble eightfold path that should be developed for the direct knowledge, complete understanding, finishing, and giving up of these five higher fetters.”*";
P_HTM[1521]="*Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, uddhambhāgiyāni saṃyojanāni.**“Mendicants, there are five higher fetters.*";
P_HTM[1522]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1523]="*Rūparāgo, arūparāgo, māno, uddhaccaṃ, avijjā—**Desire for rebirth in the realm of luminous form, desire for rebirth in the formless realm, conceit, restlessness, and ignorance.*";
P_HTM[1524]="*imāni kho, bhikkhave, pañcuddhambhāgiyāni saṃyojanāni.**These are the five higher fetters.*";
P_HTM[1525]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, pañcannaṃ uddhambhāgiyānaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ abhiññāya pariññāya parikkhayāya pahānāya ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo bhāvetabbo.**The noble eightfold path should be developed for the direct knowledge, complete understanding, finishing, and giving up of these five higher fetters.*";
P_HTM[1526]="*Katamo ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo?**What is the noble eightfold path?*";
P_HTM[1527]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sammādiṭṭhiṃ bhāveti … pe … sammāsamādhiṃ bhāveti rāgavinayapariyosānaṃ dosavinayapariyosānaṃ mohavinayapariyosānaṃ …**It’s when a mendicant develops right view, right thought, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, and right immersion, which culminate in the removal of greed, hate, and delusion …”*";
P_HTM[1528]="*amatogadhaṃ amataparāyanaṃ amatapariyosānaṃ …**“… which culminate, finish, and end in the deathless …”*";
P_HTM[1529]="*nibbānaninnaṃ nibbānapoṇaṃ nibbānapabbhāraṃ.**“… which have extinguishment as their culmination, destination, and end.*";
P_HTM[1530]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, pañcannaṃ uddhambhāgiyānaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ abhiññāya pariññāya parikkhayāya pahānāya ayaṃ ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo bhāvetabbo”ti.**This is the noble eightfold path that should be developed for the direct knowledge, complete understanding, finishing, and giving up of these five higher fetters.”*";
P_HTM[1531]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1532]="*Oghavaggo aṭṭhamo.* **";
P_HTM[1533]="*Ogho yogo upādānaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[1534]="*ganthaṃ anusayena ca;* **";
P_HTM[1535]="*Kāmaguṇā nīvaraṇaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[1536]="*khandhā oruddhambhāgiyāti.* **";
P_HTM[1537]="*Avijjāvaggo paṭhamo,* **";
P_HTM[1538]="*dutiyaṃ vihāraṃ vuccati;* **";
P_HTM[1539]="*Micchattaṃ tatiyo vaggo,* **";
P_HTM[1540]="*catutthaṃ paṭipanneneva.* **";
P_HTM[1541]="*Titthiyaṃ pañcamo vaggo,* **";
P_HTM[1542]="*chaṭṭho sūriyena ca;* **";
P_HTM[1543]="*Bahukate sattamo vaggo,* **";
P_HTM[1544]="*uppādo aṭṭhamena ca.* **";
P_HTM[1545]="*Divasavaggo navamo,* **";
P_HTM[1546]="*Dasamo appamādena ca;* **";
P_HTM[1547]="*Ekādasabalavaggo,* **";
P_HTM[1548]="*Dvādasa esanā pāḷiyaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[1549]="*Oghavaggo bhavati terasāti.* **";
P_HTM[1550]="*Maggasaṃyuttaṃ paṭhamaṃ.**The Linked Discourses on the Path is the first section.*";
P_HTM[1551]="*46. Bojjhaṅgasaṃyuttaṃ* **";
P_HTM[1552]="*10. Uddhambhāgiyasuttaṃ**The Himalaya*";
P_HTM[1553]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[1554]="*“Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, himavantaṃ pabbatarājānaṃ nissāya nāgā kāyaṃ vaḍḍhenti, balaṃ gāhenti;**“Mendicants, dragons grow and wax strong supported by the Himalayas, the king of mountains.*";
P_HTM[1555]="*te tattha kāyaṃ vaḍḍhetvā balaṃ gāhetvā kusobbhe otaranti, kusobbhe otaritvā mahāsobbhe otaranti, mahāsobbhe otaritvā kunnadiyo otaranti, kunnadiyo otaritvā mahānadiyo otaranti, mahānadiyo otaritvā mahāsamuddasāgaraṃ otaranti; te tattha mahantattaṃ vepullattaṃ āpajjanti kāyena;**When they’re strong they dive into the pools. Then they dive into the lakes, the streams, the rivers, and finally the ocean. There they acquire a great and abundant body.*";
P_HTM[1556]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sīlaṃ nissāya sīle patiṭṭhāya satta bojjhaṅge bhāvento satta bojjhaṅge bahulīkaronto mahantattaṃ vepullattaṃ pāpuṇāti dhammesu.**In the same way, a mendicant develops and cultivates the seven awakening factors depending on and grounded on ethics, acquiring great and abundant good qualities.*";
P_HTM[1557]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sīlaṃ nissāya sīle patiṭṭhāya satta bojjhaṅge bhāvento satta bojjhaṅge bahulīkaronto mahantattaṃ vepullattaṃ pāpuṇāti dhammesūti?**And how does a mendicant develop the seven awakening factors depending on and grounded on ethics, acquiring great and abundant good qualities?*";
P_HTM[1558]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu satisambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ virāganissitaṃ nirodhanissitaṃ vossaggapariṇāmiṃ;**It’s when a mendicant develops the awakening factor of mindfulness, which relies on seclusion, fading away, and cessation, and ripens as letting go.*";
P_HTM[1559]="*dhammavicayasambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti … pe …**They develop the awakening factor of investigation of principles …*";
P_HTM[1560]="*vīriyasambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti … pe …**They develop the awakening factor of energy …*";
P_HTM[1561]="*pītisambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti … pe …**They develop the awakening factor of rapture …*";
P_HTM[1562]="*passaddhisambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti … pe …**They develop the awakening factor of tranquility …*";
P_HTM[1563]="*samādhisambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti … pe …**They develop the awakening factor of immersion …*";
P_HTM[1564]="*upekkhāsambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ virāganissitaṃ nirodhanissitaṃ vossaggapariṇāmiṃ.**They develop the awakening factor of equanimity, which relies on seclusion, fading away, and cessation, and ripens as letting go.*";
P_HTM[1565]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sīlaṃ nissāya sīle patiṭṭhāya satta bojjhaṅge bhāvento satta bojjhaṅge bahulīkaronto mahantattaṃ vepullattaṃ pāpuṇāti dhammesū”ti.**That’s how a mendicant develops and cultivates the seven awakening factors depending on and grounded on ethics, acquiring great and abundant good qualities.”*";
P_HTM[1566]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1567]="*10. Appamādavaggo**Mountains*";
P_HTM[1568]="*1. Himavantasuttaṃ**The Body*";
P_HTM[1569]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[1570]="*“Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, ayaṃ kāyo āhāraṭṭhitiko, āhāraṃ paṭicca tiṭṭhati, anāhāro no tiṭṭhati;**“Mendicants, this body is sustained by food. It depends on food to continue, and without food it doesn’t continue.*";
P_HTM[1571]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, pañca nīvaraṇā āhāraṭṭhitikā, āhāraṃ paṭicca tiṭṭhanti, anāhārā no tiṭṭhanti.**In the same way, the five hindrances are sustained by fuel. They depend on fuel to continue, and without fuel they don’t continue.*";
P_HTM[1572]="*Ko ca, bhikkhave, āhāro anuppannassa vā kāmacchandassa uppādāya, uppannassa vā kāmacchandassa bhiyyobhāvāya vepullāya?**And what fuels the arising of sensual desire, or, when it has arisen, makes it increase and grow?*";
P_HTM[1573]="*Atthi, bhikkhave, subhanimittaṃ.**There is the feature of beauty.*";
P_HTM[1574]="*Tattha ayonisomanasikārabahulīkāro—**Frequent improper attention to that*";
P_HTM[1575]="*ayamāhāro anuppannassa vā kāmacchandassa uppādāya, uppannassa vā kāmacchandassa bhiyyobhāvāya vepullāya.**fuels the arising of sensual desire, or, when it has arisen, makes it increase and grow.*";
P_HTM[1576]="*Ko ca, bhikkhave, āhāro anuppannassa vā byāpādassa uppādāya, uppannassa vā byāpādassa bhiyyobhāvāya vepullāya?**And what fuels the arising of ill will, or, when it has arisen, makes it increase and grow?*";
P_HTM[1577]="*Atthi, bhikkhave, paṭighanimittaṃ.**There is the feature of harshness.*";
P_HTM[1578]="*Tattha ayonisomanasikārabahulīkāro—**Frequent improper attention to that*";
P_HTM[1579]="*ayamāhāro anuppannassa vā byāpādassa uppādāya, uppannassa vā byāpādassa bhiyyobhāvāya vepullāya.**fuels the arising of ill will, or, when it has arisen, makes it increase and grow.*";
P_HTM[1580]="*Ko ca, bhikkhave, āhāro anuppannassa vā thinamiddhassa uppādāya, uppannassa vā thinamiddhassa bhiyyobhāvāya vepullāya?**And what fuels the arising of dullness and drowsiness, or, when it has arisen, makes it increase and grow?*";
P_HTM[1581]="*Atthi, bhikkhave, arati tandi vijambhitā bhattasammado cetaso ca līnattaṃ.**There is discontent, sloth, yawning, sleepiness after eating, and mental sluggishness.*";
P_HTM[1582]="*Tattha ayonisomanasikārabahulīkāro—**Frequent improper attention to them*";
P_HTM[1583]="*ayamāhāro anuppannassa vā thinamiddhassa uppādāya, uppannassa vā thinamiddhassa bhiyyobhāvāya vepullāya.**fuels the arising of dullness and drowsiness, or, when it has arisen, makes it increase and grow.*";
P_HTM[1584]="*Ko ca, bhikkhave, āhāro anuppannassa vā uddhaccakukkuccassa uppādāya, uppannassa vā uddhaccakukkuccassa bhiyyobhāvāya vepullāya?**And what fuels the arising of restlessness and remorse, or, when it has arisen, makes it increase and grow?*";
P_HTM[1585]="*Atthi, bhikkhave, cetaso avūpasamo.**There is the unsettled mind.*";
P_HTM[1586]="*Tattha ayonisomanasikārabahulīkāro—**Frequent improper attention to that*";
P_HTM[1587]="*ayamāhāro anuppannassa vā uddhaccakukkuccassa uppādāya, uppannassa vā uddhaccakukkuccassa bhiyyobhāvāya vepullāya.**fuels the arising of restlessness and remorse, or, when it has arisen, makes it increase and grow.*";
P_HTM[1588]="*Ko ca, bhikkhave, āhāro anuppannāya vā vicikicchāya uppādāya, uppannāya vā vicikicchāya bhiyyobhāvāya vepullāya?**And what fuels the arising of doubt, or, when it has arisen, makes it increase and grow?*";
P_HTM[1589]="*Atthi, bhikkhave, vicikicchāṭṭhānīyā dhammā.**There are things that are grounds for doubt.*";
P_HTM[1590]="*Tattha ayonisomanasikārabahulīkāro—**Frequent improper attention to them*";
P_HTM[1591]="*ayamāhāro anuppannāya vā vicikicchāya uppādāya, uppannāya vā vicikicchāya bhiyyobhāvāya vepullāya.**fuels the arising of doubt, or, when it has arisen, makes it increase and grow.*";
P_HTM[1592]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, ayaṃ kāyo āhāraṭṭhitiko, āhāraṃ paṭicca tiṭṭhati, anāhāro no tiṭṭhati;**This body is sustained by food. It depends on food to continue, and without food it doesn’t continue.*";
P_HTM[1593]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, ime pañca nīvaraṇā āhāraṭṭhitikā, āhāraṃ paṭicca tiṭṭhanti, anāhārā no tiṭṭhanti.**In the same way, the five hindrances are sustained by fuel. They depend on fuel to continue, and without fuel they don’t continue.*";
P_HTM[1594]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, ayaṃ kāyo āhāraṭṭhitiko, āhāraṃ paṭicca tiṭṭhati, anāhāro no tiṭṭhati;**This body is sustained by food. It depends on food to continue, and without food it doesn’t continue.*";
P_HTM[1595]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, satta bojjhaṅgā āhāraṭṭhitikā, āhāraṃ paṭicca tiṭṭhanti, anāhārā no tiṭṭhanti.**In the same way, the seven awakening factors are sustained by fuel. They depend on fuel to continue, and without fuel they don’t continue.*";
P_HTM[1596]="*Ko ca, bhikkhave, āhāro anuppannassa vā satisambojjhaṅgassa uppādāya, uppannassa vā satisambojjhaṅgassa bhāvanāya pāripūriyā?**And what fuels the arising of the awakening factor of mindfulness, or, when it has arisen, fully develops it?*";
P_HTM[1597]="*Atthi, bhikkhave, satisambojjhaṅgaṭṭhānīyā dhammā.**There are things that are grounds for the awakening factor of mindfulness.*";
P_HTM[1598]="*Tattha yonisomanasikārabahulīkāro—**Frequent proper attention to them*";
P_HTM[1599]="*ayamāhāro anuppannassa vā satisambojjhaṅgassa uppādāya, uppannassa vā satisambojjhaṅgassa bhāvanāya pāripūriyā.**fuels the arising of the awakening factor of mindfulness, or, when it has arisen, fully develops it.*";
P_HTM[1600]="*Ko ca, bhikkhave, āhāro anuppannassa vā dhammavicayasambojjhaṅgassa uppādāya, uppannassa vā dhammavicayasambojjhaṅgassa bhāvanāya pāripūriyā?**And what fuels the arising of the awakening factor of investigation of principles, or, when it has arisen, fully develops it?*";
P_HTM[1601]="*Atthi, bhikkhave, kusalākusalā dhammā, sāvajjānavajjā dhammā, hīnapaṇītā dhammā, kaṇhasukkasappaṭibhāgā dhammā.**There are qualities that are skillful and unskillful, blameworthy and blameless, inferior and superior, and those on the side of dark and bright.*";
P_HTM[1602]="*Tattha yonisomanasikārabahulīkāro—**Frequent proper attention to them*";
P_HTM[1603]="*ayamāhāro anuppannassa vā dhammavicayasambojjhaṅgassa uppādāya, uppannassa vā dhammavicayasambojjhaṅgassa bhāvanāya pāripūriyā.**fuels the arising of the awakening factor of investigation of principles, or, when it has arisen, fully develops it.*";
P_HTM[1604]="*Ko ca, bhikkhave, āhāro anuppannassa vā vīriyasambojjhaṅgassa uppādāya, uppannassa vā vīriyasambojjhaṅgassa bhāvanāya pāripūriyā?**And what fuels the arising of the awakening factor of energy, or, when it has arisen, fully develops it?*";
P_HTM[1605]="*Atthi, bhikkhave, ārambhadhātu nikkamadhātu parakkamadhātu.**There are the elements of initiative, persistence, and exertion.*";
P_HTM[1606]="*Tattha yonisomanasikārabahulīkāro—**Frequent proper attention to them*";
P_HTM[1607]="*ayamāhāro anuppannassa vā vīriyasambojjhaṅgassa uppādāya, uppannassa vā vīriyasambojjhaṅgassa bhāvanāya pāripūriyā.**fuels the arising of the awakening factor of energy, or, when it has arisen, fully develops it.*";
P_HTM[1608]="*Ko ca, bhikkhave, āhāro anuppannassa vā pītisambojjhaṅgassa uppādāya, uppannassa vā pītisambojjhaṅgassa bhāvanāya pāripūriyā?**And what fuels the arising of the awakening factor of rapture, or, when it has arisen, fully develops it?*";
P_HTM[1609]="*Atthi, bhikkhave, pītisambojjhaṅgaṭṭhānīyā dhammā.**There are things that are grounds for the awakening factor of rapture.*";
P_HTM[1610]="*Tattha yonisomanasikārabahulīkāro—**Frequent proper attention to them*";
P_HTM[1611]="*ayamāhāro anuppannassa vā pītisambojjhaṅgassa uppādāya, uppannassa vā pītisambojjhaṅgassa bhāvanāya pāripūriyā.**fuels the arising of the awakening factor of rapture, or, when it has arisen, fully develops it.*";
P_HTM[1612]="*Ko ca, bhikkhave, āhāro anuppannassa vā passaddhisambojjhaṅgassa uppādāya, uppannassa vā passaddhisambojjhaṅgassa bhāvanāya pāripūriyā?**And what fuels the arising of the awakening factor of tranquility, or, when it has arisen, fully develops it?*";
P_HTM[1613]="*Atthi, bhikkhave, kāyapassaddhi, cittapassaddhi.**There is tranquility of the body and of the mind.*";
P_HTM[1614]="*Tattha yonisomanasikārabahulīkāro—**Frequent proper attention to that*";
P_HTM[1615]="*ayamāhāro anuppannassa vā passaddhisambojjhaṅgassa uppādāya, uppannassa vā passaddhisambojjhaṅgassa bhāvanāya pāripūriyā.**fuels the arising of the awakening factor of tranquility, or, when it has arisen, fully develops it.*";
P_HTM[1616]="*Ko ca, bhikkhave, āhāro anuppannassa vā samādhisambojjhaṅgassa uppādāya, uppannassa vā samādhisambojjhaṅgassa bhāvanāya pāripūriyā?**And what fuels the arising of the awakening factor of immersion, or, when it has arisen, fully develops it?*";
P_HTM[1617]="*Atthi, bhikkhave, samathanimittaṃ abyagganimittaṃ.**There are things that are the foundation of serenity and freedom from distraction.*";
P_HTM[1618]="*Tattha yonisomanasikārabahulīkāro—**Frequent proper attention to them*";
P_HTM[1619]="*ayamāhāro anuppannassa vā samādhisambojjhaṅgassa uppādāya, uppannassa vā samādhisambojjhaṅgassa bhāvanāya pāripūriyā.**fuels the arising of the awakening factor of immersion, or, when it has arisen, fully develops it.*";
P_HTM[1620]="*Ko ca, bhikkhave, āhāro anuppannassa vā upekkhāsambojjhaṅgassa uppādāya, uppannassa vā upekkhāsambojjhaṅgassa bhāvanāya pāripūriyā?**And what fuels the arising of the awakening factor of equanimity, or, when it has arisen, fully develops it?*";
P_HTM[1621]="*Atthi, bhikkhave, upekkhāsambojjhaṅgaṭṭhānīyā dhammā.**There are things that are grounds for the awakening factor of equanimity.*";
P_HTM[1622]="*Tattha yonisomanasikārabahulīkāro—**Frequent proper attention to them*";
P_HTM[1623]="*ayamāhāro anuppannassa vā upekkhāsambojjhaṅgassa uppādāya, uppannassa vā upekkhāsambojjhaṅgassa bhāvanāya pāripūriyā.**fuels the arising of the awakening factor of equanimity, or, when it has arisen, fully develops it.*";
P_HTM[1624]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, ayaṃ kāyo āhāraṭṭhitiko, āhāraṃ paṭicca tiṭṭhati, anāhāro no tiṭṭhati;**This body is sustained by food. It depends on food to continue, and without food it doesn’t continue.*";
P_HTM[1625]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, ime satta bojjhaṅgā āhāraṭṭhitikā, āhāraṃ paṭicca tiṭṭhanti, anāhārā no tiṭṭhantī”ti.**In the same way, the seven awakening factors are sustained by fuel. They depend on fuel to continue, and without fuel they don’t continue.”*";
P_HTM[1626]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1627]="*2. Kāyasuttaṃ**Ethics*";
P_HTM[1628]="*“Ye te, bhikkhave, bhikkhū sīlasampannā samādhisampannā ñāṇasampannā vimuttisampannā vimuttiñāṇadassanasampannā, dassanampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, tesaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ bahukāraṃ vadāmi;**“Mendicants, when a mendicant is accomplished in ethics, immersion, wisdom, freedom, or the knowledge and vision of freedom, even the sight of them is very helpful, I say.*";
P_HTM[1629]="*savanampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, tesaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ bahukāraṃ vadāmi;**Even to hear them,*";
P_HTM[1630]="*upasaṅkamanampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, tesaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ bahukāraṃ vadāmi;**approach them,*";
P_HTM[1631]="*payirupāsanampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, tesaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ bahukāraṃ vadāmi;**pay homage to them,*";
P_HTM[1632]="*anussatimpāhaṃ, bhikkhave, tesaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ bahukāraṃ vadāmi;**recollect them,*";
P_HTM[1633]="*anupabbajjampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, tesaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ bahukāraṃ vadāmi.**or go forth after them is very helpful, I say.*";
P_HTM[1634]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[1635]="*Tathārūpānaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhūnaṃ dhammaṃ sutvā dvayena vūpakāsena vūpakaṭṭho viharati—kāyavūpakāsena ca cittavūpakāsena ca.**Because after hearing the teaching of such mendicants, a mendicant will live withdrawn in both body and mind,*";
P_HTM[1636]="*So tathā vūpakaṭṭho viharanto taṃ dhammaṃ anussarati anuvitakketi.**as they recollect and think about that teaching.*";
P_HTM[1637]="*Yasmiṃ samaye, bhikkhave, bhikkhu tathā vūpakaṭṭho viharanto taṃ dhammaṃ anussarati anuvitakketi, satisambojjhaṅgo tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhuno āraddho hoti;**At such a time, a mendicant has activated the awakening factor of mindfulness;*";
P_HTM[1638]="*satisambojjhaṅgaṃ tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhu bhāveti;**they develop it*";
P_HTM[1639]="*satisambojjhaṅgo tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhuno bhāvanāpāripūriṃ gacchati.**and perfect it.*";
P_HTM[1640]="*So tathā sato viharanto taṃ dhammaṃ paññāya pavicinati pavicarati parivīmaṃsamāpajjati.**As they live mindfully in this way they investigate, explore, and inquire into that teaching with wisdom.*";
P_HTM[1641]="*Yasmiṃ samaye, bhikkhave, bhikkhu tathā sato viharanto taṃ dhammaṃ paññāya pavicinati pavicarati parivīmaṃsamāpajjati, dhammavicayasambojjhaṅgo tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhuno āraddho hoti;**At such a time, a mendicant has activated the awakening factor of investigation of principles;*";
P_HTM[1642]="*dhammavicayasambojjhaṅgaṃ tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhu bhāveti;**they develop it*";
P_HTM[1643]="*dhammavicayasambojjhaṅgo tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhuno bhāvanāpāripūriṃ gacchati.**and perfect it.*";
P_HTM[1644]="*Tassa taṃ dhammaṃ paññāya pavicinato pavicarato parivīmaṃsamāpajjato āraddhaṃ hoti vīriyaṃ asallīnaṃ.**As they investigate principles with wisdom in this way their energy is roused up and unflagging.*";
P_HTM[1645]="*Yasmiṃ samaye, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno taṃ dhammaṃ paññāya pavicinato pavicarato parivīmaṃsamāpajjato āraddhaṃ hoti vīriyaṃ asallīnaṃ, vīriyasambojjhaṅgo tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhuno āraddho hoti; vīriyasambojjhaṅgaṃ tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhu bhāveti; vīriyasambojjhaṅgo tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhuno bhāvanāpāripūriṃ gacchati.**At such a time, a mendicant has activated the awakening factor of energy; they develop it and perfect it.*";
P_HTM[1646]="*Āraddhavīriyassa uppajjati pīti nirāmisā.**When they’re energetic, spiritual rapture arises.*";
P_HTM[1647]="*Yasmiṃ samaye, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno āraddhavīriyassa uppajjati pīti nirāmisā, pītisambojjhaṅgo tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhuno āraddho hoti; pītisambojjhaṅgaṃ tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhu bhāveti; pītisambojjhaṅgo tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhuno bhāvanāpāripūriṃ gacchati.**At such a time, a mendicant has activated the awakening factor of rapture; they develop it and perfect it.*";
P_HTM[1648]="*Pītimanassa kāyopi passambhati, cittampi passambhati.**When the mind is full of rapture, the body and mind become tranquil.*";
P_HTM[1649]="*Yasmiṃ samaye, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno pītimanassa kāyopi passambhati cittampi passambhati, passaddhisambojjhaṅgo tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhuno āraddho hoti; passaddhisambojjhaṅgaṃ tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhu bhāveti; passaddhisambojjhaṅgo tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhuno bhāvanāpāripūriṃ gacchati.**At such a time, a mendicant has activated the awakening factor of tranquility; they develop it and perfect it.*";
P_HTM[1650]="*Passaddhakāyassa sukhino cittaṃ samādhiyati.**When the body is tranquil and one feels bliss, the mind becomes immersed in samādhi.*";
P_HTM[1651]="*Yasmiṃ samaye, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno passaddhakāyassa sukhino cittaṃ samādhiyati, samādhisambojjhaṅgo tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhuno āraddho hoti; samādhisambojjhaṅgaṃ tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhu bhāveti; samādhisambojjhaṅgo tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhuno bhāvanāpāripūriṃ gacchati.**At such a time, a mendicant has activated the awakening factor of immersion; they develop it and perfect it.*";
P_HTM[1652]="*So tathāsamāhitaṃ cittaṃ sādhukaṃ ajjhupekkhitā hoti.**They closely watch over that mind immersed in samādhi.*";
P_HTM[1653]="*Yasmiṃ samaye, bhikkhave, bhikkhu tathāsamāhitaṃ cittaṃ sādhukaṃ ajjhupekkhitā hoti, upekkhāsambojjhaṅgo tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhuno āraddho hoti; upekkhāsambojjhaṅgaṃ tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhu bhāveti; upekkhāsambojjhaṅgo tasmiṃ samaye bhikkhuno bhāvanāpāripūriṃ gacchati.**At such a time, a mendicant has activated the awakening factor of equanimity; they develop it and perfect it.*";
P_HTM[1654]="*Evaṃ bhāvitesu kho, bhikkhave, sattasu sambojjhaṅgesu evaṃ bahulīkatesu satta phalā sattānisaṃsā pāṭikaṅkhā.**When the seven awakening factors are developed and cultivated in this way they can expect seven fruits and benefits.*";
P_HTM[1655]="*Katame satta phalā sattānisaṃsā?**What seven?*";
P_HTM[1656]="*Diṭṭheva dhamme paṭikacca aññaṃ ārādheti.**They attain enlightenment early on in this very life.*";
P_HTM[1657]="*No ce diṭṭheva dhamme paṭikacca aññaṃ ārādheti, atha maraṇakāle aññaṃ ārādheti.**If not, they attain enlightenment at the time of death.*";
P_HTM[1658]="*No ce diṭṭheva dhamme paṭikacca aññaṃ ārādheti, no ce maraṇakāle aññaṃ ārādheti, atha pañcannaṃ orambhāgiyānaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ parikkhayā antarāparinibbāyī hoti.**If not, with the ending of the five lower fetters, they’re extinguished between one life and the next.*";
P_HTM[1659]="*No ce diṭṭheva dhamme paṭikacca aññaṃ ārādheti, no ce maraṇakāle aññaṃ ārādheti, no ce pañcannaṃ orambhāgiyānaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ parikkhayā antarāparinibbāyī hoti, atha pañcannaṃ orambhāgiyānaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ parikkhayā upahaccaparinibbāyī hoti.**If not, with the ending of the five lower fetters they’re extinguished upon landing.*";
P_HTM[1660]="*No ce diṭṭheva dhamme paṭikacca aññaṃ ārādheti, no ce maraṇakāle aññaṃ ārādheti, no ce pañcannaṃ orambhāgiyānaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ parikkhayā antarāparinibbāyī hoti, no ce pañcannaṃ orambhāgiyānaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ parikkhayā upahaccaparinibbāyī hoti, atha pañcannaṃ orambhāgiyānaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ parikkhayā asaṅkhāraparinibbāyī hoti.**If not, with the ending of the five lower fetters they’re extinguished without extra effort.*";
P_HTM[1661]="*No ce diṭṭheva dhamme paṭikacca aññaṃ ārādheti, no ce maraṇakāle aññaṃ ārādheti, no ce pañcannaṃ orambhāgiyānaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ parikkhayā antarāparinibbāyī hoti, no ce pañcannaṃ orambhāgiyānaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ parikkhayā upahaccaparinibbāyī hoti, no ce pañcannaṃ orambhāgiyānaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ parikkhayā asaṅkhāraparinibbāyī hoti, atha pañcannaṃ orambhāgiyānaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ parikkhayā sasaṅkhāraparinibbāyī hoti.**If not, with the ending of the five lower fetters they’re extinguished with extra effort.*";
P_HTM[1662]="*No ce diṭṭheva dhamme paṭikacca aññaṃ ārādheti, no ce maraṇakāle aññaṃ ārādheti, no ce pañcannaṃ orambhāgiyānaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ parikkhayā antarāparinibbāyī hoti, no ce pañcannaṃ orambhāgiyānaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ parikkhayā upahaccaparinibbāyī hoti, no ce pañcannaṃ orambhāgiyānaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ parikkhayā asaṅkhāraparinibbāyī hoti, no ce pañcannaṃ orambhāgiyānaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ parikkhayā sasaṅkhāraparinibbāyī hoti, atha pañcannaṃ orambhāgiyānaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ parikkhayā uddhaṃsoto hoti akaniṭṭhagāmī.**If not, with the ending of the five lower fetters they head upstream, going to the Akaniṭṭha realm.*";
P_HTM[1663]="*Evaṃ bhāvitesu kho, bhikkhave, sattasu bojjhaṅgesu evaṃ bahulīkatesu ime satta phalā sattānisaṃsā pāṭikaṅkhā”ti.**When the seven awakening factors are developed and cultivated in this way these are the seven fruits and benefits they can expect.”*";
P_HTM[1664]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1665]="*3. Sīlasuttaṃ**Clothes*";
P_HTM[1666]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ āyasmā sāriputto sāvatthiyaṃ viharati jetavane anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme.**At one time Venerable Sāriputta was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery.*";
P_HTM[1667]="*Tatra kho āyasmā sāriputto bhikkhū āmantesi:**There Sāriputta addressed the mendicants:*";
P_HTM[1668]="*“āvuso bhikkhavo”ti.**“Reverends, mendicants!”*";
P_HTM[1669]="*“Āvuso”ti kho te bhikkhū āyasmato sāriputtassa paccassosuṃ.**“Reverend,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[1670]="*Āyasmā sāriputto etadavoca:**Sāriputta said this:*";
P_HTM[1671]="*“Sattime, āvuso, bojjhaṅgā.**“There are these seven awakening factors.*";
P_HTM[1672]="*Katame satta?**What seven?*";
P_HTM[1673]="*Satisambojjhaṅgo, dhammavicayasambojjhaṅgo, vīriyasambojjhaṅgo, pītisambojjhaṅgo, passaddhisambojjhaṅgo, samādhisambojjhaṅgo, upekkhāsambojjhaṅgo—**The awakening factors of mindfulness, investigation of principles, energy, rapture, tranquility, immersion, and equanimity.*";
P_HTM[1674]="*ime kho, āvuso, satta bojjhaṅgā.**These are the seven awakening factors.*";
P_HTM[1675]="*Imesaṃ khvāhaṃ, āvuso, sattannaṃ bojjhaṅgānaṃ yena yena bojjhaṅgena ākaṅkhāmi pubbaṇhasamayaṃ viharituṃ, tena tena bojjhaṅgena pubbaṇhasamayaṃ viharāmi;**In the morning, I meditate on whichever of these seven awakening factors I want.*";
P_HTM[1676]="*yena yena bojjhaṅgena ākaṅkhāmi majjhanhikaṃ samayaṃ viharituṃ, tena tena bojjhaṅgena majjhanhikaṃ samayaṃ viharāmi;**At midday,*";
P_HTM[1677]="*yena yena bojjhaṅgena ākaṅkhāmi sāyanhasamayaṃ viharituṃ, tena tena bojjhaṅgena sāyanhasamayaṃ viharāmi.**and in the evening, I meditate on whichever of these seven awakening factors I want.*";
P_HTM[1678]="*Satisambojjhaṅgo iti ce me, āvuso, hoti, ‘appamāṇo’ti me hoti, ‘susamāraddho’ti me hoti, tiṭṭhantañca naṃ ‘tiṭṭhatī’ti pajānāmi.**If it’s the awakening factor of mindfulness, I know that it’s limitless and that it’s properly implemented. While it remains I understand that it remains.*";
P_HTM[1679]="*Sacepi me cavati, ‘idappaccayā me cavatī’ti pajānāmi … pe …**And if it subsides I understand that it subsides. …*";
P_HTM[1680]="*upekkhāsambojjhaṅgo iti ce me, āvuso, hoti, ‘appamāṇo’ti me hoti, ‘susamāraddho’ti me hoti, tiṭṭhantañca naṃ ‘tiṭṭhatī’ti pajānāmi.**If it’s the awakening factor of equanimity, I know that it’s limitless and that it’s properly implemented. While it remains I understand that it remains.*";
P_HTM[1681]="*Sacepi me cavati, ‘idappaccayā me cavatī’ti pajānāmi.**And if it subsides I understand that it subsides.*";
P_HTM[1682]="*Seyyathāpi, āvuso, rañño vā rājamahāmattassa vā nānārattānaṃ dussānaṃ dussakaraṇḍako pūro assa.**Suppose that a ruler or their minister had a chest full of garments of different colors.*";
P_HTM[1683]="*So yaññadeva dussayugaṃ ākaṅkheyya pubbaṇhasamayaṃ pārupituṃ, taṃ tadeva dussayugaṃ pubbaṇhasamayaṃ pārupeyya;**In the morning, they’d don whatever pair of garments they wanted.*";
P_HTM[1684]="*yaññadeva dussayugaṃ ākaṅkheyya majjhanhikaṃ samayaṃ pārupituṃ, taṃ tadeva dussayugaṃ majjhanhikaṃ samayaṃ pārupeyya;**At midday,*";
P_HTM[1685]="*yaññadeva dussayugaṃ ākaṅkheyya sāyanhasamayaṃ pārupituṃ, taṃ tadeva dussayugaṃ sāyanhasamayaṃ pārupeyya.**and in the evening, they’d don whatever pair of garments they wanted.*";
P_HTM[1686]="*Evameva khvāhaṃ, āvuso, imesaṃ sattannaṃ bojjhaṅgānaṃ yena yena bojjhaṅgena ākaṅkhāmi pubbaṇhasamayaṃ viharituṃ, tena tena bojjhaṅgena pubbaṇhasamayaṃ viharāmi;**In the same way, in the morning,*";
P_HTM[1687]="*yena yena bojjhaṅgena ākaṅkhāmi majjhanhikaṃ samayaṃ viharituṃ, tena tena bojjhaṅgena majjhanhikaṃ samayaṃ viharāmi;**at midday,*";
P_HTM[1688]="*yena yena bojjhaṅgena ākaṅkhāmi sāyanhasamayaṃ viharituṃ, tena tena bojjhaṅgena sāyanhasamayaṃ viharāmi.**and in the evening, I meditate on whichever of these seven awakening factors I want.*";
P_HTM[1689]="*Satisambojjhaṅgo iti ce me, āvuso, hoti, ‘appamāṇo’ti me hoti, ‘susamāraddho’ti me hoti, tiṭṭhantañca naṃ ‘tiṭṭhatī’ti pajānāmi.**If it’s the awakening factor of mindfulness, I know that it’s limitless and that it’s properly implemented. While it remains I understand that it remains.*";
P_HTM[1690]="*Sacepi me cavati, ‘idappaccayā me cavatī’ti pajānāmi … pe …**And if it subsides I understand that it subsides. …*";
P_HTM[1691]="*upekkhāsambojjhaṅgo iti ce me, āvuso, hoti, ‘appamāṇo’ti me hoti, ‘susamāraddho’ti me hoti, tiṭṭhantañca naṃ ‘tiṭṭhatī’ti pajānāmi.**If it’s the awakening factor of equanimity, I know that it’s limitless and that it’s properly implemented. While it remains I understand that it remains.*";
P_HTM[1692]="*Sacepi me cavati, ‘idappaccayā me cavatī’ti pajānāmī”ti.**And if it subsides I understand that it subsides.”*";
P_HTM[1693]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1694]="*4. Vatthasuttaṃ**A Monk*";
P_HTM[1695]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[1696]="*Atha kho aññataro bhikkhu yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami … pe … ekamantaṃ nisinno kho so bhikkhu bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then a mendicant went up to the Buddha … and asked him,*";
P_HTM[1697]="*“‘bojjhaṅgā, bojjhaṅgā’ti, bhante, vuccanti.**“Sir, they speak of the ‘awakening factors’.*";
P_HTM[1698]="*Kittāvatā nu kho, bhante, ‘bojjhaṅgā’ti vuccantī”ti?**How are the awakening factors defined?”*";
P_HTM[1699]="*“Bodhāya saṃvattantīti kho, bhikkhu, tasmā ‘bojjhaṅgā’ti vuccanti.**“Mendicant, they’re called awakening factors because they lead to awakening.*";
P_HTM[1700]="*Idha, bhikkhu, satisambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ virāganissitaṃ nirodhanissitaṃ vossaggapariṇāmiṃ … pe … upekkhāsambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ virāganissitaṃ nirodhanissitaṃ vossaggapariṇāmiṃ.**A mendicant develops the awakening factors of mindfulness, investigation of principles, energy, rapture, tranquility, immersion, and equanimity, which rely on seclusion, fading away, and cessation, and ripen as letting go.*";
P_HTM[1701]="*Tassime satta bojjhaṅge bhāvayato kāmāsavāpi cittaṃ vimuccati, bhavāsavāpi cittaṃ vimuccati, avijjāsavāpi cittaṃ vimuccati.**As they develop the seven awakening factors, their mind is freed from the defilements of sensuality, desire to be reborn, and ignorance.*";
P_HTM[1702]="*Vimuttasmiṃ vimuttamiti ñāṇaṃ hoti.**When they’re freed, they know they’re freed.*";
P_HTM[1703]="*‘Khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyā’ti pajānāti.**They understand: ‘Rebirth is ended, the spiritual journey has been completed, what had to be done has been done, there is no return to any state of existence.’*";
P_HTM[1704]="*Bodhāya saṃvattantīti, bhikkhu, tasmā ‘bojjhaṅgā’ti vuccantī”ti.**They’re called awakening factors because they lead to awakening.”*";
P_HTM[1705]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1706]="*5. Bhikkhusuttaṃ**Kuṇḍaliya*";
P_HTM[1707]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sākete viharati añjanavane migadāye.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāketa in the deer part at the Añjana Wood.*";
P_HTM[1708]="*Atha kho kuṇḍaliyo paribbājako yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavatā saddhiṃ sammodi.**Then the wanderer Kuṇḍaliya went up to the Buddha, and exchanged greetings with him.*";
P_HTM[1709]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho kuṇḍaliyo paribbājako bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, he sat down to one side and said to the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[1710]="*“ahamasmi, bho gotama, ārāmanissayī parisāvacaro.**“Master Gotama, I like to hang around the monasteries and visit the assemblies.*";
P_HTM[1711]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, bho gotama, pacchābhattaṃ bhuttapātarāsassa ayamācāro hoti—**When I’ve finished breakfast, it’s my habit to*";
P_HTM[1712]="*ārāmena ārāmaṃ uyyānena uyyānaṃ anucaṅkamāmi anuvicarāmi.**wander from monastery to monastery, from park to park.*";
P_HTM[1713]="*So tattha passāmi eke samaṇabrāhmaṇe itivādappamokkhānisaṃsañceva kathaṃ kathente upārambhānisaṃsañca:**There I see some ascetics and brahmins speaking for the sake of winning debates and finding fault.*";
P_HTM[1714]="*‘bhavaṃ pana gotamo kimānisaṃso viharatī’”ti?**But what benefit does Master Gotama live for?”*";
P_HTM[1715]="*“Vijjāvimuttiphalānisaṃso kho, kuṇḍaliya, tathāgato viharatī”ti.**“The benefit the Realized One lives for, Kuṇḍaliya, is the fruit of knowledge and freedom.”*";
P_HTM[1716]="*“Katame pana, bho gotama, dhammā bhāvitā bahulīkatā vijjāvimuttiṃ paripūrentī”ti?**“But what things must be developed and cultivated in order to fulfill knowledge and freedom?”*";
P_HTM[1717]="*“Satta kho, kuṇḍaliya, bojjhaṅgā bhāvitā bahulīkatā vijjāvimuttiṃ paripūrentī”ti.**“The seven awakening factors.”*";
P_HTM[1718]="*“Katame pana, bho gotama, dhammā bhāvitā bahulīkatā satta bojjhaṅge paripūrentī”ti?**“But what things must be developed and cultivated in order to fulfill the seven awakening factors?”*";
P_HTM[1719]="*“Cattāro kho, kuṇḍaliya, satipaṭṭhānā bhāvitā bahulīkatā satta bojjhaṅge paripūrentī”ti.**“The four kinds of mindfulness meditation.”*";
P_HTM[1720]="*“Katame pana, bho gotama, dhammā bhāvitā, bahulīkatā cattāro satipaṭṭhāne paripūrentī”ti?**“But what things must be developed and cultivated in order to fulfill the four kinds of mindfulness meditation?”*";
P_HTM[1721]="*“Tīṇi kho, kuṇḍaliya, sucaritāni bhāvitāni bahulīkatāni cattāro satipaṭṭhāne paripūrentī”ti.**“The three kinds of good conduct.”*";
P_HTM[1722]="*“Katame pana, bho gotama, dhammā bhāvitā bahulīkatā tīṇi sucaritāni paripūrentī”ti?**“But what things must be developed and cultivated in order to fulfill the three kinds of good conduct?”*";
P_HTM[1723]="*“Indriyasaṃvaro kho, kuṇḍaliya, bhāvito bahulīkato tīṇi sucaritāni paripūretīti.**“Sense restraint.*";
P_HTM[1724]="*Kathaṃ bhāvito ca, kuṇḍaliya, indriyasaṃvaro kathaṃ bahulīkato tīṇi sucaritāni paripūretīti?**And Kuṇḍaliya, how is sense restraint developed and cultivated so as to fulfill the three kinds of good conduct?*";
P_HTM[1725]="*Idha, kuṇḍaliya, bhikkhu cakkhunā rūpaṃ disvā manāpaṃ nābhijjhati nābhihaṃsati, na rāgaṃ janeti.**A mendicant sees an agreeable sight with their eye. They don’t desire it or enjoy it, and they don’t give rise to greed.*";
P_HTM[1726]="*Tassa ṭhito ca kāyo hoti, ṭhitaṃ cittaṃ ajjhattaṃ susaṇṭhitaṃ suvimuttaṃ.**Their mind and body are steady internally, well settled and well freed.*";
P_HTM[1727]="*Cakkhunā kho paneva rūpaṃ disvā amanāpaṃ na maṅku hoti appatiṭṭhitacitto adīnamānaso abyāpannacetaso.**But if they see a disagreeable sight they’re not dismayed; their mind isn’t hardened, dejected, or full of ill will.*";
P_HTM[1728]="*Tassa ṭhito ca kāyo hoti ṭhitaṃ cittaṃ ajjhattaṃ susaṇṭhitaṃ suvimuttaṃ.**Their mind and body are steady internally, well settled and well freed.*";
P_HTM[1729]="*Puna caparaṃ, kuṇḍaliya, bhikkhu sotena saddaṃ sutvā … pe …**Furthermore, a mendicant hears an agreeable sound with the ear …*";
P_HTM[1730]="*ghānena gandhaṃ ghāyitvā … pe …**smells an agreeable odor with the nose …*";
P_HTM[1731]="*jivhāya rasaṃ sāyitvā … pe …**tastes an agreeable flavor with the tongue …*";
P_HTM[1732]="*kāyena phoṭṭhabbaṃ phusitvā … pe …**feels an agreeable touch with the body …*";
P_HTM[1733]="*manasā dhammaṃ viññāya manāpaṃ nābhijjhati nābhihaṃsati, na rāgaṃ janeti.**knows an agreeable thought with their mind. They don’t desire it or enjoy it, and they don’t give rise to greed.*";
P_HTM[1734]="*Tassa ṭhito ca kāyo hoti, ṭhitaṃ cittaṃ ajjhattaṃ susaṇṭhitaṃ suvimuttaṃ.**Their mind and body are steady internally, well settled and well freed.*";
P_HTM[1735]="*Manasā kho paneva dhammaṃ viññāya amanāpaṃ na maṅku hoti appatiṭṭhitacitto adīnamānaso abyāpannacetaso.**But if they know a disagreeable thought they’re not dismayed; their mind isn’t hardened, dejected, or full of ill will.*";
P_HTM[1736]="*Tassa ṭhito ca kāyo hoti, ṭhitaṃ cittaṃ ajjhattaṃ susaṇṭhitaṃ suvimuttaṃ.**Their mind and body are steady internally, well settled and well freed.*";
P_HTM[1737]="*Yato kho, kuṇḍaliya, bhikkhuno cakkhunā rūpaṃ disvā manāpāmanāpesu rūpesu ṭhito ca kāyo hoti, ṭhitaṃ cittaṃ ajjhattaṃ susaṇṭhitaṃ suvimuttaṃ.**When a mendicant’s mind and body are steady internally, they’re well settled and well freed when it comes to both agreeable and disagreeable sights,*";
P_HTM[1738]="*Sotena saddaṃ sutvā … pe …**sounds,*";
P_HTM[1739]="*ghānena gandhaṃ ghāyitvā … pe …**smells,*";
P_HTM[1740]="*jivhāya rasaṃ sāyitvā … pe …**tastes,*";
P_HTM[1741]="*kāyena phoṭṭhabbaṃ phusitvā … pe …**touches,*";
P_HTM[1742]="*manasā dhammaṃ viññāya manāpāmanāpesu dhammesu ṭhito ca kāyo hoti, ṭhitaṃ cittaṃ ajjhattaṃ susaṇṭhitaṃ suvimuttaṃ.**and thoughts.*";
P_HTM[1743]="*Evaṃ bhāvito kho, kuṇḍaliya, indriyasaṃvaro evaṃ bahulīkato tīṇi sucaritāni paripūreti.**That’s how sense restraint is developed and cultivated so as to fulfill the three kinds of good conduct.*";
P_HTM[1744]="*Kathaṃ bhāvitāni ca, kuṇḍaliya, tīṇi sucaritāni kathaṃ bahulīkatāni cattāro satipaṭṭhāne paripūrenti?**And how are the three kinds of good conduct developed and cultivated so as to fulfill the four kinds of mindfulness meditation?*";
P_HTM[1745]="*Idha, kuṇḍaliya, bhikkhu kāyaduccaritaṃ pahāya kāyasucaritaṃ bhāveti, vacīduccaritaṃ pahāya vacīsucaritaṃ bhāveti, manoduccaritaṃ pahāya manosucaritaṃ bhāveti.**A mendicant gives up bad conduct by way of body, speech, and mind, and develops good conduct by way of body, speech, and mind.*";
P_HTM[1746]="*Evaṃ bhāvitāni kho, kuṇḍaliya, tīṇi sucaritāni evaṃ bahulīkatāni cattāro satipaṭṭhāne paripūrenti.**That’s how the three kinds of good conduct are developed and cultivated so as to fulfill the four kinds of mindfulness meditation.*";
P_HTM[1747]="*Kathaṃ bhāvitā ca, kuṇḍaliya, cattāro satipaṭṭhānā kathaṃ bahulīkatā satta bojjhaṅge paripūrenti?**And how are the four kinds of mindfulness meditation developed and cultivated so as to fulfill the seven awakening factors?*";
P_HTM[1748]="*Idha, kuṇḍaliya, bhikkhu kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;**A mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[1749]="*vedanāsu … pe …**They meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[1750]="*citte … pe …**mind …*";
P_HTM[1751]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[1752]="*Evaṃ bhāvitā kho, kuṇḍaliya, cattāro satipaṭṭhānā evaṃ bahulīkatā satta bojjhaṅge paripūrenti.**That’s how the four kinds of mindfulness meditation are developed and cultivated so as to fulfill the seven awakening factors.*";
P_HTM[1753]="*Kathaṃ bhāvitā ca, kuṇḍaliya, satta bojjhaṅgā kathaṃ bahulīkatā vijjāvimuttiṃ paripūrenti?**And how are the seven awakening factors developed and cultivated so as to fulfill knowledge and freedom?*";
P_HTM[1754]="*Idha, kuṇḍaliya, bhikkhu satisambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ virāganissitaṃ nirodhanissitaṃ vossaggapariṇāmiṃ … pe … upekkhāsambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ virāganissitaṃ nirodhanissitaṃ vossaggapariṇāmiṃ.**A mendicant develops the awakening factors of mindfulness, investigation of principles, energy, rapture, tranquility, immersion, and equanimity, which rely on seclusion, fading away, and cessation, and ripen as letting go.*";
P_HTM[1755]="*Evaṃ bhāvitā kho, kuṇḍaliya, satta bojjhaṅgā evaṃ bahulīkatā vijjāvimuttiṃ paripūrentī”ti.**That’s how the seven awakening factors are developed and cultivated so as to fulfill knowledge and freedom.”*";
P_HTM[1756]="*Evaṃ vutte, kuṇḍaliyo paribbājako bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When he said this, the wanderer Kuṇḍaliya said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[1757]="*“abhikkantaṃ, bho gotama, abhikkantaṃ, bho gotama.**“Excellent, Master Gotama! Excellent!*";
P_HTM[1758]="*Seyyathāpi, bho gotama, nikkujjitaṃ vā ukkujjeyya, paṭicchannaṃ vā vivareyya, mūḷhassa vā maggaṃ ācikkheyya, andhakāre vā telapajjotaṃ dhāreyya: ‘cakkhumanto rūpāni dakkhantī’ti; evameva bhotā gotamena anekapariyāyena dhammo pakāsito.**As if he were righting the overturned, or revealing the hidden, or pointing out the path to the lost, or lighting a lamp in the dark so people with good eyes can see what’s there, Master Gotama has made the teaching clear in many ways.*";
P_HTM[1759]="*Esāhaṃ bhavantaṃ gotamaṃ saraṇaṃ gacchāmi dhammañca bhikkhusaṅghañca.**I go for refuge to Master Gotama, to the teaching, and to the mendicant Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[1760]="*Upāsakaṃ maṃ bhavaṃ gotamo dhāretu ajjatagge pāṇupetaṃ saraṇaṃ gatan”ti.**From this day forth, may Master Gotama remember me as a lay follower who has gone for refuge for life.”*";
P_HTM[1761]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1762]="*6. Kuṇḍaliyasuttaṃ**A Bungalow*";
P_HTM[1763]="*“Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, kūṭāgārassa yā kāci gopānasiyo, sabbā tā kūṭaninnā kūṭapoṇā kūṭapabbhārā;**“Mendicants, the rafters of a bungalow all slant, slope, and incline to the peak.*";
P_HTM[1764]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu satta bojjhaṅge bhāvento satta bojjhaṅge bahulīkaronto nibbānaninno hoti nibbānapoṇo nibbānapabbhāro.**In the same way, a mendicant who develops and cultivates the seven awakening factors slants, slopes, and inclines to extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[1765]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhu satta bojjhaṅge bhāvento satta bojjhaṅge bahulīkaronto nibbānaninno hoti nibbānapoṇo nibbānapabbhāro?**And how does a mendicant who develops the seven awakening factors slant, slope, and incline to extinguishment?*";
P_HTM[1766]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu satisambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ virāganissitaṃ nirodhanissitaṃ vossaggapariṇāmiṃ … pe … upekkhāsambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ virāganissitaṃ nirodhanissitaṃ vossaggapariṇāmiṃ.**It’s when a mendicant develops the awakening factors of mindfulness, investigation of principles, energy, rapture, tranquility, immersion, and equanimity, which rely on seclusion, fading away, and cessation, and ripen as letting go.*";
P_HTM[1767]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu satta bojjhaṅge bhāvento satta bojjhaṅge bahulīkaronto nibbānaninno hoti nibbānapoṇo nibbānapabbhāro”ti.**That’s how a mendicant who develops and cultivates the seven awakening factors slants, slopes, and inclines to extinguishment.”*";
P_HTM[1768]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1769]="*7. Kūṭāgārasuttaṃ**With Upavāna*";
P_HTM[1770]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ āyasmā ca upavāno āyasmā ca sāriputto kosambiyaṃ viharanti ghositārāme.**At one time the venerables Upavāna and Sāriputta were staying near Kosambi, in Ghosita’s Monastery.*";
P_HTM[1771]="*Atha kho āyasmā sāriputto sāyanhasamayaṃ paṭisallānā vuṭṭhito yenāyasmā upavāno tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmatā upavānena saddhiṃ sammodi.**Then in the late afternoon, Venerable Sāriputta came out of retreat, went to Venerable Upavāna and exchanged greetings with him.*";
P_HTM[1772]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā sāriputto āyasmantaṃ upavānaṃ etadavoca:**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, he sat down to one side and said to Upavāna:*";
P_HTM[1773]="*“Jāneyya nu kho, āvuso upavāna, bhikkhu ‘paccattaṃ yonisomanasikārā evaṃ susamāraddhā me satta bojjhaṅgā phāsuvihārāya saṃvattantī’”ti?**“Reverend Upavāna, can a mendicant know by investigating inside themselves that the seven awakening factors are well implemented so that they lead to living at ease?”*";
P_HTM[1774]="*“Jāneyya kho, āvuso sāriputta, bhikkhu ‘paccattaṃ yonisomanasikārā evaṃ susamāraddhā me satta bojjhaṅgā phāsuvihārāya saṃvattantī’”ti.**“They can, Reverend Sāriputta.*";
P_HTM[1775]="*“Satisambojjhaṅgaṃ kho, āvuso, bhikkhu ārabbhamāno pajānāti ‘cittañca me suvimuttaṃ, thinamiddhañca me susamūhataṃ, uddhaccakukkuccañca me suppaṭivinītaṃ, āraddhañca me vīriyaṃ, aṭṭhiṃ katvā manasi karomi, no ca līnan’ti … pe …**As a mendicant rouses up the awakening factor of mindfulness, they understand: ‘My mind is well freed. I’ve eradicated dullness and drowsiness, and eliminated restlessness and remorse. My energy is roused up, and my mind is sharply focused, not sluggish.’ …*";
P_HTM[1776]="*upekkhāsambojjhaṅgaṃ āvuso, bhikkhu ārabbhamāno pajānāti ‘cittañca me suvimuttaṃ, thinamiddhañca me susamūhataṃ, uddhaccakukkuccañca me suppaṭivinītaṃ, āraddhañca me vīriyaṃ, aṭṭhiṃ katvā manasi karomi, no ca līnan’”ti.**As they rouse up the awakening factor of equanimity, they understand: ‘My mind is well freed. I’ve eradicated dullness and drowsiness, and eliminated restlessness and remorse. My energy is roused up, and my mind is sharply focused, not sluggish.’*";
P_HTM[1777]="*“Evaṃ kho, āvuso sāriputta, bhikkhu jāneyya ‘paccattaṃ yonisomanasikārā evaṃ susamāraddhā me satta bojjhaṅgā phāsuvihārāya saṃvattantī’”ti.**That’s how a mendicant can know by investigating inside themselves that the seven awakening factors are well implemented so that they lead to living at ease.”*";
P_HTM[1778]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1779]="*8. Upavānasuttaṃ**Arisen (1st)*";
P_HTM[1780]="*“Sattime, bhikkhave, bojjhaṅgā bhāvitā bahulīkatā anuppannā uppajjanti, nāññatra tathāgatassa pātubhāvā arahato sammāsambuddhassa.**“Mendicants, these seven awakening factors don’t arise to be developed and cultivated except when a Realized One, a perfected one, a fully awakened Buddha has appeared.*";
P_HTM[1781]="*Katame satta?**What seven?*";
P_HTM[1782]="*Satisambojjhaṅgo … pe … upekkhāsambojjhaṅgo—**The awakening factors of mindfulness, investigation of principles, energy, rapture, tranquility, immersion, and equanimity.*";
P_HTM[1783]="*ime kho, bhikkhave, satta bojjhaṅgā bhāvitā bahulīkatā anuppannā uppajjanti, nāññatra tathāgatassa pātubhāvā arahato sammāsambuddhassā”ti.**These seven awakening factors don’t arise to be developed and cultivated except when a Realized One, a perfected one, a fully awakened Buddha has appeared.”*";
P_HTM[1784]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1785]="*9. Paṭhamauppannasuttaṃ**Arisen (2nd)*";
P_HTM[1786]="*“Sattime, bhikkhave, bojjhaṅgā bhāvitā bahulīkatā anuppannā uppajjanti, nāññatra sugatavinayā.**“Mendicants, these seven awakening factors don’t arise to be developed and cultivated apart from the Holy One’s training.*";
P_HTM[1787]="*Katame satta?**What seven?*";
P_HTM[1788]="*Satisambojjhaṅgo … pe … upekkhāsambojjhaṅgo—**The awakening factors of mindfulness, investigation of principles, energy, rapture, tranquility, immersion, and equanimity.*";
P_HTM[1789]="*ime kho, bhikkhave, satta bojjhaṅgā bhāvitā bahulīkatā anuppannā uppajjanti, nāññatra sugatavinayā”ti.**These seven awakening factors don’t arise to be developed and cultivated apart from the Holy One’s training.”*";
P_HTM[1790]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1791]="*Pabbatavaggo paṭhamo.* **";
P_HTM[1792]="*Himavantaṃ kāyaṃ sīlaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[1793]="*vatthaṃ bhikkhu ca kuṇḍali;* **";
P_HTM[1794]="*Kūṭañca upavānañca,* **";
P_HTM[1795]="*uppannā apare duveti.* **";
P_HTM[1796]="*10. Dutiyauppannasuttaṃ**Living Creatures*";
P_HTM[1797]="*“Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, ye keci pāṇā cattāro iriyāpathe kappenti—**“Mendicants, living creatures engage in the four postures:*";
P_HTM[1798]="*kālena gamanaṃ, kālena ṭhānaṃ, kālena nisajjaṃ, kālena seyyaṃ, sabbe te pathaviṃ nissāya pathaviyaṃ patiṭṭhāya evamete cattāro iriyāpathe kappenti;**sometimes walking, sometimes standing, sometimes sitting, sometimes lying down. They do so depending on the earth and grounded on the earth.*";
P_HTM[1799]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sīlaṃ nissāya sīle patiṭṭhāya satta bojjhaṅge bhāveti, satta bojjhaṅge bahulīkaroti.**In the same way, a mendicant develops and cultivates the seven awakening factors depending on and grounded on ethics.*";
P_HTM[1800]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sīlaṃ nissāya sīle patiṭṭhāya satta bojjhaṅge bhāveti satta bojjhaṅge bahulīkaroti?**And how does a mendicant develop the seven awakening factors depending on and grounded on ethics?*";
P_HTM[1801]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu satisambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ virāganissitaṃ nirodhanissitaṃ vossaggapariṇāmiṃ … pe … upekkhāsambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ virāganissitaṃ nirodhanissitaṃ vossaggapariṇāmiṃ.**It’s when a mendicant develops the awakening factors of mindfulness, investigation of principles, energy, rapture, tranquility, immersion, and equanimity, which rely on seclusion, fading away, and cessation, and ripen as letting go.*";
P_HTM[1802]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sīlaṃ nissāya sīle patiṭṭhāya satta bojjhaṅge bhāveti, satta bojjhaṅge bahulīkarotī”ti.**That’s how a mendicant develops and cultivates the seven awakening factors depending on and grounded on ethics.”*";
P_HTM[1803]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1804]="*11. Balakaraṇīyavaggo**Sick*";
P_HTM[1805]="*1. Pāṇasuttaṃ**The Simile of the Sun (1st)*";
P_HTM[1806]="*“Sūriyassa, bhikkhave, udayato etaṃ pubbaṅgamaṃ etaṃ pubbanimittaṃ, yadidaṃ—aruṇuggaṃ;**“Mendicants, the dawn is the forerunner and precursor of the sunrise.*";
P_HTM[1807]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno sattannaṃ bojjhaṅgānaṃ uppādāya etaṃ pubbaṅgamaṃ etaṃ nimittaṃ, yadidaṃ—kalyāṇamittatā.**In the same way, for a mendicant good friendship is the forerunner and precursor of the arising of the seven awakening factors.*";
P_HTM[1808]="*Kalyāṇamittassetaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno pāṭikaṅkhaṃ—satta bojjhaṅge bhāvessati, satta bojjhaṅge bahulīkarissati.**A mendicant with good friends can expect to develop and cultivate the seven awakening factors.*";
P_HTM[1809]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kalyāṇamitto satta bojjhaṅge bhāveti satta bojjhaṅge bahulīkaroti?**And how does a mendicant with good friends develop and cultivate the seven awakening factors?*";
P_HTM[1810]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu satisambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ … pe … upekkhāsambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ virāganissitaṃ nirodhanissitaṃ vossaggapariṇāmiṃ.**It’s when a mendicant develops the awakening factors of mindfulness, investigation of principles, energy, rapture, tranquility, immersion, and equanimity, which rely on seclusion, fading away, and cessation, and ripen as letting go.*";
P_HTM[1811]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kalyāṇamitto satta bojjhaṅge bhāveti, satta bojjhaṅge bahulīkarotī”ti.**That’s how a mendicant with good friends develops and cultivates the seven awakening factors.”*";
P_HTM[1812]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1813]="*2. Paṭhamasūriyūpamasuttaṃ**The Simile of the Sun (2nd)*";
P_HTM[1814]="*“Sūriyassa, bhikkhave, udayato etaṃ pubbaṅgamaṃ etaṃ pubbanimittaṃ, yadidaṃ—aruṇuggaṃ;**“Mendicants, the dawn is the forerunner and precursor of the sunrise.*";
P_HTM[1815]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno sattannaṃ bojjhaṅgānaṃ uppādāya etaṃ pubbaṅgamaṃ etaṃ pubbanimittaṃ, yadidaṃ—yonisomanasikāro.**In the same way, for a mendicant proper attention is the forerunner and precursor of the arising of the seven awakening factors.*";
P_HTM[1816]="*Yonisomanasikārasampannassetaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno pāṭikaṅkhaṃ—satta bojjhaṅge bhāvessati, satta bojjhaṅge bahulīkarissati.**A mendicant accomplished in proper attention can expect to develop and cultivate the seven awakening factors.*";
P_HTM[1817]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhu yonisomanasikārasampanno satta bojjhaṅge bhāveti, satta bojjhaṅge bahulīkaroti?**And how does a mendicant with proper attention develop and cultivate the seven awakening factors?*";
P_HTM[1818]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu satisambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ … pe … upekkhāsambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ virāganissitaṃ nirodhanissitaṃ vossaggapariṇāmiṃ.**It’s when a mendicant develops the awakening factors of mindfulness, investigation of principles, energy, rapture, tranquility, immersion, and equanimity, which rely on seclusion, fading away, and cessation, and ripen as letting go.*";
P_HTM[1819]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu yonisomanasikārasampanno satta bojjhaṅge bhāveti, satta bojjhaṅge bahulīkarotī”ti.**That’s how a mendicant with proper attention develops and cultivates the seven awakening factors.”*";
P_HTM[1820]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1821]="*3. Dutiyasūriyūpamasuttaṃ**Sick (1st)*";
P_HTM[1822]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā rājagahe viharati veḷuvane kalandakanivāpe.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Rājagaha, in the Bamboo Grove, the squirrels’ feeding ground.*";
P_HTM[1823]="*Tena kho pana samayena āyasmā mahākassapo pippaliguhāyaṃ viharati ābādhiko dukkhito bāḷhagilāno.**Now at that time Venerable Mahākassapa was staying in the Pipphali cave, and he was sick, suffering, gravely ill.*";
P_HTM[1824]="*Atha kho bhagavā sāyanhasamayaṃ paṭisallānā vuṭṭhito yenāyasmā mahākassapo tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā paññatte āsane nisīdi. Nisajja kho bhagavā āyasmantaṃ mahākassapaṃ etadavoca:**Then in the late afternoon, the Buddha came out of retreat, went to Venerable Mahākassapa, sat down on the seat spread out, and said to him:*";
P_HTM[1825]="*“Kacci te, kassapa, khamanīyaṃ kacci yāpanīyaṃ? Kacci dukkhā vedanā paṭikkamanti, no abhikkamanti; paṭikkamosānaṃ paññāyati, no abhikkamo”ti?**“Kassapa, I hope you’re keeping well; I hope you’re alright. And I hope the pain is fading, not growing, that its fading is evident, not its growing.”*";
P_HTM[1826]="*“Na me, bhante, khamanīyaṃ, na yāpanīyaṃ. Bāḷhā me dukkhā vedanā abhikkamanti, no paṭikkamanti; abhikkamosānaṃ paññāyati, no paṭikkamo”ti.**“Sir, I’m not keeping well, I’m not alright. The pain is terrible and growing, not fading; its growing is evident, not its fading.”*";
P_HTM[1827]="*“Sattime, kassapa, bojjhaṅgā mayā sammadakkhātā bhāvitā bahulīkatā abhiññāya sambodhāya nibbānāya saṃvattanti.**“Kassapa, I’ve rightly explained these seven awakening factors. When developed and cultivated, they lead to direct knowledge, to awakening, and to extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[1828]="*Katame satta?**What seven?*";
P_HTM[1829]="*Satisambojjhaṅgo kho, kassapa, mayā sammadakkhāto bhāvito bahulīkato abhiññāya sambodhāya nibbānāya saṃvattati … pe … upekkhāsambojjhaṅgo kho, kassapa, mayā sammadakkhāto bhāvito bahulīkato abhiññāya sambodhāya nibbānāya saṃvattati.**The awakening factors of mindfulness, investigation of principles, energy, rapture, tranquility, immersion, and equanimity.*";
P_HTM[1830]="*Ime kho, kassapa, satta bojjhaṅgā mayā sammadakkhātā bhāvitā bahulīkatā abhiññāya sambodhāya nibbānāya saṃvattantī”ti.**These are the seven awakening factors that I’ve rightly explained. When developed and cultivated, they lead to direct knowledge, to awakening, and to extinguishment.”*";
P_HTM[1831]="*“Taggha, bhagavā, bojjhaṅgā;**“Indeed, Blessed One, these are awakening factors!*";
P_HTM[1832]="*taggha, sugata, bojjhaṅgā”ti.**Indeed, Holy One, these are awakening factors!”*";
P_HTM[1833]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[1834]="*Attamano āyasmā mahākassapo bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandi.**Satisfied, Venerable Mahākassapa was happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[1835]="*Vuṭṭhahi cāyasmā mahākassapo tamhā ābādhā.**And that’s how he recovered from that illness.*";
P_HTM[1836]="*Tathāpahīno cāyasmato mahākassapassa so ābādho ahosīti.* **";
P_HTM[1837]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1838]="*4. Paṭhamagilānasuttaṃ**Sick (2nd)*";
P_HTM[1839]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā rājagahe viharati veḷuvane kalandakanivāpe.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Rājagaha, in the Bamboo Grove, the squirrels’ feeding ground.*";
P_HTM[1840]="*Tena kho pana samayena āyasmā mahāmoggallāno gijjhakūṭe pabbate viharati ābādhiko dukkhito bāḷhagilāno.**Now at that time Venerable Mahāmoggallāna was staying on the Vulture’s Peak mountain, and he was sick, suffering, gravely ill.*";
P_HTM[1841]="*Atha kho bhagavā sāyanhasamayaṃ paṭisallānā vuṭṭhito yenāyasmā mahāmoggallāno tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā paññatte āsane nisīdi. Nisajja kho bhagavā āyasmantaṃ mahāmoggallānaṃ etadavoca:**Then in the late afternoon, the Buddha came out of retreat, went to Venerable Moggallāna, sat down on the seat spread out, and said to him:*";
P_HTM[1842]="*“Kacci te, moggallāna, khamanīyaṃ kacci yāpanīyaṃ? Kacci dukkhā vedanā paṭikkamanti, no abhikkamanti; paṭikkamosānaṃ paññāyati, no abhikkamo”ti?**“Moggallāna, I hope you’re keeping well; I hope you’re alright. And I hope the pain is fading, not growing, that its fading is evident, not its growing.”*";
P_HTM[1843]="*“Na me, bhante, khamanīyaṃ, na yāpanīyaṃ. Bāḷhā me dukkhā vedanā abhikkamanti, no paṭikkamanti; abhikkamosānaṃ paññāyati, no paṭikkamo”ti.**“Sir, I’m not keeping well, I’m not alright. The pain is terrible and growing, not fading; its growing is evident, not its fading.”*";
P_HTM[1844]="*“Sattime, moggallāna, bojjhaṅgā mayā sammadakkhātā bhāvitā bahulīkatā abhiññāya sambodhāya nibbānāya saṃvattanti.**“Moggallāna, I’ve rightly explained these seven awakening factors. When developed and cultivated, they lead to direct knowledge, to awakening, and to extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[1845]="*Katame satta?**What seven?*";
P_HTM[1846]="*Satisambojjhaṅgo kho, moggallāna, mayā sammadakkhāto bhāvito bahulīkato abhiññāya sambodhāya nibbānāya saṃvattati … pe … upekkhāsambojjhaṅgo kho, moggallāna, mayā sammadakkhāto bhāvito bahulīkato abhiññāya sambodhāya nibbānāya saṃvattati.**The awakening factors of mindfulness, investigation of principles, energy, rapture, tranquility, immersion, and equanimity.*";
P_HTM[1847]="*Ime kho, moggallāna, satta bojjhaṅgā mayā sammadakkhātā bhāvitā bahulīkatā abhiññāya sambodhāya nibbānāya saṃvattantī”ti.**These are the seven awakening factors that I’ve rightly explained. When developed and cultivated, they lead to direct knowledge, to awakening, and to extinguishment.”*";
P_HTM[1848]="*“Taggha, bhagavā, bojjhaṅgā;**“Indeed, Blessed One, these are awakening factors!*";
P_HTM[1849]="*taggha, sugata, bojjhaṅgā”ti.**Indeed, Holy One, these are awakening factors!”*";
P_HTM[1850]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[1851]="*Attamano āyasmā mahāmoggallāno bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandi.**Satisfied, Venerable Mahāmoggallāna was happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[1852]="*Vuṭṭhahi cāyasmā mahāmoggallāno tamhā ābādhā.**And that’s how he recovered from that illness.*";
P_HTM[1853]="*Tathāpahīno cāyasmato mahāmoggallānassa so ābādho ahosīti.* **";
P_HTM[1854]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1855]="*5. Dutiyagilānasuttaṃ**Sick (3rd)*";
P_HTM[1856]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā rājagahe viharati veḷuvane kalandakanivāpe.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Rājagaha, in the Bamboo Grove, the squirrels’ feeding ground.*";
P_HTM[1857]="*Tena kho pana samayena bhagavā ābādhiko hoti dukkhito bāḷhagilāno.**Now at that time he was sick, suffering, gravely ill.*";
P_HTM[1858]="*Atha kho āyasmā mahācundo yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinnaṃ kho āyasmantaṃ mahācundaṃ bhagavā etadavoca:**Then Venerable Mahācunda went up to the Buddha, bowed, and sat down to one side. The Buddha said to him:*";
P_HTM[1859]="*“paṭibhantu taṃ, cunda, bojjhaṅgā”ti.**“Cunda, express your understanding of the awakening factors.”*";
P_HTM[1860]="*“Sattime, bhante, bojjhaṅgā bhagavatā sammadakkhātā bhāvitā bahulīkatā abhiññāya sambodhāya nibbānāya saṃvattanti.**“Sir, the Buddha has rightly explained these seven awakening factors. When developed and cultivated, they lead to direct knowledge, to awakening, and to extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[1861]="*Katame satta?**What seven?*";
P_HTM[1862]="*Satisambojjhaṅgo kho, bhante, bhagavatā sammadakkhāto bhāvito bahulīkato abhiññāya sambodhāya nibbānāya saṃvattati … pe … upekkhāsambojjhaṅgo kho, bhante, bhagavatā sammadakkhāto bhāvito bahulīkato abhiññāya sambodhāya nibbānāya saṃvattati.**The awakening factors of mindfulness, investigation of principles, energy, rapture, tranquility, immersion, and equanimity.*";
P_HTM[1863]="*Ime kho, bhante, satta bojjhaṅgā bhagavatā sammadakkhātā bhāvitā bahulīkatā abhiññāya sambodhāya nibbānāya saṃvattantī”ti.**These are the seven awakening factors that the Buddha has rightly explained. When developed and cultivated, they lead to direct knowledge, to awakening, and to extinguishment.”*";
P_HTM[1864]="*“Taggha, cunda, bojjhaṅgā;**“Indeed, Cunda, these are awakening factors!*";
P_HTM[1865]="*taggha, cunda, bojjhaṅgā”ti.**Indeed, Cunda, these are awakening factors!”*";
P_HTM[1866]="*Idamavocāyasmā cundo.**This is what Cunda said,*";
P_HTM[1867]="*Samanuñño satthā ahosi.**and the teacher approved.*";
P_HTM[1868]="*Vuṭṭhahi ca bhagavā tamhā ābādhā.**And that’s how the Buddha recovered from that illness.*";
P_HTM[1869]="*Tathāpahīno ca bhagavato so ābādho ahosīti.* **";
P_HTM[1870]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1871]="*6. Tatiyagilānasuttaṃ**Going to the Far Shore*";
P_HTM[1872]="*“Sattime, bhikkhave, bojjhaṅgā bhāvitā bahulīkatā apārā pāraṃ gamanāya saṃvattanti.**“Mendicants, when these seven awakening factors are developed and cultivated they lead to going from the near shore to the far shore.*";
P_HTM[1873]="*Katame satta?**What seven?*";
P_HTM[1874]="*Satisambojjhaṅgo … pe … upekkhāsambojjhaṅgo—**The awakening factors of mindfulness, investigation of principles, energy, rapture, tranquility, immersion, and equanimity.*";
P_HTM[1875]="*ime kho, bhikkhave, satta bojjhaṅgā bhāvitā bahulīkatā apārā pāraṃ gamanāya saṃvattantīti.**These seven awakening factors, when developed and cultivated, lead to going from the near shore to the far shore.*";
P_HTM[1876]="*Appakā te manussesu,**Few are those among humans*";
P_HTM[1877]="*ye janā pāragāmino;**who cross to the far shore.*";
P_HTM[1878]="*Athāyaṃ itarā pajā,**The rest just run*";
P_HTM[1879]="*tīramevānudhāvati.**around on the near shore.*";
P_HTM[1880]="*Ye ca kho sammadakkhāte,**When the teaching is well explained,*";
P_HTM[1881]="*dhamme dhammānuvattino;**those who practice accordingly*";
P_HTM[1882]="*Te janā pāramessanti,**are the ones who will cross over*";
P_HTM[1883]="*maccudheyyaṃ suduttaraṃ.**Death’s domain so hard to pass.*";
P_HTM[1884]="*Kaṇhaṃ dhammaṃ vippahāya,**Rid of dark qualities,*";
P_HTM[1885]="*sukkaṃ bhāvetha paṇḍito;**an astute person should develop the bright.*";
P_HTM[1886]="*Okā anokamāgamma,**Leaving home behind*";
P_HTM[1887]="*viveke yattha dūramaṃ.**for the seclusion so hard to enjoy,*";
P_HTM[1888]="*Tatrābhiratimiccheyya,**you should try to find delight there,*";
P_HTM[1889]="*hitvā kāme akiñcano;**having left behind sensual pleasures.*";
P_HTM[1890]="*Pariyodapeyya attānaṃ,**With no possessions, an astute person*";
P_HTM[1891]="*cittaklesehi paṇḍito.**should cleanse themselves of mental corruptions.*";
P_HTM[1892]="*Yesaṃ sambodhiyaṅgesu,**And those whose minds are rightly developed*";
P_HTM[1893]="*sammā cittaṃ subhāvitaṃ;**in the awakening factors;*";
P_HTM[1894]="*Ādānappaṭinissagge,**letting go of attachments,*";
P_HTM[1895]="*anupādāya ye ratā;**they delight in not grasping.*";
P_HTM[1896]="*Khīṇāsavā jutimanto,**With defilements ended, brilliant,*";
P_HTM[1897]="*te loke parinibbutā”ti.**they are extinguished in this world.”*";
P_HTM[1898]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1899]="*7. Pāraṅgamasuttaṃ**Missed Out*";
P_HTM[1900]="*“Yesaṃ kesañci, bhikkhave, satta bojjhaṅgā viraddhā, viraddho tesaṃ ariyo maggo sammā dukkhakkhayagāmī.**“Mendicants, whoever has missed out on the seven awakening factors has missed out on the noble path to the complete ending of suffering.*";
P_HTM[1901]="*Yesaṃ kesañci, bhikkhave, satta bojjhaṅgā āraddhā, āraddho tesaṃ ariyo maggo sammā dukkhakkhayagāmī.**Whoever has undertaken the seven awakening factors has undertaken the noble path to the complete ending of suffering.*";
P_HTM[1902]="*Katame satta?**What seven?*";
P_HTM[1903]="*Satisambojjhaṅgo … pe … upekkhāsambojjhaṅgo—**The awakening factors of mindfulness, investigation of principles, energy, rapture, tranquility, immersion, and equanimity.*";
P_HTM[1904]="*yesaṃ kesañci, bhikkhave, ime satta bojjhaṅgā viraddhā, viraddho tesaṃ ariyo maggo sammā dukkhakkhayagāmī.**Whoever has missed out on these seven awakening factors has missed out on the noble path to the complete ending of suffering.*";
P_HTM[1905]="*Yesaṃ kesañci, bhikkhave, ime satta bojjhaṅgā āraddhā, āraddho tesaṃ ariyo maggo sammā dukkhakkhayagāmī”ti.**Whoever has undertaken these seven awakening factors has undertaken the noble path to the complete ending of suffering.”*";
P_HTM[1906]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1907]="*8. Viraddhasuttaṃ**Noble*";
P_HTM[1908]="*“Sattime, bhikkhave, bojjhaṅgā bhāvitā bahulīkatā ariyā niyyānikā nīyanti takkarassa sammā dukkhakkhayāya.**“Mendicants, when these seven awakening factors are developed and cultivated they are noble and emancipating, and bring one who practices them to the complete ending of suffering.*";
P_HTM[1909]="*Katame satta?**What seven?*";
P_HTM[1910]="*Satisambojjhaṅgo … pe … upekkhāsambojjhaṅgo—**The awakening factors of mindfulness, investigation of principles, energy, rapture, tranquility, immersion, and equanimity.*";
P_HTM[1911]="*ime kho, bhikkhave, satta bojjhaṅgā bhāvitā bahulīkatā ariyā niyyānikā nīyanti takkarassa sammā dukkhakkhayāyā”ti.**When these seven awakening factors are developed and cultivated they are noble and emancipating, and bring one who practices them to the complete ending of suffering.”*";
P_HTM[1912]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1913]="*9. Ariyasuttaṃ**Disillusionment*";
P_HTM[1914]="*“Sattime, bhikkhave, bojjhaṅgā bhāvitā bahulīkatā ekantanibbidāya virāgāya nirodhāya upasamāya abhiññāya sambodhāya nibbānāya saṃvattanti.**“Mendicants, the seven awakening factors, when developed and cultivated, lead solely to disillusionment, dispassion, cessation, peace, insight, awakening, and extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[1915]="*Katame satta?**What seven?*";
P_HTM[1916]="*Satisambojjhaṅgo … pe … upekkhāsambojjhaṅgo—**The awakening factors of mindfulness, investigation of principles, energy, rapture, tranquility, immersion, and equanimity.*";
P_HTM[1917]="*ime kho, bhikkhave, satta bojjhaṅgā bhāvitā bahulīkatā ekantanibbidāya virāgāya nirodhāya upasamāya abhiññāya sambodhāya nibbānāya saṃvattantī”ti.**These seven awakening factors, when developed and cultivated, lead solely to disillusionment, dispassion, cessation, peace, insight, awakening, and extinguishment.”*";
P_HTM[1918]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1919]="*Gilānavaggo dutiyo.* **";
P_HTM[1920]="*Pāṇā sūriyūpamā dve,* **";
P_HTM[1921]="*gilānā apare tayo;* **";
P_HTM[1922]="*Pāraṅgāmī viraddho ca,* **";
P_HTM[1923]="*ariyo nibbidāya cāti.* **";
P_HTM[1924]="*10. Nibbidāsuttaṃ**To Awakening*";
P_HTM[1925]="*Atha kho aññataro bhikkhu yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami … pe … ekamantaṃ nisinno kho so bhikkhu bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then a mendicant went up to the Buddha … and said to him:*";
P_HTM[1926]="*“‘Bojjhaṅgā, bojjhaṅgā’ti, bhante, vuccanti.**“Sir, they speak of the ‘awakening factors’.*";
P_HTM[1927]="*Kittāvatā nu kho, bhante, ‘bojjhaṅgā’ti vuccantī”ti?**How are the awakening factors defined?”*";
P_HTM[1928]="*“‘Bodhāya saṃvattantī’ti kho, bhikkhu, tasmā bojjhaṅgāti vuccanti.**“Mendicant, they’re called awakening factors because they lead to awakening.*";
P_HTM[1929]="*Idha, bhikkhu, satisambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ … pe … upekkhāsambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ virāganissitaṃ nirodhanissitaṃ vossaggapariṇāmiṃ.**A mendicant develops the awakening factors of mindfulness, investigation of principles, energy, rapture, tranquility, immersion, and equanimity, which rely on seclusion, fading away, and cessation, and ripen as letting go.*";
P_HTM[1930]="*‘Bodhāya saṃvattantī’ti kho, bhikkhu, tasmā ‘bojjhaṅgā’ti vuccantī”ti.**They’re called awakening factors because they lead to awakening.”*";
P_HTM[1931]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1932]="*12. Esanāvaggo**With Udāyī*";
P_HTM[1933]="*1. Bodhāyasuttaṃ**A Teaching on the Awakening Factors*";
P_HTM[1934]="*“Satta vo, bhikkhave, bojjhaṅge desessāmi;**“Mendicants, I will teach you the seven awakening factors.*";
P_HTM[1935]="*taṃ suṇātha.**Listen …*";
P_HTM[1936]="*Katame ca, bhikkhave, satta bojjhaṅgā?**And what are the seven awakening factors?*";
P_HTM[1937]="*Satisambojjhaṅgo … pe … upekkhāsambojjhaṅgo—**The awakening factors of mindfulness, investigation of principles, energy, rapture, tranquility, immersion, and equanimity.*";
P_HTM[1938]="*ime kho, bhikkhave, satta bojjhaṅgā”ti.**These are the seven awakening factors.”*";
P_HTM[1939]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1940]="*2. Bojjhaṅgadesanāsuttaṃ**Grounds*";
P_HTM[1941]="*“Kāmarāgaṭṭhāniyānaṃ, bhikkhave, dhammānaṃ manasikārabahulīkārā anuppanno ceva kāmacchando uppajjati, uppanno ca kāmacchando bhiyyobhāvāya vepullāya saṃvattati.**“Mendicants, when you frequently attend improperly to things that are grounds for sensual greed, sensual desire arises, and once arisen it increases and grows.*";
P_HTM[1942]="*Byāpādaṭṭhāniyānaṃ, bhikkhave, dhammānaṃ manasikārabahulīkārā anuppanno ceva byāpādo uppajjati, uppanno ca byāpādo bhiyyobhāvāya vepullāya saṃvattati.**When you frequently attend improperly to things that are grounds for ill will, ill will arises, and once arisen it increases and grows.*";
P_HTM[1943]="*Thinamiddhaṭṭhāniyānaṃ, bhikkhave, dhammānaṃ manasikārabahulīkārā anuppannañceva thinamiddhaṃ uppajjati, uppannañca thinamiddhaṃ bhiyyobhāvāya vepullāya saṃvattati.**When you frequently attend improperly to things that are grounds for dullness and drowsiness, dullness and drowsiness arise, and once arisen they increase and grow.*";
P_HTM[1944]="*Uddhaccakukkuccaṭṭhāniyānaṃ, bhikkhave, dhammānaṃ manasikārabahulīkārā anuppannañceva uddhaccakukkuccaṃ uppajjati, uppannañca uddhaccakukkuccaṃ bhiyyobhāvāya vepullāya saṃvattati.**When you frequently attend improperly to things that are grounds for restlessness and remorse, restlessness and remorse arise, and once arisen they increase and grow.*";
P_HTM[1945]="*Vicikicchāṭṭhāniyānaṃ, bhikkhave, dhammānaṃ manasikārabahulīkārā anuppannā ceva vicikicchā uppajjati, uppannā ca vicikicchā bhiyyobhāvāya vepullāya saṃvattati.**When you frequently attend improperly to things that are grounds for doubt, doubt arises, and once arisen it increases and grows.*";
P_HTM[1946]="*Satisambojjhaṅgaṭṭhāniyānaṃ, bhikkhave, dhammānaṃ manasikārabahulīkārā anuppanno ceva satisambojjhaṅgo uppajjati, uppanno ca satisambojjhaṅgo bhāvanāpāripūriṃ gacchati … pe …**When you frequently attend properly on things that are grounds for the awakening factor of mindfulness, the awakening factor of mindfulness arises, and once arisen it’s fully developed. …*";
P_HTM[1947]="*upekkhāsambojjhaṅgaṭṭhāniyānaṃ, bhikkhave, dhammānaṃ manasikārabahulīkārā anuppanno ceva upekkhāsambojjhaṅgo uppajjati, uppanno ca upekkhāsambojjhaṅgo bhāvanāpāripūriṃ gacchatī”ti.**When you frequently attend properly on things that are grounds for the awakening factor of equanimity, the awakening factor of equanimity arises, and once arisen it’s fully developed.”*";
P_HTM[1948]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1949]="*3. Ṭhāniyasuttaṃ**Improper Attention*";
P_HTM[1950]="*“Ayoniso, bhikkhave, manasikaroto anuppanno ceva kāmacchando uppajjati, uppanno ca kāmacchando bhiyyobhāvāya vepullāya saṃvattati;**“Mendicants, when you attend improperly, sensual desire,*";
P_HTM[1951]="*anuppanno ceva byāpādo uppajjati, uppanno ca byāpādo bhiyyobhāvāya vepullāya saṃvattati;**ill will,*";
P_HTM[1952]="*anuppannañceva thinamiddhaṃ uppajjati, uppannañca thinamiddhaṃ bhiyyobhāvāya vepullāya saṃvattati;**dullness and drowsiness,*";
P_HTM[1953]="*anuppannañceva uddhaccakukkuccaṃ uppajjati, uppannañca uddhaccakukkuccaṃ bhiyyobhāvāya vepullāya saṃvattati;**restlessness and remorse,*";
P_HTM[1954]="*anuppannā ceva vicikicchā uppajjati, uppannā ca vicikicchā bhiyyobhāvāya vepullāya saṃvattati;**and doubt arise, and once arisen they increase and grow.*";
P_HTM[1955]="*anuppanno ceva satisambojjhaṅgo nuppajjati, uppanno ca satisambojjhaṅgo nirujjhati … pe … anuppanno ceva upekkhāsambojjhaṅgo nuppajjati, uppanno ca upekkhāsambojjhaṅgo nirujjhati.**And the awakening factors of mindfulness, investigation of principles, energy, rapture, tranquility, immersion, and equanimity don’t arise, or if they’ve already arisen, they cease.*";
P_HTM[1956]="*Yoniso ca kho, bhikkhave, manasikaroto anuppanno ceva kāmacchando nuppajjati, uppanno ca kāmacchando pahīyati;**When you attend properly, sensual desire,*";
P_HTM[1957]="*anuppanno ceva byāpādo nuppajjati, uppanno ca byāpādo pahīyati;**ill will,*";
P_HTM[1958]="*anuppannañceva thinamiddhaṃ nuppajjati, uppannañca thinamiddhaṃ pahīyati;**dullness and drowsiness,*";
P_HTM[1959]="*anuppannañceva uddhaccakukkuccaṃ nuppajjati, uppannañca uddhaccakukkuccaṃ pahīyati;**restlessness and remorse,*";
P_HTM[1960]="*anuppannā ceva vicikicchā nuppajjati, uppannā ca vicikicchā pahīyati.**and doubt don’t arise, or if they’ve already arisen they’re given up.*";
P_HTM[1961]="*Anuppanno ceva satisambojjhaṅgo uppajjati, uppanno ca satisambojjhaṅgo bhāvanāpāripūriṃ gacchati … pe … anuppanno ceva upekkhāsambojjhaṅgo uppajjati, uppanno ca upekkhāsambojjhaṅgo bhāvanāpāripūriṃ gacchatī”ti.**And the awakening factors of mindfulness, investigation of principles, energy, rapture, tranquility, immersion, and equanimity arise, and once they’ve arisen, they’re fully developed.”*";
P_HTM[1962]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1963]="*4. Ayonisomanasikārasuttaṃ**Non*";
P_HTM[1964]="*“Satta vo, bhikkhave, aparihāniye dhamme desessāmi;**“Mendicants, I will teach you seven principles that guard against decline.*";
P_HTM[1965]="*taṃ suṇātha.**Listen …*";
P_HTM[1966]="*Katame ca, bhikkhave, satta aparihāniyā dhammā?**And what are the seven principles that guard against decline?*";
P_HTM[1967]="*Yadidaṃ—* **";
P_HTM[1968]="*satta bojjhaṅgā.**They are the seven awakening factors.*";
P_HTM[1969]="*Katame satta?**What seven?*";
P_HTM[1970]="*Satisambojjhaṅgo … pe … upekkhāsambojjhaṅgo—**The awakening factors of mindfulness, investigation of principles, energy, rapture, tranquility, immersion, and equanimity.*";
P_HTM[1971]="*ime kho, bhikkhave, satta aparihāniyā dhammā”ti.**These are the seven principles that guard against decline.”*";
P_HTM[1972]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1973]="*5. Aparihāniyasuttaṃ**The Ending of Craving*";
P_HTM[1974]="*“Yo, bhikkhave, maggo yā paṭipadā taṇhakkhayāya saṃvattati, taṃ maggaṃ taṃ paṭipadaṃ bhāvetha.**“Mendicants, you should develop the path and the practice that leads to the ending of craving.*";
P_HTM[1975]="*Katamo ca, bhikkhave, maggo katamā ca paṭipadā taṇhakkhayāya saṃvattati?**And what is the path and the practice that leads to the ending of craving?*";
P_HTM[1976]="*Yadidaṃ—* **";
P_HTM[1977]="*satta bojjhaṅgā.**It is the seven awakening factors.*";
P_HTM[1978]="*Katame satta?**What seven?*";
P_HTM[1979]="*Satisambojjhaṅgo … pe … upekkhāsambojjhaṅgo”ti.**The awakening factors of mindfulness, investigation of principles, energy, rapture, tranquility, immersion, and equanimity.”*";
P_HTM[1980]="*Evaṃ vutte, āyasmā udāyī bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When he said this, Udāyī said to him:*";
P_HTM[1981]="*“kathaṃ bhāvitā nu kho, bhante, satta bojjhaṅgā, kathaṃ bahulīkatā taṇhakkhayāya saṃvattantī”ti?**“Sir, how are the seven awakening factors developed and cultivated so as to lead to the ending of craving?”*";
P_HTM[1982]="*“Idha, udāyi, bhikkhu satisambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ virāganissitaṃ nirodhanissitaṃ vossaggapariṇāmiṃ vipulaṃ mahaggataṃ appamāṇaṃ abyāpajjaṃ.**“Udāyī, it’s when a mendicant develops the awakening factor of mindfulness, which relies on seclusion, fading away, and cessation, and ripens as letting go. And it is abundant, expansive, limitless, and free of ill will.*";
P_HTM[1983]="*Tassa satisambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāvayato vivekanissitaṃ virāganissitaṃ nirodhanissitaṃ vossaggapariṇāmiṃ vipulaṃ mahaggataṃ appamāṇaṃ abyāpajjaṃ taṇhā pahīyati.**As they do so, craving is given up.*";
P_HTM[1984]="*Taṇhāya pahānā kammaṃ pahīyati.**When craving is given up, deeds are given up.*";
P_HTM[1985]="*Kammassa pahānā dukkhaṃ pahīyati … pe …**When deeds are given up, suffering is given up. …*";
P_HTM[1986]="*upekkhāsambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ virāganissitaṃ nirodhanissitaṃ vossaggapariṇāmiṃ vipulaṃ mahaggataṃ appamāṇaṃ abyāpajjaṃ.**A mendicant develops the awakening factor of equanimity, which relies on seclusion, fading away, and cessation, and ripens as letting go. And it is abundant, expansive, limitless, and free of ill will.*";
P_HTM[1987]="*Tassa upekkhāsambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāvayato vivekanissitaṃ virāganissitaṃ nirodhanissitaṃ vossaggapariṇāmiṃ vipulaṃ mahaggataṃ appamāṇaṃ abyāpajjaṃ taṇhā pahīyati**As they do so, craving is given up.*";
P_HTM[1988]="*taṇhāya pahānā kammaṃ pahīyati.**When craving is given up, deeds are given up.*";
P_HTM[1989]="*Kammassa pahānā dukkhaṃ pahīyati.**When deeds are given up, suffering is given up.*";
P_HTM[1990]="*Iti kho, udāyi, taṇhakkhayā kammakkhayo, kammakkhayā dukkhakkhayo”ti.**And so, Udāyī, when craving ends, deeds end; when deeds end suffering ends.”*";
P_HTM[1991]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1992]="*6. Taṇhakkhayasuttaṃ**The Cessation of Craving*";
P_HTM[1993]="*“Yo, bhikkhave, maggo yā paṭipadā taṇhānirodhāya saṃvattati, taṃ maggaṃ taṃ paṭipadaṃ bhāvetha.**“Mendicants, you should develop the path and the practice that leads to the cessation of craving.*";
P_HTM[1994]="*Katamo ca, bhikkhave, maggo katamā ca paṭipadā taṇhānirodhāya saṃvattati?**And what is the path and the practice that leads to the cessation of craving?*";
P_HTM[1995]="*Yadidaṃ—* **";
