P_HTM[2887]="*47. Satipaṭṭhānasaṃyuttaṃ* **";
P_HTM[2888]="*10. Uddhambhāgiyasuttaṃ**In Ambapālī’s Wood*";
P_HTM[2889]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[2890]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā vesāliyaṃ viharati ambapālivane.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Vesālī, in Ambapālī’s Wood.*";
P_HTM[2891]="*Tatra kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**There the Buddha addressed the mendicants,*";
P_HTM[2892]="*“bhikkhavo”ti.**“Mendicants!”*";
P_HTM[2893]="*“Bhadante”ti te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Venerable sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[2894]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[2895]="*“Ekāyanvāyaṃ, bhikkhave, maggo sattānaṃ visuddhiyā sokaparidevānaṃ samatikkamāya dukkhadomanassānaṃ atthaṅgamāya ñāyassa adhigamāya nibbānassa sacchikiriyāya, yadidaṃ—cattāro satipaṭṭhānā.**“Mendicants, the four kinds of mindfulness meditation are the path to convergence. They are in order to purify sentient beings, to get past sorrow and crying, to make an end of pain and sadness, to end the cycle of suffering, and to realize extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[2896]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[2897]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;**It’s when a mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[2898]="*vedanāsu vedanānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;**They meditate observing an aspect of feelings—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[2899]="*citte cittānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;**They meditate observing an aspect of the mind—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[2900]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**They meditate observing an aspect of principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[2901]="*Ekāyanvāyaṃ, bhikkhave, maggo sattānaṃ visuddhiyā sokaparidevānaṃ samatikkamāya dukkhadomanassānaṃ atthaṅgamāya ñāyassa adhigamāya nibbānassa sacchikiriyāya, yadidaṃ—cattāro satipaṭṭhānā”ti.**The four kinds of mindfulness meditation are the path to convergence. They are in order to purify sentient beings, to get past sorrow and crying, to make an end of pain and sadness, to end the cycle of suffering, and to realize extinguishment.”*";
P_HTM[2902]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[2903]="*Attamanā te bhikkhū bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandunti.**Satisfied, the mendicants were happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[2904]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2905]="*Punagaṅgānadīādisuttaṃ**Mindful*";
P_HTM[2906]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā vesāliyaṃ viharati ambapālivane.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Vesālī, in Ambapālī’s Wood.*";
P_HTM[2907]="*Tatra kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**There the Buddha addressed the mendicants,*";
P_HTM[2908]="*“bhikkhavo”ti.**“Mendicants!”*";
P_HTM[2909]="*“Bhadante”ti te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Venerable sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[2910]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[2911]="*“Sato, bhikkhave, bhikkhu vihareyya sampajāno.**“Mendicants, a mendicant should live mindful and aware.*";
P_HTM[2912]="*Ayaṃ vo amhākaṃ anusāsanī.**This is my instruction to you.*";
P_HTM[2913]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sato hoti?**And how is a mendicant mindful?*";
P_HTM[2914]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;**It’s when a mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[2915]="*vedanāsu … pe …**They meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[2916]="*citte … pe …**mind …*";
P_HTM[2917]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[2918]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sato hoti.**That’s how a mendicant is mindful.*";
P_HTM[2919]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sampajāno hoti?**And how is a mendicant aware?*";
P_HTM[2920]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu abhikkante paṭikkante sampajānakārī hoti, ālokite vilokite sampajānakārī hoti, samiñjite pasārite sampajānakārī hoti, saṅghāṭipattacīvaradhāraṇe sampajānakārī hoti, asite pīte khāyite sāyite sampajānakārī hoti, uccārapassāvakamme sampajānakārī hoti, gate ṭhite nisinne sutte jāgarite bhāsite tuṇhībhāve sampajānakārī hoti.**It’s when a mendicant acts with situational awareness when going out and coming back; when looking ahead and aside; when bending and extending the limbs; when bearing the outer robe, bowl and robes; when eating, drinking, chewing, and tasting; when urinating and defecating; when walking, standing, sitting, sleeping, waking, speaking, and keeping silent.*";
P_HTM[2921]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sampajānakārī hoti.**That’s how a mendicant acts with situational awareness.*";
P_HTM[2922]="*Sato, bhikkhave, bhikkhu vihareyya sampajāno.**A mendicant should live mindful and aware.*";
P_HTM[2923]="*Ayaṃ vo amhākaṃ anusāsanī”ti.**This is my instruction to you.”*";
P_HTM[2924]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2925]="*Tathāgatādisuttaṃ**A Monk*";
P_HTM[2926]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati jetavane anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery.*";
P_HTM[2927]="*Atha kho aññataro bhikkhu yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho so bhikkhu bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then a mendicant went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him,*";
P_HTM[2928]="*“sādhu me, bhante, bhagavā saṃkhittena dhammaṃ desetu, yamahaṃ bhagavato dhammaṃ sutvā eko vūpakaṭṭho appamatto ātāpī pahitatto vihareyyan”ti.**“Sir, may the Buddha please teach me Dhamma in brief. When I’ve heard it, I’ll live alone, withdrawn, diligent, keen, and resolute.”*";
P_HTM[2929]="*“Evameva panidhekacce moghapurisā mañceva ajjhesanti, dhamme ca bhāsite mameva anubandhitabbaṃ maññantī”ti.**“This is exactly how some foolish people ask me for something. But when the teaching has been explained they think only of following me around.”*";
P_HTM[2930]="*“Desetu me, bhante, bhagavā saṃkhittena dhammaṃ, desetu sugato saṃkhittena dhammaṃ. Appeva nāmāhaṃ bhagavato bhāsitassa atthaṃ jāneyyaṃ, appeva nāmāhaṃ bhagavato bhāsitassa dāyādo assan”ti.**“Sir, may the Buddha teach me the Dhamma in brief! May the Holy One teach me the Dhamma in brief! Hopefully I can understand the meaning of what the Buddha says! Hopefully I can be an heir of the Buddha’s teaching!”*";
P_HTM[2931]="*“Tasmātiha tvaṃ, bhikkhu, ādimeva visodhehi kusalesu dhammesu.**“Well then, mendicant, you should purify the starting point of skillful qualities.*";
P_HTM[2932]="*Ko cādi kusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ?**What is the starting point of skillful qualities?*";
P_HTM[2933]="*Sīlañca suvisuddhaṃ, diṭṭhi ca ujukā.**Well purified ethics and correct view.*";
P_HTM[2934]="*Yato kho te, bhikkhu, sīlañca suvisuddhaṃ bhavissati diṭṭhi ca ujukā, tato tvaṃ, bhikkhu, sīlaṃ nissāya sīle patiṭṭhāya cattāro satipaṭṭhāne tividhena bhāveyyāsi.**When your ethics are well purified and your view is correct, you should develop the four kinds of mindfulness meditation in three ways, depending on and grounded on ethics.*";
P_HTM[2935]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[2936]="*Idha tvaṃ, bhikkhu, ajjhattaṃ vā kāye kāyānupassī viharāhi ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;**Meditate observing an aspect of the body internally—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[2937]="*bahiddhā vā kāye kāyānupassī viharāhi ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;**Or meditate observing an aspect of the body externally—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[2938]="*ajjhattabahiddhā vā kāye kāyānupassī viharāhi ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**Or meditate observing an aspect of the body internally and externally—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[2939]="*Ajjhattaṃ vā vedanāsu … pe …**Or meditate observing an aspect of feelings internally …*";
P_HTM[2940]="*bahiddhā vā vedanāsu …**externally …*";
P_HTM[2941]="*ajjhattabahiddhā vā vedanāsu vedanānupassī viharāhi ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**internally and externally—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[2942]="*Ajjhattaṃ vā citte …**Or meditate observing an aspect of the mind internally …*";
P_HTM[2943]="*bahiddhā vā citte …**externally …*";
P_HTM[2944]="*ajjhattabahiddhā vā citte cittānupassī viharāhi ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**internally and externally—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[2945]="*Ajjhattaṃ vā dhammesu …**Or meditate observing an aspect of principles internally …*";
P_HTM[2946]="*bahiddhā vā dhammesu …**externally …*";
P_HTM[2947]="*ajjhattabahiddhā vā dhammesu dhammānupassī viharāhi ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**internally and externally—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[2948]="*Yato kho tvaṃ, bhikkhu, sīlaṃ nissāya sīle patiṭṭhāya ime cattāro satipaṭṭhāne evaṃ tividhena bhāvessasi, tato tuyhaṃ, bhikkhu, yā ratti vā divaso vā āgamissati vuddhiyeva pāṭikaṅkhā kusalesu dhammesu, no parihānī”ti.**When you develop the four kinds of mindfulness meditation in these three ways, depending on and grounded on ethics, you can expect growth, not decline, in skillful qualities, whether by day or by night.”*";
P_HTM[2949]="*Atha kho so bhikkhu bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinanditvā anumoditvā uṭṭhāyāsanā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā pakkāmi.**And then that mendicant approved and agreed with what the Buddha said. He got up from his seat, bowed, and respectfully circled the Buddha, keeping him on his right, before leaving.*";
P_HTM[2950]="*Atha kho so bhikkhu eko vūpakaṭṭho appamatto ātāpī pahitatto viharanto nacirasseva—yassatthāya kulaputtā sammadeva agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajanti, tadanuttaraṃ—brahmacariyapariyosānaṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharati.**Then that mendicant, living alone, withdrawn, diligent, keen, and resolute, soon realized the supreme end of the spiritual path in this very life. He lived having achieved with his own insight the goal for which gentlemen rightly go forth from the lay life to homelessness.*";
P_HTM[2951]="*“Khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyā”ti abbhaññāsi.**He understood: “Rebirth is ended; the spiritual journey has been completed; what had to be done has been done; there is no return to any state of existence.”*";
P_HTM[2952]="*Aññataro ca pana so bhikkhu arahataṃ ahosīti.**And that mendicant became one of the perfected.*";
P_HTM[2953]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2954]="*Punabalādisuttaṃ**At Sālā*";
P_HTM[2955]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā kosalesu viharati sālāya brāhmaṇagāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying in the land of the Kosalans near the brahmin village of Sālā.*";
P_HTM[2956]="*Tatra kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi … pe … etadavoca:**There the Buddha addressed the mendicants:*";
P_HTM[2957]="*“Ye te, bhikkhave, bhikkhū navā acirapabbajitā adhunāgatā imaṃ dhammavinayaṃ, te vo, bhikkhave, bhikkhū catunnaṃ satipaṭṭhānānaṃ bhāvanāya samādapetabbā nivesetabbā patiṭṭhāpetabbā.**“Mendicants, those mendicants who are junior—recently gone forth, newly come to this teaching and training—should be encouraged, supported, and established in the four kinds of mindfulness meditation.*";
P_HTM[2958]="*Katamesaṃ catunnaṃ?**What four?*";
P_HTM[2959]="*Etha tumhe, āvuso, kāye kāyānupassino viharatha ātāpino sampajānā ekodibhūtā vippasannacittā samāhitā ekaggacittā, kāyassa yathābhūtaṃ ñāṇāya;**Please, reverends, meditate observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, at one, with minds that are clear, immersed in samādhi, and unified, so as to truly know the body.*";
P_HTM[2960]="*vedanāsu vedanānupassino viharatha ātāpino sampajānā ekodibhūtā vippasannacittā samāhitā ekaggacittā, vedanānaṃ yathābhūtaṃ ñāṇāya;**Meditate observing an aspect of feelings—keen, aware, at one, with minds that are clear, immersed in samādhi, and unified, so as to truly know feelings.*";
P_HTM[2961]="*citte cittānupassino viharatha ātāpino sampajānā ekodibhūtā vippasannacittā samāhitā ekaggacittā, cittassa yathābhūtaṃ ñāṇāya;**Meditate observing an aspect of the mind—keen, aware, at one, with minds that are clear, immersed in samādhi, and unified, so as to truly know the mind.*";
P_HTM[2962]="*dhammesu dhammānupassino viharatha ātāpino sampajānā ekodibhūtā vippasannacittā samāhitā ekaggacittā, dhammānaṃ yathābhūtaṃ ñāṇāya.**Meditate observing an aspect of principles—keen, aware, at one, with minds that are clear, immersed in samādhi, and unified, so as to truly know principles.*";
P_HTM[2963]="*Yepi te, bhikkhave, bhikkhū sekhā appattamānasā anuttaraṃ yogakkhemaṃ patthayamānā viharanti, tepi kāye kāyānupassino viharanti ātāpino sampajānā ekodibhūtā vippasannacittā samāhitā ekaggacittā, kāyassa pariññāya;**Those mendicants who are trainees—who haven’t achieved their heart’s desire, but live aspiring to the supreme sanctuary—also meditate observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, at one, minds that are clear, immersed in samādhi, and unified, so as to fully understand the body.*";
P_HTM[2964]="*vedanāsu vedanānupassino viharanti ātāpino sampajānā ekodibhūtā vippasannacittā samāhitā ekaggacittā, vedanānaṃ pariññāya;**They meditate observing an aspect of feelings—keen, aware, at one, with minds that are clear, immersed in samādhi, and unified, so as to fully understand feelings.*";
P_HTM[2965]="*citte cittānupassino viharanti ātāpino sampajānā ekodibhūtā vippasannacittā samāhitā ekaggacittā, cittassa pariññāya;**They meditate observing an aspect of the mind—keen, aware, at one, with minds that are clear, immersed in samādhi, and unified, so as to fully understand the mind.*";
P_HTM[2966]="*dhammesu dhammānupassino viharanti ātāpino sampajānā ekodibhūtā vippasannacittā samāhitā ekaggacittā, dhammānaṃ pariññāya.**They meditate observing an aspect of principles—keen, aware, at one, with minds that are clear, immersed in samādhi, and unified, so as to fully understand principles.*";
P_HTM[2967]="*Yepi te, bhikkhave, bhikkhū arahanto khīṇāsavā vusitavanto katakaraṇīyā ohitabhārā anuppattasadatthā parikkhīṇabhavasaṃyojanā sammadaññāvimuttā, tepi kāye kāyānupassino viharanti ātāpino sampajānā ekodibhūtā vippasannacittā samāhitā ekaggacittā, kāyena visaṃyuttā;**Those mendicants who are perfected—who have ended the defilements, completed the spiritual journey, done what had to be done, laid down the burden, achieved their own goal, utterly ended the fetters of rebirth, and are rightly freed through enlightenment—also meditate observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, at one, with minds that are clear, immersed in samādhi, and unified, detached from the body.*";
P_HTM[2968]="*vedanāsu vedanānupassino viharanti ātāpino sampajānā ekodibhūtā vippasannacittā samāhitā ekaggacittā, vedanāhi visaṃyuttā;**They meditate observing an aspect of feelings—keen, aware, at one, with minds that are clear, immersed in samādhi, and unified, detached from feelings.*";
P_HTM[2969]="*citte cittānupassino viharanti ātāpino sampajānā ekodibhūtā vippasannacittā samāhitā ekaggacittā, cittena visaṃyuttā;**They meditate observing an aspect of the mind—keen, aware, at one, with minds that are clear, immersed in samādhi, and unified, detached from the mind.*";
P_HTM[2970]="*dhammesu dhammānupassino viharanti ātāpino sampajānā ekodibhūtā vippasannacittā samāhitā ekaggacittā, dhammehi visaṃyuttā.**They meditate observing an aspect of principles—keen, aware, at one, with minds that are clear, immersed in samādhi, and unified, detached from principles.*";
P_HTM[2971]="*Yepi te, bhikkhave, bhikkhū navā acirapabbajitā adhunāgatā imaṃ dhammavinayaṃ, te vo, bhikkhave, bhikkhū imesaṃ catunnaṃ satipaṭṭhānānaṃ bhāvanāya samādapetabbā nivesetabbā patiṭṭhāpetabbā”ti.**Those mendicants who are junior—recently gone forth, newly come to this teaching and training—should be encouraged, supported, and established in these four kinds of mindfulness meditation.”*";
P_HTM[2972]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2973]="*Punaesanādisuttaṃ**A Heap of the Unskillful*";
P_HTM[2974]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[2975]="*Tatra kho bhagavā etadavoca:**There the Buddha said:*";
P_HTM[2976]="*“‘akusalarāsī’ti, bhikkhave, vadamāno pañca nīvaraṇe sammā vadamāno vadeyya.**“Rightly speaking, mendicants, you’d call these five hindrances a ‘heap of the unskillful’.*";
P_HTM[2977]="*Kevalo hāyaṃ, bhikkhave, akusalarāsi, yadidaṃ—pañca nīvaraṇā.**For these five hindrances are entirely a heap of the unskillful.*";
P_HTM[2978]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[2979]="*Kāmacchandanīvaraṇaṃ, byāpādanīvaraṇaṃ, thinamiddhanīvaraṇaṃ, uddhaccakukkuccanīvaraṇaṃ, vicikicchānīvaraṇaṃ.**The hindrances of sensual desire, ill will, dullness and drowsiness, restlessness and remorse, and doubt.*";
P_HTM[2980]="*‘Akusalarāsī’ti, bhikkhave, vadamāno ime pañca nīvaraṇe sammā vadamāno vadeyya.**Rightly speaking, you’d call these five hindrances a ‘heap of the unskillful’.*";
P_HTM[2981]="*Kevalo hāyaṃ, bhikkhave, akusalarāsi, yadidaṃ—pañca nīvaraṇā.**For these five hindrances are entirely a heap of the unskillful.*";
P_HTM[2982]="*‘Kusalarāsī’ti, bhikkhave, vadamāno cattāro satipaṭṭhāne sammā vadamāno vadeyya.**Rightly speaking, you’d call these four kinds of mindfulness meditation a ‘heap of the skillful’.*";
P_HTM[2983]="*Kevalo hāyaṃ, bhikkhave, kusalarāsi, yadidaṃ—cattāro satipaṭṭhānā.**For these four kinds of mindfulness meditation are entirely a heap of the skillful.*";
P_HTM[2984]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[2985]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;**It’s when a mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[2986]="*vedanāsu … pe …**They meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[2987]="*citte … pe …**They meditate observing an aspect of the mind …*";
P_HTM[2988]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**They meditate observing an aspect of principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[2989]="*‘Kusalarāsī’ti, bhikkhave, vadamāno ime cattāro satipaṭṭhāne sammā vadamāno vadeyya.**Rightly speaking, you’d call these four kinds of mindfulness meditation a ‘heap of the skillful’.*";
P_HTM[2990]="*Kevalo hāyaṃ, bhikkhave, kusalarāsi, yadidaṃ—cattāro satipaṭṭhānā”ti.**For these four kinds of mindfulness meditation are entirely a heap of the skillful.”*";
P_HTM[2991]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2992]="*Punaoghādisuttaṃ**A Hawk*";
P_HTM[2993]="*“Bhūtapubbaṃ, bhikkhave, sakuṇagghi lāpaṃ sakuṇaṃ sahasā ajjhappattā aggahesi.**“Once upon a time, mendicants, a hawk suddenly swooped down and grabbed a quail.*";
P_HTM[2994]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, lāpo sakuṇo sakuṇagghiyā hariyamāno evaṃ paridevasi:**And as the quail was being carried off he wailed,*";
P_HTM[2995]="*‘mayamevamha alakkhikā, mayaṃ appapuññā, ye mayaṃ agocare carimha paravisaye.**‘I’m so unlucky, so unfortunate, to have roamed out of my territory into the domain of others.*";
P_HTM[2996]="*Sacejja mayaṃ gocare careyyāma sake pettike visaye, na myāyaṃ, sakuṇagghi, alaṃ abhavissa, yadidaṃ—yuddhāyā’ti.**If today I’d roamed within my own territory, the domain of my fathers, this hawk wouldn’t have been able to beat me by fighting.’*";
P_HTM[2997]="*‘Ko pana te, lāpa, gocaro sako pettiko visayo’ti?**‘So, quail, what is your own territory, the domain of your fathers?’*";
P_HTM[2998]="*‘Yadidaṃ—naṅgalakaṭṭhakaraṇaṃ leḍḍuṭṭhānan’ti.**‘It’s a ploughed field covered with clods of earth.’*";
P_HTM[2999]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, sakuṇagghi sake bale apatthaddhā sake bale asaṃvadamānā lāpaṃ sakuṇaṃ pamuñci:**Confident in her own strength, the hawk was not daunted or intimidated. She released the quail, saying,*";
P_HTM[3000]="*‘gaccha kho tvaṃ, lāpa, tatrapi me gantvā na mokkhasī’ti.**‘Go now, quail. But even there you won’t escape me!’*";
P_HTM[3001]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, lāpo sakuṇo naṅgalakaṭṭhakaraṇaṃ leḍḍuṭṭhānaṃ gantvā mahantaṃ leḍḍuṃ abhiruhitvā sakuṇagghiṃ vadamāno aṭṭhāsi:**Then the quail went to a ploughed field covered with clods of earth. He climbed up a big clod, and standing there, he said to the hawk:*";
P_HTM[3002]="*‘ehi kho dāni me, sakuṇagghi, ehi kho dāni me, sakuṇagghī’ti.**‘Come get me, hawk! Come get me, hawk!’*";
P_HTM[3003]="*Atha kho sā, bhikkhave, sakuṇagghi sake bale apatthaddhā sake bale asaṃvadamānā ubho pakkhe sannayha lāpaṃ sakuṇaṃ sahasā ajjhappattā.**Confident in her own strength, the hawk was not daunted or intimidated. She folded her wings and suddenly swooped down on the quail.*";
P_HTM[3004]="*Yadā kho, bhikkhave, aññāsi lāpo sakuṇo ‘bahuāgato kho myāyaṃ sakuṇagghī’ti, atha tasseva leḍḍussa antaraṃ paccupādi.**When the quail knew that the hawk was nearly there, he slipped under that clod.*";
P_HTM[3005]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, sakuṇagghi tattheva uraṃ paccatāḷesi.**But the hawk crashed chest-first right there.*";
P_HTM[3006]="*Evañhi taṃ, bhikkhave, hoti yo agocare carati paravisaye.**That’s what happens when you roam out of your territory into the domain of others.*";
P_HTM[3007]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, mā agocare carittha paravisaye.**So, mendicants, don’t roam out of your own territory into the domain of others.*";
P_HTM[3008]="*Agocare, bhikkhave, carataṃ paravisaye lacchati māro otāraṃ, lacchati māro ārammaṇaṃ.**If you roam out of your own territory into the domain of others, Māra will find a vulnerability and get hold of you.*";
P_HTM[3009]="*Ko ca, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno agocaro paravisayo?**And what is not a mendicant’s own territory but the domain of others?*";
P_HTM[3010]="*Yadidaṃ—pañca kāmaguṇā.**It’s the five kinds of sensual stimulation.*";
P_HTM[3011]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[3012]="*Cakkhuviññeyyā rūpā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā piyarūpā kāmūpasaṃhitā rajanīyā,**Sights known by the eye that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasant, sensual, and arousing.*";
P_HTM[3013]="*sotaviññeyyā saddā … pe …**Sounds known by the ear …*";
P_HTM[3014]="*ghānaviññeyyā gandhā … pe …**Smells known by the nose …*";
P_HTM[3015]="*jivhāviññeyyā rasā … pe …**Tastes known by the tongue …*";
P_HTM[3016]="*kāyaviññeyyā phoṭṭhabbā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā piyarūpā kāmūpasaṃhitā rajanīyā—**Touches known by the body that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasant, sensual, and arousing.*";
P_HTM[3017]="*ayaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno agocaro paravisayo.**This is not a mendicant’s own territory but the domain of others.*";
P_HTM[3018]="*Gocare, bhikkhave, caratha sake pettike visaye.**You should roam inside your own territory, the domain of your fathers.*";
P_HTM[3019]="*Gocare, bhikkhave, carataṃ sake pettike visaye na lacchati māro otāraṃ, na lacchati māro ārammaṇaṃ.**If you roam inside your own territory, the domain of your fathers, Māra won’t find a vulnerability or get hold of you.*";
P_HTM[3020]="*Ko ca, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno gocaro sako pettiko visayo?**And what is a mendicant’s own territory, the domain of the fathers?*";
P_HTM[3021]="*Yadidaṃ—* **";
P_HTM[3022]="*cattāro satipaṭṭhānā.**It’s the four kinds of mindfulness meditation.*";
P_HTM[3023]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[3024]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;**It’s when a mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3025]="*vedanāsu … pe …**They meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[3026]="*citte … pe …**mind …*";
P_HTM[3027]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ—**principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3028]="*ayaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno gocaro sako pettiko visayo”ti.**This is a mendicant’s own territory, the domain of the fathers.”*";
P_HTM[3029]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3030]="*5. Amatavaggo**In Ambapālī’s Wood*";
P_HTM[3031]="*1. Ambapālisuttaṃ**A Monkey*";
P_HTM[3032]="*“Atthi, bhikkhave, himavato pabbatarājassa duggā visamā desā, yattha neva makkaṭānaṃ cārī na manussānaṃ.**“Mendicants, in the Himalayas there are regions that are rugged and impassable. In some such regions, neither monkeys nor humans can go,*";
P_HTM[3033]="*Atthi, bhikkhave, himavato pabbatarājassa duggā visamā desā, yattha makkaṭānañhi kho cārī, na manussānaṃ.**while in others, monkeys can go but not humans.*";
P_HTM[3034]="*Atthi, bhikkhave, himavato pabbatarājassa samā bhūmibhāgā ramaṇīyā, yattha makkaṭānañceva cārī manussānañca.**There are also level, pleasant places where both monkeys and humans can go.*";
P_HTM[3035]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, luddā makkaṭavīthīsu lepaṃ oḍḍenti makkaṭānaṃ bādhanāya.**There hunters lay snares of tar on the monkey trails to catch the monkeys.*";
P_HTM[3036]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, ye te makkaṭā abālajātikā alolajātikā, te taṃ lepaṃ disvā ārakā parivajjanti.**The monkeys who are not foolhardy and reckless see the tar and avoid it from afar.*";
P_HTM[3037]="*Yo pana so hoti makkaṭo bālajātiko lolajātiko, so taṃ lepaṃ upasaṅkamitvā hatthena gaṇhāti.**But a foolish and reckless monkey goes up to the tar and grabs it with a hand.*";
P_HTM[3038]="*So tattha bajjhati.**He gets stuck there.*";
P_HTM[3039]="*‘Hatthaṃ mocessāmī’ti dutiyena hatthena gaṇhāti.**Thinking to free his hand, he grabs it with his other hand.*";
P_HTM[3040]="*So tattha bajjhati.**He gets stuck there.*";
P_HTM[3041]="*‘Ubho hatthe mocessāmī’ti pādena gaṇhāti.**Thinking to free both hands, he grabs it with a foot.*";
P_HTM[3042]="*So tattha bajjhati.**He gets stuck there.*";
P_HTM[3043]="*‘Ubho hatthe mocessāmi pādañcā’ti dutiyena pādena gaṇhāti.**Thinking to free both hands and foot, he grabs it with his other foot.*";
P_HTM[3044]="*So tattha bajjhati.**He gets stuck there.*";
P_HTM[3045]="*‘Ubho hatthe mocessāmi pāde cā’ti tuṇḍena gaṇhāti.**Thinking to free both hands and feet, he grabs it with his snout.*";
P_HTM[3046]="*So tattha bajjhati.**He gets stuck there.*";
P_HTM[3047]="*Evañhi so, bhikkhave, makkaṭo pañcoḍḍito thunaṃ seti anayaṃ āpanno byasanaṃ āpanno yathākāmakaraṇīyo luddassa.**And so the monkey, trapped at five points, just lies there screeching. He’d meet with tragedy and disaster, and the hunter can do what he wants with him.*";
P_HTM[3048]="*Tamenaṃ, bhikkhave, luddo vijjhitvā tasmiṃyeva kaṭṭhakataṅgāre avassajjetvā yena kāmaṃ pakkamati.**The hunter spears him, pries him off that tarred block of wood, and goes wherever he wants.*";
P_HTM[3049]="*Evaṃ so taṃ, bhikkhave, hoti yo agocare carati paravisaye.**That’s what happens when you roam out of your territory into the domain of others.*";
P_HTM[3050]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, mā agocare carittha paravisaye.**So, mendicants, don’t roam out of your own territory into the domain of others.*";
P_HTM[3051]="*Agocare, bhikkhave, carataṃ paravisaye lacchati māro otāraṃ, lacchati māro ārammaṇaṃ.**If you roam out of your own territory into the domain of others, Māra will catch you and get hold of you.*";
P_HTM[3052]="*Ko ca, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno agocaro paravisayo?**And what is not a mendicant’s own territory but the domain of others?*";
P_HTM[3053]="*Yadidaṃ—* **";
P_HTM[3054]="*pañca kāmaguṇā.**It’s the five kinds of sensual stimulation.*";
P_HTM[3055]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[3056]="*Cakkhuviññeyyā rūpā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā piyarūpā kāmūpasaṃhitā rajanīyā,**Sights known by the eye that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasant, sensual, and arousing.*";
P_HTM[3057]="*sotaviññeyyā saddā … pe …**Sounds known by the ear …*";
P_HTM[3058]="*ghānaviññeyyā gandhā … pe …**Smells known by the nose …*";
P_HTM[3059]="*jivhāviññeyyā rasā … pe …**Tastes known by the tongue …*";
P_HTM[3060]="*kāyaviññeyyā phoṭṭhabbā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā piyarūpā kāmūpasaṃhitā rajanīyā.**Touches known by the body that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasant, sensual, and arousing.*";
P_HTM[3061]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno agocaro paravisayo.**This is not a mendicant’s own territory but the domain of others.*";
P_HTM[3062]="*Gocare, bhikkhave, caratha sake pettike visaye.**You should roam inside your own territory, the domain of your fathers.*";
P_HTM[3063]="*Gocare, bhikkhave, carataṃ sake pettike visaye na lacchati māro otāraṃ, na lacchati māro ārammaṇaṃ.**If you roam inside your own territory, the domain of your fathers, Māra won’t catch you or get hold of you.*";
P_HTM[3064]="*Ko ca, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno gocaro sako pettiko visayo?**And what is a mendicant’s own territory, the domain of the fathers?*";
P_HTM[3065]="*Yadidaṃ—* **";
P_HTM[3066]="*cattāro satipaṭṭhānā.**It’s the four kinds of mindfulness meditation.*";
P_HTM[3067]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[3068]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;**It’s when a mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3069]="*vedanāsu … pe …**They meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[3070]="*citte … pe …**mind …*";
P_HTM[3071]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3072]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno gocaro sako pettiko visayo”ti.**This is a mendicant’s own territory, the domain of the fathers.”*";
P_HTM[3073]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3074]="*2. Satisuttaṃ**Cooks*";
P_HTM[3075]="*“Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, bālo abyatto akusalo sūdo rājānaṃ vā rājamahāmattaṃ vā nānaccayehi sūpehi paccupaṭṭhito assa—**“Mendicants, suppose a foolish, incompetent, unskillful cook was to serve a ruler or their minister with an excessive variety of curries:*";
P_HTM[3076]="*ambilaggehipi, tittakaggehipi, kaṭukaggehipi, madhuraggehipi, khārikehipi, akhārikehipi, loṇikehipi, aloṇikehipi.**superbly sour, bitter, pungent, and sweet; hot and mild, and salty and bland.*";
P_HTM[3077]="*Sa kho so, bhikkhave, bālo abyatto akusalo sūdo sakassa bhattu nimittaṃ na uggaṇhāti:**But that cook didn’t take their master’s hint:*";
P_HTM[3078]="*‘idaṃ vā me ajja bhattu sūpeyyaṃ ruccati, imassa vā abhiharati, imassa vā bahuṃ gaṇhāti, imassa vā vaṇṇaṃ bhāsati.**‘Today my master preferred this sauce, or he reached for it, or he took a lot of it, or he praised it.*";
P_HTM[3079]="*Ambilaggaṃ vā me ajja bhattu sūpeyyaṃ ruccati, ambilaggassa vā abhiharati, ambilaggassa vā bahuṃ gaṇhāti, ambilaggassa vā vaṇṇaṃ bhāsati. Tittakaggaṃ vā me ajja … kaṭukaggaṃ vā me ajja … madhuraggaṃ vā me ajja … khārikaṃ vā me ajja … akhārikaṃ vā me ajja … loṇikaṃ vā me ajja … aloṇikaṃ vā me ajja bhattu sūpeyyaṃ ruccati, aloṇikassa vā abhiharati, aloṇikassa vā bahuṃ gaṇhāti, aloṇikassa vā vaṇṇaṃ bhāsatī’ti.**Today my master preferred the sour or bitter or pungent or sweet or hot or mild or salty sauce. Or he preferred the bland sauce, or he reached for the bland one, or he took a lot of it, or he praised it.’*";
P_HTM[3080]="*Sa kho so, bhikkhave, bālo abyatto akusalo sūdo na ceva lābhī hoti acchādanassa, na lābhī vetanassa, na lābhī abhihārānaṃ.**That foolish, incompetent, unskillful cook doesn’t get presented with clothes, wages, or bonuses.*";
P_HTM[3081]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[3082]="*Tathā hi so, bhikkhave, bālo abyatto akusalo sūdo sakassa bhattu nimittaṃ na uggaṇhāti.**Because they don’t take their master’s hint.*";
P_HTM[3083]="*Evameva kho, bhikkhave, idhekacco bālo abyatto akusalo bhikkhu kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**In the same way, a foolish, incompetent, unskillful mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3084]="*Tassa kāye kāyānupassino viharato cittaṃ na samādhiyati, upakkilesā na pahīyanti.**As they meditate observing an aspect of the body, their mind doesn’t enter immersion, and their corruptions aren’t given up.*";
P_HTM[3085]="*So taṃ nimittaṃ na uggaṇhāti.**But they don’t take the hint.*";
P_HTM[3086]="*Vedanāsu vedanānupassī viharati … pe …**They meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[3087]="*citte cittānupassī viharati … pe …**mind …*";
P_HTM[3088]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3089]="*Tassa dhammesu dhammānupassino viharato cittaṃ na samādhiyati, upakkilesā na pahīyanti.**As they meditate observing an aspect of principles, the mind doesn’t enter immersion, and the corruptions aren’t given up.*";
P_HTM[3090]="*So taṃ nimittaṃ na uggaṇhāti.**But they don’t take the hint.*";
P_HTM[3091]="*Sa kho so, bhikkhave, bālo abyatto akusalo bhikkhu na ceva lābhī hoti diṭṭheva dhamme sukhavihārānaṃ, na lābhī satisampajaññassa.**That foolish, incompetent, unskillful mendicant doesn’t get blissful meditations in this very life, nor do they get mindfulness and situational awareness.*";
P_HTM[3092]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[3093]="*Tathā hi so, bhikkhave, bālo abyatto akusalo bhikkhu sakassa cittassa nimittaṃ na uggaṇhāti.**Because they don’t take their mind’s hint.*";
P_HTM[3094]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, paṇḍito byatto kusalo sūdo rājānaṃ vā rājamahāmattaṃ vā nānaccayehi sūpehi paccupaṭṭhito assa—**Suppose an astute, competent, skillful cook was to serve a ruler or their minister with an excessive variety of curries:*";
P_HTM[3095]="*ambilaggehipi, tittakaggehipi, kaṭukaggehipi, madhuraggehipi, khārikehipi, akhārikehipi, loṇikehipi, aloṇikehipi.**superbly sour, bitter, pungent, and sweet; hot and mild, and salty and bland.*";
P_HTM[3096]="*Sa kho so, bhikkhave, paṇḍito byatto kusalo sūdo sakassa bhattu nimittaṃ uggaṇhāti:**And that cook took their master’s hint:*";
P_HTM[3097]="*‘idaṃ vā me ajja bhattu sūpeyyaṃ ruccati, imassa vā abhiharati, imassa vā bahuṃ gaṇhāti, imassa vā vaṇṇaṃ bhāsati.**‘Today my master preferred this sauce, or he reached for it, or he took a lot of it, or he praised it.*";
P_HTM[3098]="*Ambilaggaṃ vā me ajja bhattu sūpeyyaṃ ruccati, ambilaggassa vā abhiharati, ambilaggassa vā bahuṃ gaṇhāti, ambilaggassa vā vaṇṇaṃ bhāsati. Tittakaggaṃ vā me ajja … kaṭukaggaṃ vā me ajja … madhuraggaṃ vā me ajja … khārikaṃ vā me ajja … akhārikaṃ vā me ajja … loṇikaṃ vā me ajja … aloṇikaṃ vā me ajja bhattu sūpeyyaṃ ruccati, aloṇikassa vā abhiharati, aloṇikassa vā bahuṃ gaṇhāti, aloṇikassa vā vaṇṇaṃ bhāsatī’ti.**Today my master preferred the sour or bitter or pungent or sweet or hot or mild or salty sauce. Or he preferred the bland sauce, or he reached for the bland one, or he took a lot of it, or he praised it.’*";
P_HTM[3099]="*Sa kho so, bhikkhave, paṇḍito byatto kusalo sūdo lābhī ceva hoti acchādanassa, lābhī vetanassa, lābhī abhihārānaṃ.**That astute, competent, skillful cook gets presented with clothes, wages, and bonuses.*";
P_HTM[3100]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[3101]="*Tathā hi so, bhikkhave, paṇḍito byatto kusalo sūdo sakassa bhattu nimittaṃ uggaṇhāti.**Because they take their master’s hint.*";
P_HTM[3102]="*Evameva kho, bhikkhave, idhekacco paṇḍito byatto kusalo bhikkhu kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**In the same way, an astute, competent, skillful mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3103]="*Tassa kāye kāyānupassino viharato cittaṃ samādhiyati, upakkilesā pahīyanti.**As they meditate observing an aspect of the body, their mind enters immersion, and their corruptions are given up.*";
P_HTM[3104]="*So taṃ nimittaṃ uggaṇhāti.**They take the hint.*";
P_HTM[3105]="*Vedanāsu vedanānupassī viharati … pe …**They meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[3106]="*citte cittānupassī viharati … pe …**mind …*";
P_HTM[3107]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3108]="*Tassa dhammesu dhammānupassino viharato cittaṃ samādhiyati, upakkilesā pahīyanti.**As they meditate observing an aspect of principles, their mind enters immersion, and their corruptions are given up.*";
P_HTM[3109]="*So taṃ nimittaṃ uggaṇhāti.**They take the hint.*";
P_HTM[3110]="*Sa kho so, bhikkhave, paṇḍito byatto kusalo bhikkhu lābhī ceva hoti diṭṭheva dhamme sukhavihārānaṃ, lābhī hoti satisampajaññassa.**That astute, competent, skillful mendicant gets blissful meditations in this very life, and they get mindfulness and situational awareness.*";
P_HTM[3111]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[3112]="*Tathā hi so, bhikkhave, paṇḍito byatto kusalo bhikkhu sakassa cittassa nimittaṃ uggaṇhātī”ti.**Because they take their mind’s hint.”*";
P_HTM[3113]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3114]="*3. Bhikkhusuttaṃ**Sick*";
P_HTM[3115]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[3116]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā vesāliyaṃ viharati veḷuvagāmake.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Vesālī, at the little village of Beluva.*";
P_HTM[3117]="*Tatra kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**There the Buddha addressed the mendicants:*";
P_HTM[3118]="*“etha tumhe, bhikkhave, samantā vesāliyā yathāmittaṃ yathāsandiṭṭhaṃ yathāsambhattaṃ vassaṃ upetha.**“Mendicants, please enter the rainy season residence with whatever friends or acquaintances you have around Vesālī.*";
P_HTM[3119]="*Idhevāhaṃ veḷuvagāmake vassaṃ upagacchāmī”ti.**I’ll commence the rainy season residence right here in the little village of Beluva.”*";
P_HTM[3120]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho te bhikkhū bhagavato paṭissutvā samantā vesāliyā yathāmittaṃ yathāsandiṭṭhaṃ yathāsambhattaṃ vassaṃ upagacchuṃ.**“Yes, sir,” those mendicants replied. They did as the Buddha said,*";
P_HTM[3121]="*Bhagavā pana tattheva veḷuvagāmake vassaṃ upagacchi.**while the Buddha commenced the rainy season residence right there in the little village of Beluva.*";
P_HTM[3122]="*Atha kho bhagavato vassūpagatassa kharo ābādho uppajji, bāḷhā vedanā vattanti māraṇantikā.**After the Buddha had commenced the rainy season residence, he fell severely ill, struck by dreadful pains, close to death.*";
P_HTM[3123]="*Tatra sudaṃ bhagavā sato sampajāno adhivāsesi avihaññamāno.**But he endured with mindfulness and situational awareness, without worrying.*";
P_HTM[3124]="*Atha kho bhagavato etadahosi:**Then it occurred to the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[3125]="*“na kho me taṃ patirūpaṃ, yohaṃ anāmantetvā upaṭṭhāke anapaloketvā bhikkhusaṃghaṃ parinibbāyeyyaṃ.**“It would not be appropriate for me to become fully extinguished before informing my attendants and taking leave of the mendicant Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[3126]="*Yannūnāhaṃ imaṃ ābādhaṃ vīriyena paṭipaṇāmetvā jīvitasaṅkhāraṃ adhiṭṭhāya vihareyyan”ti.**Why don’t I forcefully suppress this illness, stabilize the life force, and live on?”*";
P_HTM[3127]="*Atha kho bhagavā taṃ ābādhaṃ vīriyena paṭipaṇāmetvā jīvitasaṅkhāraṃ adhiṭṭhāya vihāsi.**So that is what he did.*";
P_HTM[3128]="*Atha kho bhagavato so ābādho paṭippassambhi.**Then the Buddha’s illness died down.*";
P_HTM[3129]="*Atha kho bhagavā gilānā vuṭṭhito aciravuṭṭhito gelaññā vihārā nikkhamitvā vihārapacchāyāyaṃ paññatte āsane nisīdi.**Soon after the Buddha had recovered from that sickness, he left his dwelling and sat in the shade of the porch on the seat spread out.*";
P_HTM[3130]="*Atha kho āyasmā ānando yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā ānando bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Venerable Ānanda went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him:*";
P_HTM[3131]="*“diṭṭho me, bhante, bhagavato phāsu;**“Sir, it’s fantastic that the Buddha is comfortable,*";
P_HTM[3132]="*diṭṭhaṃ, bhante, bhagavato khamanīyaṃ;**that he’s well,*";
P_HTM[3133]="*diṭṭhaṃ, bhante, bhagavato yāpanīyaṃ.**and that he’s alright.*";
P_HTM[3134]="*Api ca me, bhante, madhurakajāto viya kāyo, disāpi me na pakkhāyanti, dhammāpi maṃ nappaṭibhanti bhagavato gelaññena.**Because when the Buddha was sick, my body felt like it was drugged. I was disorientated, and the teachings didn’t spring to mind.*";
P_HTM[3135]="*Api ca me, bhante, ahosi kācideva assāsamattā:**Still, at least I was consoled by the thought that*";
P_HTM[3136]="*‘na tāva bhagavā parinibbāyissati, na yāva bhagavā bhikkhusaṃghaṃ ārabbha kiñcideva udāharatī’”ti.**the Buddha won’t become fully extinguished without making some statement regarding the Saṅgha of mendicants.”*";
P_HTM[3137]="*“Kiṃ pana dāni, ānanda, bhikkhusaṃgho mayi paccāsīsati?**“But what could the mendicant Saṅgha expect from me now, Ānanda?*";
P_HTM[3138]="*Desito, ānanda, mayā dhammo anantaraṃ abāhiraṃ karitvā.**I’ve taught the Dhamma without making any distinction between secret and public teachings.*";
P_HTM[3139]="*Natthānanda, tathāgatassa dhammesu ācariyamuṭṭhi.**The Realized One doesn’t have the closed fist of a teacher when it comes to the teachings.*";
P_HTM[3140]="*Yassa nūna, ānanda, evamassa:**If there’s anyone who thinks:*";
P_HTM[3141]="*‘ahaṃ bhikkhusaṃghaṃ pariharissāmī’ti vā, ‘mamuddesiko bhikkhusaṃgho’ti vā, so nūna, ānanda, bhikkhusaṃghaṃ ārabbha kiñcideva udāhareyya.**‘I’ll take charge of the Saṅgha of mendicants,’ or ‘the Saṅgha of mendicants is meant for me,’ let them make a statement regarding the Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[3142]="*Tathāgatassa kho, ānanda, na evaṃ hoti:**But the Realized One doesn’t think like this,*";
P_HTM[3143]="*‘ahaṃ bhikkhusaṃghaṃ pariharissāmī’ti vā, ‘mamuddesiko bhikkhusaṃgho’ti vā.* **";
P_HTM[3144]="*Sa kiṃ, ānanda, tathāgato bhikkhusaṃghaṃ ārabbha kiñcideva udāharissati.**so why should he make some statement regarding the Saṅgha?*";
P_HTM[3145]="*Etarahi kho panāhaṃ, ānanda, jiṇṇo vuddho mahallako addhagato vayoanuppatto.**I’m now old, elderly and senior. I’m advanced in years and have reached the final stage of life.*";
P_HTM[3146]="*Āsītiko me vayo vattati.**I’m currently eighty years old.*";
P_HTM[3147]="*Seyyathāpi, ānanda, jajjarasakaṭaṃ veḷamissakena yāpeti;**Just as a decrepit cart keeps going by relying on straps,*";
P_HTM[3148]="*evameva kho, ānanda, veḷamissakena maññe tathāgatassa kāyo yāpeti.**in the same way, the Realized One’s body keeps going by relying on straps, or so you’d think.*";
P_HTM[3149]="*Yasmiṃ, ānanda, samaye tathāgato sabbanimittānaṃ amanasikārā ekaccānaṃ vedanānaṃ nirodhā animittaṃ cetosamādhiṃ upasampajja viharati, phāsutaro, ānanda, tasmiṃ samaye tathāgatassa kāyo hoti.**Sometimes the Realized One, not focusing on any signs, and with the cessation of certain feelings, enters and remains in the signless immersion of the heart. Only then does the Realized One’s body become more comfortable.*";
P_HTM[3150]="*Tasmātihānanda, attadīpā viharatha attasaraṇā anaññasaraṇā, dhammadīpā dhammasaraṇā anaññasaraṇā.**So Ānanda, be your own island, your own refuge, with no other refuge. Let the teaching be your island and your refuge, with no other refuge.*";
P_HTM[3151]="*Kathañcānanda, bhikkhu attadīpo viharati attasaraṇo anaññasaraṇo, dhammadīpo dhammasaraṇo anaññasaraṇo?**And how does a mendicant do this?*";
P_HTM[3152]="*Idhānanda, bhikkhu kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;**It’s when a mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3153]="*vedanāsu … pe …**They meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[3154]="*citte … pe …**mind …*";
P_HTM[3155]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3156]="*Evaṃ kho, ānanda, bhikkhu attadīpo viharati attasaraṇo anaññasaraṇo, dhammadīpo dhammasaraṇo anaññasaraṇo.**That’s how a mendicant is their own island, their own refuge, with no other refuge. That’s how the teaching is their island and their refuge, with no other refuge.*";
P_HTM[3157]="*Ye hi keci, ānanda, etarahi vā mamaccaye vā attadīpā viharissanti attasaraṇā anaññasaraṇā, dhammadīpā dhammasaraṇā anaññasaraṇā; tamatagge mete, ānanda, bhikkhū bhavissanti ye keci sikkhākāmā”ti.**Whether now or after I have passed, any who shall live as their own island, their own refuge, with no other refuge; with the teaching as their island and their refuge, with no other refuge—those mendicants of mine who want to train shall be among the best of the best.”*";
P_HTM[3158]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3159]="*4. Sālasuttaṃ**The Nuns’ Quarters*";
P_HTM[3160]="*Atha kho āyasmā ānando pubbaṇhasamayaṃ nivāsetvā pattacīvaramādāya yena aññataro bhikkhunupassayo tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā paññatte āsane nisīdi.**Then Venerable Ānanda robed up in the morning and, taking his bowl and robe, went to the nuns’ quarters, and sat down on the seat spread out.*";
P_HTM[3161]="*Atha kho sambahulā bhikkhuniyo yenāyasmā ānando tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu. Ekamantaṃ nisinnā kho tā bhikkhuniyo āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ etadavocuṃ:**Then several nuns went up to Venerable Ānanda bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him:*";
P_HTM[3162]="*“Idha, bhante ānanda, sambahulā bhikkhuniyo catūsu satipaṭṭhānesu suppatiṭṭhitacittā viharantiyo uḷāraṃ pubbenāparaṃ visesaṃ sañjānantī”ti.**“Sir, Ānanda, several nuns meditate with their minds firmly established in the four kinds of mindfulness meditation. They have realized a higher distinction than they had before.”*";
P_HTM[3163]="*“Evametaṃ, bhaginiyo, evametaṃ, bhaginiyo.**“That’s how it is, sisters! That’s how it is, sisters!*";
P_HTM[3164]="*Yo hi koci, bhaginiyo, bhikkhu vā bhikkhunī vā catūsu satipaṭṭhānesu suppatiṭṭhitacitto viharati, tassetaṃ pāṭikaṅkhaṃ:**Any monk or nun who meditates with their mind firmly established in the four kinds of mindfulness meditation can expect to*";
P_HTM[3165]="*‘uḷāraṃ pubbenāparaṃ visesaṃ sañjānissatī’”ti.**realize a higher distinction than they had before.”*";
P_HTM[3166]="*Atha kho āyasmā ānando tā bhikkhuniyo dhammiyā kathāya sandassetvā samādapetvā samuttejetvā sampahaṃsetvā uṭṭhāyāsanā pakkāmi.**Then Ānanda educated, encouraged, fired up, and inspired those nuns with a Dhamma talk, after which he got up from his seat and left.*";
P_HTM[3167]="*Atha kho āyasmā ānando sāvatthiyaṃ piṇḍāya caritvā pacchābhattaṃ piṇḍapātapaṭikkanto yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā ānando bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Ānanda wandered for alms in Sāvatthī. After the meal, on his return from alms-round, he went to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and told him what had happened.*";
P_HTM[3168]="*“Idhāhaṃ, bhante, pubbaṇhasamayaṃ nivāsetvā pattacīvaramādāya yena aññataro bhikkhunupassayo tenupasaṅkamiṃ; upasaṅkamitvā paññatte āsane nisīdiṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3169]="*Atha kho, bhante, sambahulā bhikkhuniyo yenāhaṃ tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā maṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu. Ekamantaṃ nisinnā kho, bhante, tā bhikkhuniyo maṃ etadavocuṃ:* **";
P_HTM[3170]="*‘idha, bhante ānanda, sambahulā bhikkhuniyo catūsu satipaṭṭhānesu suppatiṭṭhitacittā viharantiyo uḷāraṃ pubbenāparaṃ visesaṃ sañjānantī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3171]="*Evaṃ vuttāhaṃ, bhante, tā bhikkhuniyo etadavocaṃ:* **";
P_HTM[3172]="*‘evametaṃ, bhaginiyo, evametaṃ, bhaginiyo.* **";
P_HTM[3173]="*Yo hi koci, bhaginiyo, bhikkhu vā bhikkhunī vā catūsu satipaṭṭhānesu suppatiṭṭhitacitto viharati, tassetaṃ pāṭikaṅkhaṃ—uḷāraṃ pubbenāparaṃ visesaṃ sañjānissatī’”ti.* **";
P_HTM[3174]="*“Evametaṃ, ānanda, evametaṃ, ānanda.**“That’s so true, Ānanda! That’s so true!*";
P_HTM[3175]="*Yo hi koci, ānanda, bhikkhu vā bhikkhunī vā catūsu satipaṭṭhānesu suppatiṭṭhitacitto viharati, tassetaṃ pāṭikaṅkhaṃ:**Any monk or nun who meditates with their mind firmly established in the four kinds of mindfulness meditation can expect to*";
P_HTM[3176]="*‘uḷāraṃ pubbenāparaṃ visesaṃ sañjānissati’.**realize a higher distinction than they had before.*";
P_HTM[3177]="*Katamesu catūsu?**What four?*";
P_HTM[3178]="*Idhānanda, bhikkhu kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**It’s when a mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3179]="*Tassa kāye kāyānupassino viharato kāyārammaṇo vā uppajjati kāyasmiṃ pariḷāho, cetaso vā līnattaṃ, bahiddhā vā cittaṃ vikkhipati.**As they meditate observing an aspect of the body, based on the body there arises physical tension, or mental sluggishness, or the mind is externally scattered.*";
P_HTM[3180]="*Tenānanda, bhikkhunā kismiñcideva pasādanīye nimitte cittaṃ paṇidahitabbaṃ.**That mendicant should direct their mind towards an inspiring foundation.*";
P_HTM[3181]="*Tassa kismiñcideva pasādanīye nimitte cittaṃ paṇidahato pāmojjaṃ jāyati.**As they do so, joy springs up.*";
P_HTM[3182]="*Pamuditassa pīti jāyati.**Being joyful, rapture springs up.*";
P_HTM[3183]="*Pītimanassa kāyo passambhati.**When the mind is full of rapture, the body becomes tranquil.*";
P_HTM[3184]="*Passaddhakāyo sukhaṃ vedayati.**When the body is tranquil, one feels bliss.*";
P_HTM[3185]="*Sukhino cittaṃ samādhiyati.**And when blissful, the mind becomes immersed in samādhi.*";
P_HTM[3186]="*So iti paṭisañcikkhati:**Then they reflect:*";
P_HTM[3187]="*‘yassa khvāhaṃ atthāya cittaṃ paṇidahiṃ, so me attho abhinipphanno.**‘I have accomplished the goal for which I directed my mind.*";
P_HTM[3188]="*Handa dāni paṭisaṃharāmī’ti.**Let me now pull back.’*";
P_HTM[3189]="*So paṭisaṃharati ceva na ca vitakketi na ca vicāreti.**They pull back, and neither place the mind nor keep it connected.*";
P_HTM[3190]="*‘Avitakkomhi avicāro, ajjhattaṃ satimā sukhamasmī’ti pajānāti.**They understand: ‘I’m neither placing the mind nor keeping it connected. Mindful within myself, I’m happy.’*";
P_HTM[3191]="*Puna caparaṃ, ānanda, bhikkhu vedanāsu … pe …**Furthermore, a mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[3192]="*citte … pe …**mind …*";
P_HTM[3193]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3194]="*Tassa dhammesu dhammānupassino viharato dhammārammaṇo vā uppajjati kāyasmiṃ pariḷāho, cetaso vā līnattaṃ, bahiddhā vā cittaṃ vikkhipati.**As they meditate observing an aspect of principles, based on principles there arises physical tension, or mental sluggishness, or the mind is externally scattered.*";
P_HTM[3195]="*Tenānanda, bhikkhunā kismiñcideva pasādanīye nimitte cittaṃ paṇidahitabbaṃ.**That mendicant should direct their mind towards an inspiring foundation.*";
P_HTM[3196]="*Tassa kismiñcideva pasādanīye nimitte cittaṃ paṇidahato pāmojjaṃ jāyati.**As they do so, joy springs up.*";
P_HTM[3197]="*Pamuditassa pīti jāyati.**Being joyful, rapture springs up.*";
P_HTM[3198]="*Pītimanassa kāyo passambhati.**When the mind is full of rapture, the body becomes tranquil.*";
P_HTM[3199]="*Passaddhakāyo sukhaṃ vedayati.**When the body is tranquil, one feels bliss.*";
P_HTM[3200]="*Sukhino cittaṃ samādhiyati.**And when blissful, the mind becomes immersed in samādhi.*";
P_HTM[3201]="*So iti paṭisañcikkhati:**Then they reflect:*";
P_HTM[3202]="*‘yassa khvāhaṃ atthāya cittaṃ paṇidahiṃ, so me attho abhinipphanno.**‘I have accomplished the goal for which I directed my mind.*";
P_HTM[3203]="*Handa dāni paṭisaṃharāmī’ti.**Let me now pull back.’*";
P_HTM[3204]="*So paṭisaṃharati ceva na ca vitakketi na ca vicāreti.**They pull back, and neither place the mind nor keep it connected.*";
P_HTM[3205]="*‘Avitakkomhi avicāro, ajjhattaṃ satimā sukhamasmī’ti pajānāti.**They understand: ‘I’m neither placing the mind nor keeping it connected. Mindful within myself, I’m happy.’*";
P_HTM[3206]="*Evaṃ kho, ānanda, paṇidhāya bhāvanā hoti.**That’s how there is directed development.*";
P_HTM[3207]="*Kathañcānanda, appaṇidhāya bhāvanā hoti?**And how is there undirected development?*";
P_HTM[3208]="*Bahiddhā, ānanda, bhikkhu cittaṃ appaṇidhāya ‘appaṇihitaṃ me bahiddhā cittan’ti pajānāti.**Not directing their mind externally, a mendicant understands: ‘My mind is not directed externally.’*";
P_HTM[3209]="*Atha pacchāpure ‘asaṅkhittaṃ vimuttaṃ appaṇihitan’ti pajānāti.**And they understand: ‘Over a period of time it’s unconstricted, freed, and undirected.’*";
P_HTM[3210]="*Atha ca pana ‘kāye kāyānupassī viharāmi ātāpī sampajāno satimā sukhamasmī’ti pajānāti.**And they also understand: ‘I meditate observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, mindful; I am happy.’*";
P_HTM[3211]="*Bahiddhā, ānanda, bhikkhu cittaṃ appaṇidhāya ‘appaṇihitaṃ me bahiddhā cittan’ti pajānāti.**Not directing their mind externally, a mendicant understands: ‘My mind is not directed externally.’*";
P_HTM[3212]="*Atha pacchāpure ‘asaṅkhittaṃ vimuttaṃ appaṇihitan’ti pajānāti.**And they understand: ‘Over a period of time it’s unconstricted, freed, and undirected.’*";
P_HTM[3213]="*Atha ca pana ‘vedanāsu vedanānupassī viharāmi ātāpī sampajāno satimā sukhamasmī’ti pajānāti.**And they also understand: ‘I meditate observing an aspect of feelings—keen, aware, mindful; I am happy.’*";
P_HTM[3214]="*Bahiddhā, ānanda, bhikkhu cittaṃ appaṇidhāya ‘appaṇihitaṃ me bahiddhā cittan’ti pajānāti.**Not directing their mind externally, a mendicant understands: ‘My mind is not directed externally.’*";
P_HTM[3215]="*Atha pacchāpure ‘asaṅkhittaṃ vimuttaṃ appaṇihitan’ti pajānāti.**And they understand: ‘Over a period of time it’s unconstricted, freed, and undirected.’*";
P_HTM[3216]="*Atha ca pana ‘citte cittānupassī viharāmi ātāpī sampajāno satimā sukhamasmī’ti pajānāti.**And they also understand: ‘I meditate observing an aspect of the mind—keen, aware, mindful; I am happy.’*";
P_HTM[3217]="*Bahiddhā, ānanda, bhikkhu cittaṃ appaṇidhāya ‘appaṇihitaṃ me bahiddhā cittan’ti pajānāti.**Not directing their mind externally, a mendicant understands: ‘My mind is not directed externally.’*";
P_HTM[3218]="*Atha pacchāpure ‘asaṅkhittaṃ vimuttaṃ appaṇihitan’ti pajānāti.**And they understand: ‘Over a period of time it’s unconstricted, freed, and undirected.’*";
P_HTM[3219]="*Atha ca pana ‘dhammesu dhammānupassī viharāmi ātāpī sampajāno satimā sukhamasmī’ti pajānāti.**And they also understand: ‘I meditate observing an aspect of principles—keen, aware, mindful; I am happy.’*";
P_HTM[3220]="*Evaṃ kho, ānanda, appaṇidhāya bhāvanā hoti.**That’s how there is undirected development.*";
P_HTM[3221]="*Iti kho, ānanda, desitā mayā paṇidhāya bhāvanā, desitā appaṇidhāya bhāvanā.**So, Ānanda, I’ve taught you directed development and undirected development.*";
P_HTM[3222]="*Yaṃ, ānanda, satthārā karaṇīyaṃ sāvakānaṃ hitesinā anukampakena anukampaṃ upādāya, kataṃ vo taṃ mayā.**Out of compassion, I’ve done what a teacher should do who wants what’s best for their disciples.*";
P_HTM[3223]="*Etāni, ānanda, rukkhamūlāni, etāni suññāgārāni. Jhāyathānanda, mā pamādattha; mā pacchā vippaṭisārino ahuvattha. Ayaṃ vo amhākaṃ anusāsanī”ti.**Here are these roots of trees, and here are these empty huts. Practice absorption, mendicants! Don’t be negligent! Don’t regret it later! This is my instruction to you.”*";
P_HTM[3224]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[3225]="*Attamano āyasmā ānando bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandīti.**Satisfied, Venerable Ānanda was happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[3226]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3227]="*Ambapālivaggo paṭhamo.* **";
P_HTM[3228]="*Ambapāli sato bhikkhu,* **";
P_HTM[3229]="*Sālā kusalarāsi ca;* **";
P_HTM[3230]="*Sakuṇagghi makkaṭo sūdo,* **";
P_HTM[3231]="*Gilāno bhikkhunupassayoti.* **";
P_HTM[3232]="*5. Akusalarāsisuttaṃ**A Great Man*";
P_HTM[3233]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[3234]="*Atha kho āyasmā sāriputto yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā sāriputto bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Sāriputta went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[3235]="*“‘mahāpuriso, mahāpuriso’ti, bhante, vuccati.**“Sir, they speak of ‘a great man’.*";
P_HTM[3236]="*Kittāvatā nu kho, bhante, mahāpuriso hotī”ti?**How is a great man defined?”*";
P_HTM[3237]="*“Vimuttacittattā khvāhaṃ, sāriputta, ‘mahāpuriso’ti vadāmi.**“Sāriputta, someone whose mind is free is a great man, I say.*";
P_HTM[3238]="*Avimuttacittattā ‘no mahāpuriso’ti vadāmi.**If their mind is not free, I say they’re not a great man.*";
P_HTM[3239]="*Kathañca, sāriputta, vimuttacitto hoti?**And how does someone have a free mind?*";
P_HTM[3240]="*Idha, sāriputta, bhikkhu kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**It’s when a mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3241]="*Tassa kāye kāyānupassino viharato cittaṃ virajjati, vimuccati anupādāya āsavehi.**As they meditate observing an aspect of the body, their mind becomes dispassionate, and is freed from the defilements by not grasping.*";
P_HTM[3242]="*Vedanāsu … pe …**They meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[3243]="*citte … pe …**mind …*";
P_HTM[3244]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3245]="*Tassa dhammesu dhammānupassino viharato cittaṃ virajjati, vimuccati anupādāya āsavehi.**As they meditate observing an aspect of principles, their mind becomes dispassionate, and is freed from the defilements by not grasping.*";
P_HTM[3246]="*Evaṃ kho, sāriputta, vimuttacitto hoti.**That’s how someone has a free mind.*";
P_HTM[3247]="*Vimuttacittattā khvāhaṃ, sāriputta, ‘mahāpuriso’ti vadāmi.**Someone whose mind is free is a great man, I say.*";
P_HTM[3248]="*Avimuttacittattā ‘no mahāpuriso’ti vadāmī”ti.**If their mind is not free, I say they’re not a great man.”*";
P_HTM[3249]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3250]="*6. Sakuṇagghisuttaṃ**At Nālandā*";
P_HTM[3251]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā nālandāyaṃ viharati pāvārikambavane.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Nālandā in Pāvārika’s mango grove.*";
P_HTM[3252]="*Atha kho āyasmā sāriputto yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā sāriputto bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Sāriputta went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him:*";
P_HTM[3253]="*“evaṃpasanno ahaṃ, bhante, bhagavati.**“Sir, I have such confidence in the Buddha that*";
P_HTM[3254]="*Na cāhu, na ca bhavissati, na cetarahi vijjati añño samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā bhagavatā bhiyyobhiññataro, yadidaṃ—sambodhiyan”ti.**I believe there’s no other ascetic or brahmin—whether past, future, or present—whose direct knowledge is superior to the Buddha when it comes to awakening.”*";
P_HTM[3255]="*“Uḷārā kho tyāyaṃ, sāriputta, āsabhī vācā bhāsitā, ekaṃso gahito, sīhanādo nadito:**“That’s a grand and dramatic statement, Sāriputta. You’ve roared a definitive, categorical lion’s roar, saying:*";
P_HTM[3256]="*‘evaṃpasanno ahaṃ, bhante, bhagavati.**‘I have such confidence in the Buddha that*";
P_HTM[3257]="*Na cāhu, na ca bhavissati na cetarahi vijjati añño samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā bhagavatā bhiyyobhiññataro, yadidaṃ—sambodhiyan’ti.**I believe there’s no other ascetic or brahmin—whether past, future, or present—whose direct knowledge is superior to the Buddha when it comes to awakening.’*";
P_HTM[3258]="*Kiṃ nu te, sāriputta, ye te ahesuṃ atītamaddhānaṃ arahanto sammāsambuddhā, sabbe te bhagavanto cetasā ceto paricca viditā:**What about all the perfected ones, the fully awakened Buddhas who lived in the past? Have you comprehended their minds to know that*";
P_HTM[3259]="*‘evaṃsīlā te bhagavanto ahesuṃ’ iti vā, ‘evaṃdhammā te bhagavanto ahesuṃ’ iti vā, ‘evaṃpaññā te bhagavanto ahesuṃ’ iti vā, ‘evaṃvihārino te bhagavanto ahesuṃ’ iti vā, ‘evaṃvimuttā te bhagavanto ahesuṃ’ iti vā”ti?**those Buddhas had such ethics, or such qualities, or such wisdom, or such meditation, or such freedom?”*";
P_HTM[3260]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3261]="*“Kiṃ pana te, sāriputta, ye te bhavissanti anāgatamaddhānaṃ arahanto sammāsambuddhā, sabbe te bhagavanto cetasā ceto paricca viditā:**“And what about all the perfected ones, the fully awakened Buddhas who will live in the future? Have you comprehended their minds to know that*";
P_HTM[3262]="*‘evaṃsīlā te bhagavanto bhavissanti’ iti vā, ‘evaṃdhammā te bhagavanto bhavissanti’ iti vā, ‘evaṃpaññā te bhagavanto bhavissanti’ iti vā, ‘evaṃvihārino te bhagavanto bhavissanti’ iti vā, ‘evaṃvimuttā te bhagavanto bhavissanti’ iti vā”ti?**those Buddhas will have such ethics, or such qualities, or such wisdom, or such meditation, or such freedom?”*";
P_HTM[3263]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3264]="*“Kiṃ pana tyāhaṃ, sāriputta, etarahi, arahaṃ sammāsambuddho cetasā ceto paricca vidito:**“And what about me, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha at present? Have you comprehended my mind to know that*";
P_HTM[3265]="*‘evaṃsīlo bhagavā’ iti vā, ‘evaṃdhammo bhagavā’ iti vā, ‘evaṃpañño bhagavā’ iti vā, ‘evaṃvihārī bhagavā’ iti vā, ‘evaṃvimutto bhagavā’ iti vā”ti?**I have such ethics, or such qualities, or such wisdom, or such meditation, or such freedom?”*";
P_HTM[3266]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3267]="*“Ettha ca te, sāriputta, atītānāgatapaccuppannesu arahantesu sammāsambuddhesu cetopariyañāṇaṃ natthi.**“Well then, Sāriputta, given that you don’t comprehend the minds of Buddhas past, future, or present,*";
P_HTM[3268]="*Atha kiñcarahi tyāyaṃ, sāriputta, uḷārā āsabhī vācā bhāsitā, ekaṃso gahito, sīhanādo nadito:**what exactly are you doing, making such a grand and dramatic statement, roaring such a definitive, categorical lion’s roar?”*";
P_HTM[3269]="*‘evaṃpasanno ahaṃ, bhante, bhagavati.* **";
P_HTM[3270]="*Na cāhu, na ca bhavissati, na cetarahi vijjati añño samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā bhagavatā’ bhiyyobhiññataro, yadidaṃ—sambodhiyan”ti?* **";
P_HTM[3271]="*“Na kho me, bhante, atītānāgatapaccuppannesu arahantesu sammāsambuddhesu cetopariyañāṇaṃ atthi,**“Sir, though I don’t comprehend the minds of Buddhas past, future, and present,*";
P_HTM[3272]="*api ca me dhammanvayo vidito.**still I understand this by inference from the teaching.*";
P_HTM[3273]="*Seyyathāpi, bhante, rañño paccantimaṃ nagaraṃ daḷhuddhāpaṃ daḷhapākāratoraṇaṃ ekadvāraṃ.**Suppose there was a king’s frontier citadel with fortified embankments, ramparts, and arches, and a single gate.*";
P_HTM[3274]="*Tatrassa dovāriko paṇḍito byatto medhāvī aññātānaṃ nivāretā ñātānaṃ pavesetā.**And it has a gatekeeper who is astute, competent, and intelligent. He keeps strangers out and lets known people in.*";
P_HTM[3275]="*So tassa nagarassa samantā anupariyāyapathaṃ anukkamamāno na passeyya pākārasandhiṃ vā pākāravivaraṃ vā, antamaso biḷāranikkhamanamattampi.**As he walks around the patrol path, he doesn’t see a hole or cleft in the wall, not even one big enough for a cat to slip out.*";
P_HTM[3276]="*Tassa evamassa:**He thinks,*";
P_HTM[3277]="*‘ye kho keci oḷārikā pāṇā imaṃ nagaraṃ pavisanti vā nikkhamanti vā, sabbe te imināva dvārena pavisanti vā nikkhamanti vā’ti.**‘Whatever sizable creatures enter or leave the citadel, all of them do so via this gate.’*";
P_HTM[3278]="*Evameva kho me, bhante, dhammanvayo vidito:**In the same way, I understand this by inference from the teaching:*";
P_HTM[3279]="*‘yepi te, bhante, ahesuṃ atītamaddhānaṃ arahanto sammāsambuddhā, sabbe te bhagavanto pañca nīvaraṇe pahāya, cetaso upakkilese paññāya dubbalīkaraṇe, catūsu satipaṭṭhānesu suppatiṭṭhitacittā, satta bojjhaṅge yathābhūtaṃ bhāvetvā, anuttaraṃ sammāsambodhiṃ abhisambujjhiṃsu.**‘All the perfected ones, fully awakened Buddhas—whether past, future, or present—give up the five hindrances, corruptions of the heart that weaken wisdom. Their mind is firmly established in the four kinds of mindfulness meditation. They correctly develop the seven awakening factors. And they wake up to the supreme perfect awakening.’”*";
P_HTM[3280]="*Yepi te, bhante, bhavissanti anāgatamaddhānaṃ arahanto sammāsambuddhā, sabbe te bhagavanto pañca nīvaraṇe pahāya, cetaso upakkilese paññāya dubbalīkaraṇe, catūsu satipaṭṭhānesu suppatiṭṭhitacittā, satta bojjhaṅge yathābhūtaṃ bhāvetvā, anuttaraṃ sammāsambodhiṃ abhisambujjhissanti.* **";
P_HTM[3281]="*Bhagavāpi, bhante, etarahi arahaṃ sammāsambuddho pañca nīvaraṇe pahāya, cetaso upakkilese paññāya dubbalīkaraṇe, catūsu satipaṭṭhānesu suppatiṭṭhitacitto, satta bojjhaṅge yathābhūtaṃ bhāvetvā, anuttaraṃ sammāsambodhiṃ abhisambuddho’”ti.* **";
P_HTM[3282]="*“Sādhu sādhu, sāriputta.**“Good, good, Sāriputta!*";
P_HTM[3283]="*Tasmātiha tvaṃ, sāriputta, imaṃ dhammapariyāyaṃ abhikkhaṇaṃ bhāseyyāsi bhikkhūnaṃ bhikkhunīnaṃ upāsakānaṃ upāsikānaṃ.**So Sāriputta, you should frequently speak this exposition of the teaching to the monks, nuns, laymen, and laywomen.*";
P_HTM[3284]="*Yesampi hi, sāriputta, moghapurisānaṃ bhavissati tathāgate kaṅkhā vā vimati vā, tesampimaṃ dhammapariyāyaṃ sutvā yā tathāgate kaṅkhā vā vimati vā sā pahīyissatī”ti.**Though there will be some foolish people who have doubt or uncertainty regarding the Realized One, when they hear this exposition of the teaching they’ll give up that doubt or uncertainty.”*";
P_HTM[3285]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3286]="*7. Makkaṭasuttaṃ**With Cunda*";
P_HTM[3287]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati jetavane anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery.*";
P_HTM[3288]="*Tena kho pana samayena āyasmā sāriputto magadhesu viharati nālakagāmake ābādhiko dukkhito bāḷhagilāno.**At that time Venerable Sāriputta was staying in the Magadhan lands near the little village of Nālaka, and he was sick, suffering, gravely ill.*";
P_HTM[3289]="*Cundo ca samaṇuddeso āyasmato sāriputtassa upaṭṭhāko hoti.**And the novice Cunda was his carer.*";
P_HTM[3290]="*Atha kho āyasmā sāriputto teneva ābādhena parinibbāyi.**Then Venerable Sāriputta became fully extinguished because of that sickness.*";
P_HTM[3291]="*Atha kho cundo samaṇuddeso āyasmato sāriputtassa pattacīvaramādāya yena sāvatthi jetavanaṃ anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāmo yenāyasmā ānando tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho cundo samaṇuddeso āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ etadavoca:**Then Cunda took Sāriputta’s bowl and robes and set out for Sāvatthī. He went to see Venerable Ānanda at Jeta’s grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him:*";
P_HTM[3292]="*“āyasmā, bhante, sāriputto parinibbuto.**“Sir, Venerable Sāriputta has become fully extinguished.*";
P_HTM[3293]="*Idamassa pattacīvaran”ti.**This is his bowl and robe.”*";
P_HTM[3294]="*“Atthi kho idaṃ, āvuso cunda, kathāpābhataṃ bhagavantaṃ dassanāya.**“Reverend Cunda, we should see the Buddha about this matter.*";
P_HTM[3295]="*Āyāmāvuso cunda, yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamissāma; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavato etamatthaṃ ārocessāmā”ti.**Come, let’s go to the Buddha and inform him about this.”*";
P_HTM[3296]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho cundo samaṇuddeso āyasmato ānandassa paccassosi.**“Yes, sir,” replied Cunda.*";
P_HTM[3297]="*Atha kho āyasmā ca ānando cundo ca samaṇuddeso yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā ānando bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Ānanda and Cunda went to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him:*";
P_HTM[3298]="*“ayaṃ, bhante, cundo samaṇuddeso evamāha:**“Sir, this novice Cunda says that*";
P_HTM[3299]="*‘āyasmā, bhante, sāriputto parinibbuto;**Venerable Sāriputta has become fully extinguished.*";
P_HTM[3300]="*idamassa pattacīvaran’ti.**This is his bowl and robe.*";
P_HTM[3301]="*Api ca me, bhante, madhurakajāto viya kāyo, disāpi me na pakkhāyanti, dhammāpi maṃ nappaṭibhanti ‘āyasmā sāriputto parinibbuto’ti sutvā”.**Since I heard this, my body feels like it’s drugged. I’m disorientated, and the teachings don’t spring to mind.”*";
P_HTM[3302]="*“Kiṃ nu kho te, ānanda, sāriputto sīlakkhandhaṃ vā ādāya parinibbuto, samādhikkhandhaṃ vā ādāya parinibbuto, paññākkhandhaṃ vā ādāya parinibbuto, vimuttikkhandhaṃ vā ādāya parinibbuto, vimuttiñāṇadassanakkhandhaṃ vā ādāya parinibbuto”ti?**“Well, Ānanda, when Sāriputta became fully extinguished, did he take away your entire spectrum of ethical conduct, of immersion, of wisdom, of freedom, or of the knowledge and vision of freedom?”*";
P_HTM[3303]="*“Na ca kho me, bhante, āyasmā sāriputto sīlakkhandhaṃ vā ādāya parinibbuto, samādhikkhandhaṃ vā … pe …**“No, sir, he did not.*";
P_HTM[3304]="*paññākkhandhaṃ vā … pe …* **";
P_HTM[3305]="*vimuttikkhandhaṃ vā … pe …* **";
P_HTM[3306]="*vimuttiñāṇadassanakkhandhaṃ vā ādāya parinibbuto.* **";
P_HTM[3307]="*Api ca me, bhante, āyasmā sāriputto ovādako ahosi otiṇṇo viññāpako sandassako samādapako samuttejako sampahaṃsako, akilāsu dhammadesanāya, anuggāhako sabrahmacārīnaṃ.**But Venerable Sāriputta was my adviser and counselor. He educated, encouraged, fired up, and inspired me. He never tired of teaching the Dhamma, and he supported his spiritual companions.*";
P_HTM[3308]="*Taṃ mayaṃ āyasmato sāriputtassa dhammojaṃ dhammabhogaṃ dhammānuggahaṃ anussarāmā”ti.**I remember the nectar of the teaching, the riches of the teaching, the support of the teaching given by Venerable Sāriputta.”*";
P_HTM[3309]="*“Nanu taṃ, ānanda, mayā paṭikacceva akkhātaṃ:**“Ānanda, did I not prepare for this when I explained that*";
P_HTM[3310]="*‘sabbehi piyehi manāpehi nānābhāvo vinābhāvo aññathābhāvo.**we must be parted and separated from all we hold dear and beloved?*";
P_HTM[3311]="*Taṃ kutettha, ānanda, labbhā. Yaṃ taṃ jātaṃ bhūtaṃ saṅkhataṃ palokadhammaṃ, taṃ vata mā palujjīti—**How could it possibly be so that what is born, created, conditioned, and liable to fall apart should not fall apart?*";
P_HTM[3312]="*netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**That is not possible.*";
P_HTM[3313]="*Seyyathāpi, ānanda, mahato rukkhassa tiṭṭhato sāravato yo mahantataro khandho so palujjeyya;**Suppose there was a large tree standing with heartwood, and the largest branch fell off.*";
P_HTM[3314]="*evameva kho ānanda, mahato bhikkhusaṃghassa tiṭṭhato sāravato sāriputto parinibbuto.**In the same way, in the great Saṅgha that stands with heartwood, Sāriputta has become fully extinguished.*";
P_HTM[3315]="*Taṃ kutettha, ānanda, labbhā. Yaṃ taṃ jātaṃ bhūtaṃ saṅkhataṃ palokadhammaṃ, taṃ vata mā palujjī’ti—**How could it possibly be so that what is born, created, conditioned, and liable to fall apart should not fall apart?*";
P_HTM[3316]="*netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**That is not possible.*";
P_HTM[3317]="*Tasmātihānanda, attadīpā viharatha attasaraṇā anaññasaraṇā, dhammadīpā dhammasaraṇā anaññasaraṇā.**So Ānanda, be your own island, your own refuge, with no other refuge. Let the teaching be your island and your refuge, with no other refuge.*";
P_HTM[3318]="*Kathañcānanda, bhikkhu attadīpo viharati attasaraṇo anaññasaraṇo, dhammadīpo dhammasaraṇo anaññasaraṇo?**And how does a mendicant do this?*";
P_HTM[3319]="*Idhānanda, bhikkhu kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;**It’s when a mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3320]="*vedanāsu … pe …**They meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[3321]="*citte … pe …**mind …*";
P_HTM[3322]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3323]="*Evaṃ kho, ānanda, bhikkhu attadīpo viharati attasaraṇo anaññasaraṇo, dhammadīpo dhammasaraṇo anaññasaraṇo.**That’s how a mendicant is their own island, their own refuge, with no other refuge. That’s how the teaching is their island and their refuge, with no other refuge.*";
P_HTM[3324]="*Ye hi keci, ānanda, etarahi vā mamaccaye vā attadīpā viharissanti attasaraṇā anaññasaraṇā, dhammadīpā dhammasaraṇā anaññasaraṇā; tamatagge mete, ānanda, bhikkhū bhavissanti ye keci sikkhākāmā”ti.**Whether now or after I have passed, any who shall live as their own island, their own refuge, with no other refuge; with the teaching as their island and their refuge, with no other refuge—those mendicants of mine who want to train shall be among the best of the best.”*";
P_HTM[3325]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3326]="*8. Sūdasuttaṃ**At Ukkacelā*";
P_HTM[3327]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā vajjīsu viharati ukkacelāyaṃ gaṅgāya nadiyā tīre mahatā bhikkhusaṅghena saddhiṃ aciraparinibbutesu sāriputtamoggallānesu.**At one time the Buddha was staying in the land of the Vajjīs near Ukkacelā on the bank of the Ganges river, together with a large Saṅgha of mendicants. It was not long after Sāriputta and Moggallāna had become fully extinguished.*";
P_HTM[3328]="*Tena kho pana samayena bhagavā bhikkhusaṅghaparivuto ajjhokāse nisinno hoti.**Now, at that time the Buddha was sitting in the open, surrounded by the Saṅgha of monks.*";
P_HTM[3329]="*Atha kho bhagavā tuṇhībhūtaṃ bhikkhusaṃghaṃ anuviloketvā bhikkhū āmantesi:**Then the Buddha looked around the Saṅgha of monks, who were silent. He addressed them:*";
P_HTM[3330]="*“api myāyaṃ, bhikkhave, parisā suññā viya khāyati parinibbutesu sāriputtamoggallānesu.**“Mendicants, this assembly seems empty to me now that Sāriputta and Moggallāna have become fully extinguished.*";
P_HTM[3331]="*Asuññā me, bhikkhave, parisā hoti, anapekkhā tassaṃ disāyaṃ hoti, yassaṃ disāyaṃ sāriputtamoggallānā viharanti.**When Sāriputta and Moggallāna were alive, my assembly was never empty; I had no concern for any region where they stayed.*";
P_HTM[3332]="*Ye hi te, bhikkhave, ahesuṃ atītamaddhānaṃ arahanto sammāsambuddhā, tesampi bhagavantānaṃ etapparamaṃyeva sāvakayugaṃ ahosi—**The Buddhas of the past or the future have pairs of chief disciples who are no better than*";
P_HTM[3333]="*seyyathāpi mayhaṃ sāriputtamoggallānā.**Sāriputta and Moggallāna were to me.*";
P_HTM[3334]="*Yepi te, bhikkhave, bhavissanti anāgatamaddhānaṃ arahanto sammāsambuddhā, tesampi bhagavantānaṃ etapparamaṃyeva sāvakayugaṃ bhavissati—seyyathāpi mayhaṃ sāriputtamoggallānā.* **";
P_HTM[3335]="*Acchariyaṃ, bhikkhave, sāvakānaṃ, abbhutaṃ, bhikkhave, sāvakānaṃ.**It’s an incredible and amazing quality of such disciples*";
P_HTM[3336]="*Satthu ca nāma sāsanakarā bhavissanti ovādappaṭikarā, catunnañca parisānaṃ piyā bhavissanti manāpā garubhāvanīyā ca.**that they fulfill the Teacher’s instructions and follow his advice. And they’re liked and approved, respected and admired by the four assemblies.*";
P_HTM[3337]="*Acchariyaṃ, bhikkhave, tathāgatassa, abbhutaṃ, bhikkhave, tathāgatassa.**And it’s an incredible and amazing quality of the Realized One*";
P_HTM[3338]="*Evarūpepi nāma sāvakayuge parinibbute natthi tathāgatassa soko vā paridevo vā.**that when such a pair of disciples becomes fully extinguished he does not sorrow or lament.*";
P_HTM[3339]="*Taṃ kutettha, bhikkhave, labbhā. Yaṃ taṃ jātaṃ bhūtaṃ saṅkhataṃ palokadhammaṃ, taṃ vata mā palujjīti—**How could it possibly be so that what is born, created, conditioned, and liable to fall apart should not fall apart?*";
P_HTM[3340]="*netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**That is not possible.*";
P_HTM[3341]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, mahato rukkhassa tiṭṭhato sāravato ye mahantatarā khandhā te palujjeyyuṃ;**Suppose there was a large tree standing with heartwood, and the largest branch fell off.*";
P_HTM[3342]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, mahato bhikkhusaṃghassa tiṭṭhato sāravato sāriputtamoggallānā parinibbutā.**In the same way, in the great Saṅgha that stands with heartwood, Sāriputta and Moggallāna have become fully extinguished.*";
P_HTM[3343]="*Taṃ kutettha, bhikkhave, labbhā. Yaṃ taṃ jātaṃ bhūtaṃ saṅkhataṃ palokadhammaṃ, taṃ vata mā palujjīti—**How could it possibly be so that what is born, created, conditioned, and liable to fall apart should not fall apart?*";
P_HTM[3344]="*netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**That is not possible.*";
P_HTM[3345]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, attadīpā viharatha attasaraṇā anaññasaraṇā, dhammadīpā dhammasaraṇā anaññasaraṇā.**So mendicants, be your own island, your own refuge, with no other refuge. Let the teaching be your island and your refuge, with no other refuge.*";
P_HTM[3346]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhu attadīpo viharati attasaraṇo anaññasaraṇo, dhammadīpo dhammasaraṇo anaññasaraṇo?**And how does a mendicant do this?*";
P_HTM[3347]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;**It’s when a mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3348]="*vedanāsu … pe …**They meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[3349]="*citte … pe …**mind …*";
P_HTM[3350]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3351]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu attadīpo viharati attasaraṇo anaññasaraṇo, dhammadīpo dhammasaraṇo anaññasaraṇo.**That’s how a mendicant is their own island, their own refuge, with no other refuge. That’s how the teaching is their island and their refuge, with no other refuge.*";
P_HTM[3352]="*Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, etarahi vā mamaccaye vā attadīpā viharissanti attasaraṇā anaññasaraṇā, dhammadīpā dhammasaraṇā anaññasaraṇā; tamatagge mete, bhikkhave, bhikkhū bhavissanti ye keci sikkhākāmā”ti.**Whether now or after I have passed, any who shall live as their own island, their own refuge, with no other refuge; with the teaching as their island and their refuge, with no other refuge—those mendicants of mine who want to train shall be among the best of the best.”*";
P_HTM[3353]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3354]="*9. Gilānasuttaṃ**With Bāhiya*";
P_HTM[3355]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[3356]="*Atha kho āyasmā bāhiyo yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā bāhiyo bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Venerable Bāhiya went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him:*";
P_HTM[3357]="*“sādhu me, bhante, bhagavā saṅkhittena dhammaṃ desetu, yamahaṃ bhagavato dhammaṃ sutvā eko vūpakaṭṭho appamatto ātāpī pahitatto vihareyyan”ti.**“Sir, may the Buddha please teach me Dhamma in brief. When I’ve heard it, I’ll live alone, withdrawn, diligent, keen, and resolute.”*";
P_HTM[3358]="*“Tasmātiha tvaṃ, bāhiya, ādimeva visodhehi kusalesu dhammesu.**“Well then, Bāhiya, you should purify the starting point of skillful qualities.*";
P_HTM[3359]="*Ko cādi kusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ?**What is the starting point of skillful qualities?*";
P_HTM[3360]="*Sīlañca suvisuddhaṃ, diṭṭhi ca ujukā.**Well purified ethics and correct view.*";
P_HTM[3361]="*Yato ca kho te, bāhiya, sīlañca suvisuddhaṃ bhavissati, diṭṭhi ca ujukā, tato tvaṃ, bāhiya, sīlaṃ nissāya sīle patiṭṭhāya cattāro satipaṭṭhāne bhāveyyāsi.**When your ethics are well purified and your view is correct, you should develop the four kinds of mindfulness meditation, depending on and grounded on ethics.*";
P_HTM[3362]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[3363]="*Idha tvaṃ, bāhiya, kāye kāyānupassī viharāhi ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;**Meditate observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3364]="*vedanāsu … pe …**Meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[3365]="*citte … pe …**mind …*";
P_HTM[3366]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharāhi ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3367]="*Yato kho tvaṃ, bāhiya, sīlaṃ nissāya sīle patiṭṭhāya ime cattāro satipaṭṭhāne evaṃ bhāvessasi, tato tuyhaṃ, bāhiya, yā ratti vā divaso vā āgamissati, vuddhiyeva pāṭikaṅkhā kusalesu dhammesu, no parihānī”ti.**When you develop these four kinds of mindfulness meditation, depending on and grounded on ethics, you can expect growth, not decline, in skillful qualities, whether by day or by night.”*";
P_HTM[3368]="*Atha kho āyasmā bāhiyo bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinanditvā anumoditvā uṭṭhāyāsanā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā pakkāmi.**And then Venerable Bāhiya approved and agreed with what the Buddha said. He got up from his seat, bowed, and respectfully circled the Buddha, keeping him on his right, before leaving.*";
P_HTM[3369]="*Atha kho āyasmā bāhiyo eko vūpakaṭṭho appamatto ātāpī pahitatto viharanto nacirasseva—yassatthāya kulaputtā sammadeva agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajanti, tadanuttaraṃ—brahmacariyapariyosānaṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja vihāsi.**Then Bāhiya, living alone, withdrawn, diligent, keen, and resolute, soon realized the supreme end of the spiritual path in this very life. He lived having achieved with his own insight the goal for which gentlemen rightly go forth from the lay life to homelessness.*";
P_HTM[3370]="*“Khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyā”ti abbhaññāsi.**He understood: “Rebirth is ended; the spiritual journey has been completed; what had to be done has been done; there is no return to any state of existence.”*";
P_HTM[3371]="*Aññataro ca panāyasmā bāhiyo arahataṃ ahosīti.**And Venerable Bāhiya became one of the perfected.*";
P_HTM[3372]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3373]="*10. Bhikkhunupassayasuttaṃ**With Uttiya*";
P_HTM[3374]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[3375]="*Atha kho āyasmā uttiyo yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami … pe … ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā uttiyo bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Venerable Uttiya went up to the Buddha … and asked him,*";
P_HTM[3376]="*“sādhu me, bhante, bhagavā saṅkhittena dhammaṃ desetu, yamahaṃ bhagavato dhammaṃ sutvā eko vūpakaṭṭho appamatto ātāpī pahitatto vihareyyan”ti.**“Sir, may the Buddha please teach me Dhamma in brief. When I’ve heard it, I’ll live alone, withdrawn, diligent, keen, and resolute.”*";
P_HTM[3377]="*“Tasmātiha tvaṃ, uttiya, ādimeva visodhehi kusalesu dhammesu.**“Well then, Uttiya, you should purify the starting point of skillful qualities.*";
P_HTM[3378]="*Ko cādi kusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ?**What is the starting point of skillful qualities?*";
P_HTM[3379]="*Sīlañca suvisuddhaṃ, diṭṭhi ca ujukā.**Well purified ethics and correct view.*";
P_HTM[3380]="*Yato ca kho te, uttiya, sīlañca suvisuddhaṃ bhavissati, diṭṭhi ca ujukā, tato tvaṃ, uttiya, sīlaṃ nissāya sīle patiṭṭhāya cattāro satipaṭṭhāne bhāveyyāsi.**When your ethics are well purified and your view is correct, you should develop the four kinds of mindfulness meditation, depending on and grounded on ethics.*";
P_HTM[3381]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[3382]="*Idha tvaṃ, uttiya, kāye kāyānupassī viharāhi ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;**Meditate observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3383]="*vedanāsu … pe …**Meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[3384]="*citte … pe …**mind …*";
P_HTM[3385]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharāhi ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3386]="*Yato kho tvaṃ, uttiya, sīlaṃ nissāya sīle patiṭṭhāya ime cattāro satipaṭṭhāne evaṃ bhāvessasi, tato tvaṃ, uttiya, gamissasi maccudheyyassa pāran”ti.**When you develop these four kinds of mindfulness meditation, depending on and grounded on ethics, you’ll pass beyond Death’s domain.”*";
P_HTM[3387]="*Atha kho āyasmā uttiyo bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinanditvā anumoditvā uṭṭhāyāsanā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā pakkāmi.**And then Venerable Uttiya approved and agreed with what the Buddha said. He got up from his seat, bowed, and respectfully circled the Buddha, keeping him on his right, before leaving.*";
P_HTM[3388]="*Atha kho āyasmā uttiyo eko vūpakaṭṭho appamatto ātāpī pahitatto viharanto nacirasseva—yassatthāya kulaputtā sammadeva agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajanti, tadanuttaraṃ—brahmacariyapariyosānaṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja vihāsi.**Then Uttiya, living alone, withdrawn, diligent, keen, and resolute, soon realized the supreme end of the spiritual path in this very life. He lived having achieved with his own insight the goal for which gentlemen rightly go forth from the lay life to homelessness.*";
P_HTM[3389]="*“Khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyā”ti abbhaññāsi.**He understood: “Rebirth is ended; the spiritual journey has been completed; what had to be done has been done; there is no return to any state of existence.”*";
P_HTM[3390]="*Aññataro ca panāyasmā uttiyo arahataṃ ahosīti.**And Venerable Uttiya became one of the perfected.*";
P_HTM[3391]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3392]="*6. Gaṅgāpeyyālavaggo**At Nālandā*";
P_HTM[3393]="*1. Mahāpurisasuttaṃ**Noble*";
P_HTM[3394]="*“Cattārome, bhikkhave, satipaṭṭhānā bhāvitā bahulīkatā ariyā niyyānikā niyyanti takkarassa sammā dukkhakkhayāya.**“Mendicants, when these four kinds of mindfulness meditation are developed and cultivated they are noble and emancipating, and bring one who practices them to the complete ending of suffering.*";
P_HTM[3395]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[3396]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;**It’s when a mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3397]="*vedanāsu … pe …**They meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[3398]="*citte … pe …**mind …*";
P_HTM[3399]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3400]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, cattāro satipaṭṭhānā bhāvitā bahulīkatā ariyā niyyānikā niyyanti takkarassa sammā dukkhakkhayāyā”ti.**When these four kinds of mindfulness meditation are developed and cultivated they are noble and emancipating, and bring one who practices them to the complete ending of suffering.”*";
P_HTM[3401]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3402]="*2. Nālandasuttaṃ**With Brahmā*";
P_HTM[3403]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā uruvelāyaṃ viharati najjā nerañjarāya tīre ajapālanigrodhe paṭhamābhisambuddho.**At one time, when he was first awakened, the Buddha was staying near Uruvelā at the goatherd’s banyan tree on the bank of the Nerañjarā River.*";
P_HTM[3404]="*Atha kho bhagavato rahogatassa paṭisallīnassa evaṃ cetaso parivitakko udapādi:**Then as he was in private retreat this thought came to his mind,*";
P_HTM[3405]="*“ekāyanvāyaṃ maggo sattānaṃ visuddhiyā sokaparidevānaṃ samatikkamāya dukkhadomanassānaṃ atthaṅgamāya ñāyassa adhigamāya nibbānassa sacchikiriyāya, yadidaṃ—cattāro satipaṭṭhānā.**“The four kinds of mindfulness meditation are the path to convergence. They are in order to purify sentient beings, to get past sorrow and crying, to make an end of pain and sadness, to end the cycle of suffering, and to realize extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[3406]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[3407]="*Kāye vā bhikkhu kāyānupassī vihareyya ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;**A mendicant would meditate observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3408]="*vedanāsu vā bhikkhu … pe …**Or they’d meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[3409]="*citte vā bhikkhu … pe …**or mind …*";
P_HTM[3410]="*dhammesu vā bhikkhu dhammānupassī vihareyya ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**or principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3411]="*Ekāyanvāyaṃ maggo sattānaṃ visuddhiyā sokaparidevānaṃ samatikkamāya dukkhadomanassānaṃ atthaṅgamāya ñāyassa adhigamāya nibbānassa sacchikiriyāya, yadidaṃ—cattāro satipaṭṭhānā”ti.**The four kinds of mindfulness meditation are the path to convergence. They are in order to purify sentient beings, to get past sorrow and crying, to make an end of pain and sadness, to end the cycle of suffering, and to realize extinguishment.”*";
P_HTM[3412]="*Atha kho brahmā sahampati bhagavato cetasā cetoparivitakkamaññāya—seyyathāpi nāma balavā puriso samiñjitaṃ vā bāhaṃ pasāreyya, pasāritaṃ vā bāhaṃ samiñjeyya; evameva kho brahmaloke antarahito bhagavato purato pāturahosi.**Then Brahmā Sahampati knew what the Buddha was thinking. As easily as a strong person would extend or contract their arm, he vanished from the Brahmā realm and reappeared in front of the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[3413]="*Atha kho brahmā sahampati ekaṃsaṃ uttarāsaṅgaṃ karitvā yena bhagavā tenañjaliṃ paṇāmetvā bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**He arranged his robe over one shoulder, raised his joined palms toward the Buddha, and said:*";
P_HTM[3414]="*“evametaṃ, bhagavā, evametaṃ, sugata.**“That’s so true, Blessed One! That’s so true, Holy One!*";
P_HTM[3415]="*Ekāyanvāyaṃ, bhante, maggo sattānaṃ visuddhiyā sokaparidevānaṃ samatikkamāya dukkhadomanassānaṃ atthaṅgamāya ñāyassa adhigamāya nibbānassa sacchikiriyāya, yadidaṃ—cattāro satipaṭṭhānā.**Sir, the four kinds of mindfulness meditation are the path to convergence. They are in order to purify sentient beings, to get past sorrow and crying, to make an end of pain and sadness, to end the cycle of suffering, and to realize extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[3416]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[3417]="*Kāye vā, bhante, bhikkhu kāyānupassī vihareyya ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;**A mendicant would meditate observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3418]="*vedanāsu vā, bhante, bhikkhu … pe …**Or they’d meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[3419]="*citte vā, bhante, bhikkhu … pe …**or mind …*";
P_HTM[3420]="*dhammesu vā, bhante, bhikkhu dhammānupassī vihareyya ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**or principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3421]="*Ekāyanvāyaṃ, bhante, maggo sattānaṃ visuddhiyā sokaparidevānaṃ samatikkamāya dukkhadomanassānaṃ atthaṅgamāya ñāyassa adhigamāya nibbānassa sacchikiriyāya, yadidaṃ—cattāro satipaṭṭhānā”ti.**The four kinds of mindfulness meditation are the path to convergence. They are in order to purify sentient beings, to get past sorrow and crying, to make an end of pain and sadness, to end the cycle of suffering, and to realize extinguishment.”*";
P_HTM[3422]="*Idamavoca brahmā sahampati.**That’s what Brahmā Sahampati said.*";
P_HTM[3423]="*Idaṃ vatvā athāparaṃ etadavoca:**Then he went on to say:*";
P_HTM[3424]="*“Ekāyanaṃ jātikhayantadassī,**“The compassionate one, who sees the ending of rebirth,*";
P_HTM[3425]="*Maggaṃ pajānāti hitānukampī;**understands the path to convergence.*";
P_HTM[3426]="*Etena maggena tariṃsu pubbe,**By this path people crossed over before,*";
P_HTM[3427]="*Tarissanti ye ca taranti oghan”ti.**will cross, and are crossing.”*";
P_HTM[3428]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3429]="*3. Cundasuttaṃ**At Sedaka*";
P_HTM[3430]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sumbhesu viharati sedakaṃ nāma sumbhānaṃ nigamo.**At one time the Buddha was staying in the land of the Sumbhas, near the town of the Sumbhas called Sedaka.*";
P_HTM[3431]="*Tatra kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**There the Buddha addressed the mendicants:*";
P_HTM[3432]="*“bhūtapubbaṃ, bhikkhave, caṇḍālavaṃsiko caṇḍālavaṃsaṃ ussāpetvā medakathālikaṃ antevāsiṃ āmantesi:**“Once upon a time, mendicants, an acrobat set up his bamboo pole and said to his apprentice Medakathālikā,*";
P_HTM[3433]="*‘ehi tvaṃ, samma medakathālike, caṇḍālavaṃsaṃ abhiruhitvā mama uparikhandhe tiṭṭhāhī’ti.**‘Come now, dear Medakathālikā, climb up the bamboo pole and stand on my shoulders.’*";
P_HTM[3434]="*‘Evaṃ, ācariyā’ti kho, bhikkhave, medakathālikā antevāsī caṇḍālavaṃsikassa paṭissutvā caṇḍālavaṃsaṃ abhiruhitvā ācariyassa uparikhandhe aṭṭhāsi.**‘Yes, teacher,’ she replied. She climbed up the bamboo pole and stood on her teacher’s shoulders.*";
P_HTM[3435]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, caṇḍālavaṃsiko medakathālikaṃ antevāsiṃ etadavoca:**Then the acrobat said to Medakathālikā,*";
P_HTM[3436]="*‘tvaṃ, samma medakathālike, mamaṃ rakkha, ahaṃ taṃ rakkhissāmi.**‘You look after me, dear Medakathālikā, and I’ll look after you.*";
P_HTM[3437]="*Evaṃ mayaṃ aññamaññaṃ guttā aññamaññaṃ rakkhitā sippāni ceva dassessāma, lābhañca lacchāma, sotthinā ca caṇḍālavaṃsā orohissāmā’ti.**That’s how, guarding and looking after each other, we’ll display our skill, collect our fee, and get down safely from the bamboo pole.’*";
P_HTM[3438]="*Evaṃ vutte, bhikkhave, medakathālikā antevāsī caṇḍālavaṃsikaṃ etadavoca:**When he said this, Medakathālikā said to her teacher,*";
P_HTM[3439]="*‘na kho panetaṃ, ācariya, evaṃ bhavissati.**‘That’s not how it is, teacher!*";
P_HTM[3440]="*Tvaṃ, ācariya, attānaṃ rakkha, ahaṃ attānaṃ rakkhissāmi.**You should look after yourself, and I’ll look after myself.*";
P_HTM[3441]="*Evaṃ mayaṃ attaguttā attarakkhitā sippāni ceva dassessāma, lābhañca lacchāma, sotthinā ca caṇḍālavaṃsā orohissāmā’”ti.**That’s how, guarding and looking after ourselves, we’ll display our skill, collect our fee, and get down safely from the bamboo pole.’*";
P_HTM[3442]="*“So tattha ñāyo”ti bhagavā etadavoca, “yathā medakathālikā antevāsī ācariyaṃ avoca.**That’s the way,” said the Buddha. “It’s just as Medakathālikā said to her teacher.*";
P_HTM[3443]="*Attānaṃ, bhikkhave, rakkhissāmīti satipaṭṭhānaṃ sevitabbaṃ;**Thinking ‘I’ll look after myself,’ you should cultivate mindfulness meditation.*";
P_HTM[3444]="*paraṃ rakkhissāmīti satipaṭṭhānaṃ sevitabbaṃ.**Thinking ‘I’ll look after others,’ you should cultivate mindfulness meditation.*";
P_HTM[3445]="*Attānaṃ, bhikkhave, rakkhanto paraṃ rakkhati, paraṃ rakkhanto attānaṃ rakkhati.**Looking after yourself, you look after others; and looking after others, you look after yourself.*";
P_HTM[3446]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, attānaṃ rakkhanto paraṃ rakkhati?**And how do you look after others by looking after yourself?*";
P_HTM[3447]="*Āsevanāya, bhāvanāya, bahulīkammena—**By development, cultivation, and practice of meditation.*";
P_HTM[3448]="*evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, attānaṃ rakkhanto paraṃ rakkhati.* **";
P_HTM[3449]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, paraṃ rakkhanto attānaṃ rakkhati?**And how do you look after yourself by looking after others?*";
P_HTM[3450]="*Khantiyā, avihiṃsāya, mettacittatāya, anudayatāya—**By acceptance, harmlessness, love, and sympathy.*";
P_HTM[3451]="*evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, paraṃ rakkhanto attānaṃ rakkhati.* **";
P_HTM[3452]="*Attānaṃ, bhikkhave, rakkhissāmīti satipaṭṭhānaṃ sevitabbaṃ;**Thinking ‘I’ll look after myself,’ you should cultivate mindfulness meditation.*";
P_HTM[3453]="*paraṃ rakkhissāmīti satipaṭṭhānaṃ sevitabbaṃ.**Thinking ‘I’ll look after others,’ you should cultivate mindfulness meditation.*";
P_HTM[3454]="*Attānaṃ, bhikkhave, rakkhanto paraṃ rakkhati, paraṃ rakkhanto attānaṃ rakkhatī”ti.**Looking after yourself, you look after others; and looking after others, you look after yourself.”*";
P_HTM[3455]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3456]="*4. Ukkacelasuttaṃ**The Finest Lady in the Land*";
P_HTM[3457]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[3458]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sumbhesu viharati sedakaṃ nāma sumbhānaṃ nigamo.**At one time the Buddha was staying in the land of the Sumbhas, near the town of the Sumbhas called Sedaka.*";
P_HTM[3459]="*Tatra kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**There the Buddha addressed the mendicants,*";
P_HTM[3460]="*“bhikkhavo”ti.**“Mendicants!”*";
P_HTM[3461]="*“Bhadante”ti te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Venerable sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[3462]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[3463]="*“Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, ‘janapadakalyāṇī, janapadakalyāṇī’ti kho, bhikkhave, mahājanakāyo sannipateyya.**“Mendicants, suppose that on hearing, ‘The finest lady in the land! The finest lady in the land!’ a large crowd would gather.*";
P_HTM[3464]="*‘Sā kho panassa janapadakalyāṇī paramapāsāvinī nacce, paramapāsāvinī gīte.**And the finest lady in the land would dance and sing in a most thrilling way.*";
P_HTM[3465]="*Janapadakalyāṇī naccati gāyatī’ti kho, bhikkhave, bhiyyoso mattāya mahājanakāyo sannipateyya.**On hearing, ‘The finest lady in the land is dancing and singing! The finest lady in the land is dancing and singing!’ an even larger crowd would gather.*";
P_HTM[3466]="*Atha puriso āgaccheyya jīvitukāmo amaritukāmo sukhakāmo dukkhappaṭikūlo.**Then a person would come along who wants to live and doesn’t want to die, who wants to be happy and recoils from pain.*";
P_HTM[3467]="*Tamenaṃ evaṃ vadeyya:**They’d say to him,*";
P_HTM[3468]="*‘ayaṃ te, ambho purisa, samatittiko telapatto antarena ca mahāsamajjaṃ antarena ca janapadakalyāṇiyā pariharitabbo.**‘Mister, this is a bowl full to the brim with oil. You must carry it in between this large crowd and the finest lady in the land.*";
P_HTM[3469]="*Puriso ca te ukkhittāsiko piṭṭhito piṭṭhito anubandhissati.**And a man with a drawn sword will follow behind you.*";
P_HTM[3470]="*Yattheva naṃ thokampi chaḍḍessati tattheva te siro pātessatī’ti.**Wherever you spill even a drop, he’ll chop off your head right there.’*";
P_HTM[3471]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhikkhave,**What do you think, mendicants?*";
P_HTM[3472]="*api nu so puriso amuṃ telapattaṃ amanasikaritvā bahiddhā pamādaṃ āhareyyā”ti?**Would that person lose focus on that bowl, and negligently get distracted outside?”*";
P_HTM[3473]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3474]="*“Upamā kho myāyaṃ, bhikkhave, katā atthassa viññāpanāya.**“I’ve made up this simile to make a point.*";
P_HTM[3475]="*Ayaṃ cevettha attho—**And this is what it means.*";
P_HTM[3476]="*samatittiko telapattoti kho, bhikkhave, kāyagatāya etaṃ satiyā adhivacanaṃ.**‘A bowl of oil filled to the brim’ is a term for mindfulness of the body.*";
P_HTM[3477]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, evaṃ sikkhitabbaṃ:**So you should train like this:*";
P_HTM[3478]="*‘kāyagatā sati no bhāvitā bhavissati bahulīkatā yānīkatā vatthukatā anuṭṭhitā paricitā susamāraddhā’ti.**‘We will develop mindfulness of the body. We’ll cultivate it, make it our vehicle and our basis, keep it up, consolidate it, and properly implement it.’*";
P_HTM[3479]="*Evañhi kho, bhikkhave, sikkhitabban”ti.**That’s how you should train.”*";
P_HTM[3480]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3481]="*Nālandavaggo dutiyo.* **";
P_HTM[3482]="*Mahāpuriso nālandaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[3483]="*Cundo celañca bāhiyo;* **";
P_HTM[3484]="*Uttiyo ariyo brahmā,* **";
P_HTM[3485]="*Sedakaṃ janapadena cāti.* **";
P_HTM[3486]="*5. Bāhiyasuttaṃ**Ethics*";
P_HTM[3487]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[3488]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ āyasmā ca ānando āyasmā ca bhaddo pāṭaliputte viharanti kukkuṭārāme.**At one time the venerables Ānanda and Bhadda were staying at Pāṭaliputta, in the Chicken Monastery.*";
P_HTM[3489]="*Atha kho āyasmā bhaddo sāyanhasamayaṃ paṭisallānā vuṭṭhito yenāyasmā ānando tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmatā ānandena saddhiṃ sammodi.**Then in the late afternoon, Venerable Bhadda came out of retreat, went to Venerable Ānanda, and exchanged greetings with him.*";
P_HTM[3490]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā bhaddo āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ etadavoca:**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, he sat down to one side and said to Ānanda:*";
P_HTM[3491]="*“yānimāni, āvuso ānanda, kusalāni sīlāni vuttāni bhagavatā, imāni kusalāni sīlāni kimatthiyāni vuttāni bhagavatā”ti?**“Reverend Ānanda, the Buddha has spoken of skillful ethics. What’s their purpose?”*";
P_HTM[3492]="*“Sādhu sādhu, āvuso bhadda.**“Good, good, Reverend Bhadda!*";
P_HTM[3493]="*Bhaddako kho te, āvuso bhadda, ummaṅgo, bhaddakaṃ paṭibhānaṃ, kalyāṇī paripucchā.**Your approach and articulation are excellent, and it’s a good question.*";
P_HTM[3494]="*Evañhi tvaṃ, āvuso bhadda, pucchasi:**For you asked:*";
P_HTM[3495]="*‘yānimāni, āvuso ānanda, kusalāni sīlāni vuttāni bhagavatā, imāni kusalāni sīlāni kimatthiyāni vuttāni bhagavatā’”ti?**‘The Buddha has spoken of skillful ethics. What’s their purpose?’”*";
P_HTM[3496]="*“Evamāvuso”ti.**“Yes, reverend.”*";
P_HTM[3497]="*“Yānimāni, āvuso bhadda, kusalāni sīlāni vuttāni bhagavatā, imāni kusalāni sīlāni yāvadeva catunnaṃ satipaṭṭhānānaṃ bhāvanāya vuttāni bhagavatā.**“The Buddha has spoken of skillful ethics to the extent necessary for developing the four kinds of mindfulness meditation.*";
P_HTM[3498]="*Katamesaṃ catunnaṃ?**What four?*";
P_HTM[3499]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;**It’s when a mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3500]="*vedanāsu … pe …**They meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[3501]="*citte … pe …**mind …*";
P_HTM[3502]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3503]="*Yānimāni, āvuso bhadda, kusalāni sīlāni vuttāni bhagavatā, imāni kusalāni sīlāni yāvadeva imesaṃ catunnaṃ satipaṭṭhānānaṃ bhāvanāya vuttāni bhagavatā”ti.**The Buddha has spoken of skillful ethics to the extent necessary for developing the four kinds of mindfulness meditation.”*";
P_HTM[3504]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3505]="*6. Uttiyasuttaṃ**Long Lasting*";
P_HTM[3506]="*Taṃyeva nidānaṃ.**The same setting.*";
P_HTM[3507]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā bhaddo āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ etadavoca:* **";
P_HTM[3508]="*“ko nu kho, āvuso ānanda, hetu, ko paccayo yena tathāgate parinibbute saddhammo na ciraṭṭhitiko hoti?**“What is the cause, Reverend Ānanda, what is the reason why the true teaching does not last long after the final extinguishment of the Realized One?*";
P_HTM[3509]="*Ko panāvuso ānanda, hetu, ko paccayo yena tathāgate parinibbute saddhammo ciraṭṭhitiko hotī”ti?**What is the cause, what is the reason why the true teaching does last long after the final extinguishment of the Realized One?”*";
P_HTM[3510]="*“Sādhu sādhu, āvuso bhadda.**“Good, good, Reverend Bhadda!*";
P_HTM[3511]="*Bhaddako kho te, āvuso bhadda, ummaṅgo, bhaddakaṃ paṭibhānaṃ, kalyāṇī paripucchā.**Your approach and articulation are excellent, and it’s a good question.*";
P_HTM[3512]="*Evañhi tvaṃ, āvuso bhadda, pucchasi:**For you asked:*";
P_HTM[3513]="*‘ko nu kho, āvuso ānanda, hetu, ko paccayo yena tathāgate parinibbute saddhammo na ciraṭṭhitiko hoti?**‘What is the cause, Reverend Ānanda, what is the reason why the true teaching does not last long after the final extinguishment of the Realized One?*";
P_HTM[3514]="*Ko panāvuso ānanda, hetu, ko paccayo yena tathāgate parinibbute saddhammo ciraṭṭhitiko hotī’”ti?**What is the cause, what is the reason why the true teaching does last long after the final extinguishment of the Realized One?’”*";
P_HTM[3515]="*“Evamāvuso”ti.**“Yes, reverend.”*";
P_HTM[3516]="*“Catunnaṃ kho, āvuso, satipaṭṭhānānaṃ abhāvitattā abahulīkatattā tathāgate parinibbute saddhammo na ciraṭṭhitiko hoti.**“It’s because of not developing and cultivating the four kinds of mindfulness meditation that the true teaching doesn’t last long after the final extinguishment of the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[3517]="*Catunnañca kho, āvuso, satipaṭṭhānānaṃ bhāvitattā bahulīkatattā tathāgate parinibbute saddhammo ciraṭṭhitiko hoti.**It’s because of developing and cultivating the four kinds of mindfulness meditation that the true teaching does last long after the final extinguishment of the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[3518]="*Katamesaṃ catunnaṃ?**What four?*";
P_HTM[3519]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;**It’s when a mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3520]="*vedanāsu … pe …**They meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[3521]="*citte … pe …**mind …*";
P_HTM[3522]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3523]="*Imesaṃ kho, āvuso, catunnaṃ satipaṭṭhānānaṃ abhāvitattā abahulīkatattā tathāgate parinibbute saddhammo na ciraṭṭhitiko hoti.**It’s because of not developing and cultivating these four kinds of mindfulness meditation that the true teaching doesn’t last long after the final extinguishment of the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[3524]="*Imesañca kho, āvuso, catunnaṃ satipaṭṭhānānaṃ bhāvitattā bahulīkatattā tathāgate parinibbute saddhammo ciraṭṭhitiko hotī”ti.**It’s because of developing and cultivating these four kinds of mindfulness meditation that the true teaching does last long after the final extinguishment of the Realized One.”*";
P_HTM[3525]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3526]="*7. Ariyasuttaṃ**Decline*";
P_HTM[3527]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ āyasmā ca ānando āyasmā ca bhaddo pāṭaliputte viharanti kukkuṭārāme.**At one time the venerables Ānanda and Bhadda were staying at Pāṭaliputta, in the Chicken Monastery.*";
P_HTM[3528]="*Atha kho āyasmā bhaddo sāyanhasamayaṃ paṭisallānā vuṭṭhito yenāyasmā ānando tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmatā ānandena saddhiṃ sammodi.**Then in the late afternoon, Venerable Bhadda came out of retreat, went to Venerable Ānanda, and exchanged greetings with him.*";
P_HTM[3529]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā bhaddo āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ etadavoca:**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, he sat down to one side and said to Ānanda:*";
P_HTM[3530]="*“ko nu kho, āvuso ānanda, hetu, ko paccayo yena saddhammaparihānaṃ hoti?**“What’s the cause, Reverend Ānanda, what’s the reason why the true teaching declines?*";
P_HTM[3531]="*Ko nu kho, āvuso ānanda, hetu, ko paccayo yena saddhammaaparihānaṃ hotī”ti?**And what’s the cause, what’s the reason why the true teaching doesn’t decline?”*";
P_HTM[3532]="*“Sādhu sādhu, āvuso bhadda.**“Good, good, Reverend Bhadda!*";
P_HTM[3533]="*Bhaddako kho te, āvuso bhadda, ummaṅgo, bhaddakaṃ paṭibhānaṃ, kalyāṇī paripucchā.**Your approach and articulation are excellent, and it’s a good question.*";
P_HTM[3534]="*Evañhi tvaṃ, āvuso bhadda, pucchasi:**For you asked:*";
P_HTM[3535]="*‘ko nu kho, āvuso ānanda, hetu, ko paccayo yena saddhammaparihānaṃ hoti?**‘What’s the cause, what’s the reason why the true teaching declines?*";
P_HTM[3536]="*Ko panāvuso ānanda, hetu, ko paccayo yena saddhammaaparihānaṃ hotī’”ti?**And what’s the cause, what’s the reason why the true teaching doesn’t decline?’”*";
P_HTM[3537]="*“Evamāvuso”ti.**“Yes, reverend.”*";
P_HTM[3538]="*“Catunnaṃ kho, āvuso, satipaṭṭhānānaṃ abhāvitattā abahulīkatattā saddhammaparihānaṃ hoti.**“It’s because of not developing and cultivating the four kinds of mindfulness meditation that the true teaching declines.*";
P_HTM[3539]="*Catunnañca kho, āvuso, satipaṭṭhānānaṃ bhāvitattā bahulīkatattā saddhammaaparihānaṃ hoti.**It’s because of developing and cultivating the four kinds of mindfulness meditation that the true teaching doesn’t decline.*";
P_HTM[3540]="*Katamesaṃ catunnaṃ?**What four?*";
P_HTM[3541]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;**It’s when a mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3542]="*vedanāsu … pe …**They meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[3543]="*citte … pe …**mind …*";
P_HTM[3544]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3545]="*Imesaṃ kho, āvuso, catunnaṃ satipaṭṭhānānaṃ abhāvitattā abahulīkatattā saddhammaparihānaṃ hoti.**It’s because of not developing and cultivating these four kinds of mindfulness meditation that the true teaching declines.*";
P_HTM[3546]="*Imesañca kho, āvuso, catunnaṃ satipaṭṭhānānaṃ bhāvitattā bahulīkatattā saddhammaaparihānaṃ hotī”ti.**And it’s because of developing and cultivating these four kinds of mindfulness meditation that the true teaching doesn’t decline.”*";
P_HTM[3547]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3548]="*8. Brahmasuttaṃ**Plain Version*";
P_HTM[3549]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[3550]="*“Cattārome, bhikkhave, satipaṭṭhānā.**“Mendicants, there are these four kinds of mindfulness meditation.*";
P_HTM[3551]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[3552]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;**It’s when a mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3553]="*vedanāsu … pe …**They meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[3554]="*citte … pe …**mind …*";
P_HTM[3555]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3556]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, cattāro satipaṭṭhānā”ti.**These are the four kinds of mindfulness meditation.”*";
P_HTM[3557]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3558]="*9. Sedakasuttaṃ**A Certain Brahmin*";
P_HTM[3559]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[3560]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati jetavane anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery.*";
P_HTM[3561]="*Atha kho aññataro brāhmaṇo yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavatā saddhiṃ sammodi.**Then a certain brahmin went up to the Buddha, and exchanged greetings with him.*";
P_HTM[3562]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho so brāhmaṇo bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, he sat down to one side and said to the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[3563]="*“ko nu kho, bho gotama, hetu, ko paccayo yena tathāgate parinibbute saddhammo na ciraṭṭhitiko hoti?**“What is the cause, Master Gotama, what is the reason why the true teaching does not last long after the final extinguishment of the Realized One?*";
P_HTM[3564]="*Ko pana, bho gotama, hetu, ko paccayo yena tathāgate parinibbute saddhammo ciraṭṭhitiko hotī”ti?**And what is the cause, what is the reason why the true teaching does last long after the final extinguishment of the Realized One?”*";
P_HTM[3565]="*“Catunnaṃ kho, brāhmaṇa, satipaṭṭhānānaṃ abhāvitattā abahulīkatattā tathāgate parinibbute saddhammo na ciraṭṭhitiko hoti.**“Brahmin, it’s because of not developing and cultivating the four kinds of mindfulness meditation that the true teaching doesn’t last long after the final extinguishment of the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[3566]="*Catunnañca kho, brāhmaṇa, satipaṭṭhānānaṃ bhāvitattā bahulīkatattā tathāgate parinibbute saddhammo ciraṭṭhitiko hoti.**It’s because of developing and cultivating the four kinds of mindfulness meditation that the true teaching does last long after the final extinguishment of the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[3567]="*Katamesaṃ catunnaṃ?**What four?*";
P_HTM[3568]="*Idha, brāhmaṇa, bhikkhu kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;**It’s when a mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3569]="*vedanāsu … pe …**They meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[3570]="*citte … pe …**mind …*";
P_HTM[3571]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3572]="*Imesaṃ kho, brāhmaṇa, catunnaṃ satipaṭṭhānānaṃ abhāvitattā abahulīkatattā tathāgate parinibbute saddhammo na ciraṭṭhitiko hoti.**It’s because of not developing and cultivating these four kinds of mindfulness meditation that the true teaching doesn’t last long after the final extinguishment of the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[3573]="*Imesañca kho, brāhmaṇa, catunnaṃ satipaṭṭhānānaṃ bhāvitattā bahulīkatattā tathāgate parinibbute saddhammo ciraṭṭhitiko hotī”ti.**It’s because of developing and cultivating these four kinds of mindfulness meditation that the true teaching does last long after the final extinguishment of the Realized One.”*";
P_HTM[3574]="*Evaṃ vutte, so brāhmaṇo bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When he said this, the brahmin said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[3575]="*“abhikkantaṃ, bho gotama … pe …**“Excellent, Master Gotama! Excellent! …*";
P_HTM[3576]="*upāsakaṃ maṃ bhavaṃ gotamo dhāretu ajjatagge pāṇupetaṃ saraṇaṃ gatan”ti.**From this day forth, may Master Gotama remember me as a lay follower who has gone for refuge for life.”*";
P_HTM[3577]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3578]="*10. Janapadakalyāṇīsuttaṃ**Partly*";
P_HTM[3579]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ āyasmā ca sāriputto āyasmā ca mahāmoggallāno āyasmā ca anuruddho sākete viharanti kaṇḍakīvane.**At one time the venerables Sāriputta, Mahāmoggallāna, and Anuruddha were staying near Sāketa, in the Thorny Wood.*";
P_HTM[3580]="*Atha kho āyasmā ca sāriputto āyasmā ca mahāmoggallāno sāyanhasamayaṃ paṭisallānā vuṭṭhitā yenāyasmā anuruddho tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmatā anuruddhena saddhiṃ sammodiṃsu.**Then in the late afternoon, Sāriputta and Mahāmoggallāna came out of retreat, went to Anuruddha, and exchanged greetings with him.*";
P_HTM[3581]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā sāriputto āyasmantaṃ anuruddhaṃ etadavoca:**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, they sat down to one side. Sāriputta said to Anuruddha:*";
P_HTM[3582]="*“‘sekho, sekho’ti, āvuso anuruddha, vuccati.**“Reverend, they speak of this person called ‘a trainee’.*";
P_HTM[3583]="*Kittāvatā nu kho, āvuso, sekho hotī”ti?**How is a trainee defined?”*";
P_HTM[3584]="*“Catunnaṃ kho, āvuso, satipaṭṭhānānaṃ padesaṃ bhāvitattā sekho hoti.**“Reverends, a trainee is someone who has partly developed the four kinds of mindfulness meditation.*";
P_HTM[3585]="*Katamesaṃ catunnaṃ?**What four?*";
P_HTM[3586]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;**It’s when a mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3587]="*vedanāsu … pe …**They meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[3588]="*citte … pe …**mind …*";
P_HTM[3589]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3590]="*Imesaṃ kho, āvuso, catunnaṃ satipaṭṭhānānaṃ padesaṃ bhāvitattā sekho hotī”ti.**A trainee is someone who has partly developed the four kinds of mindfulness meditation.”*";
P_HTM[3591]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3592]="*7. Appamādavaggo**Ethics and Duration*";
P_HTM[3593]="*1. Sīlasuttaṃ**Completely*";
P_HTM[3594]="*Taṃyeva nidānaṃ.**The same setting.*";
P_HTM[3595]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā sāriputto āyasmantaṃ anuruddhaṃ etadavoca:* **";
P_HTM[3596]="*“‘asekho, asekho’ti, āvuso anuruddha, vuccati.**“Reverend, they speak of this person called ‘an adept’.*";
P_HTM[3597]="*Kittāvatā nu kho, āvuso, asekho hotī”ti?**How is an adept defined?”*";
P_HTM[3598]="*“Catunnaṃ kho, āvuso, satipaṭṭhānānaṃ samattaṃ bhāvitattā asekho hoti.**“Reverends, an adept is someone who has completely developed the four kinds of mindfulness meditation.*";
P_HTM[3599]="*Katamesaṃ catunnaṃ?**What four?*";
P_HTM[3600]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;**It’s when a mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3601]="*vedanāsu … pe …**They meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[3602]="*citte … pe …**mind …*";
P_HTM[3603]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3604]="*Imesaṃ kho, āvuso, catunnaṃ satipaṭṭhānānaṃ samattaṃ bhāvitattā asekho hotī”ti.**An adept is someone who has completely developed the four kinds of mindfulness meditation.”*";
P_HTM[3605]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3606]="*2. Ciraṭṭhitisuttaṃ**The World*";
P_HTM[3607]="*Taṃyeva nidānaṃ.**The same setting.*";
P_HTM[3608]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā sāriputto āyasmantaṃ anuruddhaṃ etadavoca:* **";
P_HTM[3609]="*“katamesaṃ, āvuso anuruddha, dhammānaṃ bhāvitattā bahulīkatattā mahābhiññataṃ patto”ti?**“Reverend Anuruddha, what things have you developed and cultivated to attain great direct knowledge?”*";
P_HTM[3610]="*“Catunnaṃ, āvuso, satipaṭṭhānānaṃ bhāvitattā bahulīkatattā mahābhiññataṃ patto.**“Reverend, I attained great direct knowledge by developing and cultivating the four kinds of mindfulness meditation.*";
P_HTM[3611]="*Katamesaṃ catunnaṃ?**What four?*";
P_HTM[3612]="*Idhāhaṃ, āvuso, kāye kāyānupassī viharāmi ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;**It’s when I meditate observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3613]="*vedanāsu … pe …**I meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[3614]="*citte … pe …**mind …*";
P_HTM[3615]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharāmi ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3616]="*Imesaṃ khvāhaṃ, āvuso, catunnaṃ satipaṭṭhānānaṃ bhāvitattā bahulīkatattā mahābhiññataṃ patto.**I attained great direct knowledge by developing and cultivating these four kinds of mindfulness meditation.*";
P_HTM[3617]="*Imesañca panāhaṃ, āvuso, catunnaṃ satipaṭṭhānānaṃ bhāvitattā bahulīkatattā sahassaṃ lokaṃ abhijānāmī”ti.**And it’s because of developing and cultivating these four kinds of mindfulness meditation that I directly know the entire galaxy.”*";
P_HTM[3618]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3619]="*3. Parihānasuttaṃ**With Sirivaḍḍha*";
P_HTM[3620]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ āyasmā ānando rājagahe viharati veḷuvane kalandakanivāpe.**At one time Venerable Ānanda was staying near Rājagaha, in the Bamboo Grove, the squirrels’ feeding ground.*";
P_HTM[3621]="*Tena kho pana samayena sirivaḍḍho gahapati ābādhiko hoti dukkhito bāḷhagilāno.**Now at that time the householder Sirivaḍḍha was sick, suffering, gravely ill.*";
P_HTM[3622]="*Atha kho sirivaḍḍho gahapati aññataraṃ purisaṃ āmantesi:**Then he addressed a man:*";
P_HTM[3623]="*“ehi tvaṃ, ambho purisa, yenāyasmā ānando tenupasaṅkama; upasaṅkamitvā mama vacanena āyasmato ānandassa pāde sirasā vanda:**“Please, mister, go to Venerable Ānanda, and in my name bow with your head to his feet. Say to him:*";
P_HTM[3624]="*‘sirivaḍḍho, bhante, gahapati ābādhiko dukkhito bāḷhagilāno.**‘Sir, the householder Sirivaḍḍha is sick, suffering, gravely ill.*";
P_HTM[3625]="*So āyasmato ānandassa pāde sirasā vandatī’ti.**He bows with his head to your feet.’*";
P_HTM[3626]="*Evañca vadehi:**And then say:*";
P_HTM[3627]="*‘sādhu kira, bhante, āyasmā ānando yena sirivaḍḍhassa gahapatissa nivesanaṃ tenupasaṅkamatu anukampaṃ upādāyā’”ti.**‘Sir, please visit him at his home out of compassion.’”*";
P_HTM[3628]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho so puriso sirivaḍḍhassa gahapatissa paṭissutvā yenāyasmā ānando tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho so puriso āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ etadavoca:**“Yes, sir,” that man replied. He did as Sirivaḍḍha asked.*";
P_HTM[3629]="*“sirivaḍḍho, bhante, gahapati ābādhiko dukkhito bāḷhagilāno, so āyasmato ānandassa pāde sirasā vandati.* **";
P_HTM[3630]="*Evañca vadeti:* **";
P_HTM[3631]="*‘sādhu kira, bhante, āyasmā ānando yena sirivaḍḍhassa gahapatissa nivesanaṃ tenupasaṅkamatu anukampaṃ upādāyā’”ti.* **";
P_HTM[3632]="*Adhivāsesi kho āyasmā ānando tuṇhībhāvena.**Ānanda consented in silence.*";
P_HTM[3633]="*Atha kho āyasmā ānando pubbaṇhasamayaṃ nivāsetvā pattacīvaramādāya yena sirivaḍḍhassa gahapatissa nivesanaṃ tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā paññatte āsane nisīdi. Nisajja kho āyasmā ānando sirivaḍḍhaṃ gahapatiṃ etadavoca:**Then Venerable Ānanda robed up in the morning and, taking his bowl and robe, went to the home of the householder Sirivaḍḍha, sat down on the seat spread out, and said to him:*";
P_HTM[3634]="*“kacci te, gahapati, khamanīyaṃ kacci yāpanīyaṃ, kacci dukkhā vedanā paṭikkamanti, no abhikkamanti; paṭikkamosānaṃ paññāyati, no abhikkamo”ti?**“Householder, I hope you’re coping; I hope you’re getting better. And I hope the pain is fading, not growing, that its fading is evident, not its growing.”*";
P_HTM[3635]="*“Na me, bhante, khamanīyaṃ na yāpanīyaṃ. Bāḷhā me dukkhā vedanā abhikkamanti, no paṭikkamanti; abhikkamosānaṃ paññāyati, no paṭikkamo”ti.**“Sir, I’m not keeping well, I’m not alright. The pain is terrible and growing, not fading; its growing is evident, not its fading.”*";
P_HTM[3636]="*“Tasmātiha te, gahapati, evaṃ sikkhitabbaṃ:**“So you should train like this:*";
P_HTM[3637]="*‘kāye kāyānupassī viharissāmi ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;**‘I’ll meditate observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3638]="*vedanāsu … pe …**I’ll meditate on an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[3639]="*citte … pe …**mind …*";
P_HTM[3640]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharissāmi ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassan’ti.**principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.’*";
P_HTM[3641]="*Evañhi te, gahapati, sikkhitabban”ti.**That’s how you should train.”*";
P_HTM[3642]="*“Yeme, bhante, bhagavatā cattāro satipaṭṭhānā desitā saṃvijjanti, te dhammā mayi, ahañca tesu dhammesu sandissāmi.**“These four kinds of mindfulness meditation that were taught by the Buddha are found in me, and I am seen in them.*";
P_HTM[3643]="*Ahañhi, bhante, kāye kāyānupassī viharāmi ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;**For I meditate observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3644]="*vedanāsu … pe …**I meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[3645]="*citte … pe …**mind …*";
P_HTM[3646]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharāmi ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3647]="*Yāni cimāni, bhante, bhagavatā pañcorambhāgiyāni saṃyojanāni desitāni, nāhaṃ, bhante, tesaṃ kiñci attani appahīnaṃ samanupassāmī”ti.**And of the five lower fetters taught by the Buddha, I don’t see any that I haven’t given up.”*";
P_HTM[3648]="*“Lābhā te, gahapati, suladdhaṃ te, gahapati.**“You’re fortunate, householder, so very fortunate!*";
P_HTM[3649]="*Anāgāmiphalaṃ tayā, gahapati, byākatan”ti.**You have declared the fruit of non-return.”*";
P_HTM[3650]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3651]="*4. Suddhasuttaṃ**With Mānadinna*";
P_HTM[3652]="*Taṃyeva nidānaṃ.**The same setting.*";
P_HTM[3653]="*Tena kho pana samayena mānadinno gahapati ābādhiko hoti dukkhito bāḷhagilāno.**Now at that time the householder Mānadinna was sick, suffering, gravely ill.*";
P_HTM[3654]="*Atha kho mānadinno gahapati aññataraṃ purisaṃ āmantesi:**Then he addressed a man:*";
P_HTM[3655]="*“ehi tvaṃ, ambho purisa … pe …**“Please, mister, go to Venerable Ānanda …” …*";
P_HTM[3656]="*na me, bhante, khamanīyaṃ na yāpanīyaṃ. Bāḷhā me dukkhā vedanā abhikkamanti, no paṭikkamanti; abhikkamosānaṃ paññāyati, no paṭikkamoti.**“Sir, I’m not keeping well, I’m not alright. The pain is terrible and growing, not fading; its growing is evident, not its fading.*";
P_HTM[3657]="*Evarūpāya cāhaṃ, bhante, dukkhāya vedanāya phuṭṭho samāno kāye kāyānupassī viharāmi ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;**When I experience such painful feelings I meditate observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3658]="*vedanāsu … pe …**I meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[3659]="*citte … pe …**mind …*";
P_HTM[3660]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharāmi ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3661]="*Yāni cimāni, bhante, bhagavatā pañcorambhāgiyāni saṃyojanāni desitāni, nāhaṃ, bhante, tesaṃ kiñci attani appahīnaṃ samanupassāmī”ti.**And of the five lower fetters taught by the Buddha, I don’t see any that I haven’t given up.”*";
P_HTM[3662]="*“Lābhā te, gahapati, suladdhaṃ te, gahapati.**“You’re fortunate, householder, so very fortunate!*";
P_HTM[3663]="*Anāgāmiphalaṃ tayā, gahapati, byākatan”ti.**You have declared the fruit of non-return.”*";
P_HTM[3664]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3665]="*Sīlaṭṭhitivaggo tatiyo.* **";
P_HTM[3666]="*Sīlaṃ ṭhiti parihānaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[3667]="*suddhaṃ brāhmaṇapadesaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[3668]="*Samattaṃ loko sirivaḍḍho,* **";
P_HTM[3669]="*mānadinnena te dasāti.* **";
P_HTM[3670]="*5. Aññatarabrāhmaṇasuttaṃ**Not Learned From Anyone Else*";
P_HTM[3671]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[3672]="*“‘Ayaṃ kāye kāyānupassanā’ti me, bhikkhave, pubbe ananussutesu dhammesu cakkhuṃ udapādi, ñāṇaṃ udapādi, paññā udapādi, vijjā udapādi, āloko udapādi.**“‘This is the observation of an aspect of the body.’ Such, mendicants, was the vision, knowledge, wisdom, realization, and light that arose in me regarding teachings not learned before from another.*";
P_HTM[3673]="*‘Sā kho panāyaṃ kāye kāyānupassanā bhāvetabbā’ti me, bhikkhave … pe …**‘This observation of an aspect of the body should be developed.’ …*";
P_HTM[3674]="*bhāvitā’ti me, bhikkhave, pubbe ananussutesu dhammesu cakkhuṃ udapādi, ñāṇaṃ udapādi, paññā udapādi, vijjā udapādi, āloko udapādi.**‘This observation of an aspect of the body has been developed.’ Such was the vision, knowledge, wisdom, realization, and light that arose in me regarding teachings not learned before from another.*";
P_HTM[3675]="*‘Ayaṃ vedanāsu vedanānupassanā’ti me, bhikkhave, pubbe ananussutesu dhammesu cakkhuṃ udapādi, ñāṇaṃ udapādi, paññā udapādi, vijjā udapādi, āloko udapādi.**‘This is the observation of an aspect of feelings.’ …*";
P_HTM[3676]="*‘Sā kho panāyaṃ vedanāsu vedanānupassanā bhāvetabbā’ti me, bhikkhave … pe …**‘This observation of an aspect of feelings should be developed.’ …*";
P_HTM[3677]="*bhāvitā’ti me, bhikkhave, pubbe ananussutesu dhammesu cakkhuṃ udapādi, ñāṇaṃ udapādi, paññā udapādi, vijjā udapādi, āloko udapādi.**‘This observation of an aspect of feelings has been developed.’ …*";
P_HTM[3678]="*‘Ayaṃ citte cittānupassanā’ti me, bhikkhave, pubbe ananussutesu dhammesu cakkhuṃ udapādi, ñāṇaṃ udapādi, paññā udapādi, vijjā udapādi, āloko udapādi.**‘This is the observation of an aspect of the mind.’ …*";
P_HTM[3679]="*‘Sā kho panāyaṃ citte cittānupassanā bhāvetabbā’ti me, bhikkhave … pe …**‘This observation of an aspect of the mind should be developed.’ …*";
P_HTM[3680]="*bhāvitā’ti me, bhikkhave, pubbe ananussutesu dhammesu cakkhuṃ udapādi, ñāṇaṃ udapādi, paññā udapādi, vijjā udapādi, āloko udapādi.**‘This observation of an aspect of the mind has been developed.’ …*";
P_HTM[3681]="*‘Ayaṃ dhammesu dhammānupassanā’ti me, bhikkhave, pubbe ananussutesu dhammesu cakkhuṃ udapādi, ñāṇaṃ udapādi, paññā udapādi, vijjā udapādi, āloko udapādi.**‘This is the observation of an aspect of principles.’ …*";
P_HTM[3682]="*‘Sā kho panāyaṃ dhammesu dhammānupassanā bhāvetabbā’ti me, bhikkhave … pe …**‘This observation of an aspect of principles should be developed.’ …*";
P_HTM[3683]="*bhāvitā’ti me, bhikkhave, pubbe ananussutesu dhammesu cakkhuṃ udapādi, ñāṇaṃ udapādi, paññā udapādi, vijjā udapādi, āloko udapādī”ti.**‘This observation of an aspect of principles has been developed.’ Such was the vision, knowledge, wisdom, realization, and light that arose in me regarding teachings not learned before from another.”*";
P_HTM[3684]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3685]="*6. Padesasuttaṃ**Fading Away*";
P_HTM[3686]="*“Cattārome, bhikkhave, satipaṭṭhānā bhāvitā bahulīkatā ekantanibbidāya virāgāya nirodhāya upasamāya abhiññāya sambodhāya nibbānāya saṃvattanti.**“Mendicants, these four kinds of mindfulness meditation, when developed and cultivated, lead solely to disillusionment, dispassion, cessation, peace, insight, awakening, and extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[3687]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[3688]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;**It’s when a mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3689]="*vedanāsu … pe …**They meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[3690]="*citte … pe …**mind …*";
P_HTM[3691]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3692]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, cattāro satipaṭṭhānā bhāvitā bahulīkatā ekantanibbidāya virāgāya nirodhāya upasamāya abhiññāya sambodhāya nibbānāya saṃvattantī”ti.**These four kinds of mindfulness meditation, when developed and cultivated, lead solely to disillusionment, dispassion, cessation, peace, insight, awakening, and extinguishment.”*";
P_HTM[3693]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3694]="*7. Samattasuttaṃ**Missed Out*";
P_HTM[3695]="*“Yesaṃ kesañci, bhikkhave, cattāro satipaṭṭhānā viraddhā, viraddho tesaṃ ariyo maggo sammā dukkhakkhayagāmī.**“Mendicants, whoever has missed out on the four kinds of mindfulness meditation has missed out on the noble path to the complete ending of suffering.*";
P_HTM[3696]="*Yesaṃ kesañci, bhikkhave, cattāro satipaṭṭhānā āraddhā, āraddho tesaṃ ariyo maggo sammā dukkhakkhayagāmī.**Whoever has undertaken the four kinds of mindfulness meditation has undertaken the noble path to the complete ending of suffering.*";
P_HTM[3697]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[3698]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;**It’s when a mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3699]="*vedanāsu … pe …**They meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[3700]="*citte … pe …**mind …*";
P_HTM[3701]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3702]="*Yesaṃ kesañci, bhikkhave, ime cattāro satipaṭṭhānā viraddhā, viraddho tesaṃ ariyo maggo sammā dukkhakkhayagāmī.**Whoever has missed out on these four kinds of mindfulness meditation has missed out on the noble path to the complete ending of suffering.*";
P_HTM[3703]="*Yesaṃ kesañci, bhikkhave, ime cattāro satipaṭṭhānā āraddhā, āraddho tesaṃ ariyo maggo sammā dukkhakkhayagāmī”ti.**Whoever has undertaken these four kinds of mindfulness meditation has undertaken the noble path to the complete ending of suffering.”*";
P_HTM[3704]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3705]="*8. Lokasuttaṃ**Developed*";
P_HTM[3706]="*“Cattārome, bhikkhave, satipaṭṭhānā bhāvitā bahulīkatā apārā pāraṃ gamanāya saṃvattanti.**“Mendicants, when these four kinds of mindfulness meditation are developed and cultivated they lead to going from the near shore to the far shore.*";
P_HTM[3707]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[3708]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;**It’s when a mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3709]="*vedanāsu … pe …**They meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[3710]="*citte … pe …**mind …*";
P_HTM[3711]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3712]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, cattāro satipaṭṭhānā bhāvitā bahulīkatā apārā pāraṃ gamanāya saṃvattantī”ti.**When these four kinds of mindfulness meditation are developed and cultivated they lead to going from the near shore to the far shore.”*";
P_HTM[3713]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3714]="*9. Sirivaḍḍhasuttaṃ**Mindful*";
P_HTM[3715]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[3716]="*“Sato, bhikkhave, bhikkhu vihareyya sampajāno.**“Mendicants, a mendicant should live mindful and aware.*";
P_HTM[3717]="*Ayaṃ vo amhākaṃ anusāsanī.**This is my instruction to you.*";
P_HTM[3718]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sato hoti?**And how is a mendicant mindful?*";
P_HTM[3719]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;**It’s when a mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3720]="*vedanāsu … pe …**They meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[3721]="*citte … pe …**mind …*";
P_HTM[3722]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3723]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sato hoti.**That’s how a mendicant is mindful.*";
P_HTM[3724]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sampajāno hoti?**And how is a mendicant aware?*";
P_HTM[3725]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno viditā vedanā uppajjanti, viditā upaṭṭhahanti, viditā abbhatthaṃ gacchanti.**It’s when a mendicant knows feelings as they arise, as they remain, and as they go away.*";
P_HTM[3726]="*Viditā vitakkā uppajjanti, viditā upaṭṭhahanti, viditā abbhatthaṃ gacchanti.**They know thoughts as they arise, as they remain, and as they go away.*";
P_HTM[3727]="*Viditā saññā uppajjanti, viditā upaṭṭhahanti, viditā abbhatthaṃ gacchanti.**They know perceptions as they arise, as they remain, and as they go away.*";
P_HTM[3728]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sampajāno hoti.**That’s how a mendicant is aware.*";
P_HTM[3729]="*Sato, bhikkhave, bhikkhu vihareyya sampajāno.**A mendicant should live mindful and aware.*";
P_HTM[3730]="*Ayaṃ vo amhākaṃ anusāsanī”ti.**This is my instruction to you.”*";
P_HTM[3731]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3732]="*10. Mānadinnasuttaṃ**Enlightenment*";
P_HTM[3733]="*“Cattārome, bhikkhave, satipaṭṭhānā.**“Mendicants, there are these four kinds of mindfulness meditation.*";
P_HTM[3734]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[3735]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;**It’s when a mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3736]="*vedanāsu … pe …**They meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[3737]="*citte … pe …**mind …*";
P_HTM[3738]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3739]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, cattāro satipaṭṭhānā.**These are the four kinds of mindfulness meditation.*";
P_HTM[3740]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, catunnaṃ satipaṭṭhānānaṃ bhāvitattā bahulīkatattā dvinnaṃ phalānaṃ aññataraṃ phalaṃ pāṭikaṅkhaṃ—**Because of developing and cultivating these four kinds of mindfulness meditation, one of two results can be expected:*";
P_HTM[3741]="*diṭṭheva dhamme aññā, sati vā upādisese anāgāmitā”ti.**enlightenment in the present life, or if there’s something left over, non-return.”*";
P_HTM[3742]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3743]="*8. Balakaraṇīyavaggo**Not Learned From Anyone Else*";
P_HTM[3744]="*1. Ananussutasuttaṃ**Desire*";
P_HTM[3745]="*“Cattārome, bhikkhave, satipaṭṭhānā.**“Mendicants, there are these four kinds of mindfulness meditation.*";
P_HTM[3746]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[3747]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**It’s when a mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3748]="*Tassa kāye kāyānupassino viharato yo kāyasmiṃ chando so pahīyati.**As they do so they give up desire for the body.*";
P_HTM[3749]="*Chandassa pahānā amataṃ sacchikataṃ hoti.**When desire is given up they realize the deathless.*";
P_HTM[3750]="*Vedanāsu vedanānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**They meditate observing an aspect of feelings—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3751]="*Tassa vedanāsu vedanānupassino viharato yo vedanāsu chando so pahīyati.**As they do so they give up desire for feelings.*";
P_HTM[3752]="*Chandassa pahānā amataṃ sacchikataṃ hoti.**When desire is given up they realize the deathless.*";
P_HTM[3753]="*Citte cittānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**They meditate observing an aspect of the mind—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3754]="*Tassa citte cittānupassino viharato yo cittamhi chando so pahīyati.**As they do so they give up desire for the mind.*";
P_HTM[3755]="*Chandassa pahānā amataṃ sacchikataṃ hoti.**When desire is given up they realize the deathless.*";
P_HTM[3756]="*Dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**They meditate observing an aspect of principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3757]="*Tassa dhammesu dhammānupassino viharato yo dhammesu chando so pahīyati.**As they do so they give up desire for principles.*";
P_HTM[3758]="*Chandassa pahānā amataṃ sacchikataṃ hotī”ti.**When desire is given up they realize the deathless.”*";
P_HTM[3759]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3760]="*2. Virāgasuttaṃ**Complete Understanding*";
P_HTM[3761]="*“Cattārome, bhikkhave, satipaṭṭhānā.**“Mendicants, there are these four kinds of mindfulness meditation.*";
P_HTM[3762]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[3763]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**It’s when a mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3764]="*Tassa kāye kāyānupassino viharato kāyo pariññāto hoti.**As they do so they completely understand the body.*";
P_HTM[3765]="*Kāyassa pariññātattā amataṃ sacchikataṃ hoti.**When the body is completely understood they realize the deathless.*";
P_HTM[3766]="*Vedanāsu vedanānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**They meditate observing an aspect of feelings—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3767]="*Tassa vedanāsu vedanānupassino viharato vedanā pariññātā honti.**As they do so they completely understand feelings.*";
P_HTM[3768]="*Vedanānaṃ pariññātattā amataṃ sacchikataṃ hoti.**When feelings are completely understood they realize the deathless.*";
P_HTM[3769]="*Citte cittānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**They meditate observing an aspect of the mind—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3770]="*Tassa citte cittānupassino viharato cittaṃ pariññātaṃ hoti.**As they do so they completely understand the mind.*";
P_HTM[3771]="*Cittassa pariññātattā amataṃ sacchikataṃ hoti.**When the mind is completely understood they realize the deathless.*";
P_HTM[3772]="*Dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**They meditate observing an aspect of principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3773]="*Tassa dhammesu dhammānupassino viharato dhammā pariññātā honti.**As they do so they completely understand principles.*";
P_HTM[3774]="*Dhammānaṃ pariññātattā amataṃ sacchikataṃ hotī”ti.**When principles are completely understood they realize the deathless.”*";
P_HTM[3775]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3776]="*3. Viraddhasuttaṃ**Development*";
P_HTM[3777]="*“Catunnaṃ, bhikkhave, satipaṭṭhānānaṃ bhāvanaṃ desessāmi.**“Mendicants, I will teach you the development of the four kinds of mindfulness meditation.*";
P_HTM[3778]="*Taṃ suṇātha.**Listen …*";
P_HTM[3779]="*Katamā, bhikkhave, catunnaṃ satipaṭṭhānānaṃ bhāvanā?**And what is the development of the four kinds of mindfulness meditation?*";
P_HTM[3780]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;**It’s when a mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3781]="*vedanāsu … pe …**They meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[3782]="*citte … pe …**mind …*";
P_HTM[3783]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3784]="*Ayaṃ kho, bhikkhave, catunnaṃ satipaṭṭhānānaṃ bhāvanā”ti.**This is the development of the four kinds of mindfulness meditation.”*";
P_HTM[3785]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3786]="*4. Bhāvitasuttaṃ**Analysis*";
P_HTM[3787]="*“Satipaṭṭhānañca vo, bhikkhave, desessāmi satipaṭṭhānabhāvanañca satipaṭṭhānabhāvanāgāminiñca paṭipadaṃ.**“Mendicants, I will teach you mindfulness meditation, the development of mindfulness meditation, and the practice that leads to the development of mindfulness meditation.*";
P_HTM[3788]="*Taṃ suṇātha.**Listen …*";
P_HTM[3789]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, satipaṭṭhānaṃ?**And what is mindfulness meditation?*";
P_HTM[3790]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;**It’s when a mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3791]="*vedanāsu vedanānupassī viharati … pe …**They meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[3792]="*citte cittānupassī viharati … pe …**mind …*";
P_HTM[3793]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3794]="*Idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, satipaṭṭhānaṃ.**This is called mindfulness meditation.*";
P_HTM[3795]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, satipaṭṭhānabhāvanā?**And what is the development of mindfulness meditation?*";
P_HTM[3796]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu samudayadhammānupassī kāyasmiṃ viharati, vayadhammānupassī kāyasmiṃ viharati, samudayavayadhammānupassī kāyasmiṃ viharati, ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**It’s when a mendicant meditates observing the body as liable to originate, as liable to vanish, and as liable to originate and vanish—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3797]="*Samudayadhammānupassī vedanāsu viharati … pe …**They observe feelings …*";
P_HTM[3798]="*samudayadhammānupassī citte viharati … pe …**mind …*";
P_HTM[3799]="*samudayadhammānupassī dhammesu viharati, vayadhammānupassī dhammesu viharati, samudayavayadhammānupassī dhammesu viharati, ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**principles as liable to originate, as liable to vanish, and as liable to originate and vanish—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3800]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, satipaṭṭhānabhāvanā.**This is called the development of mindfulness meditation.*";
P_HTM[3801]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, satipaṭṭhānabhāvanāgāminī paṭipadā?**And what is the practice that leads to the development of mindfulness meditation?*";
P_HTM[3802]="*Ayameva ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo, seyyathidaṃ—**It is simply this noble eightfold path, that is:*";
P_HTM[3803]="*sammādiṭṭhi, sammāsaṅkappo, sammāvācā, sammākammanto, sammāājīvo, sammāvāyāmo, sammāsati, sammāsamādhi.**right view, right thought, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, and right immersion.*";
P_HTM[3804]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, satipaṭṭhānabhāvanāgāminī paṭipadā”ti.**This is called the practice that leads to the development of mindfulness meditation.”*";
P_HTM[3805]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3806]="*Ananussutavaggo catuttho.* **";
P_HTM[3807]="*Ananussutaṃ virāgo,* **";
P_HTM[3808]="*viraddho bhāvanā sati;* **";
P_HTM[3809]="*Aññā chandaṃ pariññāya,* **";
P_HTM[3810]="*bhāvanā vibhaṅgena cāti.* **";
P_HTM[3811]="*5. Satisuttaṃ**The Deathless*";
P_HTM[3812]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[3813]="*“Catūsu, bhikkhave, satipaṭṭhānesu suppatiṭṭhitacittā viharatha.**“Mendicants, you should meditate with your mind firmly established in the four kinds of mindfulness meditation.*";
P_HTM[3814]="*Mā vo amataṃ panassa.**Don’t let the deathless escape you.*";
P_HTM[3815]="*Katamesu catūsu?**What four?*";
P_HTM[3816]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;**It’s when a mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3817]="*vedanāsu … pe …**They meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[3818]="*citte … pe …**mind …*";
P_HTM[3819]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3820]="*Imesu, bhikkhave, catūsu satipaṭṭhānesu suppatiṭṭhitacittā viharatha.**You should meditate with your mind firmly established in the four kinds of mindfulness meditation.*";
P_HTM[3821]="*Mā vo amataṃ panassā”ti.**Don’t let the deathless escape you.”*";
P_HTM[3822]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3823]="*6. Aññāsuttaṃ**Origin*";
P_HTM[3824]="*“Catunnaṃ, bhikkhave, satipaṭṭhānānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca desessāmi.**“Mendicants, I will teach you the origin and the ending of the four kinds of mindfulness meditation.*";
P_HTM[3825]="*Taṃ suṇātha.**Listen …*";
P_HTM[3826]="*Ko ca, bhikkhave, kāyassa samudayo?**And what is the origin of the body?*";
P_HTM[3827]="*Āhārasamudayā kāyassa samudayo;**The body originates from food.*";
P_HTM[3828]="*āhāranirodhā kāyassa atthaṅgamo.**When food ceases, the body ends.*";
P_HTM[3829]="*Phassasamudayā vedanānaṃ samudayo;**Feelings originate from contact.*";
P_HTM[3830]="*phassanirodhā vedanānaṃ atthaṅgamo.**When contact ceases, feelings end.*";
P_HTM[3831]="*Nāmarūpasamudayā cittassa samudayo;**The mind originates from name and form.*";
P_HTM[3832]="*nāmarūpanirodhā cittassa atthaṅgamo.**When name and form cease, the mind ends.*";
P_HTM[3833]="*Manasikārasamudayā dhammānaṃ samudayo;**Principles originate from attention.*";
P_HTM[3834]="*manasikāranirodhā dhammānaṃ atthaṅgamo”ti.**When focus ends, principles end.”*";
P_HTM[3835]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3836]="*7. Chandasuttaṃ**The Path*";
P_HTM[3837]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[3838]="*Tatra kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**There the Buddha addressed the mendicants:*";
P_HTM[3839]="*“ekamidāhaṃ, bhikkhave, samayaṃ uruvelāyaṃ viharāmi najjā nerañjarāya tīre ajapālanigrodhe paṭhamābhisambuddho.**“Mendicants, at one time, when I was first awakened, I was staying near Uruvelā at the goatherd’s banyan tree on the bank of the Nerañjarā River.*";
P_HTM[3840]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, bhikkhave, rahogatassa paṭisallīnassa evaṃ cetaso parivitakko udapādi:**As I was in private retreat this thought came to mind:*";
P_HTM[3841]="*‘ekāyanvāyaṃ maggo sattānaṃ visuddhiyā sokaparidevānaṃ samatikkamāya dukkhadomanassānaṃ atthaṅgamāya ñāyassa adhigamāya nibbānassa sacchikiriyāya, yadidaṃ—cattāro satipaṭṭhānā.**‘The four kinds of mindfulness meditation are the path to convergence. They are in order to purify sentient beings, to get past sorrow and crying, to make an end of pain and sadness, to end the cycle of suffering, and to realize extinguishment.’*";
P_HTM[3842]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[3843]="*Kāye vā bhikkhu kāyānupassī vihareyya ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;**A mendicant would meditate observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3844]="*vedanāsu vā bhikkhu vedanānupassī vihareyya … pe …**Or they’d meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[3845]="*citte vā bhikkhu cittānupassī vihareyya … pe …**or mind …*";
P_HTM[3846]="*dhammesu vā bhikkhu dhammānupassī vihareyya ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**or principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3847]="*Ekāyanvāyaṃ maggo sattānaṃ visuddhiyā sokaparidevānaṃ samatikkamāya dukkhadomanassānaṃ atthaṅgamāya ñāyassa adhigamāya nibbānassa sacchikiriyāya, yadidaṃ—cattāro satipaṭṭhānā’ti.**The four kinds of mindfulness meditation are the path to convergence. They are in order to purify sentient beings, to get past sorrow and crying, to make an end of pain and sadness, to end the cycle of suffering, and to realize extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[3848]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, brahmā sahampati mama cetasā cetoparivitakkamaññāya—seyyathāpi nāma balavā puriso samiñjitaṃ vā bāhaṃ pasāreyya, pasāritaṃ vā bāhaṃ samiñjeyya; evameva—brahmaloke antarahito mama purato pāturahosi.**And then Brahmā Sahampati, knowing what I was thinking, as easily as a strong person would extend or contract their arm, vanished from the Brahmā realm and reappeared in front of me.*";
P_HTM[3849]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, brahmā sahampati ekaṃsaṃ uttarāsaṅgaṃ karitvā yenāhaṃ tenañjaliṃ paṇāmetvā maṃ etadavoca:**He arranged his robe over one shoulder, knelt on his right knee, raised his joined palms toward the Buddha, and said:*";
P_HTM[3850]="*‘evametaṃ, bhagavā, evametaṃ, sugata.**‘That’s so true, Blessed One! That’s so true, Holy One!*";
P_HTM[3851]="*Ekāyanvāyaṃ, bhante, maggo sattānaṃ visuddhiyā sokaparidevānaṃ samatikkamāya dukkhadomanassānaṃ atthaṅgamāya ñāyassa adhigamāya nibbānassa sacchikiriyāya, yadidaṃ—cattāro satipaṭṭhānā.**Sir, the four kinds of mindfulness meditation are the path to convergence. They are in order to purify sentient beings, to get past sorrow and crying, to make an end of pain and sadness, to end the cycle of suffering, and to realize extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[3852]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[3853]="*Kāye vā, bhante, bhikkhu kāyānupassī vihareyya ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;**A mendicant would meditate observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3854]="*vedanāsu vā … pe …**Or they’d meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[3855]="*citte vā … pe …**or mind …*";
P_HTM[3856]="*dhammesu vā, bhante, bhikkhu dhammānupassī vihareyya ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**or principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3857]="*Ekāyanvāyaṃ, bhante, maggo sattānaṃ visuddhiyā sokaparidevānaṃ samatikkamāya dukkhadomanassānaṃ atthaṅgamāya ñāyassa adhigamāya nibbānassa sacchikiriyāya, yadidaṃ—cattāro satipaṭṭhānā’ti.**The four kinds of mindfulness meditation are the path to convergence. They are in order to purify sentient beings, to get past sorrow and crying, to make an end of pain and sadness, to end the cycle of suffering, and to realize extinguishment.’*";
P_HTM[3858]="*Idamavoca, bhikkhave, brahmā sahampati.**That’s what Brahmā Sahampati said.*";
P_HTM[3859]="*Idaṃ vatvā athāparaṃ etadavoca:**Then he went on to say:*";
P_HTM[3860]="*‘Ekāyanaṃ jātikhayantadassī,**‘The compassionate one, who sees the ending of rebirth,*";
P_HTM[3861]="*Maggaṃ pajānāti hitānukampī;**understands the path to convergence.*";
P_HTM[3862]="*Etena maggena tariṃsu pubbe,**By this path people crossed over before,*";
P_HTM[3863]="*Tarissanti ye ca taranti oghan’”ti.**will cross over, and are crossing over.’”*";
P_HTM[3864]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3865]="*8. Pariññātasuttaṃ**Mindful*";
P_HTM[3866]="*“Sato, bhikkhave, bhikkhu vihareyya.**“Mendicants, a mendicant should live mindfully.*";
P_HTM[3867]="*Ayaṃ vo amhākaṃ anusāsanī.**This is my instruction to you.*";
P_HTM[3868]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sato hoti?**And how is a mendicant mindful?*";
P_HTM[3869]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;**It’s when a mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3870]="*vedanāsu … pe …**They meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[3871]="*citte … pe …**mind …*";
P_HTM[3872]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3873]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sato hoti.**That’s how a mendicant is mindful.*";
P_HTM[3874]="*Sato, bhikkhave, bhikkhu vihareyya.**A mendicant should live mindfully.*";
P_HTM[3875]="*Ayaṃ vo amhākaṃ anusāsanī”ti.**This is my instruction to you.”*";
P_HTM[3876]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3877]="*9. Bhāvanāsuttaṃ**A Heap of the Skillful*";
P_HTM[3878]="*“‘Kusalarāsī’ti, bhikkhave, vadamāno cattāro satipaṭṭhāne sammā vadamāno vadeyya.**“Rightly speaking, mendicants, you’d call these four kinds of mindfulness meditation a ‘heap of the skillful’.*";
P_HTM[3879]="*Kevalo hāyaṃ, bhikkhave, kusalarāsi, yadidaṃ—cattāro satipaṭṭhānā.**For these four kinds of mindfulness meditation are entirely a heap of the skillful.*";
P_HTM[3880]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[3881]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;**It’s when a mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3882]="*vedanāsu … pe …**They meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[3883]="*citte … pe …**mind …*";
P_HTM[3884]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3885]="*‘Kusalarāsī’ti, bhikkhave, vadamāno ime cattāro satipaṭṭhāne sammā vadamāno vadeyya.**Rightly speaking, you’d call these four kinds of mindfulness meditation a ‘heap of the skillful’.*";
P_HTM[3886]="*Kevalo hāyaṃ, bhikkhave, kusalarāsi, yadidaṃ—cattāro satipaṭṭhānā”ti.**For these four kinds of mindfulness meditation are entirely a heap of the skillful.”*";
P_HTM[3887]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3888]="*10. Vibhaṅgasuttaṃ**Restraint in the Monastic Code*";
P_HTM[3889]="*Atha kho aññataro bhikkhu yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami … pe … ekamantaṃ nisinno kho so bhikkhu bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then a mendicant went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him:*";
P_HTM[3890]="*“Sādhu me, bhante, bhagavā saṃkhittena dhammaṃ desetu, yamahaṃ bhagavato dhammaṃ sutvā eko vūpakaṭṭho appamatto ātāpī pahitatto vihareyyan”ti.**“Sir, may the Buddha please teach me Dhamma in brief. When I’ve heard it, I’ll live alone, withdrawn, diligent, keen, and resolute.”*";
P_HTM[3891]="*“Tasmātiha tvaṃ, bhikkhu, ādimeva visodhehi kusalesu dhammesu.**“Well then, mendicant, you should purify the starting point of skillful qualities.*";
P_HTM[3892]="*Ko cādi kusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ?**What is the starting point of skillful qualities?*";
P_HTM[3893]="*Idha tvaṃ, bhikkhu, pātimokkhasaṃvarasaṃvuto viharāhi ācāragocarasampanno aṇumattesu vajjesu bhayadassāvī, samādāya sikkhassu sikkhāpadesu.**Live restrained in the monastic code, conducting yourself well and seeking alms in suitable places. Seeing danger in the slightest fault, keep the rules you’ve undertaken.*";
P_HTM[3894]="*Yato kho tvaṃ, bhikkhu, pātimokkhasaṃvarasaṃvuto viharissasi ācāragocarasampanno aṇumattesu vajjesu bhayadassāvī samādāya sikkhassu sikkhāpadesu; tato tvaṃ, bhikkhu, sīlaṃ nissāya sīle patiṭṭhāya cattāro satipaṭṭhāne bhāveyyāsi.**When you’ve done this, you should develop the four kinds of mindfulness meditation, depending on and grounded on ethics.*";
P_HTM[3895]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[3896]="*Idha tvaṃ, bhikkhu, kāye kāyānupassī viharāhi ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;**Meditate observing an aspect of the body internally—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3897]="*vedanāsu … pe …**Meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[3898]="*citte … pe …**mind …*";
P_HTM[3899]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharāhi ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3900]="*Yato kho tvaṃ, bhikkhu, sīlaṃ nissāya sīle patiṭṭhāya ime cattāro satipaṭṭhāne evaṃ bhāvessasi, tato tuyhaṃ, bhikkhu, yā ratti vā divaso vā āgamissati vuddhiyeva pāṭikaṅkhā kusalesu dhammesu, no parihānī”ti.**When you develop the four kinds of mindfulness meditation in this way, depending on and grounded on ethics, you can expect growth, not decline, in skillful qualities, whether by day or by night.”*";
P_HTM[3901]="*Atha kho so bhikkhu bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinanditvā anumoditvā uṭṭhāyāsanā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā pakkāmi.**And then that mendicant approved and agreed with what the Buddha said. He got up from his seat, bowed, and respectfully circled the Buddha, keeping him on his right, before leaving.*";
P_HTM[3902]="*Atha kho so bhikkhu eko vūpakaṭṭho appamatto ātāpī pahitatto viharanto nacirasseva—yassatthāya kulaputtā sammadeva agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajanti, tadanuttaraṃ—brahmacariyapariyosānaṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharati.**Then that mendicant, living alone, withdrawn, diligent, keen, and resolute, soon realized the supreme end of the spiritual path in this very life. He lived having achieved with his own insight the goal for which gentlemen rightly go forth from the lay life to homelessness.*";
P_HTM[3903]="*“Khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyā”ti abbhaññāsi.**He understood: “Rebirth is ended; the spiritual journey has been completed; what had to be done has been done; there is no return to any state of existence.”*";
P_HTM[3904]="*Aññataro ca pana so bhikkhu arahataṃ ahosīti.**And that mendicant became one of the perfected.*";
P_HTM[3905]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3906]="*9. Esanāvaggo**The Deathless*";
P_HTM[3907]="*1. Amatasuttaṃ**Bad Conduct*";
P_HTM[3908]="*Atha kho aññataro bhikkhu yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami … pe …**Then a mendicant went up to the Buddha … and said:*";
P_HTM[3909]="*“sādhu me, bhante, bhagavā saṅkhittena dhammaṃ desetu, yamahaṃ bhagavato dhammaṃ sutvā eko vūpakaṭṭho appamatto ātāpī pahitatto vihareyyan”ti.**“Sir, may the Buddha please teach me Dhamma in brief. When I’ve heard it, I’ll live alone, withdrawn, diligent, keen, and resolute.”*";
P_HTM[3910]="*“Tasmātiha tvaṃ, bhikkhu, ādimeva visodhehi kusalesu dhammesu.**“Well then, mendicant, you should purify skillful qualities starting from the beginning.*";
P_HTM[3911]="*Ko cādi kusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ?**What is the beginning of skillful qualities?*";
P_HTM[3912]="*Idha tvaṃ, bhikkhu, kāyaduccaritaṃ pahāya kāyasucaritaṃ bhāvessasi.**Give up bad conduct by way of body, speech, and mind and develop good conduct by way of body, speech, and mind.*";
P_HTM[3913]="*Vacīduccaritaṃ pahāya vacīsucaritaṃ bhāvessasi.* **";
P_HTM[3914]="*Manoduccaritaṃ pahāya manosucaritaṃ bhāvessasi.* **";
P_HTM[3915]="*Yato kho tvaṃ, bhikkhu, kāyaduccaritaṃ pahāya kāyasucaritaṃ bhāvessasi, vacīduccaritaṃ pahāya vacīsucaritaṃ bhāvessasi, manoduccaritaṃ pahāya manosucaritaṃ bhāvessasi, tato tvaṃ, bhikkhu, sīlaṃ nissāya sīle patiṭṭhāya cattāro satipaṭṭhāne bhāveyyāsi.**When you’ve done this, you should develop the four kinds of mindfulness meditation, depending on and grounded on ethics.*";
P_HTM[3916]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[3917]="*Idha tvaṃ, bhikkhu, kāye kāyānupassī viharāhi ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;**Meditate observing an aspect of the body internally—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3918]="*vedanāsu … pe …**Meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[3919]="*citte … pe …**mind …*";
P_HTM[3920]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharāhi ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3921]="*Yato kho tvaṃ, bhikkhu, sīlaṃ nissāya sīle patiṭṭhāya ime cattāro satipaṭṭhāne evaṃ bhāvessasi, tato tuyhaṃ, bhikkhu, yā ratti vā divaso vā āgamissati vuddhiyeva pāṭikaṅkhā kusalesu dhammesu, no parihānī”ti … pe …**When you develop the four kinds of mindfulness meditation in this way, depending on and grounded on ethics, you can expect growth, not decline, in skillful qualities, whether by day or by night.” …*";
P_HTM[3922]="*aññataro ca pana so bhikkhu arahataṃ ahosīti.**And that mendicant became one of the perfected.*";
P_HTM[3923]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3924]="*2. Samudayasuttaṃ**Friends*";
P_HTM[3925]="*“Ye, bhikkhave, anukampeyyātha, ye ca kho sotabbaṃ maññeyyuṃ mittā vā amaccā vā ñātī vā sālohitā vā, te vo, bhikkhave, catunnaṃ satipaṭṭhānānaṃ bhāvanāya samādapetabbā nivesetabbā patiṭṭhāpetabbā.**“Mendicants, those for whom you have sympathy, and those worth listening to—friends and colleagues, relatives and family—should be encouraged, supported, and established in the development of the four kinds of mindfulness meditation.*";
P_HTM[3926]="*Katamesaṃ, catunnaṃ?**What four?*";
P_HTM[3927]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;**It’s when a mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3928]="*vedanāsu … pe …**They meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[3929]="*citte … pe …**mind …*";
P_HTM[3930]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3931]="*Ye, bhikkhave, anukampeyyātha, ye ca sotabbaṃ maññeyyuṃ mittā vā amaccā vā ñātī vā sālohitā vā, te vo, bhikkhave, imesaṃ catunnaṃ satipaṭṭhānānaṃ bhāvanāya samādapetabbā nivesetabbā patiṭṭhāpetabbā”ti.**Those for whom you have sympathy, and those worth listening to—friends and colleagues, relatives and family—should be encouraged, supported, and established in the development of the four kinds of mindfulness meditation.”*";
P_HTM[3932]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3933]="*3. Maggasuttaṃ**Feelings*";
P_HTM[3934]="*“Tisso imā, bhikkhave, vedanā.**“Mendicants, there are these three feelings.*";
P_HTM[3935]="*Katamā tisso?**What three?*";
P_HTM[3936]="*Sukhā vedanā, dukkhā vedanā, adukkhamasukhā vedanā—**Pleasant, painful, and neutral feeling.*";
P_HTM[3937]="*imā kho, bhikkhave, tisso vedanā.**These are the three feelings.*";
P_HTM[3938]="*Imāsaṃ kho, bhikkhave, tissannaṃ vedanānaṃ pariññāya cattāro satipaṭṭhānā bhāvetabbā.**The four kinds of mindfulness meditation should be developed to completely understand these three feelings.*";
P_HTM[3939]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[3940]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;**It’s when a mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3941]="*vedanāsu … pe …**They meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[3942]="*citte … pe …**mind …*";
P_HTM[3943]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3944]="*Imāsaṃ kho, bhikkhave, tissannaṃ vedanānaṃ pariññāya ime cattāro satipaṭṭhānā bhāvetabbā”ti.**These four kinds of mindfulness meditation should be developed to completely understand these three feelings.”*";
P_HTM[3945]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3946]="*4. Satisuttaṃ**Defilements*";
P_HTM[3947]="*“Tayome, bhikkhave āsavā.**“Mendicants, there are these three defilements.*";
P_HTM[3948]="*Katame tayo?**What three?*";
P_HTM[3949]="*Kāmāsavo, bhavāsavo, avijjāsavo—**The defilements of sensuality, desire to be reborn, and ignorance.*";
P_HTM[3950]="*ime kho, bhikkhave, tayo āsavā.**These are the three defilements.*";
P_HTM[3951]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, tiṇṇannaṃ āsavānaṃ pahānāya cattāro satipaṭṭhānā bhāvetabbā.**The four kinds of mindfulness meditation should be developed to give up these three defilements.*";
P_HTM[3952]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[3953]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;**It’s when a mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3954]="*vedanāsu … pe …**They meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[3955]="*citte … pe …**mind …*";
P_HTM[3956]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3957]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, tiṇṇannaṃ āsavānaṃ pahānāya ime cattāro satipaṭṭhānā bhāvetabbā”ti.**These four kinds of mindfulness meditation should be developed to give up these three defilements.”*";
P_HTM[3958]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3959]="*Amatavaggo pañcamo.* **";
P_HTM[3960]="*Amataṃ samudayo maggo,* **";
P_HTM[3961]="*Sati kusalarāsi ca;* **";
P_HTM[3962]="*Pātimokkhaṃ duccaritaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[3963]="*Mittavedanā āsavena cāti.* **";
P_HTM[3964]="*5. Kusalarāsisuttaṃ**51–62. Gaṅgānadīādisuttadvādasaka*";
P_HTM[3965]="*“Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, gaṅgā nadī pācīnaninnā pācīnapoṇā pācīnapabbhārā;**“Mendicants, the Ganges river slants, slopes, and inclines to the east.*";
P_HTM[3966]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu cattāro satipaṭṭhāne bhāvento cattāro satipaṭṭhāne bahulīkaronto nibbānaninno hoti nibbānapoṇo nibbānapabbhāro.**In the same way, a mendicant who develops and cultivates the four kinds of mindfulness meditation slants, slopes, and inclines to extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[3967]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhu cattāro satipaṭṭhāne bhāvento cattāro satipaṭṭhāne bahulīkaronto nibbānaninno hoti nibbānapoṇo nibbānapabbhāro?**And how does a mendicant who develops the four kinds of mindfulness meditation slant, slope, and incline to extinguishment?*";
P_HTM[3968]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;**It’s when a mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3969]="*vedanāsu … pe …**They meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[3970]="*citte … pe …**mind …*";
P_HTM[3971]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[3972]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu cattāro satipaṭṭhāne bhāvento cattāro satipaṭṭhāne bahulīkaronto nibbānaninno hoti nibbānapoṇo nibbānapabbhāro”ti vitthāretabbaṃ.**That’s how a mendicant who develops and cultivates the four kinds of mindfulness meditation slants, slopes, and inclines to extinguishment.”*";
P_HTM[3973]="*Gaṅgāpeyyālavaggo chaṭṭho.**(To be expanded for each of the different rivers as in SN 45.91–102.)*";
P_HTM[3974]="*Cha pācīnato ninnā,**Six on slanting to the east,*";
P_HTM[3975]="*cha ninnā ca samuddato;**and six on slanting to the ocean;*";
P_HTM[3976]="*Ete dve cha dvādasa honti,**these two sixes make twelve,*";
P_HTM[3977]="*vaggo tena pavuccatīti.**and that’s how this chapter is recited.*";
P_HTM[3978]="*6. Pātimokkhasaṃvarasuttaṃ**63–72. Tathāgatādisutta*";
P_HTM[3979]="*“Yāvatā, bhikkhave, sattā apadā vā dvipadā vā catuppadā vā bahuppadā vā”ti vitthāretabbaṃ.**“Mendicants, the Realized One, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha, is said to be the best of all sentient beings—be they footless, with two feet, four feet, or many feet …”*";
P_HTM[3980]="*Appamādavaggo sattamo.**(To be expanded as in SN 45.139–148.)*";
P_HTM[3981]="*Tathāgataṃ padaṃ kūṭaṃ,**The Realized One, footprint, roof peak,*";
P_HTM[3982]="*mūlaṃ sāro ca vassikaṃ;**roots, heartwood, jasmine,*";
P_HTM[3983]="*Rājā candimasūriyā,**monarch, sun and moon,*";
P_HTM[3984]="*vatthena dasamaṃ padanti.**and cloth is the tenth.*";
P_HTM[3985]="*7. Duccaritasuttaṃ**73–84. Balādisutta*";
P_HTM[3986]="*“Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, ye keci balakaraṇīyā kammantā karīyantī”ti vitthāretabbaṃ.**“Mendicants, all the hard work that gets done depends on the earth and is grounded on the earth. …”*";
P_HTM[3987]="*Balakaraṇīyavaggo aṭṭhamo.**(To be expanded as in SN 45.149–160.)*";
P_HTM[3988]="*Balaṃ bījañca nāgo ca,**Hard work, seeds, and dragons,*";
P_HTM[3989]="*rukkho kumbhena sūkiyā;**a tree, a pot, and a spike,*";
P_HTM[3990]="*Ākāsena ca dve meghā,**the sky, and two on clouds,*";
P_HTM[3991]="*nāvā āgantukā nadīti.**a ship, a guest house, and a river.*";
P_HTM[3992]="*8. Mittasuttaṃ**85–94. Esanādisutta*";
P_HTM[3993]="*“Tisso imā, bhikkhave, esanā.**“Mendicants, there are these three searches.*";
P_HTM[3994]="*Katamā tisso?**What three?*";
P_HTM[3995]="*Kāmesanā, bhavesanā, brahmacariyesanā”ti vitthāretabbaṃ.**The search for sensual pleasures, the search for continued existence, and the search for a spiritual path. …”*";
P_HTM[3996]="*Esanāvaggo navamo.**(To be expanded as in SN 45.161–170.)*";
P_HTM[3997]="*Esanā vidhā āsavo,**Searches, discriminations, defilements,*";
P_HTM[3998]="*Bhavo ca dukkhatā tisso;**states of existence, three kinds of suffering,*";
P_HTM[3999]="*Khilaṃ malañca nīgho ca,**barrenness, stains, and troubles,*";
P_HTM[4000]="*Vedanā taṇhā tasināya cāti.**feelings, craving, and thirst.*";
P_HTM[4001]="*9. Vedanāsuttaṃ**95–104. Uddhambhāgiyādisutta*";
P_HTM[4002]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, uddhambhāgiyāni saṃyojanāni.**(To be expanded as in SN 45.171–179, with the following as the final discourse.) “Mendicants, there are five higher fetters.*";
P_HTM[4003]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[4004]="*Rūparāgo, arūparāgo, māno, uddhaccaṃ, avijjā—**Desire for rebirth in the realm of luminous form, desire for rebirth in the formless realm, conceit, restlessness, and ignorance.*";
P_HTM[4005]="*imāni kho, bhikkhave, pañcuddhambhāgiyāni saṃyojanāni.**These are the five higher fetters.*";
P_HTM[4006]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, pañcannaṃ uddhambhāgiyānaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ abhiññāya pariññāya parikkhayāya pahānāya cattāro satipaṭṭhānā bhāvetabbā.**The four kinds of mindfulness meditation should be developed for the direct knowledge, complete understanding, finishing, and giving up of these five higher fetters.*";
P_HTM[4007]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[4008]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;**It’s when a mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[4009]="*vedanāsu … pe …**They meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[4010]="*citte … pe …**mind …*";
P_HTM[4011]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[4012]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, pañcannaṃ uddhambhāgiyānaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ abhiññāya pariññāya parikkhayāya pahānāya ime cattāro satipaṭṭhānā bhāvetabbā”ti.**These four kinds of mindfulness meditation should be developed for the direct knowledge, complete understanding, finishing, and giving up of these five higher fetters.”*";
P_HTM[4013]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4014]="*(Yathā maggasaṃyuttaṃ tathā satipaṭṭhānasaṃyuttaṃ vitthāretabbaṃ.)**(The Linked Discourses on Mindfulness Meditation should be expanded as in the Linked Discourses on the Path.)*";
P_HTM[4015]="*Oghavaggo dasamo.* **";
P_HTM[4016]="*Ogho yogo upādānaṃ,**Floods, bonds, grasping,*";
P_HTM[4017]="*ganthā anusayena ca;**ties, and underlying tendencies,*";
P_HTM[4018]="*Kāmaguṇā nīvaraṇā,**kinds of sensual stimulation, hindrances,*";
P_HTM[4019]="*khandhā oruddhambhāgiyāti.**aggregates, and fetters high and low.*";
P_HTM[4020]="*Satipaṭṭhānasaṃyuttaṃ tatiyaṃ.**The Linked Discourses on Mindfulness Meditation is the third section.*";
P_HTM[4021]="*48. Indriyasaṃyuttaṃ* **";
P_HTM[4022]="*10. Āsavasuttaṃ**Plain Version*";
P_HTM[4023]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[4024]="*Tatra kho bhagavā etadavoca.**There the Buddha said:*";
P_HTM[4025]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, indriyāni.**“Mendicants, there are these five faculties.*";
P_HTM[4026]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[4027]="*Saddhindriyaṃ, vīriyindriyaṃ, satindriyaṃ, samādhindriyaṃ, paññindriyaṃ—**The faculties of faith, energy, mindfulness, immersion, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[4028]="*imāni kho, bhikkhave, pañcindriyānī”ti.**These are the five faculties.”*";
P_HTM[4029]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4030]="*1. Suddhikavaggo**Suddhikavagga*";
P_HTM[4031]="*1-12. Gaṅgānadīādisuttadvādasakaṃ**A Stream*";
P_HTM[4032]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, indriyāni.**“Mendicants, there are these five faculties.*";
P_HTM[4033]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[4034]="*Saddhindriyaṃ, vīriyindriyaṃ, satindriyaṃ, samādhindriyaṃ, paññindriyaṃ.**The faculties of faith, energy, mindfulness, immersion, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[4035]="*Yato kho, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako imesaṃ pañcannaṃ indriyānaṃ assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti—**A noble disciple comes to truly understand these five faculties’ gratification, drawback, and escape.*";
P_HTM[4036]="*ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako sotāpanno avinipātadhammo niyato sambodhiparāyaṇo”ti.**Such a noble disciple is called a stream-enterer, not liable to be reborn in the underworld, bound for awakening.”*";
P_HTM[4037]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4038]="*2. Mudutaravaggo**Suddhikavagga*";
P_HTM[4039]="*1-10. Tathāgatādisuttadasakaṃ**A Stream*";
P_HTM[4040]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, indriyāni.**“Mendicants, there are these five faculties.*";
P_HTM[4041]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[4042]="*Saddhindriyaṃ, vīriyindriyaṃ, satindriyaṃ, samādhindriyaṃ, paññindriyaṃ.**The faculties of faith, energy, mindfulness, immersion, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[4043]="*Yato kho, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako imesaṃ pañcannaṃ indriyānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti—**A noble disciple comes to truly understand these five faculties’ origin, ending, gratification, drawback, and escape.*";
P_HTM[4044]="*ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako sotāpanno avinipātadhammo niyato sambodhiparāyaṇo”ti.**Such a noble disciple is called a stream-enterer, not liable to be reborn in the underworld, bound for awakening.”*";
P_HTM[4045]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4046]="*3. Chaḷindriyavaggo**Plain Version*";
P_HTM[4047]="*1-12. Balādisuttadvādasakaṃ**A Perfected One (1st)*";
P_HTM[4048]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, indriyāni.**“Mendicants, there are these five faculties.*";
P_HTM[4049]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[4050]="*Saddhindriyaṃ, vīriyindriyaṃ, satindriyaṃ, samādhindriyaṃ, paññindriyaṃ.**The faculties of faith, energy, mindfulness, immersion, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[4051]="*Yato kho, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako imesaṃ pañcannaṃ indriyānaṃ assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ viditvā anupādāvimutto hoti—**A noble disciple comes to be freed by not grasping after truly understanding these five faculties’ gratification, drawback, and escape.*";
P_HTM[4052]="*ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, bhikkhu arahaṃ khīṇāsavo vusitavā katakaraṇīyo ohitabhāro anuppattasadattho parikkhīṇabhavasaṃyojano sammadaññāvimutto”ti.**Such a mendicant is called a perfected one, with defilements ended, who has completed the spiritual journey, done what had to be done, laid down the burden, achieved their own true goal, utterly ended the fetters of rebirth, and is rightly freed through enlightenment.”*";
P_HTM[4053]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4054]="*4. Sukhindriyavaggo**Plain Version*";
P_HTM[4055]="*1-10. Esanādisuttadasakaṃ**A Perfected One (2nd)*";
P_HTM[4056]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, indriyāni.**“Mendicants, there are these five faculties.*";
P_HTM[4057]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[4058]="*Saddhindriyaṃ, vīriyindriyaṃ, satindriyaṃ, samādhindriyaṃ, paññindriyaṃ.**The faculties of faith, energy, mindfulness, immersion, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[4059]="*Yato kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu imesaṃ pañcannaṃ indriyānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ viditvā anupādāvimutto hoti—**A mendicant comes to be freed by not grasping after truly understanding these five faculties’ origin, ending, gratification, drawback, and escape.*";
P_HTM[4060]="*ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, bhikkhu arahaṃ khīṇāsavo vusitavā katakaraṇīyo ohitabhāro anuppattasadattho parikkhīṇabhavasaṃyojano sammadaññāvimutto”ti.**Such a mendicant is called a perfected one, with defilements ended, who has completed the spiritual journey, done what had to be done, laid down the burden, achieved their own true goal, utterly ended the fetters of rebirth, and is rightly freed through enlightenment.”*";
P_HTM[4061]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4062]="*5. Jarāvaggo**Plain Version*";
P_HTM[4063]="*1-10. Uddhambhāgiyādisuttadasakaṃ**Ascetics and Brahmins (1st)*";
P_HTM[4064]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, indriyāni.**“Mendicants, there are these five faculties.*";
P_HTM[4065]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[4066]="*Saddhindriyaṃ … pe … paññindriyaṃ.**The faculties of faith, energy, mindfulness, immersion, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[4067]="*Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā imesaṃ pañcannaṃ indriyānaṃ assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ nappajānanti,**There are ascetics and brahmins who don’t truly understand the gratification, drawback, and escape when it comes to these five faculties.*";
P_HTM[4068]="*na me te, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā samaṇesu vā samaṇasammatā brāhmaṇesu vā brāhmaṇasammatā, na ca panete āyasmanto sāmaññatthaṃ vā brahmaññatthaṃ vā diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharanti.**I don’t regard them as true ascetics and brahmins. Those venerables don’t realize the goal of life as an ascetic or brahmin, and don’t live having realized it with their own insight.*";
P_HTM[4069]="*Ye ca kho keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā imesaṃ pañcannaṃ indriyānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ pajānanti,**There are ascetics and brahmins who do truly understand the gratification, drawback, and escape when it comes to these five faculties.*";
P_HTM[4070]="*te kho me, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā samaṇesu ceva samaṇasammatā brāhmaṇesu ca brāhmaṇasammatā; te ca panāyasmanto sāmaññatthañca brahmaññatthañca diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharantī”ti.**I regard them as true ascetics and brahmins. Those venerables realize the goal of life as an ascetic or brahmin, and live having realized it with their own insight.”*";
P_HTM[4071]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4072]="*6. Sūkarakhatavaggo**Plain Version*";
P_HTM[4073]="*1. Suddhikasuttaṃ**Ascetics and Brahmins (2nd)*";
P_HTM[4074]="*“Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā saddhindriyaṃ nappajānanti, saddhindriyasamudayaṃ nappajānanti, saddhindriyanirodhaṃ nappajānanti, saddhindriyanirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ nappajānanti;**“Mendicants, there are ascetics and brahmins who don’t understand the faculty of faith, its origin, its cessation, and the practice that leads to its cessation.*";
P_HTM[4075]="*vīriyindriyaṃ nappajānanti … pe …**They don’t understand the faculty of energy …*";
P_HTM[4076]="*satindriyaṃ nappajānanti … pe …**mindfulness …*";
P_HTM[4077]="*samādhindriyaṃ nappajānanti … pe …**immersion …*";
P_HTM[4078]="*paññindriyaṃ nappajānanti, paññindriyasamudayaṃ nappajānanti, paññindriyanirodhaṃ nappajānanti, paññindriyanirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ nappajānanti,**wisdom, its origin, its cessation, and the practice that leads to its cessation.*";
P_HTM[4079]="*na me te, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā samaṇesu vā samaṇasammatā brāhmaṇesu vā brāhmaṇasammatā, na ca panete āyasmanto sāmaññatthaṃ vā brahmaññatthaṃ vā diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharanti.**I don’t regard them as true ascetics and brahmins. Those venerables don’t realize the goal of life as an ascetic or brahmin, and don’t live having realized it with their own insight.*";
P_HTM[4080]="*Ye ca kho keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā saddhindriyaṃ pajānanti, saddhindriyasamudayaṃ pajānanti, saddhindriyanirodhaṃ pajānanti, saddhindriyanirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ pajānanti;**There are ascetics and brahmins who do understand the faculty of faith, its origin, its cessation, and the practice that leads to its cessation.*";
P_HTM[4081]="*vīriyindriyaṃ pajānanti, vīriyindriyasamudayaṃ pajānanti, vīriyindriyanirodhaṃ pajānanti, vīriyindriyanirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ pajānanti;**They do understand the faculty of energy …*";
P_HTM[4082]="*satindriyaṃ pajānanti … pe …**mindfulness …*";
P_HTM[4083]="*samādhindriyaṃ pajānanti … pe …**immersion …*";
P_HTM[4084]="*paññindriyaṃ pajānanti, paññindriyasamudayaṃ pajānanti, paññindriyanirodhaṃ pajānanti, paññindriyanirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ pajānanti,**wisdom, its origin, its cessation, and the practice that leads to its cessation.*";
P_HTM[4085]="*te kho me, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā samaṇesu ceva samaṇasammatā brāhmaṇesu ca brāhmaṇasammatā, te ca panāyasmanto sāmaññatthañca brahmaññatthañca diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharantī”ti.**I regard them as true ascetics and brahmins. Those venerables realize the goal of life as an ascetic or brahmin, and live having realized it with their own insight.”*";
P_HTM[4086]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4087]="*2. Paṭhamasotāpannasuttaṃ**Should Be Seen*";
P_HTM[4088]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, indriyāni.**“Mendicants, there are these five faculties.*";
P_HTM[4089]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[4090]="*Saddhindriyaṃ … pe … paññindriyaṃ.**The faculties of faith, energy, mindfulness, immersion, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[4091]="*Kattha ca, bhikkhave, saddhindriyaṃ daṭṭhabbaṃ?**And where should the faculty of faith be seen?*";
P_HTM[4092]="*Catūsu sotāpattiyaṅgesu—**In the four factors of stream-entry.*";
P_HTM[4093]="*ettha saddhindriyaṃ daṭṭhabbaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4094]="*Kattha ca, bhikkhave, vīriyindriyaṃ daṭṭhabbaṃ?**And where should the faculty of energy be seen?*";
P_HTM[4095]="*Catūsu sammappadhānesu—**In the four right efforts.*";
P_HTM[4096]="*ettha vīriyindriyaṃ daṭṭhabbaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4097]="*Kattha ca, bhikkhave, satindriyaṃ daṭṭhabbaṃ?**And where should the faculty of mindfulness be seen?*";
P_HTM[4098]="*Catūsu satipaṭṭhānesu—**In the four kinds of mindfulness meditation.*";
P_HTM[4099]="*ettha satindriyaṃ daṭṭhabbaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4100]="*Kattha ca, bhikkhave, samādhindriyaṃ daṭṭhabbaṃ?**And where should the faculty of immersion be seen?*";
P_HTM[4101]="*Catūsu jhānesu—**In the four absorptions.*";
P_HTM[4102]="*ettha samādhindriyaṃ daṭṭhabbaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4103]="*Kattha ca, bhikkhave, paññindriyaṃ daṭṭhabbaṃ?**And where should the faculty of wisdom be seen?*";
P_HTM[4104]="*Catūsu ariyasaccesu—**In the four noble truths.*";
P_HTM[4105]="*ettha paññindriyaṃ daṭṭhabbaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4106]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, pañcindriyānī”ti.**These are the five faculties.”*";
P_HTM[4107]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4108]="*3. Dutiyasotāpannasuttaṃ**Analysis (1st)*";
P_HTM[4109]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, indriyāni.**“Mendicants, there are these five faculties.*";
P_HTM[4110]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[4111]="*Saddhindriyaṃ … pe … paññindriyaṃ.**The faculties of faith, energy, mindfulness, immersion, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[4112]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, saddhindriyaṃ?**And what is the faculty of faith?*";
P_HTM[4113]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako saddho hoti, saddahati tathāgatassa bodhiṃ:**It’s when a noble disciple has faith in the Realized One’s awakening:*";
P_HTM[4114]="*‘itipi so bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho vijjācaraṇasampanno sugato lokavidū anuttaro purisadammasārathi satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavā’ti—**‘That Blessed One is perfected, a fully awakened Buddha, accomplished in knowledge and conduct, holy, knower of the world, supreme guide for those who wish to train, teacher of gods and humans, awakened, blessed.’*";
P_HTM[4115]="*idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, saddhindriyaṃ.**This is called the faculty of faith.*";
P_HTM[4116]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, vīriyindriyaṃ?**And what is the faculty of energy?*";
P_HTM[4117]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako āraddhavīriyo viharati akusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ pahānāya, kusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ upasampadāya, thāmavā daḷhaparakkamo anikkhittadhuro kusalesu dhammesu—**It’s when a mendicant lives with energy roused up for giving up unskillful qualities and embracing skillful qualities. They’re strong, staunchly vigorous, not slacking off when it comes to developing skillful qualities.*";
P_HTM[4118]="*idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, vīriyindriyaṃ.**This is called the faculty of energy.*";
P_HTM[4119]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, satindriyaṃ?**And what is the faculty of mindfulness?*";
P_HTM[4120]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako satimā hoti paramena satinepakkena samannāgato cirakatampi cirabhāsitampi saritā anussaritā—**It’s when a noble disciple is mindful. They have utmost mindfulness and alertness, and can remember and recall what was said and done long ago.*";
P_HTM[4121]="*idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, satindriyaṃ.**This is called the faculty of mindfulness.*";
P_HTM[4122]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, samādhindriyaṃ?**And what is the faculty of immersion?*";
P_HTM[4123]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako vossaggārammaṇaṃ karitvā labhati samādhiṃ, labhati cittassa ekaggataṃ—**It’s when a noble disciple, relying on letting go, gains immersion, gains unification of mind.*";
P_HTM[4124]="*idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, samādhindriyaṃ.**This is called the faculty of immersion.*";
P_HTM[4125]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, paññindriyaṃ?**And what is the faculty of wisdom?*";
P_HTM[4126]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako paññavā hoti udayatthagāminiyā paññāya samannāgato ariyāya nibbedhikāya, sammā dukkhakkhayagāminiyā—**It’s when a noble disciple is wise. They have the wisdom of arising and passing away which is noble, penetrative, and leads to the complete ending of suffering.*";
P_HTM[4127]="*idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, paññindriyaṃ.**This is called the faculty of wisdom.*";
P_HTM[4128]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, pañcindriyānī”ti.**These are the five faculties.”*";
P_HTM[4129]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4130]="*4. Paṭhamaarahantasuttaṃ**Analysis (2nd)*";
P_HTM[4131]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, indriyāni.**“Mendicants, there are these five faculties.*";
P_HTM[4132]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[4133]="*Saddhindriyaṃ … pe … paññindriyaṃ.**The faculties of faith, energy, mindfulness, immersion, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[4134]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, saddhindriyaṃ?**And what is the faculty of faith?*";
P_HTM[4135]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako saddho hoti, saddahati tathāgatassa bodhiṃ:**It’s when a noble disciple has faith in the Realized One’s awakening:*";
P_HTM[4136]="*‘itipi so bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho vijjācaraṇasampanno sugato lokavidū anuttaro purisadammasārathi satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavā’ti—**‘That Blessed One is perfected, a fully awakened Buddha, accomplished in knowledge and conduct, holy, knower of the world, supreme guide for those who wish to train, teacher of gods and humans, awakened, blessed.’*";
P_HTM[4137]="*idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, saddhindriyaṃ.**This is called the faculty of faith.*";
P_HTM[4138]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, vīriyindriyaṃ?**And what is the faculty of energy?*";
P_HTM[4139]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako āraddhavīriyo viharati akusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ pahānāya, kusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ upasampadāya, thāmavā daḷhaparakkamo anikkhittadhuro kusalesu dhammesu.**It’s when a mendicant lives with energy roused up for giving up unskillful qualities and embracing skillful qualities. They’re strong, staunchly vigorous, not slacking off when it comes to developing skillful qualities.*";
P_HTM[4140]="*So anuppannānaṃ pāpakānaṃ akusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ anuppādāya chandaṃ janeti vāyamati vīriyaṃ ārabhati cittaṃ paggaṇhāti padahati;**They generate enthusiasm, try, make an effort, exert the mind, and strive so that bad, unskillful qualities don’t arise.*";
P_HTM[4141]="*uppannānaṃ pāpakānaṃ akusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ pahānāya chandaṃ janeti vāyamati vīriyaṃ ārabhati cittaṃ paggaṇhāti padahati;**They generate enthusiasm, try, make an effort, exert the mind, and strive so that bad, unskillful qualities that have arisen are given up.*";
P_HTM[4142]="*anuppannānaṃ kusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ uppādāya chandaṃ janeti vāyamati vīriyaṃ ārabhati cittaṃ paggaṇhāti padahati;**They generate enthusiasm, try, make an effort, exert the mind, and strive so that skillful qualities arise.*";
P_HTM[4143]="*uppannānaṃ kusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ ṭhitiyā asammosāya bhiyyobhāvāya vepullāya bhāvanāya pāripūriyā chandaṃ janeti vāyamati vīriyaṃ ārabhati cittaṃ paggaṇhāti padahati—**They generate enthusiasm, try, make an effort, exert the mind, and strive so that skillful qualities that have arisen remain, are not lost, but increase, mature, and are completed by development.*";
P_HTM[4144]="*idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, vīriyindriyaṃ.**This is called the faculty of energy.*";
P_HTM[4145]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, satindriyaṃ?**And what is the faculty of mindfulness?*";
P_HTM[4146]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako satimā hoti paramena satinepakkena samannāgato, cirakatampi cirabhāsitampi saritā anussaritā.**It’s when a noble disciple is mindful. They have utmost mindfulness and alertness, and can remember and recall what was said and done long ago.*";
P_HTM[4147]="*So kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;**They meditate observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[4148]="*vedanāsu … pe …**They meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[4149]="*citte … pe …**mind …*";
P_HTM[4150]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ—**principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[4151]="*idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, satindriyaṃ.**This is called the faculty of mindfulness.*";
P_HTM[4152]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, samādhindriyaṃ?**And what is the faculty of immersion?*";
P_HTM[4153]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako vossaggārammaṇaṃ karitvā labhati samādhiṃ, labhati cittassa ekaggataṃ.**It’s when a noble disciple, relying on letting go, gains immersion, gains unification of mind.*";
P_HTM[4154]="*So vivicceva kāmehi vivicca akusalehi dhammehi savitakkaṃ savicāraṃ vivekajaṃ pītisukhaṃ paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Quite secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unskillful qualities, they enter and remain in the first absorption, which has the rapture and bliss born of seclusion, while placing the mind and keeping it connected.*";
P_HTM[4155]="*Vitakkavicārānaṃ vūpasamā ajjhattaṃ sampasādanaṃ cetaso ekodibhāvaṃ avitakkaṃ avicāraṃ samādhijaṃ pītisukhaṃ dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**As the placing of the mind and keeping it connected are stilled, they enter and remain in the second absorption, which has the rapture and bliss born of immersion, with internal clarity and confidence, and unified mind, without placing the mind and keeping it connected.*";
P_HTM[4156]="*Pītiyā ca virāgā upekkhako ca viharati sato ca sampajāno sukhañca kāyena paṭisaṃvedeti yaṃ taṃ ariyā ācikkhanti ‘upekkhako satimā sukhavihārī’ti tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**And with the fading away of rapture, they enter and remain in the third absorption, where they meditate with equanimity, mindful and aware, personally experiencing the bliss of which the noble ones declare, ‘Equanimous and mindful, one meditates in bliss.’*";
P_HTM[4157]="*Sukhassa ca pahānā dukkhassa ca pahānā pubbeva somanassadomanassānaṃ atthaṅgamā adukkhamasukhaṃ upekkhāsatipārisuddhiṃ catutthaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati—**Giving up pleasure and pain, and ending former happiness and sadness, they enter and remain in the fourth absorption, without pleasure or pain, with pure equanimity and mindfulness.*";
P_HTM[4158]="*idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, samādhindriyaṃ.**This is called the faculty of immersion.*";
P_HTM[4159]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, paññindriyaṃ?**And what is the faculty of wisdom?*";
P_HTM[4160]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako paññavā hoti udayatthagāminiyā paññāya samannāgato ariyāya nibbedhikāya, sammā dukkhakkhayagāminiyā.**It’s when a noble disciple is wise. They have the wisdom of arising and passing away which is noble, penetrative, and leads to the complete ending of suffering.*";
P_HTM[4161]="*So ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti, ‘ayaṃ dukkhasamudayo’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti, ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodho’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti, ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti—**They truly understand: ‘This is suffering’ … ‘This is the origin of suffering’ … ‘This is the cessation of suffering’ … ‘This is the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering’.*";
P_HTM[4162]="*idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, paññindriyaṃ.**This is called the faculty of wisdom.*";
P_HTM[4163]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, pañcindriyānī”ti.**These are the five faculties.”*";
P_HTM[4164]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4165]="*Suddhikavaggo paṭhamo.* **";
P_HTM[4166]="*Suddhikañceva dve sotā,* **";
P_HTM[4167]="*arahantā apare duve;* **";
P_HTM[4168]="*Samaṇabrāhmaṇā daṭṭhabbaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[4169]="*vibhaṅgā apare duveti.* **";
P_HTM[4170]="*5. Dutiyaarahantasuttaṃ**Gain*";
P_HTM[4171]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, indriyāni.**“Mendicants, there are these five faculties.*";
P_HTM[4172]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[4173]="*Saddhindriyaṃ … pe … paññindriyaṃ … pe ….**The faculties of faith, energy, mindfulness, immersion, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[4174]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, saddhindriyaṃ?**And what is the faculty of faith?*";
P_HTM[4175]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako saddho hoti, saddahati tathāgatassa bodhiṃ:**It’s when a noble disciple has faith in the Realized One’s awakening:*";
P_HTM[4176]="*‘itipi so bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho vijjācaraṇasampanno sugato lokavidū anuttaro purisadammasārathi satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavā’ti—**‘That Blessed One is perfected, a fully awakened Buddha, accomplished in knowledge and conduct, holy, knower of the world, supreme guide for those who wish to train, teacher of gods and humans, awakened, blessed.’*";
P_HTM[4177]="*idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, saddhindriyaṃ.**This is called the faculty of faith.*";
P_HTM[4178]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, vīriyindriyaṃ?**And what is the faculty of energy?*";
P_HTM[4179]="*Yaṃ kho, bhikkhave, cattāro sammappadhāne ārabbha vīriyaṃ paṭilabhati—**The energy that’s gained in connection with the four right efforts.*";
P_HTM[4180]="*idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, vīriyindriyaṃ.**This is called the faculty of energy.*";
P_HTM[4181]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, satindriyaṃ?**And what is the faculty of mindfulness?*";
P_HTM[4182]="*Yaṃ kho, bhikkhave, cattāro satipaṭṭhāne ārabbha satiṃ paṭilabhati—**The mindfulness that’s gained in connection with the four kinds of mindfulness meditation.*";
P_HTM[4183]="*idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, satindriyaṃ.**This is called the faculty of mindfulness.*";
P_HTM[4184]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, samādhindriyaṃ?**And what is the faculty of immersion?*";
P_HTM[4185]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako vossaggārammaṇaṃ karitvā labhati samādhiṃ, labhati cittassa ekaggataṃ—**It’s when a noble disciple, relying on letting go, gains immersion, gains unification of mind.*";
P_HTM[4186]="*idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, samādhindriyaṃ.**This is called the faculty of immersion.*";
P_HTM[4187]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, paññindriyaṃ?**And what is the faculty of wisdom?*";
P_HTM[4188]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako paññavā hoti udayatthagāminiyā paññāya samannāgato ariyāya nibbedhikāya sammā dukkhakkhayagāminiyā—**It’s when a noble disciple is wise. They have the wisdom of arising and passing away which is noble, penetrative, and leads to the complete ending of suffering.*";
P_HTM[4189]="*idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, paññindriyaṃ.**This is called the faculty of wisdom.*";
P_HTM[4190]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, pañcindriyānī”ti.**These are the five faculties.”*";
P_HTM[4191]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4192]="*6. Paṭhamasamaṇabrāhmaṇasuttaṃ**In Brief (1st)*";
P_HTM[4193]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, indriyāni.**“Mendicants, there are these five faculties.*";
P_HTM[4194]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[4195]="*Saddhindriyaṃ … pe … paññindriyaṃ—**The faculties of faith, energy, mindfulness, immersion, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[4196]="*imāni kho, bhikkhave, pañcindriyāni.**These are the five faculties.*";
P_HTM[4197]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, pañcannaṃ indriyānaṃ samattā paripūrattā arahaṃ hoti, tato mudutarehi anāgāmī hoti, tato mudutarehi sakadāgāmī hoti, tato mudutarehi sotāpanno hoti, tato mudutarehi dhammānusārī hoti, tato mudutarehi saddhānusārī hotī”ti.**Someone who has completed and fulfilled these five faculties is a perfected one. If they are weaker than that, they’re a non-returner. If they are weaker still, they’re a once-returner. If they are weaker still, they’re a stream-enterer. If they’re weaker still, they’re a follower of the teachings. If they’re weaker still, they’re a follower by faith.”*";
P_HTM[4198]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4199]="*7. Dutiyasamaṇabrāhmaṇasuttaṃ**In Brief (2nd)*";
P_HTM[4200]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, indriyāni.**“Mendicants, there are these five faculties.*";
P_HTM[4201]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[4202]="*Saddhindriyaṃ … pe … paññindriyaṃ—**The faculties of faith, energy, mindfulness, immersion, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[4203]="*imāni kho, bhikkhave, pañcindriyāni.**These are the five faculties.*";
P_HTM[4204]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, pañcannaṃ indriyānaṃ samattā paripūrattā arahaṃ hoti, tato mudutarehi anāgāmī hoti, tato mudutarehi sakadāgāmī hoti, tato mudutarehi sotāpanno hoti, tato mudutarehi dhammānusārī hoti, tato mudutarehi saddhānusārī hoti.**Someone who has completed and fulfilled these five faculties is a perfected one. If they are weaker than that, they’re a non-returner … a once-returner … a stream-enterer … a follower of the teachings … a follower by faith.*";
P_HTM[4205]="*Iti kho, bhikkhave, indriyavemattatā phalavemattatā hoti, phalavemattatā puggalavemattatā”ti.**So from a diversity of faculties there’s a diversity of fruits. And from a diversity of fruits there’s a diversity of persons.”*";
P_HTM[4206]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4207]="*8. Daṭṭhabbasuttaṃ**In Brief (3rd)*";
P_HTM[4208]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, indriyāni.**“Mendicants, there are these five faculties.*";
P_HTM[4209]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[4210]="*Saddhindriyaṃ … pe … paññindriyaṃ—**The faculties of faith, energy, mindfulness, immersion, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[4211]="*imāni kho, bhikkhave, pañcindriyāni.**These are the five faculties.*";
P_HTM[4212]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, pañcannaṃ indriyānaṃ samattā paripūrattā arahaṃ hoti, tato mudutarehi anāgāmī hoti, tato mudutarehi sakadāgāmī hoti, tato mudutarehi sotāpanno hoti, tato mudutarehi dhammānusārī hoti, tato mudutarehi saddhānusārī hoti.**Someone who has completed and fulfilled these five faculties is a perfected one. If they are weaker than that, they’re a non-returner … a once-returner … a stream-enterer … a follower of the teachings … a follower by faith.*";
P_HTM[4213]="*Iti kho, bhikkhave, paripūraṃ paripūrakārī ārādheti, padesaṃ padesakārī ārādheti.**So, mendicants, if you practice partially you succeed partially. If you practice fully you succeed fully.*";
P_HTM[4214]="*‘Avañjhāni tvevāhaṃ, bhikkhave, pañcindriyānī’ti vadāmī”ti.**These five faculties are not a waste, I say.”*";
P_HTM[4215]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4216]="*9. Paṭhamavibhaṅgasuttaṃ**In Detail (1st)*";
P_HTM[4217]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, indriyāni.**“Mendicants, there are these five faculties.*";
P_HTM[4218]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[4219]="*Saddhindriyaṃ … pe … paññindriyaṃ—**The faculties of faith, energy, mindfulness, immersion, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[4220]="*imāni kho, bhikkhave, pañcindriyāni.**These are the five faculties.*";
P_HTM[4221]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, pañcannaṃ indriyānaṃ samattā paripūrattā arahaṃ hoti, tato mudutarehi antarāparinibbāyī hoti, tato mudutarehi upahaccaparinibbāyī hoti, tato mudutarehi asaṅkhāraparinibbāyī hoti, tato mudutarehi sasaṅkhāraparinibbāyī hoti, tato mudutarehi uddhaṃsoto hoti akaniṭṭhagāmī, tato mudutarehi sakadāgāmī hoti, tato mudutarehi sotāpanno hoti, tato mudutarehi dhammānusārī hoti, tato mudutarehi saddhānusārī hotī”ti.**Someone who has completed and fulfilled these five faculties is a perfected one. If they are weaker than that, they’re one who is extinguished between one life and the next … one who is extinguished upon landing … one who is extinguished without extra effort … one who is extinguished with extra effort … one who heads upstream, going to the Akaniṭṭha realm … a once-returner … a stream-enterer … a follower of the teachings … a follower by faith.”*";
P_HTM[4222]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4223]="*10. Dutiyavibhaṅgasuttaṃ**In Detail (2nd)*";
P_HTM[4224]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, indriyāni.**“Mendicants, there are these five faculties.*";
P_HTM[4225]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[4226]="*Saddhindriyaṃ … pe … paññindriyaṃ—**The faculties of faith, energy, mindfulness, immersion, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[4227]="*imāni kho, bhikkhave, pañcindriyāni.**These are the five faculties.*";
P_HTM[4228]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, pañcannaṃ indriyānaṃ samattā paripūrattā arahaṃ hoti, tato mudutarehi antarāparinibbāyī hoti, tato mudutarehi upahaccaparinibbāyī hoti, tato mudutarehi asaṅkhāraparinibbāyī hoti, tato mudutarehi sasaṅkhāraparinibbāyī hoti, tato mudutarehi uddhaṃsoto hoti akaniṭṭhagāmī, tato mudutarehi sakadāgāmī hoti, tato mudutarehi sotāpanno hoti, tato mudutarehi dhammānusārī hoti, tato mudutarehi saddhānusārī hoti.**Someone who has completed and fulfilled these five faculties is a perfected one. If they are weaker than that, they’re one who is extinguished between one life and the next … one who is extinguished upon landing … one who is extinguished without extra effort … one who is extinguished with extra effort … one who heads upstream, going to the Akaniṭṭha realm … a once-returner … a stream-enterer … a follower of the teachings … a follower by faith.*";
P_HTM[4229]="*Iti kho, bhikkhave, indriyavemattatā phalavemattatā hoti, phalavemattatā puggalavemattatā hotī”ti.**So from a diversity of faculties there’s a diversity of fruits. And from a diversity of fruits there’s a diversity of persons.”*";
P_HTM[4230]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4231]="*7. Bodhipakkhiyavaggo**Weaker*";
P_HTM[4232]="*1. Paṭilābhasuttaṃ**In Detail (3rd)*";
P_HTM[4233]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, indriyāni.**“Mendicants, there are these five faculties.*";
P_HTM[4234]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[4235]="*Saddhindriyaṃ … pe … paññindriyaṃ—**The faculties of faith, energy, mindfulness, immersion, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[4236]="*imāni kho, bhikkhave, pañcindriyāni.**These are the five faculties.*";
P_HTM[4237]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, pañcannaṃ indriyānaṃ samattā paripūrattā arahaṃ hoti, tato mudutarehi antarāparinibbāyī hoti, tato mudutarehi upahaccaparinibbāyī hoti, tato mudutarehi asaṅkhāraparinibbāyī hoti, tato mudutarehi sasaṅkhāraparinibbāyī hoti, tato mudutarehi uddhaṃsoto hoti akaniṭṭhagāmī, tato mudutarehi sakadāgāmī hoti, tato mudutarehi sotāpanno hoti, tato mudutarehi dhammānusārī hoti, tato mudutarehi saddhānusārī hoti.**Someone who has completed and fulfilled these five faculties is a perfected one. If they are weaker than that, they’re one who is extinguished between one life and the next … one who is extinguished upon landing … one who is extinguished without extra effort … one who is extinguished with extra effort … one who heads upstream, going to the Akaniṭṭha realm … a once-returner … a stream-enterer … a follower of the teachings … a follower by faith.*";
P_HTM[4238]="*Iti kho, bhikkhave, paripūraṃ paripūrakārī ārādheti, padesaṃ padesakārī ārādheti.**So, mendicants, if you practice partially you succeed partially. If you practice fully you succeed fully.*";
P_HTM[4239]="*‘Avañjhāni tvevāhaṃ, bhikkhave, pañcindriyānī’ti vadāmī”ti.**These five faculties are not a waste, I say.”*";
P_HTM[4240]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4241]="*2. Paṭhamasaṃkhittasuttaṃ**Practicing*";
P_HTM[4242]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, indriyāni.**“Mendicants, there are these five faculties.*";
P_HTM[4243]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[4244]="*Saddhindriyaṃ … pe … paññindriyaṃ—**The faculties of faith, energy, mindfulness, immersion, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[4245]="*imāni kho, bhikkhave, pañcindriyāni.**These are the five faculties.*";
P_HTM[4246]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, pañcannaṃ indriyānaṃ samattā paripūrattā arahaṃ hoti, tato mudutarehi arahattaphalasacchikiriyāya paṭipanno hoti, tato mudutarehi anāgāmī hoti, tato mudutarehi anāgāmiphalasacchikiriyāya paṭipanno hoti, tato mudutarehi sakadāgāmī hoti, tato mudutarehi sakadāgāmiphalasacchikiriyāya paṭipanno hoti, tato mudutarehi sotāpanno hoti, tato mudutarehi sotāpattiphalasacchikiriyāya paṭipanno hoti.**Someone who has completed and fulfilled these five faculties is a perfected one. If they are weaker than that, they’re practicing to realize the fruit of perfection … a non-returner … practicing to realize the fruit of non-return … a once-returner … practicing to realize the fruit of once-return … a stream-enterer … practicing to realize the fruit of stream-entry.*";
P_HTM[4247]="*Yassa kho, bhikkhave, imāni pañcindriyāni sabbena sabbaṃ sabbathā sabbaṃ natthi, tamahaṃ ‘bāhiro puthujjanapakkhe ṭhito’ti vadāmī”ti.**Someone who totally and utterly lacks these five faculties is an outsider who belongs with the ordinary persons, I say.”*";
P_HTM[4248]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4249]="*3. Dutiyasaṃkhittasuttaṃ**Endowed*";
P_HTM[4250]="*Atha kho aññataro bhikkhu yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho so bhikkhu bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then a mendicant went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him:*";
P_HTM[4251]="*“‘Indriyasampanno, indriyasampanno’ti, bhante, vuccati.**“Sir, they speak of someone who is ‘accomplished regarding the faculties’.*";
P_HTM[4252]="*Kittāvatā nu kho, bhante, indriyasampanno hotī”ti?**How is someone accomplished regarding the faculties defined?”*";
P_HTM[4253]="*“Idha, bhikkhu, bhikkhu saddhindriyaṃ bhāveti upasamagāmiṃ sambodhagāmiṃ, vīriyindriyaṃ bhāveti upasamagāmiṃ sambodhagāmiṃ, satindriyaṃ bhāveti upasamagāmiṃ sambodhagāmiṃ, samādhindriyaṃ bhāveti upasamagāmiṃ sambodhagāmiṃ, paññindriyaṃ bhāveti upasamagāmiṃ sambodhagāmiṃ.**“Mendicant, it’s when a mendicant develops the faculties of faith, energy, mindfulness, immersion, and wisdom that lead to peace and awakening.*";
P_HTM[4254]="*Ettāvatā kho, bhikkhu, bhikkhu indriyasampanno hotī”ti.**This is how someone who is accomplished regarding the faculties is defined.”*";
P_HTM[4255]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4256]="*4. Tatiyasaṃkhittasuttaṃ**The Ending of Defilements*";
P_HTM[4257]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, indriyāni.**“Mendicants, there are these five faculties.*";
P_HTM[4258]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[4259]="*Saddhindriyaṃ … pe … paññindriyaṃ—**The faculties of faith, energy, mindfulness, immersion, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[4260]="*imāni kho, bhikkhave, pañcindriyāni.**These are the five faculties.*";
P_HTM[4261]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, pañcannaṃ indriyānaṃ bhāvitattā bahulīkatattā bhikkhu āsavānaṃ khayā anāsavaṃ cetovimuttiṃ paññāvimuttiṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharatī”ti.**It’s because of developing and cultivating these five faculties that a mendicant realizes the undefiled freedom of heart and freedom by wisdom in this very life. And they live having realized it with their own insight due to the ending of defilements.”*";
P_HTM[4262]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4263]="*Mudutaravaggo dutiyo.* **";
P_HTM[4264]="*Paṭilābho tayo saṃkhittā,* **";
P_HTM[4265]="*vitthārā apare tayo;* **";
P_HTM[4266]="*Paṭipanno ca sampanno,* **";
P_HTM[4267]="*dasamaṃ āsavakkhayanti.* **";
P_HTM[4268]="*5. Paṭhamavitthārasuttaṃ**Future Lives*";
P_HTM[4269]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, indriyāni.**“Mendicants, there are these five faculties.*";
P_HTM[4270]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[4271]="*Saddhindriyaṃ … pe … paññindriyaṃ.**The faculties of faith, energy, mindfulness, immersion, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[4272]="*Yāvakīvañcāhaṃ, bhikkhave, imesaṃ pañcannaṃ indriyānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ nābbhaññāsiṃ, neva tāvāhaṃ, bhikkhave, sadevake loke samārake sabrahmake sassamaṇabrāhmaṇiyā pajāya sadevamanussāya ‘anuttaraṃ sammāsambodhiṃ abhisambuddho’ti paccaññāsiṃ.**As long as I didn’t truly understand these five faculties’ gratification, drawback, and escape for what they are, I didn’t announce my supreme perfect awakening in this world with its gods, Māras, and Brahmās, this population with its ascetics and brahmins, its gods and humans.*";
P_HTM[4273]="*Yato ca khvāhaṃ, bhikkhave, imesaṃ pañcannaṃ indriyānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ abbhaññāsiṃ, athāhaṃ, bhikkhave, sadevake loke samārake sabrahmake sassamaṇabrāhmaṇiyā pajāya sadevamanussāya ‘anuttaraṃ sammāsambodhiṃ abhisambuddho’ti paccaññāsiṃ.**But when I did truly understand these five faculties’ gratification, drawback, and escape for what they are, I announced my supreme perfect awakening in this world with its gods, Māras, and Brahmās, this population with its ascetics and brahmins, its gods and humans.*";
P_HTM[4274]="*Ñāṇañca pana me dassanaṃ udapādi:**Knowledge and vision arose in me:*";
P_HTM[4275]="*‘akuppā me vimutti, ayamantimā jāti, natthi dāni punabbhavo’”ti.**‘My freedom is unshakable; this is my last rebirth; now there are no more future lives.’”*";
P_HTM[4276]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4277]="*6. Dutiyavitthārasuttaṃ**The Life Faculty*";
P_HTM[4278]="*“Tīṇimāni, bhikkhave, indriyāni.**“Mendicants, there are these three faculties.*";
P_HTM[4279]="*Katamāni tīṇi?**What three?*";
P_HTM[4280]="*Itthindriyaṃ, purisindriyaṃ, jīvitindriyaṃ—**The faculties of femininity, masculinity, and life.*";
P_HTM[4281]="*imāni kho, bhikkhave, tīṇi indriyānī”ti.**These are the three faculties.”*";
P_HTM[4282]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4283]="*7. Tatiyavitthārasuttaṃ**The Faculty of Enlightenment*";
P_HTM[4284]="*“Tīṇimāni, bhikkhave, indriyāni.**“Mendicants, there are these three faculties.*";
P_HTM[4285]="*Katamāni tīṇi?**What three?*";
P_HTM[4286]="*Anaññātaññassāmītindriyaṃ, aññindriyaṃ, aññātāvindriyaṃ—**The faculty of understanding that one’s enlightenment is imminent. The faculty of enlightenment. The faculty of one who is enlightened.*";
P_HTM[4287]="*imāni kho, bhikkhave, tīṇi indriyānī”ti.**These are the three faculties.”*";
P_HTM[4288]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4289]="*8. Paṭipannasuttaṃ**A One*";
P_HTM[4290]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, indriyāni.**“Mendicants, there are these five faculties.*";
P_HTM[4291]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[4292]="*Saddhindriyaṃ … pe … paññindriyaṃ—**The faculties of faith, energy, mindfulness, immersion, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[4293]="*imāni kho, bhikkhave, pañcindriyāni.**These are the five faculties.*";
P_HTM[4294]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, pañcannaṃ indriyānaṃ samattā paripūrattā arahaṃ hoti, tato mudutarehi antarāparinibbāyī hoti, tato mudutarehi upahaccaparinibbāyī hoti, tato mudutarehi asaṅkhāraparinibbāyī hoti, tato mudutarehi sasaṅkhāraparinibbāyī hoti, tato mudutarehi uddhaṃsoto hoti akaniṭṭhagāmī, tato mudutarehi sakadāgāmī hoti, tato mudutarehi ekabījī hoti, tato mudutarehi kolaṃkolo hoti, tato mudutarehi sattakkhattuparamo hoti, tato mudutarehi dhammānusārī hoti, tato mudutarehi saddhānusārī hotī”ti.**Someone who has completed and fulfilled these five faculties is a perfected one. If they are weaker than that, they’re one who is extinguished between one life and the next … one who is extinguished upon landing … one who is extinguished without extra effort … one who is extinguished with extra effort … one who heads upstream, going to the Akaniṭṭha realm … a once-returner … a one-seeder … one who goes from family to family … one who has seven rebirths at most … a follower of the teachings … a follower by faith.”*";
P_HTM[4295]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4296]="*9. Sampannasuttaṃ**Plain Version*";
P_HTM[4297]="*“Chayimāni, bhikkhave, indriyāni.**“Mendicants, there are these six faculties.*";
P_HTM[4298]="*Katamāni cha?**What six?*";
P_HTM[4299]="*Cakkhundriyaṃ, sotindriyaṃ, ghānindriyaṃ, jivhindriyaṃ, kāyindriyaṃ, manindriyaṃ—**The faculties of the eye, ear, nose, tongue, body, and mind.*";
P_HTM[4300]="*imāni kho, bhikkhave, cha indriyānī”ti.**These are the six faculties.”*";
P_HTM[4301]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4302]="*10. Āsavakkhayasuttaṃ**A Stream*";
P_HTM[4303]="*“Chayimāni, bhikkhave, indriyāni.**“Mendicants, there are these six faculties.*";
P_HTM[4304]="*Katamāni cha?**What six?*";
P_HTM[4305]="*Cakkhundriyaṃ … pe … manindriyaṃ.**The faculties of the eye, ear, nose, tongue, body, and mind.*";
P_HTM[4306]="*Yato kho, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako imesaṃ channaṃ indriyānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti—**A noble disciple comes to truly understand these six faculties’ origin, ending, gratification, drawback, and escape.*";
P_HTM[4307]="*ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako sotāpanno avinipātadhammo niyato sambodhiparāyaṇo”ti.**Such a noble disciple is called a stream-enterer, not liable to be reborn in the underworld, bound for awakening.”*";
P_HTM[4308]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4309]="*8. Gaṅgāpeyyālavaggo**The Six Faculties*";
P_HTM[4310]="*1. Punabbhavasuttaṃ**A Perfected One*";
P_HTM[4311]="*“Chayimāni, bhikkhave, indriyāni.**“Mendicants, there are these six faculties.*";
P_HTM[4312]="*Katamāni cha?**What six?*";
P_HTM[4313]="*Cakkhundriyaṃ, sotindriyaṃ, ghānindriyaṃ, jivhindriyaṃ, kāyindriyaṃ, manindriyaṃ.**The faculties of the eye, ear, nose, tongue, body, and mind.*";
P_HTM[4314]="*Yato kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu imesaṃ channaṃ indriyānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ viditvā anupādāvimutto hoti—**A mendicant comes to be freed by not grasping after truly understanding these six faculties’ origin, ending, gratification, drawback, and escape.*";
P_HTM[4315]="*ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, ‘bhikkhu arahaṃ khīṇāsavo vusitavā katakaraṇīyo ohitabhāro anuppattasadattho parikkhīṇabhavasaṃyojano sammadaññāvimutto’”ti.**Such a mendicant is called a perfected one, with defilements ended, who has completed the spiritual journey, done what had to be done, laid down the burden, achieved their own true goal, utterly ended the fetters of rebirth, and is rightly freed through enlightenment.”*";
P_HTM[4316]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4317]="*2. Jīvitindriyasuttaṃ**Awakened*";
P_HTM[4318]="*“Chayimāni, bhikkhave, indriyāni.**“Mendicants, there are these six faculties.*";
P_HTM[4319]="*Katamāni cha?**What six?*";
P_HTM[4320]="*Cakkhundriyaṃ, sotindriyaṃ, ghānindriyaṃ, jivhindriyaṃ, kāyindriyaṃ, manindriyaṃ.**The faculties of the eye, ear, nose, tongue, body, and mind.*";
P_HTM[4321]="*Yāvakīvañcāhaṃ, bhikkhave, imesaṃ channaṃ indriyānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ nābbhaññāsiṃ, neva tāvāhaṃ, bhikkhave, sadevake loke samārake sabrahmake sassamaṇabrāhmaṇiyā pajāya sadevamanussāya ‘anuttaraṃ sammāsambodhiṃ abhisambuddho’ti paccaññāsiṃ.**As long as I didn’t truly understand these six faculties’ gratification, drawback, and escape for what they are, I didn’t announce my supreme perfect awakening in this world with its gods, Māras, and Brahmās, this population with its ascetics and brahmins, its gods and humans.*";
P_HTM[4322]="*Yato ca khvāhaṃ, bhikkhave, imesaṃ channaṃ indriyānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ abbhaññāsiṃ, athāhaṃ, bhikkhave, sadevake loke samārake sabrahmake sassamaṇabrāhmaṇiyā pajāya sadevamanussāya ‘anuttaraṃ sammāsambodhiṃ abhisambuddho’ti paccaññāsiṃ.**But when I did truly understand these six faculties’ gratification, drawback, and escape for what they are, I announced my supreme perfect awakening in this world with its gods, Māras, and Brahmās, this population with its ascetics and brahmins, its gods and humans.*";
P_HTM[4323]="*Ñāṇañca pana me dassanaṃ udapādi:**Knowledge and vision arose in me:*";
P_HTM[4324]="*‘akuppā me vimutti, ayamantimā jāti, natthi dāni punabbhavo’”ti.**‘My freedom is unshakable; this is my last rebirth; now there are no more future lives.’”*";
P_HTM[4325]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4326]="*3. Aññindriyasuttaṃ**Ascetics and Brahmins (1st)*";
P_HTM[4327]="*“Chayimāni, bhikkhave, indriyāni.**“Mendicants, there are these six faculties.*";
P_HTM[4328]="*Katamāni cha?**What six?*";
P_HTM[4329]="*Cakkhundriyaṃ, sotindriyaṃ, ghānindriyaṃ, jivhindriyaṃ, kāyindriyaṃ, manindriyaṃ.**The faculties of the eye, ear, nose, tongue, body, and mind.*";
P_HTM[4330]="*Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā imesaṃ channaṃ indriyānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ nappajānanti,**There are ascetics and brahmins who don’t truly understand the origin, ending, gratification, drawback, and escape when it comes to these six faculties.*";
P_HTM[4331]="*na me te, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā samaṇesu vā samaṇasammatā brāhmaṇesu vā brāhmaṇasammatā, na ca panete āyasmanto sāmaññatthaṃ vā brahmaññatthaṃ vā diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharanti.**I don’t regard them as true ascetics and brahmins. Those venerables don’t realize the goal of life as an ascetic or brahmin, and don’t live having realized it with their own insight.*";
P_HTM[4332]="*Ye ca kho keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā imesaṃ channaṃ indriyānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ pajānanti,**There are ascetics and brahmins who do truly understand the origin, ending, gratification, drawback, and escape when it comes to these six faculties.*";
P_HTM[4333]="*te kho me, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā samaṇesu ceva samaṇasammatā brāhmaṇesu ca brāhmaṇasammatā, te ca panāyasmanto sāmaññatthañca brahmaññatthañca diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharantī”ti.**I regard them as true ascetics and brahmins. Those venerables realize the goal of life as an ascetic or brahmin, and live having realized it with their own insight.”*";
P_HTM[4334]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4335]="*4. Ekabījīsuttaṃ**Ascetics and Brahmins (2nd)*";
P_HTM[4336]="*“Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā cakkhundriyaṃ nappajānanti, cakkhundriyasamudayaṃ nappajānanti, cakkhundriyanirodhaṃ nappajānanti, cakkhundriyanirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ nappajānanti;**“Mendicants, there are ascetics and brahmins who don’t understand the eye faculty, its origin, its cessation, and the practice that leads to its cessation.*";
P_HTM[4337]="*sotindriyaṃ … pe …**They don’t understand the ear faculty …*";
P_HTM[4338]="*ghānindriyaṃ … pe …**nose faculty …*";
P_HTM[4339]="*jivhindriyaṃ … pe …**tongue faculty …*";
P_HTM[4340]="*kāyindriyaṃ … pe …**body faculty …*";
P_HTM[4341]="*manindriyaṃ nappajānanti, manindriyasamudayaṃ nappajānanti, manindriyanirodhaṃ nappajānanti, manindriyanirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ nappajānanti.**mind faculty, its origin, its cessation, and the practice that leads to its cessation.*";
P_HTM[4342]="*Na me te, bhikkhave … pe … sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharanti.**I don’t regard them as true ascetics and brahmins. Those venerables don’t realize the goal of life as an ascetic or brahmin, and don’t live having realized it with their own insight.*";
P_HTM[4343]="*Ye ca kho keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā cakkhundriyaṃ pajānanti, cakkhundriyasamudayaṃ pajānanti, cakkhundriyanirodhaṃ pajānanti, cakkhundriyanirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ pajānanti,**There are ascetics and brahmins who do understand the eye faculty, its origin, its cessation, and the practice that leads to its cessation.*";
P_HTM[4344]="*sotindriyaṃ … pe …**They understand the ear faculty …*";
P_HTM[4345]="*ghānindriyaṃ … pe …**nose faculty …*";
P_HTM[4346]="*jivhindriyaṃ … pe …**tongue faculty …*";
P_HTM[4347]="*kāyindriyaṃ … pe …**body faculty …*";
P_HTM[4348]="*manindriyaṃ pajānanti, manindriyasamudayaṃ pajānanti, manindriyanirodhaṃ pajānanti, manindriyanirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ pajānanti,**mind faculty, its origin, its cessation, and the practice that leads to its cessation.*";
P_HTM[4349]="*te kho me, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā samaṇesu ceva samaṇasammatā brāhmaṇesu ca brāhmaṇasammatā, te ca panāyasmanto sāmaññatthañca brahmaññatthañca diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharantī”ti.**I regard them as true ascetics and brahmins. Those venerables realize the goal of life as an ascetic or brahmin, and live having realized it with their own insight.”*";
P_HTM[4350]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4351]="*Chaḷindriyavaggo tatiyo.* **";
P_HTM[4352]="*Punabbhavo jīvitaññāya,* **";
P_HTM[4353]="*ekabījī ca suddhakaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[4354]="*Soto arahasambuddho,* **";
P_HTM[4355]="*dve ca samaṇabrāhmaṇāti.* **";
P_HTM[4356]="*5. Suddhakasuttaṃ**Plain Version*";
P_HTM[4357]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, indriyāni.**“Mendicants, there are these five faculties.*";
P_HTM[4358]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[4359]="*Sukhindriyaṃ, dukkhindriyaṃ, somanassindriyaṃ, domanassindriyaṃ, upekkhindriyaṃ—**The faculties of pleasure, pain, happiness, sadness, and equanimity.*";
P_HTM[4360]="*imāni kho, bhikkhave, pañcindriyānī”ti.**These are the five faculties.”*";
P_HTM[4361]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4362]="*6. Sotāpannasuttaṃ**A Stream*";
P_HTM[4363]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, indriyāni.**“Mendicants, there are these five faculties.*";
P_HTM[4364]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[4365]="*Sukhindriyaṃ, dukkhindriyaṃ, somanassindriyaṃ, domanassindriyaṃ, upekkhindriyaṃ.**The faculties of pleasure, pain, happiness, sadness, and equanimity.*";
P_HTM[4366]="*Yato kho, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako imesaṃ pañcannaṃ indriyānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti—**A noble disciple comes to truly understand these five faculties’ origin, ending, gratification, drawback, and escape.*";
P_HTM[4367]="*ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako sotāpanno avinipātadhammo niyato sambodhiparāyaṇo”ti.**Such a noble disciple is called a stream-enterer, not liable to be reborn in the underworld, bound for awakening.”*";
P_HTM[4368]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4369]="*7. Arahantasuttaṃ**A Perfected One*";
P_HTM[4370]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, indriyāni.**“Mendicants, there are these five faculties.*";
P_HTM[4371]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[4372]="*Sukhindriyaṃ, dukkhindriyaṃ, somanassindriyaṃ, domanassindriyaṃ, upekkhindriyaṃ.**The faculties of pleasure, pain, happiness, sadness, and equanimity.*";
P_HTM[4373]="*Yato kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu imesaṃ pañcannaṃ indriyānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ viditvā anupādāvimutto hoti—**A mendicant comes to be freed by not grasping after truly understanding these five faculties’ origin, ending, gratification, drawback, and escape.*";
P_HTM[4374]="*ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, bhikkhu arahaṃ khīṇāsavo vusitavā katakaraṇīyo ohitabhāro anuppattasadattho parikkhīṇabhavasaṃyojano sammadaññāvimutto”ti.**Such a mendicant is called a perfected one, with defilements ended, who has completed the spiritual journey, done what had to be done, laid down the burden, achieved their own true goal, utterly ended the fetters of rebirth, and is rightly freed through enlightenment.”*";
P_HTM[4375]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4376]="*8. Sambuddhasuttaṃ**Ascetics and Brahmins (1st)*";
P_HTM[4377]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, indriyāni.**“Mendicants, there are these five faculties.*";
P_HTM[4378]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[4379]="*Sukhindriyaṃ, dukkhindriyaṃ, somanassindriyaṃ, domanassindriyaṃ, upekkhindriyaṃ.**The faculties of pleasure, pain, happiness, sadness, and equanimity.*";
P_HTM[4380]="*Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā imesaṃ pañcannaṃ indriyānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ nappajānanti,**There are ascetics and brahmins who don’t truly understand the origin, ending, gratification, drawback, and escape when it comes to these five faculties.*";
P_HTM[4381]="*na me te, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā samaṇesu vā samaṇasammatā brāhmaṇesu vā brāhmaṇasammatā, na ca panete āyasmanto sāmaññatthaṃ vā brahmaññatthaṃ vā diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharanti.**I don’t regard them as true ascetics and brahmins. Those venerables don’t realize the goal of life as an ascetic or brahmin, and don’t live having realized it with their own insight.*";
P_HTM[4382]="*Ye ca kho keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā imesaṃ pañcannaṃ indriyānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ pajānanti,**There are ascetics and brahmins who do truly understand the origin, ending, gratification, drawback, and escape when it comes to these five faculties.*";
P_HTM[4383]="*te kho me, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā samaṇesu ceva samaṇasammatā brāhmaṇesu ca brāhmaṇasammatā, te ca panāyasmanto sāmaññatthañca brahmaññatthañca diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharantī”ti.**I regard them as true ascetics and brahmins. Those venerables realize the goal of life as an ascetic or brahmin, and live having realized it with their own insight.”*";
P_HTM[4384]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4385]="*9. Paṭhamasamaṇabrāhmaṇasuttaṃ**Ascetics and Brahmins (2nd)*";
P_HTM[4386]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, indriyāni.**“Mendicants, there are these five faculties.*";
P_HTM[4387]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[4388]="*Sukhindriyaṃ, dukkhindriyaṃ, somanassindriyaṃ, domanassindriyaṃ, upekkhindriyaṃ.**The faculties of pleasure, pain, happiness, sadness, and equanimity.*";
P_HTM[4389]="*Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā sukhindriyaṃ nappajānanti, sukhindriyasamudayaṃ nappajānanti, sukhindriyanirodhaṃ nappajānanti, sukhindriyanirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ nappajānanti;**“Mendicants, there are ascetics and brahmins who don’t understand the faculty of pleasure, its origin, its cessation, and the practice that leads to its cessation.*";
P_HTM[4390]="*dukkhindriyaṃ nappajānanti … pe …**There are ascetics and brahmins who don’t understand the faculty of pain …*";
P_HTM[4391]="*somanassindriyaṃ nappajānanti … pe …**happiness …*";
P_HTM[4392]="*domanassindriyaṃ nappajānanti … pe …**sadness …*";
P_HTM[4393]="*upekkhindriyaṃ nappajānanti, upekkhindriyasamudayaṃ nappajānanti, upekkhindriyanirodhaṃ nappajānanti, upekkhindriyanirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ nappajānanti;**equanimity, its origin, its cessation, and the practice that leads to its cessation.*";
P_HTM[4394]="*na me te, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā samaṇesu vā samaṇasammatā brāhmaṇesu vā brāhmaṇasammatā, na ca panete āyasmanto sāmaññatthaṃ vā brahmaññatthaṃ vā diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharanti.**I don’t regard them as true ascetics and brahmins. Those venerables don’t realize the goal of life as an ascetic or brahmin, and don’t live having realized it with their own insight.*";
P_HTM[4395]="*Ye ca kho keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā sukhindriyaṃ pajānanti, sukhindriyasamudayaṃ pajānanti, sukhindriyanirodhaṃ pajānanti, sukhindriyanirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ pajānanti;**There are ascetics and brahmins who do understand the faculty of pleasure, its origin, its cessation, and the practice that leads to its cessation.*";
P_HTM[4396]="*dukkhindriyaṃ pajānanti … pe …**There are ascetics and brahmins who do understand the faculty of pain …*";
P_HTM[4397]="*somanassindriyaṃ pajānanti … pe …**happiness …*";
P_HTM[4398]="*domanassindriyaṃ pajānanti … pe …**sadness …*";
P_HTM[4399]="*upekkhindriyaṃ pajānanti, upekkhindriyasamudayaṃ pajānanti, upekkhindriyanirodhaṃ pajānanti, upekkhindriyanirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ pajānanti,**equanimity, its origin, its cessation, and the practice that leads to its cessation.*";
P_HTM[4400]="*te ca kho me, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā samaṇesu ceva samaṇasammatā brāhmaṇesu ca brāhmaṇasammatā, te ca panāyasmanto sāmaññatthañca brahmaññatthañca diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharantī”ti.**I regard them as true ascetics and brahmins. Those venerables realize the goal of life as an ascetic or brahmin, and live having realized it with their own insight.”*";
P_HTM[4401]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4402]="*10. Dutiyasamaṇabrāhmaṇasuttaṃ**Analysis (1st)*";
P_HTM[4403]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, indriyāni.**“Mendicants, there are these five faculties.*";
P_HTM[4404]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[4405]="*Sukhindriyaṃ, dukkhindriyaṃ, somanassindriyaṃ, domanassindriyaṃ, upekkhindriyaṃ.**The faculties of pleasure, pain, happiness, sadness, and equanimity.*";
P_HTM[4406]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, sukhindriyaṃ?**And what is the faculty of pleasure?*";
P_HTM[4407]="*Yaṃ kho, bhikkhave, kāyikaṃ sukhaṃ, kāyikaṃ sātaṃ, kāyasamphassajaṃ sukhaṃ sātaṃ vedayitaṃ—**Physical enjoyment, physical pleasure, the enjoyable, pleasant feeling that’s born from physical contact.*";
P_HTM[4408]="*idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, sukhindriyaṃ.**This is called the faculty of pleasure.*";
P_HTM[4409]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, dukkhindriyaṃ?**And what is the faculty of pain?*";
P_HTM[4410]="*Yaṃ kho, bhikkhave, kāyikaṃ dukkhaṃ, kāyikaṃ asātaṃ, kāyasamphassajaṃ dukkhaṃ asātaṃ vedayitaṃ—**Physical pain, physical displeasure, the painful, unpleasant feeling that’s born from physical contact.*";
P_HTM[4411]="*idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, dukkhindriyaṃ.**This is called the faculty of pain.*";
P_HTM[4412]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, somanassindriyaṃ?**And what is the faculty of happiness?*";
P_HTM[4413]="*Yaṃ kho, bhikkhave, cetasikaṃ sukhaṃ, cetasikaṃ sātaṃ, manosamphassajaṃ sukhaṃ sātaṃ vedayitaṃ—**Mental enjoyment, mental pleasure, the enjoyable, pleasant feeling that’s born from mind contact.*";
P_HTM[4414]="*idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, somanassindriyaṃ.**This is called the faculty of happiness.*";
P_HTM[4415]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, domanassindriyaṃ?**And what is the faculty of sadness?*";
P_HTM[4416]="*Yaṃ kho, bhikkhave, cetasikaṃ dukkhaṃ, cetasikaṃ asātaṃ, manosamphassajaṃ dukkhaṃ asātaṃ vedayitaṃ—**Mental pain, mental displeasure, the painful, unpleasant feeling that’s born from mind contact.*";
P_HTM[4417]="*idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, domanassindriyaṃ.**This is called the faculty of sadness.*";
P_HTM[4418]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, upekkhindriyaṃ?**And what is the faculty of equanimity?*";
P_HTM[4419]="*Yaṃ kho, bhikkhave, kāyikaṃ vā cetasikaṃ vā nevasātaṃ nāsātaṃ vedayitaṃ—**Neither pleasant nor unpleasant feeling, whether physical or mental.*";
P_HTM[4420]="*idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, upekkhindriyaṃ.**This is the faculty of equanimity.*";
P_HTM[4421]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, pañcindriyānī”ti.**These are the five faculties.”*";
P_HTM[4422]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
