P_HTM[5949]="*5. Oghavaggo**The Iron Ball*";
P_HTM[5950]="*1. Paṭhamarahogatasuttaṃ**Several Mendicants (1st)*";
P_HTM[5951]="*Atha kho sambahulā bhikkhū yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu. Ekamantaṃ nisinnā kho te bhikkhū bhagavantaṃ etadavocuṃ:**Then several mendicants went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him:*";
P_HTM[5952]="*“katamā nu kho, bhante, iddhi, katamo iddhipādo, katamā iddhipādabhāvanā, katamā iddhipādabhāvanāgāminī paṭipadā”ti?**“Sir, what is psychic power? What is the basis of psychic power? What is the development of the bases of psychic power? And what is the practice that leads to the development of the bases of psychic power?”*";
P_HTM[5953]="*“Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu anekavihitaṃ iddhividhaṃ paccanubhoti—ekopi hutvā bahudhā hoti … pe … yāva brahmalokāpi kāyena vasaṃ vatteti—**“Mendicants, take a mendicant who wields the many kinds of psychic power: multiplying themselves and becoming one again … controlling the body as far as the Brahmā realm.*";
P_HTM[5954]="*ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, iddhi.**This is called psychic power.*";
P_HTM[5955]="*Katamo ca, bhikkhave, iddhipādo?**And what is the basis of psychic power?*";
P_HTM[5956]="*Yo, bhikkhave, maggo, yā paṭipadā iddhilābhāya iddhipaṭilābhāya saṃvattati—**The path and practice that leads to gaining psychic power.*";
P_HTM[5957]="*ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, iddhipādo.**This is called the basis of psychic power.*";
P_HTM[5958]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, iddhipādabhāvanā?**And what is the development of the bases of psychic power?*";
P_HTM[5959]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu chandasamādhippadhānasaṅkhārasamannāgataṃ iddhipādaṃ bhāveti,**It’s when a mendicant develops the basis of psychic power that has immersion due to enthusiasm …*";
P_HTM[5960]="*vīriyasamādhi … pe …**energy …*";
P_HTM[5961]="*cittasamādhi …**mental development …*";
P_HTM[5962]="*vīmaṃsāsamādhippadhānasaṅkhārasamannāgataṃ iddhipādaṃ bhāveti—**inquiry, and active effort.*";
P_HTM[5963]="*ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, iddhipādabhāvanā.**This is called the development of the bases of psychic power.*";
P_HTM[5964]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, iddhipādabhāvanāgāminī paṭipadā?**And what is the practice that leads to the development of the bases of psychic power?*";
P_HTM[5965]="*Ayameva ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo, seyyathidaṃ—**It is simply this noble eightfold path, that is:*";
P_HTM[5966]="*sammādiṭṭhi … pe … sammāsamādhi—**right view, right thought, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, and right immersion.*";
P_HTM[5967]="*ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, iddhipādabhāvanāgāminī paṭipadā”ti.**This is called the practice that leads to the development of the bases of psychic power.”*";
P_HTM[5968]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5969]="*2. Dutiyarahogatasuttaṃ**Several Mendicants (2nd)*";
P_HTM[5970]="*Atha kho sambahulā bhikkhū yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamiṃsu … pe …**Then several mendicants went up to the Buddha …*";
P_HTM[5971]="*ekamantaṃ nisinne kho te bhikkhū bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said to them:*";
P_HTM[5972]="*“katamā nu kho, bhikkhave, iddhi, katamo iddhipādo, katamā iddhipādabhāvanā, katamā iddhipādabhāvanāgāminī paṭipadā”ti?**“Mendicants, what is psychic power? What is the basis of psychic power? What is the development of the bases of psychic power? And what is the practice that leads to the development of the bases of psychic power?”*";
P_HTM[5973]="*“Bhagavaṃmūlakā no, bhante, dhammā bhagavaṃnettikā … pe ….**“Our teachings are rooted in the Buddha. He is our guide and our refuge. …”*";
P_HTM[5974]="*“Katamā ca, bhikkhave, iddhi?**“And what is psychic power?*";
P_HTM[5975]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu anekavihitaṃ iddhividhaṃ paccanubhoti—ekopi hutvā bahudhā hoti … pe … yāva brahmalokāpi kāyena vasaṃ vatteti—**It’s a mendicant who wields the many kinds of psychic power: multiplying themselves and becoming one again … controlling the body as far as the Brahmā realm.*";
P_HTM[5976]="*ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, iddhi.**This is called psychic power.*";
P_HTM[5977]="*Katamo ca, bhikkhave, iddhipādo?**And what is the basis of psychic power?*";
P_HTM[5978]="*Yo, bhikkhave, maggo, yā paṭipadā iddhilābhāya iddhipaṭilābhāya saṃvattati—**The path and practice that leads to gaining psychic power.*";
P_HTM[5979]="*ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, iddhipādo.**This is called the basis of psychic power.*";
P_HTM[5980]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, iddhipādabhāvanā?**And what is the development of the bases of psychic power?*";
P_HTM[5981]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu chandasamādhippadhānasaṅkhārasamannāgataṃ iddhipādaṃ bhāveti,**It’s when a mendicant develops the basis of psychic power that has immersion due to enthusiasm …*";
P_HTM[5982]="*vīriyasamādhi … pe …**energy …*";
P_HTM[5983]="*cittasamādhi …**mental development …*";
P_HTM[5984]="*vīmaṃsāsamādhippadhānasaṅkhārasamannāgataṃ iddhipādaṃ bhāveti—**inquiry, and active effort.*";
P_HTM[5985]="*ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, iddhipādabhāvanā.**This is called the development of the bases of psychic power.*";
P_HTM[5986]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, iddhipādabhāvanāgāminī paṭipadā?**And what is the practice that leads to the development of the bases of psychic power?*";
P_HTM[5987]="*Ayameva ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo, seyyathidaṃ—**It is simply this noble eightfold path, that is:*";
P_HTM[5988]="*sammādiṭṭhi … pe … sammāsamādhi—**right view, right thought, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, and right immersion.*";
P_HTM[5989]="*ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, iddhipādabhāvanāgāminī paṭipadā”ti.**This is called the practice that leads to the development of the bases of psychic power.”*";
P_HTM[5990]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5991]="*3. Sutanusuttaṃ**About Moggallāna*";
P_HTM[5992]="*Tatra kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**There the Buddha addressed the mendicants:*";
P_HTM[5993]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhikkhave,**“What do you think, mendicants?*";
P_HTM[5994]="*katamesaṃ dhammānaṃ bhāvitattā bahulīkatattā moggallāno bhikkhu evaṃmahiddhiko evaṃmahānubhāvo”ti?**What things has the mendicant Moggallāna developed and cultivated so as to have such power and might?”*";
P_HTM[5995]="*“Bhagavaṃmūlakā no, bhante, dhammā bhagavaṃnettikā … pe …**“Our teachings are rooted in the Buddha. He is our guide and our refuge. …”*";
P_HTM[5996]="*“catunnaṃ kho, bhikkhave, iddhipādānaṃ bhāvitattā bahulīkatattā moggallāno bhikkhu evaṃmahiddhiko evaṃmahānubhāvo.**“The mendicant Moggallāna has become so powerful and mighty by developing and cultivating the four bases of psychic power.*";
P_HTM[5997]="*Katamesaṃ catunnaṃ?**What four?*";
P_HTM[5998]="*Idha, bhikkhave, moggallāno bhikkhu chandasamādhippadhānasaṅkhārasamannāgataṃ iddhipādaṃ bhāveti—**Moggallāna develops the basis of psychic power that has immersion due to enthusiasm, and active effort.*";
P_HTM[5999]="*iti me chando na ca atilīno bhavissati, na ca atippaggahito bhavissati, na ca ajjhattaṃ saṅkhitto bhavissati, na ca bahiddhā vikkhitto bhavissati.**He thinks: ‘My enthusiasm won’t be too lax or too tense. And it’ll be neither constricted internally nor scattered externally.’*";
P_HTM[6000]="*Pacchāpuresaññī ca viharati—**And he meditates perceiving continuity:*";
P_HTM[6001]="*yathā pure tathā pacchā, yathā pacchā tathā pure;**as before, so after; as after, so before;*";
P_HTM[6002]="*yathā adho tathā uddhaṃ, yathā uddhaṃ tathā adho;**as below, so above; as above, so below;*";
P_HTM[6003]="*yathā divā tathā rattiṃ, yathā rattiṃ tathā divā.**as by day, so by night; as by night, so by day.*";
P_HTM[6004]="*Iti vivaṭena cetasā apariyonaddhena sappabhāsaṃ cittaṃ bhāveti.**And so, with an open and unenveloped heart, he develops a mind that’s full of radiance.*";
P_HTM[6005]="*Vīriyasamādhi … pe …**He develops the basis of psychic power that has immersion due to energy …*";
P_HTM[6006]="*cittasamādhi …**mental development …*";
P_HTM[6007]="*vīmaṃsāsamādhippadhānasaṅkhārasamannāgataṃ iddhipādaṃ bhāveti—**inquiry, and active effort.*";
P_HTM[6008]="*iti me vīmaṃsā na ca atilīnā bhavissati, na ca atippaggahitā bhavissati, na ca ajjhattaṃ saṅkhittā bhavissati, na ca bahiddhā vikkhittā bhavissati … pe …**He thinks: ‘My inquiry won’t be too lax or too tense. And it’ll be neither constricted internally nor scattered externally.’ …*";
P_HTM[6009]="*iti vivaṭena cetasā apariyonaddhena sappabhāsaṃ cittaṃ bhāveti.**And so, with an open and unenveloped heart, he develops a mind that’s full of radiance.*";
P_HTM[6010]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, catunnaṃ iddhipādānaṃ bhāvitattā bahulīkatattā moggallāno bhikkhu evaṃmahiddhiko evaṃmahānubhāvo.**The mendicant Moggallāna has become so powerful and mighty by developing and cultivating these four bases of psychic power.*";
P_HTM[6011]="*Imesañca pana, bhikkhave, catunnaṃ iddhipādānaṃ bhāvitattā bahulīkatattā moggallāno bhikkhu evaṃ anekavihitaṃ iddhividhaṃ paccanubhoti—ekopi hutvā bahudhā hoti, bahudhāpi hutvā eko hoti … pe … yāva brahmalokāpi kāyena vasaṃ vatteti.**And by developing and cultivating these four bases of psychic power, the mendicant Moggallāna wields the many kinds of psychic power: multiplying himself and becoming one again … controlling the body as far as the Brahmā realm.*";
P_HTM[6012]="*Imesañca pana, bhikkhave, catunnaṃ iddhipādānaṃ bhāvitattā bahulīkatattā moggallāno bhikkhu āsavānaṃ khayā anāsavaṃ cetovimuttiṃ paññāvimuttiṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharatī”ti.**And by developing and cultivating these four bases of psychic power, the mendicant Moggallāna realizes the undefiled freedom of heart and freedom by wisdom in this very life. And he lives having realized it with his own insight due to the ending of defilements.”*";
P_HTM[6013]="*Ekādasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6014]="*4. Paṭhamakaṇḍakīsuttaṃ**The Realized One*";
P_HTM[6015]="*Tatra kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**There the Buddha addressed the mendicants:*";
P_HTM[6016]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhikkhave,**“What do you think, mendicants?*";
P_HTM[6017]="*katamesaṃ dhammānaṃ bhāvitattā bahulīkatattā tathāgato evaṃmahiddhiko evaṃmahānubhāvo”ti?**What things has the Realized One developed and cultivated so as to have such power and might?”*";
P_HTM[6018]="*“Bhagavaṃmūlakā no, bhante, dhammā … pe …**“Our teachings are rooted in the Buddha. …”*";
P_HTM[6019]="*“catunnaṃ kho, bhikkhave, iddhipādānaṃ bhāvitattā bahulīkatattā tathāgato evaṃmahiddhiko evaṃmahānubhāvo.**“The Realized One has become so powerful and mighty by developing and cultivating the four bases of psychic power.*";
P_HTM[6020]="*Katamesaṃ catunnaṃ?**What four?*";
P_HTM[6021]="*Idha, bhikkhave, tathāgato chandasamādhippadhānasaṅkhārasamannāgataṃ iddhipādaṃ bhāveti—**It’s when a mendicant develops the basis of psychic power that has immersion due to enthusiasm, and active effort.*";
P_HTM[6022]="*iti me chando na ca atilīno bhavissati, na ca atippaggahito bhavissati, na ca ajjhattaṃ saṅkhitto bhavissati, na ca bahiddhā vikkhitto bhavissati.**He thinks: ‘My enthusiasm won’t be too lax or too tense. And it’ll be neither constricted internally nor scattered externally.’*";
P_HTM[6023]="*Pacchāpuresaññī ca viharati—**And he meditates perceiving continuity:*";
P_HTM[6024]="*yathā pure tathā pacchā, yathā pacchā tathā pure;**as before, so after; as after, so before;*";
P_HTM[6025]="*yathā adho tathā uddhaṃ, yathā uddhaṃ tathā adho;**as below, so above; as above, so below;*";
P_HTM[6026]="*yathā divā tathā rattiṃ, yathā rattiṃ tathā divā.**as by day, so by night; as by night, so by day.*";
P_HTM[6027]="*Iti vivaṭena cetasā apariyonaddhena sappabhāsaṃ cittaṃ bhāveti.**And so, with an open and unenveloped heart, he develops a mind that’s full of radiance.*";
P_HTM[6028]="*Vīriyasamādhi … pe …**He develops the basis of psychic power that has immersion due to energy …*";
P_HTM[6029]="*cittasamādhi …**mental development …*";
P_HTM[6030]="*vīmaṃsāsamādhippadhānasaṅkhārasamannāgataṃ iddhipādaṃ bhāveti—**inquiry, and active effort.*";
P_HTM[6031]="*iti me vīmaṃsā na ca atilīnā bhavissati, na ca atipaggahitā bhavissati, na ca ajjhattaṃ saṅkhittā bhavissati, na ca bahiddhā vikkhittā bhavissati.**He thinks: ‘My inquiry won’t be too lax or too tense. And it’ll be neither constricted internally nor scattered externally.’*";
P_HTM[6032]="*Pacchāpuresaññī ca viharati—**And he meditates perceiving continuity:*";
P_HTM[6033]="*yathā pure tathā pacchā, yathā pacchā tathā pure;**as before, so after; as after, so before;*";
P_HTM[6034]="*yathā adho tathā uddhaṃ, yathā uddhaṃ tathā adho;**as below, so above; as above, so below;*";
P_HTM[6035]="*yathā divā tathā rattiṃ, yathā rattiṃ tathā divā.**as by day, so by night; as by night, so by day.*";
P_HTM[6036]="*Iti vivaṭena cetasā apariyonaddhena sappabhāsaṃ cittaṃ bhāveti.**And so, with an open and unenveloped heart, he develops a mind that’s full of radiance.*";
P_HTM[6037]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, catunnaṃ iddhipādānaṃ bhāvitattā bahulīkatattā tathāgato evaṃmahiddhiko evaṃmahānubhāvo.**The Realized One has become so powerful and mighty by developing and cultivating these four bases of psychic power.*";
P_HTM[6038]="*Imesañca pana, bhikkhave, catunnaṃ iddhipādānaṃ bhāvitattā bahulīkatattā tathāgato anekavihitaṃ iddhividhaṃ paccanubhoti—ekopi hutvā bahudhā hoti … pe … yāva brahmalokāpi kāyena vasaṃ vatteti.**And by developing and cultivating these four bases of psychic power, the Realized One wields the many kinds of psychic power: multiplying himself and becoming one again … controlling the body as far as the Brahmā realm.*";
P_HTM[6039]="*Imesañca pana, bhikkhave, catunnaṃ iddhipādānaṃ bhāvitattā bahulīkatattā tathāgato āsavānaṃ khayā anāsavaṃ cetovimuttiṃ paññāvimuttiṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharatī”ti.**And by developing and cultivating these four bases of psychic power, the Realized One realizes the undefiled freedom of heart and freedom by wisdom in this very life. And he lives having realized it with his own insight due to the ending of defilements.”*";
P_HTM[6040]="*Dvādasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6041]="*(Chapi abhiññāyo vitthāretabbā.)**(The six direct knowledges should also be expanded.)*";
P_HTM[6042]="*Ayoguḷavaggo tatiyo.* **";
P_HTM[6043]="*Maggo ayoguḷo bhikkhu,* **";
P_HTM[6044]="*suddhikañcāpi dve phalā;* **";
P_HTM[6045]="*Dve cānandā duve bhikkhū,* **";
P_HTM[6046]="*moggallāno tathāgatoti.* **";
P_HTM[6047]="*5. Dutiyakaṇḍakīsuttaṃ**33–44. Gaṅgānadīādisutta*";
P_HTM[6048]="*“Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, gaṅgā nadī pācīnaninnā pācīnapoṇā pācīnapabbhārā;**“Mendicants, the Ganges river slants, slopes, and inclines to the east.*";
P_HTM[6049]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu cattāro iddhipāde bhāvento cattāro iddhipāde bahulīkaronto nibbānaninno hoti nibbānapoṇo nibbānapabbhāro.**In the same way, a mendicant who develops and cultivates the four bases of psychic power slants, slopes, and inclines to extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[6050]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhu cattāro iddhipāde bhāvento cattāro iddhipāde bahulīkaronto nibbānaninno hoti nibbānapoṇo nibbānapabbhāro?**And how does a mendicant who develops the four bases of psychic power slant, slope, and incline to extinguishment?*";
P_HTM[6051]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu chandasamādhippadhānasaṅkhārasamannāgataṃ iddhipādaṃ bhāveti,**It’s when a mendicant develops the basis of psychic power that has immersion due to enthusiasm …*";
P_HTM[6052]="*vīriyasamādhi … pe …**energy …*";
P_HTM[6053]="*cittasamādhi …**mental development …*";
P_HTM[6054]="*vīmaṃsāsamādhippadhānasaṅkhārasamannāgataṃ iddhipādaṃ bhāveti.**inquiry, and active effort.*";
P_HTM[6055]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu cattāro iddhipāde bhāvento cattāro iddhipāde bahulīkaronto nibbānaninno hoti nibbānapoṇo nibbānapabbhāro”ti.**In the same way, a mendicant who develops and cultivates the four bases of psychic power slants, slopes, and inclines to extinguishment.”*";
P_HTM[6056]="*Dvādasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6057]="*Gaṅgāpeyyālavaggo catuttho.**(To be expanded for each of the different rivers as in SN 45.91–102.)*";
P_HTM[6058]="*Cha pācīnato ninnā,**Six on slanting to the east,*";
P_HTM[6059]="*cha ninnā ca samuddato;**and six on slanting to the ocean;*";
P_HTM[6060]="*Dvete cha dvādasa honti,**these two sixes make twelve,*";
P_HTM[6061]="*vaggo tena pavuccatīti.**and that’s how this chapter is recited.*";
P_HTM[6062]="*6. Tatiyakaṇḍakīsuttaṃ**45. Appamādavagga*";
P_HTM[6063]="*(Appamādavaggo vitthāretabbo.)**(To be expanded as in the chapter on diligence at SN 45.139–148.)*";
P_HTM[6064]="*Tathāgataṃ padaṃ kūṭaṃ,**The Realized One, footprint, roof peak,*";
P_HTM[6065]="*mūlaṃ sāro ca vassikaṃ;**roots, heartwood, jasmine,*";
P_HTM[6066]="*Rājā candimasūriyā,**monarch, sun and moon,*";
P_HTM[6067]="*vatthena dasamaṃ padanti.**and cloth is the tenth.*";
P_HTM[6068]="*7. Taṇhakkhayasuttaṃ**55. Balakaraṇīyavagga*";
P_HTM[6069]="*(Balakaraṇīyavaggo vitthāretabbo.)**(To be expanded as in the chapter on hard work at SN 45.149–160.)*";
P_HTM[6070]="*Balaṃ bījañca nāgo ca,**Hard work, seeds, and dragons,*";
P_HTM[6071]="*rukkho kumbhena sūkiyā;**a tree, a pot, and a spike,*";
P_HTM[6072]="*Ākāsena ca dve meghā,**the sky, and two on clouds,*";
P_HTM[6073]="*nāvā āgantukā nadīti.**a ship, a guest house, and a river.*";
P_HTM[6074]="*8. Salaḷāgārasuttaṃ**67. Esanāvagga*";
P_HTM[6075]="*(Esanāvaggo vitthāretabbo.)**(To be expanded as in the chapter on searches at SN 45.161–170.)*";
P_HTM[6076]="*Esanā vidhā āsavo,**Searches, discriminations, defilements,*";
P_HTM[6077]="*Bhavo ca dukkhatā tisso;**states of existence, three kinds of suffering,*";
P_HTM[6078]="*Khilaṃ malañca nīgho ca,**barrenness, stains, and troubles,*";
P_HTM[6079]="*Vedanā taṇhā tasinā cāti.**feelings, craving, and thirst.*";
P_HTM[6080]="*9. Ambapālivanasuttaṃ**77–86. Oghādisutta*";
P_HTM[6081]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, uddhambhāgiyāni saṃyojanāni.**“Mendicants, there are five higher fetters.*";
P_HTM[6082]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[6083]="*Rūparāgo, arūparāgo, māno, uddhaccaṃ, avijjā—**Desire for rebirth in the realm of luminous form, desire for rebirth in the formless realm, conceit, restlessness, and ignorance.*";
P_HTM[6084]="*imāni kho, bhikkhave, pañcuddhambhāgiyāni saṃyojanāni.**These are the five higher fetters.*";
P_HTM[6085]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, pañcannaṃ uddhambhāgiyānaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ abhiññāya pariññāya parikkhayāya pahānāya cattāro iddhipādā bhāvetabbā.**The four bases of psychic power should be developed for the direct knowledge, complete understanding, finishing, and giving up of these five higher fetters.*";
P_HTM[6086]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[6087]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu chandasamādhippadhānasaṅkhārasamannāgataṃ iddhipādaṃ bhāveti,**It’s when a mendicant develops the basis of psychic power that has immersion due to enthusiasm …*";
P_HTM[6088]="*vīriyasamādhi … pe …**energy …*";
P_HTM[6089]="*cittasamādhi …**mental development …*";
P_HTM[6090]="*vīmaṃsāsamādhippadhānasaṅkhārasamannāgataṃ iddhipādaṃ bhāveti.**inquiry, and active effort.*";
P_HTM[6091]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, pañcannaṃ uddhambhāgiyānaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ abhiññāya pariññāya parikkhayāya pahānāya ime cattāro iddhipādā bhāvetabbā”ti.**These four bases of psychic power should be developed for the direct knowledge, complete understanding, finishing, and giving up of these five higher fetters.”*";
P_HTM[6092]="*(Yathā maggasaṃyuttaṃ tathā vitthāretabbaṃ.)**(To be expanded as in the Linked Discourses on the Path at SN 45.171–180.)*";
P_HTM[6093]="*Oghavaggo aṭṭhamo.* **";
P_HTM[6094]="*Ogho yogo upādānaṃ,**Floods, bonds, grasping,*";
P_HTM[6095]="*ganthā anusayena ca;**ties, and underlying tendencies,*";
P_HTM[6096]="*Kāmaguṇā nīvaraṇā,**kinds of sensual stimulation, hindrances,*";
P_HTM[6097]="*khandhā oruddhambhāgiyāti.**aggregates, and fetters high and low.*";
P_HTM[6098]="*Iddhipādasaṃyuttaṃ sattamaṃ.**The Linked Discourses on the Bases of psychic Power is the seventh section.*";
P_HTM[6099]="*52. Anuruddhasaṃyuttaṃ* **";
P_HTM[6100]="*10. Bāḷhagilānasuttaṃ**In Private (1st)*";
P_HTM[6101]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[6102]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ āyasmā anuruddho sāvatthiyaṃ viharati jetavane anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme.**At one time Venerable Sāriputta was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery.*";
P_HTM[6103]="*Atha kho āyasmato anuruddhassa rahogatassa paṭisallīnassa evaṃ cetaso parivitakko udapādi:**Then as Anuruddha was in private retreat this thought came to his mind:*";
P_HTM[6104]="*“yesaṃ kesañci cattāro satipaṭṭhānā viraddhā, viraddho tesaṃ ariyo maggo sammā dukkhakkhayagāmī.**“Whoever has missed out on these four kinds of mindfulness meditation has missed out on the noble path to the complete ending of suffering.*";
P_HTM[6105]="*Yesaṃ kesañci cattāro satipaṭṭhānā āraddhā, āraddho tesaṃ ariyo maggo sammā dukkhakkhayagāmī”ti.**Whoever has undertaken these four kinds of mindfulness meditation has undertaken the noble path to the complete ending of suffering.”*";
P_HTM[6106]="*Atha kho āyasmā mahāmoggallāno āyasmato anuruddhassa cetasā cetoparivitakkamaññāya—seyyathāpi nāma balavā puriso samiñjitaṃ vā bāhaṃ pasāreyya, pasāritaṃ vā bāhaṃ samiñjeyya; evameva—āyasmato anuruddhassa sammukhe pāturahosi.**Then Venerable Mahāmoggallāna knew what Venerable Anuruddha was thinking. As easily as a strong person would extend or contract their arm, he reappeared in front of Anuruddha,*";
P_HTM[6107]="*Atha kho āyasmā mahāmoggallāno āyasmantaṃ anuruddhaṃ etadavoca:**and said to him:*";
P_HTM[6108]="*“kittāvatā nu kho, āvuso anuruddha, bhikkhuno cattāro satipaṭṭhānā āraddhā hontī”ti?**“Reverend Anuruddha, how do you define the undertaking of the four kinds of mindfulness meditation by a mendicant?”*";
P_HTM[6109]="*“Idhāvuso, bhikkhu ajjhattaṃ kāye samudayadhammānupassī viharati, ajjhattaṃ kāye vayadhammānupassī viharati, ajjhattaṃ kāye samudayavayadhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**“Reverend, it’s when a mendicant meditates observing the body internally as liable to originate, as liable to vanish, and as liable to originate and vanish—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[6110]="*Bahiddhā kāye samudayadhammānupassī viharati, bahiddhā kāye vayadhammānupassī viharati, bahiddhā kāye samudayavayadhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**They meditate observing the body externally as liable to originate, as liable to vanish, and as liable to originate and vanish—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[6111]="*Ajjhattabahiddhā kāye samudayadhammānupassī viharati, ajjhattabahiddhā kāye vayadhammānupassī viharati, ajjhattabahiddhā kāye samudayavayadhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**They meditate observing the body internally and externally as liable to originate, as liable to vanish, and as liable to originate and vanish—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[6112]="*So sace ākaṅkhati: ‘appaṭikūle paṭikūlasaññī vihareyyan’ti, paṭikūlasaññī tattha viharati;**If they wish: ‘May I meditate perceiving the repulsive in the unrepulsive,’ that’s what they do.*";
P_HTM[6113]="*sace ākaṅkhati: ‘paṭikūle appaṭikūlasaññī vihareyyan’ti, appaṭikūlasaññī tattha viharati;**If they wish: ‘May I meditate perceiving the unrepulsive in the repulsive,’ that’s what they do.*";
P_HTM[6114]="*sace ākaṅkhati: ‘appaṭikūle ca paṭikūle ca paṭikūlasaññī vihareyyan’ti, paṭikūlasaññī tattha viharati;**If they wish: ‘May I meditate perceiving the repulsive in the unrepulsive and the repulsive,’ that’s what they do.*";
P_HTM[6115]="*sace ākaṅkhati: ‘paṭikūle ca appaṭikūle ca appaṭikūlasaññī vihareyyan’ti, appaṭikūlasaññī tattha viharati;**If they wish: ‘May I meditate perceiving the unrepulsive in the repulsive and the unrepulsive,’ that’s what they do.*";
P_HTM[6116]="*sace ākaṅkhati: ‘appaṭikūlañca paṭikūlañca tadubhayaṃ abhinivajjetvā upekkhako vihareyyaṃ sato sampajāno’ti, upekkhako tattha viharati sato sampajāno.**If they wish: ‘May I meditate staying equanimous, mindful and aware, rejecting both the repulsive and the unrepulsive,’ that’s what they do.*";
P_HTM[6117]="*Ajjhattaṃ vedanāsu samudayadhammānupassī viharati, ajjhattaṃ vedanāsu vayadhammānupassī viharati, ajjhattaṃ vedanāsu samudayavayadhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**They meditate observing feelings internally …*";
P_HTM[6118]="*Bahiddhā vedanāsu samudayadhammānupassī viharati, bahiddhā vedanāsu vayadhammānupassī viharati, bahiddhā vedanāsu samudayavayadhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**externally …*";
P_HTM[6119]="*Ajjhattabahiddhā vedanāsu samudayadhammānupassī viharati, ajjhattabahiddhā vedanāsu vayadhammānupassī viharati, ajjhattabahiddhā vedanāsu samudayavayadhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**internally and externally as liable to originate, as liable to vanish, and as liable to originate and vanish …*";
P_HTM[6120]="*So sace ākaṅkhati: ‘appaṭikūle paṭikūlasaññī vihareyyan’ti, paṭikūlasaññī tattha viharati;* **";
P_HTM[6121]="*sace ākaṅkhati: ‘paṭikūle appaṭikūlasaññī vihareyyan’ti, appaṭikūlasaññī tattha viharati;* **";
P_HTM[6122]="*sace ākaṅkhati: ‘appaṭikūle ca paṭikūle ca paṭikūlasaññī vihareyyan’ti, paṭikūlasaññī tattha viharati;* **";
P_HTM[6123]="*sace ākaṅkhati: ‘paṭikūle ca appaṭikūle ca appaṭikūlasaññī vihareyyan’ti, appaṭikūlasaññī tattha viharati;* **";
P_HTM[6124]="*sace ākaṅkhati: ‘appaṭikūlañca paṭikūlañca tadubhayaṃ abhinivajjetvā upekkhako vihareyyaṃ sato sampajāno’ti, upekkhako tattha viharati sato sampajāno.* **";
P_HTM[6125]="*Ajjhattaṃ citte … pe …**They meditate observing the mind internally …*";
P_HTM[6126]="*bahiddhā citte … pe …**externally …*";
P_HTM[6127]="*ajjhattabahiddhā citte samudayadhammānupassī viharati … ajjhattabahiddhā citte vayadhammānupassī viharati … ajjhattabahiddhā citte samudayavayadhammānupassī viharati ātāpī … pe … abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**internally and externally as liable to originate, as liable to vanish, and as liable to originate and vanish …*";
P_HTM[6128]="*So sace ākaṅkhati: ‘appaṭikūle paṭikūlasaññī vihareyyan’ti, paṭikūlasaññī tattha viharati … pe …* **";
P_HTM[6129]="*upekkhako tattha viharati sato sampajāno.* **";
P_HTM[6130]="*Ajjhattaṃ dhammesu … pe …**They meditate observing principles internally …*";
P_HTM[6131]="*bahiddhā dhammesu … pe …**externally …*";
P_HTM[6132]="*ajjhattabahiddhā dhammesu samudayadhammānupassī viharati … ajjhattabahiddhā dhammesu vayadhammānupassī viharati … ajjhattabahiddhā dhammesu samudayavayadhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**internally and externally as liable to originate, as liable to vanish, and as liable to originate and vanish …*";
P_HTM[6133]="*So sace ākaṅkhati: ‘appaṭikūle paṭikūlasaññī vihareyyan’ti, paṭikūlasaññī tattha viharati … pe …**If they wish: ‘May I meditate perceiving the repulsive in the unrepulsive,’ that’s what they do. …*";
P_HTM[6134]="*upekkhako tattha viharati sato sampajāno.**If they wish: ‘May I meditate staying equanimous, mindful and aware, ignoring both the repulsive and the unrepulsive,’ that’s what they do.*";
P_HTM[6135]="*Ettāvatā kho, āvuso, bhikkhuno cattāro satipaṭṭhānā āraddhā hontī”ti.**That’s how to define the undertaking of the four kinds of mindfulness meditation by a mendicant.”*";
P_HTM[6136]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6137]="*1. Ekadhammavaggo**In Private*";
P_HTM[6138]="*1. Kappasahassasuttaṃ**In Private (2nd)*";
P_HTM[6139]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[6140]="*Atha kho āyasmato anuruddhassa rahogatassa paṭisallīnassa evaṃ cetaso parivitakko udapādi:**Then as Anuruddha was in private retreat this thought came to his mind:*";
P_HTM[6141]="*“yesaṃ kesañci cattāro satipaṭṭhānā viraddhā, viraddho tesaṃ ariyo maggo sammā dukkhakkhayagāmī;**“Whoever has missed out on these four kinds of mindfulness meditation has missed out on the noble path to the complete ending of suffering.*";
P_HTM[6142]="*yesaṃ kesañci cattāro satipaṭṭhānā āraddhā, āraddho tesaṃ ariyo maggo sammā dukkhakkhayagāmī”ti.**Whoever has undertaken these four kinds of mindfulness meditation has undertaken the noble path to the complete ending of suffering.”*";
P_HTM[6143]="*Atha kho āyasmā mahāmoggallāno āyasmato anuruddhassa cetasā cetoparivitakkamaññāya—seyyathāpi nāma balavā puriso samiñjitaṃ vā bāhaṃ pasāreyya, pasāritaṃ vā bāhaṃ samiñjeyya; evameva—āyasmato anuruddhassa sammukhe pāturahosi. Atha kho āyasmā mahāmoggallāno āyasmantaṃ anuruddhaṃ etadavoca:**Then Venerable Mahāmoggallāna knew what Venerable Anuruddha was thinking. As easily as a strong person would extend or contract their arm, he reappeared in front of Anuruddha and said to him:*";
P_HTM[6144]="*“kittāvatā nu kho, āvuso anuruddha, bhikkhuno cattāro satipaṭṭhānā āraddhā hontī”ti?**“Reverend Anuruddha, how do you define the undertaking of the four kinds of mindfulness meditation by a mendicant?”*";
P_HTM[6145]="*“Idhāvuso, bhikkhu ajjhattaṃ kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**“Reverend, it’s when a mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of the body internally—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[6146]="*Bahiddhā kāye kāyānupassī viharati … pe …**They meditate observing an aspect of the body externally …*";
P_HTM[6147]="*ajjhattabahiddhā kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**internally and externally—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[6148]="*Ajjhattaṃ vedanāsu vedanānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**They meditate observing an aspect of feelings internally …*";
P_HTM[6149]="*Bahiddhā vedanāsu vedanānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**externally …*";
P_HTM[6150]="*Ajjhattabahiddhā vedanāsu vedanānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**internally and externally …*";
P_HTM[6151]="*Ajjhattaṃ citte … pe …**They meditate observing an aspect of the mind internally …*";
P_HTM[6152]="*bahiddhā citte … pe …**externally …*";
P_HTM[6153]="*ajjhattabahiddhā citte cittānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**internally and externally …*";
P_HTM[6154]="*Ajjhattaṃ dhammesu … pe …**They meditate observing an aspect of principles internally …*";
P_HTM[6155]="*bahiddhā dhammesu … pe …**externally …*";
P_HTM[6156]="*ajjhattabahiddhā dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**internally and externally—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[6157]="*Ettāvatā kho, āvuso, bhikkhuno cattāro satipaṭṭhānā āraddhā hontī”ti.**That’s how to define the undertaking of the four kinds of mindfulness meditation by a mendicant.”*";
P_HTM[6158]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6159]="*2. Iddhividhasuttaṃ**On the Bank of the Sutanu*";
P_HTM[6160]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ āyasmā anuruddho sāvatthiyaṃ viharati sutanutīre.**At one time Venerable Anuruddha was staying near Sāvatthī on the bank of the Sutanu.*";
P_HTM[6161]="*Atha kho sambahulā bhikkhū yenāyasmā anuruddho tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmatā anuruddhena saddhiṃ sammodiṃsu.**Then several mendicants went up to Venerable Anuruddha, and exchanged greetings with him.*";
P_HTM[6162]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu. Ekamantaṃ nisinnā kho te bhikkhū āyasmantaṃ anuruddhaṃ etadavocuṃ:**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, they sat down to one side, and said to him:*";
P_HTM[6163]="*“katamesaṃ āyasmā anuruddho dhammānaṃ bhāvitattā bahulīkatattā mahābhiññataṃ patto”ti?**“What things has Venerable Anuruddha developed and cultivated to attain great direct knowledge?”*";
P_HTM[6164]="*“Catunnaṃ khvāhaṃ, āvuso, satipaṭṭhānānaṃ bhāvitattā bahulīkatattā mahābhiññataṃ patto.**“Reverends, I attained great direct knowledge by developing and cultivating the four kinds of mindfulness meditation.*";
P_HTM[6165]="*Katamesaṃ catunnaṃ?**What four?*";
P_HTM[6166]="*Idhāhaṃ, āvuso, kāye kāyānupassī viharāmi ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;**I meditate observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[6167]="*vedanāsu … pe …**I meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[6168]="*citte … pe …**mind …*";
P_HTM[6169]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharāmi ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ—**principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[6170]="*imesaṃ khvāhaṃ, āvuso, catunnaṃ satipaṭṭhānānaṃ bhāvitattā bahulīkatattā mahābhiññataṃ patto.**I attained great direct knowledge by developing and cultivating these four kinds of mindfulness meditation.*";
P_HTM[6171]="*Imesañca panāhaṃ, āvuso, catunnaṃ satipaṭṭhānānaṃ bhāvitattā bahulīkatattā hīnaṃ dhammaṃ hīnato abbhaññāsiṃ, majjhimaṃ dhammaṃ majjhimato abbhaññāsiṃ, paṇītaṃ dhammaṃ paṇītato abbhaññāsin”ti.**And it was by developing and cultivating these four kinds of mindfulness meditation that I directly knew the lower realm as lower, the middle realm as middle, and the higher realm as higher.”*";
P_HTM[6172]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6173]="*3. Dibbasotasuttaṃ**At Thorny Wood (1st)*";
P_HTM[6174]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ āyasmā ca anuruddho āyasmā ca sāriputto āyasmā ca mahāmoggallāno sākete viharanti kaṇḍakīvane.**At one time the venerables Anuruddha, Sāriputta, and Mahāmoggallāna were staying near Sāketa, in the Thorny Wood.*";
P_HTM[6175]="*Atha kho āyasmā ca sāriputto āyasmā ca mahāmoggallāno sāyanhasamayaṃ paṭisallānā vuṭṭhitā yenāyasmā anuruddho tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmatā anuruddhena saddhiṃ sammodiṃsu.**Then in the late afternoon, Sāriputta and Mahāmoggallāna came out of retreat, went to Anuruddha, and exchanged greetings with him.*";
P_HTM[6176]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā sāriputto āyasmantaṃ anuruddhaṃ etadavoca:**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, they sat down to one side. Sāriputta said to Anuruddha:*";
P_HTM[6177]="*“sekhenāvuso anuruddha, bhikkhunā katame dhammā upasampajja vihātabbā”ti?**“Reverend Anuruddha, what things should a trainee mendicant enter and remain in?”*";
P_HTM[6178]="*“Sekhenāvuso sāriputta, bhikkhunā cattāro satipaṭṭhānā upasampajja vihātabbā.**“Reverend Sāriputta, a trainee mendicant should enter and remain in the four kinds of mindfulness meditation.*";
P_HTM[6179]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[6180]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;**It’s when a mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[6181]="*vedanāsu … pe …**They meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[6182]="*citte … pe …**mind …*";
P_HTM[6183]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ—**principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[6184]="*sekhenāvuso sāriputta, bhikkhunā ime cattāro satipaṭṭhānā upasampajja vihātabbā”ti.**A trainee mendicant should enter and remain in these four kinds of mindfulness meditation.”*";
P_HTM[6185]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[6186]="*4. Cetopariyasuttaṃ**At Thorny Wood (2nd)*";
P_HTM[6187]="*Sāketanidānaṃ.**At Sāketa.*";
P_HTM[6188]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā sāriputto āyasmantaṃ anuruddhaṃ etadavoca:**Sāriputta said to Anuruddha:*";
