P_HTM[7519]="*3. Tatiyapuññābhisandasuttaṃ**With Mahānāma (1st)*";
P_HTM[7520]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[7521]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sakkesu viharati kapilavatthusmiṃ nigrodhārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying in the land of the Sakyans, near Kapilavatthu in the Banyan Tree Monastery.*";
P_HTM[7522]="*Atha kho mahānāmo sakko yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho mahānāmo sakko bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Mahānāma the Sakyan went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him:*";
P_HTM[7523]="*“idaṃ, bhante, kapilavatthu iddhañceva phītañca bāhujaññaṃ ākiṇṇamanussaṃ sambādhabyūhaṃ.**“Sir, this Kapilavatthu is successful and prosperous and full of people, with cramped cul-de-sacs.*";
P_HTM[7524]="*So khvāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavantaṃ vā payirupāsitvā manobhāvanīye vā bhikkhū sāyanhasamayaṃ kapilavatthuṃ pavisanto;**In the late afternoon, after paying homage to the Buddha or an esteemed mendicant, I enter Kapilavatthu.*";
P_HTM[7525]="*bhantenapi hatthinā samāgacchāmi;**I encounter a stray elephant,*";
P_HTM[7526]="*bhantenapi assena samāgacchāmi;**horse,*";
P_HTM[7527]="*bhantenapi rathena samāgacchāmi;**chariot,*";
P_HTM[7528]="*bhantenapi sakaṭena samāgacchāmi;**cart,*";
P_HTM[7529]="*bhantenapi purisena samāgacchāmi.**or person.*";
P_HTM[7530]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, bhante, tasmiṃ samaye mussateva bhagavantaṃ ārabbha sati, mussati dhammaṃ ārabbha sati, mussati saṃghaṃ ārabbha sati.**At that time I lose mindfulness regarding the Buddha, the teaching, and the Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[7531]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, bhante, evaṃ hoti:**I think:*";
P_HTM[7532]="*‘imamhi cāhaṃ samaye kālaṃ kareyyaṃ, kā mayhaṃ gati, ko abhisamparāyo’”ti?**‘If I were to die at this time, where would I be reborn in my next life?’”*";
P_HTM[7533]="*“Mā bhāyi, mahānāma, mā bhāyi, mahānāma.**“Do not fear, Mahānāma, do not fear!*";
P_HTM[7534]="*Apāpakaṃ te maraṇaṃ bhavissati apāpikā kālaṃkiriyā.**Your death will not be a bad one; your passing will not be a bad one.*";
P_HTM[7535]="*Yassa kassaci, mahānāma, dīgharattaṃ saddhāparibhāvitaṃ cittaṃ sīlaparibhāvitaṃ cittaṃ sutaparibhāvitaṃ cittaṃ cāgaparibhāvitaṃ cittaṃ paññāparibhāvitaṃ cittaṃ, tassa yo hi khvāyaṃ kāyo rūpī cātumahābhūtiko mātāpettikasambhavo odanakummāsūpacayo aniccucchādanaparimaddanabhedanaviddhaṃsanadhammo.**Take someone whose mind has for a long time been imbued with faith, ethics, learning, generosity, and wisdom. Their body consists of form, made up of the four primary elements, produced by mother and father, built up from rice and porridge, liable to impermanence, to wearing away and erosion, to breaking up and destruction.*";
P_HTM[7536]="*Taṃ idheva kākā vā khādanti gijjhā vā khādanti kulalā vā khādanti sunakhā vā khādanti siṅgālā vā khādanti vividhā vā pāṇakajātā khādanti;**Right here the crows, vultures, hawks, dogs, jackals, and many kinds of little creatures devour it.*";
P_HTM[7537]="*yañca khvassa cittaṃ dīgharattaṃ saddhāparibhāvitaṃ … pe … paññāparibhāvitaṃ taṃ uddhagāmi hoti visesagāmi.**But their mind rises up, headed for a higher place.*";
P_HTM[7538]="*Seyyathāpi, mahānāma, puriso sappikumbhaṃ vā telakumbhaṃ vā gambhīraṃ udakarahadaṃ ogāhitvā bhindeyya.**Suppose a person was to sink a pot of ghee or oil into a deep lake and break it open.*";
P_HTM[7539]="*Tatra yā assa sakkharā vā kaṭhalā vā sā adhogāmī assa, yañca khvassa tatra sappi vā telaṃ vā taṃ uddhagāmi assa visesagāmi.**Its shards and chips would sink down, while the ghee or oil in it would rise up, headed for a higher place.*";
P_HTM[7540]="*Evameva kho, mahānāma, yassa kassaci dīgharattaṃ saddhāparibhāvitaṃ cittaṃ … pe …**In the same way, take someone whose mind has for a long time been imbued with faith, ethics, learning, generosity, and wisdom. Their body consists of form, made up of the four elements, produced by mother and father, built up from rice and porridge, liable to impermanence, to wearing away and erosion, to breaking up and destruction.*";
P_HTM[7541]="*paññāparibhāvitaṃ cittaṃ tassa yo hi khvāyaṃ kāyo rūpī cātumahābhūtiko mātāpettikasambhavo odanakummāsūpacayo aniccucchādanaparimaddanabhedanaviddhaṃsanadhammo taṃ idheva kākā vā khādanti gijjhā vā khādanti kulalā vā khādanti sunakhā vā khādanti siṅgālā vā khādanti vividhā vā pāṇakajātā khādanti;**Right here the crows, vultures, hawks, dogs, jackals, and many kinds of little creatures devour it.*";
P_HTM[7542]="*yañca khvassa cittaṃ dīgharattaṃ saddhāparibhāvitaṃ … pe … paññāparibhāvitaṃ taṃ uddhagāmi hoti visesagāmi.**But their mind rises up, headed for a higher place.*";
P_HTM[7543]="*Tuyhaṃ kho pana, mahānāma, dīgharattaṃ saddhāparibhāvitaṃ cittaṃ … pe … paññāparibhāvitaṃ cittaṃ.**Your mind, Mahānāma, has for a long time been imbued with faith, ethics, learning, generosity, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[7544]="*Mā bhāyi, mahānāma, mā bhāyi, mahānāma.**Do not fear, Mahānāma, do not fear!*";
P_HTM[7545]="*Apāpakaṃ te maraṇaṃ bhavissati, apāpikā kālaṃkiriyā”ti.**Your death will not be a bad one; your passing will not be a bad one.”*";
P_HTM[7546]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[7547]="*4. Paṭhamadevapadasuttaṃ**With Mahānāma (2nd)*";
P_HTM[7548]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[7549]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sakkesu viharati kapilavatthusmiṃ nigrodhārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying in the land of the Sakyans, near Kapilavatthu in the Banyan Tree Monastery.*";
P_HTM[7550]="*Atha kho mahānāmo sakko yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho mahānāmo sakko bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Mahānāma the Sakyan went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him:*";
P_HTM[7551]="*“idaṃ, bhante, kapilavatthu iddhañceva phītañca bāhujaññaṃ ākiṇṇamanussaṃ sambādhabyūhaṃ.**“Sir, this Kapilavatthu is successful and prosperous and full of people, with cramped cul-de-sacs.*";
P_HTM[7552]="*So khvāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavantaṃ vā payirupāsitvā manobhāvanīye vā bhikkhū sāyanhasamayaṃ kapilavatthuṃ pavisanto;**In the late afternoon, after paying homage to the Buddha or an esteemed mendicant, I enter Kapilavatthu.*";
P_HTM[7553]="*bhantenapi hatthinā samāgacchāmi;**I encounter a stray elephant,*";
P_HTM[7554]="*bhantenapi assena samāgacchāmi;**horse,*";
P_HTM[7555]="*bhantenapi rathena samāgacchāmi;**chariot,*";
P_HTM[7556]="*bhantenapi sakaṭena samāgacchāmi;**cart,*";
P_HTM[7557]="*bhantenapi purisena samāgacchāmi.**or person.*";
P_HTM[7558]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, bhante, tasmiṃ samaye mussateva bhagavantaṃ ārabbha sati, mussati dhammaṃ ārabbha sati, mussati saṅghaṃ ārabbha sati.**At that time I lose mindfulness regarding the Buddha, the teaching, and the Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[7559]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, bhante, evaṃ hoti:**I think:*";
P_HTM[7560]="*‘imamhi cāhaṃ samaye kālaṃ kareyyaṃ, kā mayhaṃ gati, ko abhisamparāyo’”ti?**‘If I were to die at this time, where would I be reborn in my next life?’”*";
P_HTM[7561]="*“Mā bhāyi, mahānāma, mā bhāyi, mahānāma.**“Do not fear, Mahānāma, do not fear!*";
P_HTM[7562]="*Apāpakaṃ te maraṇaṃ bhavissati apāpikā kālaṅkiriyā.**Your death will not be a bad one; your passing will not be a bad one.*";
P_HTM[7563]="*Catūhi kho, mahānāma, dhammehi samannāgato ariyasāvako nibbānaninno hoti nibbānapoṇo nibbānapabbhāro.**A noble disciple who has four things slants, slopes, and inclines towards extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[7564]="*Katamehi catūhi?**What four?*";
P_HTM[7565]="*Idha, mahānāma, ariyasāvako buddhe aveccappasādena samannāgato hoti—**It’s when a noble disciple has experiential confidence in the Buddha …*";
P_HTM[7566]="*itipi so bhagavā … pe … satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavāti.* **";
P_HTM[7567]="*Dhamme … pe …**the teaching …*";
P_HTM[7568]="*saṅghe … pe …**the Saṅgha …*";
P_HTM[7569]="*ariyakantehi sīlehi samannāgato hoti akhaṇḍehi … pe … samādhisaṃvattanikehi.**And they have the ethical conduct loved by the noble ones … leading to immersion.*";
P_HTM[7570]="*Seyyathāpi, mahānāma, rukkho pācīnaninno pācīnapoṇo pācīnapabbhāro, so mūlacchinno katamena papateyyā”ti?**Suppose there was a tree that slants, slopes, and inclines to the east. If it was cut off at the root where would it fall?”*";
P_HTM[7571]="*“Yena, bhante, ninno yena poṇo yena pabbhāro”ti.**“Sir, it would fall in the direction that it slants, slopes, and inclines.”*";
P_HTM[7572]="*“Evameva kho, mahānāma, imehi catūhi dhammehi samannāgato ariyasāvako nibbānaninno hoti nibbānapoṇo nibbānapabbhāro”ti.**“In the same way, a noble disciple who has four things slants, slopes, and inclines towards extinguishment.”*";
P_HTM[7573]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[7574]="*5. Dutiyadevapadasuttaṃ**With Godhā the Sakyan*";
P_HTM[7575]="*Kapilavatthunidānaṃ.**At Kapilavatthu.*";
P_HTM[7576]="*Atha kho mahānāmo sakko yena godhā sakko tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā godhaṃ sakkaṃ etadavoca:**Then Mahānāma the Sakyan went up to Godhā the Sakyan, and said to him,*";
P_HTM[7577]="*“katihi tvaṃ, godhe, dhammehi samannāgataṃ sotāpannapuggalaṃ ājānāsi avinipātadhammaṃ niyataṃ sambodhiparāyaṇan”ti?**“Godhā, how many things must a person have for you to recognize them as a stream-enterer, not liable to be reborn in the underworld, bound for awakening?”*";
P_HTM[7578]="*“Tīhi khvāhaṃ, mahānāma, dhammehi samannāgataṃ sotāpannapuggalaṃ ājānāmi avinipātadhammaṃ niyataṃ sambodhiparāyaṇaṃ.**“Mahānāma, a person must have three things for me to recognize them as a stream-enterer.*";
P_HTM[7579]="*Katamehi tīhi?**What three?*";
P_HTM[7580]="*Idha, mahānāma, ariyasāvako buddhe aveccappasādena samannāgato hoti—**It’s when a noble disciple has experiential confidence in the Buddha …*";
P_HTM[7581]="*itipi so bhagavā … pe … satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavāti.* **";
P_HTM[7582]="*Dhamme … pe …**the teaching …*";
P_HTM[7583]="*saṅghe aveccappasādena samannāgato hoti—**and the Saṅgha …*";
P_HTM[7584]="*suppaṭipanno bhagavato sāvakasaṅgho … pe … anuttaraṃ puññakkhettaṃ lokassāti.* **";
P_HTM[7585]="*Imehi khvāhaṃ, mahānāma, tīhi dhammehi samannāgataṃ sotāpannapuggalaṃ ājānāmi avinipātadhammaṃ niyataṃ sambodhiparāyaṇaṃ.**When a person has these three things I recognize them as a stream-enterer.*";
P_HTM[7586]="*Tvaṃ pana, mahānāma, katihi dhammehi samannāgataṃ sotāpannapuggalaṃ ājānāsi avinipātadhammaṃ niyataṃ sambodhiparāyaṇan”ti?**But Mahānāma, how many things must a person have for you to recognize them as a stream-enterer?”*";
P_HTM[7587]="*“Catūhi khvāhaṃ, godhe, dhammehi samannāgataṃ sotāpannapuggalaṃ ājānāmi avinipātadhammaṃ niyataṃ sambodhiparāyaṇaṃ.**“Godhā, a person must have four things for me to recognize them as a stream-enterer.*";
P_HTM[7588]="*Katamehi catūhi?**What four?*";
P_HTM[7589]="*Idha, godhe, ariyasāvako buddhe aveccappasādena samannāgato hoti—**It’s when a noble disciple has experiential confidence in the Buddha …*";
P_HTM[7590]="*itipi so bhagavā … pe … satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavāti.* **";
P_HTM[7591]="*Dhamme … pe …**the teaching …*";
P_HTM[7592]="*saṅghe … pe …**the Saṅgha …*";
P_HTM[7593]="*ariyakantehi sīlehi samannāgato hoti akhaṇḍehi … pe … samādhisaṃvattanikehi.**And they have the ethical conduct loved by the noble ones … leading to immersion.*";
P_HTM[7594]="*Imehi khvāhaṃ, godhe, catūhi dhammehi samannāgataṃ sotāpannapuggalaṃ ājānāmi avinipātadhammaṃ niyataṃ sambodhiparāyaṇan”ti.**When a person has these four things I recognize them as a stream-enterer.”*";
P_HTM[7595]="*“Āgamehi tvaṃ, mahānāma, āgamehi tvaṃ, mahānāma.**“Hold on, Mahānāma, hold on!*";
P_HTM[7596]="*Bhagavāva etaṃ jāneyya etehi dhammehi samannāgataṃ vā asamannāgataṃ vā”ti.**Only the Buddha would know whether or not they have these things.”*";
P_HTM[7597]="*“Āyāma, godhe, yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkameyyāma; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavato etamatthaṃ ārocessāmā”ti.**“Come, Godhā, let’s go to the Buddha and inform him about this.”*";
P_HTM[7598]="*Atha kho mahānāmo sakko godhā ca sakko yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho mahānāmo sakko bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Mahānāma and Godhā went to the Buddha, bowed, and sat down to one side. Mahānāma told the Buddha all that had happened, and then said:*";
P_HTM[7599]="*“Idhāhaṃ, bhante, yena godhā sakko tenupasaṅkamiṃ; upasaṅkamitvā godhaṃ sakkaṃ etadavocaṃ:* **";
P_HTM[7600]="*‘katihi tvaṃ, godhe, dhammehi samannāgataṃ sotāpannapuggalaṃ ājānāsi avinipātadhammaṃ niyataṃ sambodhiparāyaṇaṃ’?* **";
P_HTM[7601]="*Evaṃ vutte, bhante, godhā sakko maṃ etadavoca—* **";
P_HTM[7602]="*Tīhi khvāhaṃ, mahānāma, dhammehi samannāgataṃ sotāpannapuggalaṃ ājānāmi avinipātadhammaṃ niyataṃ sambodhiparāyaṇaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[7603]="*Katamehi tīhi?* **";
P_HTM[7604]="*Idha, mahānāma, ariyasāvako buddhe aveccappasādena samannāgato hoti—* **";
P_HTM[7605]="*itipi so bhagavā … pe … satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavāti.* **";
P_HTM[7606]="*Dhamme … pe …* **";
P_HTM[7607]="*saṅghe aveccappasādena samannāgato hoti—* **";
P_HTM[7608]="*suppaṭipanno bhagavato sāvakasaṅgho … pe … anuttaraṃ puññakkhettaṃ lokassāti.* **";
P_HTM[7609]="*Imehi khvāhaṃ, mahānāma, tīhi dhammehi samannāgataṃ sotāpannapuggalaṃ ājānāmi avinipātadhammaṃ niyataṃ sambodhiparāyaṇaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[7610]="*Tvaṃ pana, mahānāma, katamehi dhammehi samannāgataṃ sotāpannapuggalaṃ ājānāsi avinipātadhammaṃ niyataṃ sambodhiparāyaṇan’ti?* **";
P_HTM[7611]="*Evaṃ vuttāhaṃ, bhante, godhaṃ sakkaṃ etadavocaṃ:* **";
P_HTM[7612]="*‘catūhi khvāhaṃ, godhe, dhammehi samannāgataṃ sotāpannapuggalaṃ ājānāmi avinipātadhammaṃ niyataṃ sambodhiparāyaṇaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[7613]="*Katamehi catūhi?* **";
P_HTM[7614]="*Idha, godhe, ariyasāvako buddhe aveccappasādena samannāgato hoti—* **";
P_HTM[7615]="*itipi so bhagavā … pe … satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavāti.* **";
P_HTM[7616]="*Dhamme … pe …* **";
P_HTM[7617]="*saṅghe … pe …* **";
P_HTM[7618]="*ariyakantehi sīlehi samannāgato hoti akhaṇḍehi … pe … samādhisaṃvattanikehi.* **";
P_HTM[7619]="*Imehi khvāhaṃ, godhe, catūhi dhammehi samannāgataṃ sotāpannapuggalaṃ ājānāmi avinipātadhammaṃ niyataṃ sambodhiparāyaṇan’ti.* **";
P_HTM[7620]="*Evaṃ vutte, bhante, godhā sakko maṃ etadavoca:* **";
P_HTM[7621]="*‘āgamehi tvaṃ, mahānāma, āgamehi tvaṃ, mahānāma.* **";
P_HTM[7622]="*Bhagavāva etaṃ jāneyya etehi dhammehi samannāgataṃ vā asamannāgataṃ vā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[7623]="*Idha, bhante, kocideva dhammo samuppādo uppajjeyya, ekato assa bhagavā ekato bhikkhusaṅgho ca.**“Sir, some issue regarding the teaching might come up. The Buddha might take one side, and the Saṅgha of monks the other.*";
P_HTM[7624]="*Yeneva bhagavā tenevāhaṃ assaṃ.**I’d side with the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[7625]="*Evaṃ pasannaṃ maṃ, bhante, bhagavā dhāretu.**May the Buddha remember me as having such confidence.*";
P_HTM[7626]="*Idha, bhante, kocideva dhammo samuppādo uppajjeyya, ekato assa bhagavā ekato bhikkhusaṅgho bhikkhunisaṅgho ca.**Some issue regarding the teaching might come up. The Buddha might take one side, and the Saṅgha of monks and the Saṅgha of nuns the other. …*";
P_HTM[7627]="*Yeneva bhagavā tenevāhaṃ assaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[7628]="*Evaṃ pasannaṃ maṃ, bhante, bhagavā dhāretu.* **";
P_HTM[7629]="*Idha, bhante, kocideva dhammo samuppādo uppajjeyya, ekato assa bhagavā ekato bhikkhusaṅgho bhikkhunisaṅgho ca upāsakā ca.**The Buddha might take one side, and the Saṅgha of monks and the Saṅgha of nuns and the laymen the other. …*";
P_HTM[7630]="*Yeneva bhagavā tenevāhaṃ assaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[7631]="*Evaṃ pasannaṃ maṃ, bhante, bhagavā dhāretu.* **";
P_HTM[7632]="*Idha, bhante, kocideva dhammo samuppādo uppajjeyya, ekato assa bhagavā ekato bhikkhusaṅgho bhikkhunisaṅgho upāsakā upāsikāyo ca.**The Buddha might take one side, and the Saṅgha of monks and the Saṅgha of nuns and the laymen and the laywomen the other. …*";
P_HTM[7633]="*Yeneva bhagavā tenevāhaṃ assaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[7634]="*Evaṃ pasannaṃ maṃ, bhante, bhagavā dhāretu.* **";
P_HTM[7635]="*Idha, bhante, kocideva dhammo samuppādo uppajjeyya, ekato assa bhagavā ekato bhikkhusaṅgho bhikkhunisaṅgho upāsakā upāsikāyo sadevako ca loko samārako sabrahmako sassamaṇabrāhmaṇī pajā sadevamanussā.**The Buddha might take one side, and the Saṅgha of monks and the Saṅgha of nuns and the laymen and the laywomen and the world—with its gods, Māras and Brahmās, this population with its ascetics and brahmins, gods and humans—the other.*";
P_HTM[7636]="*Yeneva bhagavā tenevāhaṃ assaṃ.**I’d side with the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[7637]="*Evaṃ pasannaṃ maṃ, bhante, bhagavā dhāretū”ti.**May the Buddha remember me as having such confidence.”*";
P_HTM[7638]="*“Evaṃvādī tvaṃ, godhe, mahānāmaṃ sakkaṃ kiṃ vadesī”ti?**“Godhā, what do you have to say to Mahānāma when he speaks like this?”*";
P_HTM[7639]="*“Evaṃvādāhaṃ, bhante, mahānāmaṃ sakkaṃ na kiñci vadāmi, aññatra kalyāṇā aññatra kusalā”ti.**“Sir, I have nothing to say to Mahānāma when he speaks like this, except what is good and wholesome.”*";
P_HTM[7640]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[7641]="*6. Devasabhāgasuttaṃ**About Sarakāni (1st)*";
P_HTM[7642]="*Kapilavatthunidānaṃ.**At Kapilavatthu.*";
P_HTM[7643]="*Tena kho pana samayena saraṇāni sakko kālaṅkato hoti.**Now at that time Sarakāni the Sakyan had passed away.*";
P_HTM[7644]="*So bhagavatā byākato:**The Buddha declared that he was*";
P_HTM[7645]="*“sotāpanno avinipātadhammo niyato sambodhiparāyaṇo”ti.**a stream-enterer, not liable to be reborn in the underworld, bound for awakening.*";
P_HTM[7646]="*Tatra sudaṃ sambahulā sakkā saṅgamma samāgamma ujjhāyanti khīyanti vipācenti:**At that, several Sakyans came together complaining, grumbling, and objecting,*";
P_HTM[7647]="*“acchariyaṃ vata bho, abbhutaṃ vata bho.**“It’s incredible, it’s amazing!*";
P_HTM[7648]="*Ettha dāni ko na sotāpanno bhavissati.**Who can’t become a stream-enterer these days?*";
P_HTM[7649]="*Yatra hi nāma saraṇāni sakko kālaṅkato;**For the Buddha even declared Sarakāni to be a stream-enterer after he passed away.*";
P_HTM[7650]="*so bhagavatā byākato:* **";
P_HTM[7651]="*‘sotāpanno avinipātadhammo niyato sambodhiparāyaṇo’ti.* **";
P_HTM[7652]="*Saraṇāni sakko sikkhādubbalyamāpādi, majjapānaṃ apāyī”ti.**Sarakāni was too weak for the training; he used to drink alcohol.”*";
P_HTM[7653]="*Atha kho mahānāmo sakko yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho mahānāmo sakko bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Mahānāma the Sakyan went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and told him what had happened. The Buddha said:*";
P_HTM[7654]="*“idha, bhante, saraṇāni sakko kālaṅkato.* **";
P_HTM[7655]="*So bhagavatā byākato:* **";
P_HTM[7656]="*‘sotāpanno avinipātadhammo niyato sambodhiparāyaṇo’ti.* **";
P_HTM[7657]="*Tatra sudaṃ, bhante, sambahulā sakkā saṅgamma samāgamma ujjhāyanti khīyanti vipācenti—* **";
P_HTM[7658]="*acchariyaṃ vata, bho, abbhutaṃ vata, bho.* **";
P_HTM[7659]="*Ettha dāni ko na sotāpanno bhavissati.* **";
P_HTM[7660]="*Yatra hi nāma saraṇāni sakko kālaṅkato;* **";
P_HTM[7661]="*so bhagavatā byākato:* **";
P_HTM[7662]="*‘sotāpanno avinipātadhammo niyato sambodhiparāyaṇo’ti.* **";
P_HTM[7663]="*Saraṇāni sakko sikkhādubbalyamāpādi, majjapānaṃ apāyī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[7664]="*“Yo so, mahānāma, dīgharattaṃ upāsako buddhaṃ saraṇaṃ gato dhammaṃ saraṇaṃ gato saṅghaṃ saraṇaṃ gato, so kathaṃ vinipātaṃ gaccheyya.**“Mahānāma, when a lay follower has for a long time gone for refuge to the Buddha, the teaching, and the Saṅgha, how could they go to the underworld?*";
P_HTM[7665]="*Yañhi taṃ, mahānāma, sammā vadamāno vadeyya:**And if anyone should rightly be said to*";
P_HTM[7666]="*‘dīgharattaṃ upāsako buddhaṃ saraṇaṃ gato dhammaṃ saraṇaṃ gato saṅghaṃ saraṇaṃ gato’ti, saraṇāni sakkaṃ sammā vadamāno vadeyya.**have for a long time gone for refuge to the Buddha, the teaching, and the Saṅgha, it’s Sarakāni the Sakyan.*";
P_HTM[7667]="*Saraṇāni, mahānāma, sakko dīgharattaṃ upāsako buddhaṃ saraṇaṃ gato dhammaṃ saraṇaṃ gato saṅghaṃ saraṇaṃ gato.**Sarakāni the Sakyan has for a long time gone for refuge to the Buddha, the teaching, and the Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[7668]="*So kathaṃ vinipātaṃ gaccheyya.**How could he go to the underworld?*";
P_HTM[7669]="*Idha, mahānāma, ekacco puggalo buddhe aveccappasādena samannāgato hoti—**Take a certain person who has experiential confidence in the Buddha …*";
P_HTM[7670]="*itipi so bhagavā … pe … satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavāti.* **";
P_HTM[7671]="*Dhamme … pe …**the teaching …*";
P_HTM[7672]="*saṅghe … pe …**the Saṅgha …*";
P_HTM[7673]="*hāsapañño javanapañño vimuttiyā ca samannāgato.**They have laughing wisdom and swift wisdom, and are endowed with freedom.*";
P_HTM[7674]="*So āsavānaṃ khayā anāsavaṃ cetovimuttiṃ paññāvimuttiṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharati.**They’ve realized the undefiled freedom of heart and freedom by wisdom in this very life. And they live having realized it with their own insight due to the ending of defilements.*";
P_HTM[7675]="*Ayampi kho, mahānāma, puggalo parimutto nirayā parimutto tiracchānayoniyā parimutto pettivisayā parimutto apāyaduggativinipātā.**This person is exempt from hell, the animal realm, and the ghost realm. They’re exempt from places of loss, bad places, the underworld.*";
P_HTM[7676]="*Idha pana, mahānāma, ekacco puggalo buddhe aveccappasādena samannāgato hoti—**Take another person who has experiential confidence in the Buddha …*";
P_HTM[7677]="*itipi so bhagavā … pe … satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavāti.* **";
P_HTM[7678]="*Dhamme … pe …**the teaching …*";
P_HTM[7679]="*saṃghe … pe …**the Saṅgha …*";
P_HTM[7680]="*hāsapañño javanapañño na ca vimuttiyā samannāgato.**They have laughing wisdom and swift wisdom, and are endowed with freedom.*";
P_HTM[7681]="*So pañcannaṃ orambhāgiyānaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ parikkhayā opapātiko hoti tattha parinibbāyī anāvattidhammo tasmā lokā.**With the ending of the five lower fetters they’re reborn spontaneously. They are extinguished there, and are not liable to return from that world.*";
P_HTM[7682]="*Ayampi kho, mahānāma, puggalo parimutto nirayā parimutto tiracchānayoniyā parimutto pettivisayā parimutto apāyaduggativinipātā.**This person, too, is exempt from hell, the animal realm, and the ghost realm. They’re exempt from places of loss, bad places, the underworld.*";
P_HTM[7683]="*Idha pana, mahānāma, ekacco puggalo buddhe aveccappasādena samannāgato hoti—**Take another person who has experiential confidence in the Buddha …*";
P_HTM[7684]="*itipi so bhagavā … pe … satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavāti.* **";
P_HTM[7685]="*Dhamme … pe …**the teaching …*";
P_HTM[7686]="*saṅghe … pe …**the Saṅgha …*";
P_HTM[7687]="*na hāsapañño na javanapañño na ca vimuttiyā samannāgato.**But they don’t have laughing wisdom or swift wisdom, nor are they endowed with freedom.*";
P_HTM[7688]="*So tiṇṇaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ parikkhayā rāgadosamohānaṃ tanuttā sakadāgāmī hoti, sakideva imaṃ lokaṃ āgantvā dukkhassantaṃ karoti.**With the ending of three fetters, and the weakening of greed, hate, and delusion, they’re a once-returner. They come back to this world once only, then make an end of suffering.*";
P_HTM[7689]="*Ayampi kho, mahānāma, puggalo parimutto nirayā parimutto tiracchānayoniyā parimutto pettivisayā parimutto apāyaduggativinipātā.**This person, too, is exempt from hell, the animal realm, and the ghost realm. They’re exempt from places of loss, bad places, the underworld.*";
P_HTM[7690]="*Idha pana, mahānāma, ekacco puggalo buddhe aveccappasādena samannāgato hoti—**Take another person who has experiential confidence in the Buddha …*";
P_HTM[7691]="*itipi so bhagavā … pe … satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavāti;* **";
P_HTM[7692]="*dhamme … pe …**the teaching …*";
P_HTM[7693]="*saṅghe … pe …**the Saṅgha …*";
P_HTM[7694]="*na hāsapañño na javanapañño na ca vimuttiyā samannāgato.**But they don’t have laughing wisdom or swift wisdom, nor are they endowed with freedom.*";
P_HTM[7695]="*So tiṇṇaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ parikkhayā sotāpanno hoti avinipātadhammo niyato sambodhiparāyaṇoti.**With the ending of three fetters they’re a stream-enterer, not liable to be reborn in the underworld, bound for awakening.*";
P_HTM[7696]="*Ayampi kho, mahānāma, puggalo parimutto nirayā parimutto tiracchānayoniyā parimutto pettivisayā parimutto apāyaduggativinipātā.**This person, too, is exempt from hell, the animal realm, and the ghost realm. They’re exempt from places of loss, bad places, the underworld.*";
P_HTM[7697]="*Idha pana, mahānāma, ekacco puggalo na heva kho buddhe aveccappasādena samannāgato hoti …**Take another person who doesn’t have experiential confidence in the Buddha …*";
P_HTM[7698]="*na dhamme … pe …**the teaching …*";
P_HTM[7699]="*na saṅghe … pe …**the Saṅgha …*";
P_HTM[7700]="*na hāsapañño na javanapañño na ca vimuttiyā samannāgato.**They don’t have laughing wisdom or swift wisdom, nor are they endowed with freedom.*";
P_HTM[7701]="*Api cassa ime dhammā honti—**Still, they have these qualities:*";
P_HTM[7702]="*saddhindriyaṃ, vīriyindriyaṃ, satindriyaṃ, samādhindriyaṃ, paññindriyaṃ.**the faculties of faith, energy, mindfulness, immersion, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[7703]="*Tathāgatappaveditā cassa dhammā paññāya mattaso nijjhānaṃ khamanti.**And they accept the principles proclaimed by the Realized One after considering them with a degree of wisdom.*";
P_HTM[7704]="*Ayampi kho, mahānāma, puggalo agantā nirayaṃ agantā tiracchānayoniṃ agantā pettivisayaṃ agantā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ.**This person, too, doesn’t go to hell, the animal realm, and the ghost realm. They don’t go to places of loss, bad places, the underworld.*";
P_HTM[7705]="*Idha pana, mahānāma, ekacco puggalo na heva kho buddhe aveccappasādena samannāgato hoti …**Take another person who doesn’t have experiential confidence in the Buddha …*";
P_HTM[7706]="*na dhamme … pe …**the teaching …*";
P_HTM[7707]="*na saṃghe … pe …**the Saṅgha …*";
P_HTM[7708]="*na hāsapañño na javanapañño na ca vimuttiyā samannāgato,**They don’t have laughing wisdom or swift wisdom, nor are they endowed with freedom.*";
P_HTM[7709]="*api cassa ime dhammā honti**Still, they have these qualities:*";
P_HTM[7710]="*saddhindriyaṃ … pe … paññindriyaṃ.**the faculties of faith, energy, mindfulness, immersion, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[7711]="*Tathāgate cassa saddhāmattaṃ hoti pemamattaṃ.**And they have a degree of faith and love for the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[7712]="*Ayampi kho, mahānāma, puggalo agantā nirayaṃ agantā tiracchānayoniṃ agantā pettivisayaṃ agantā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ.**This person, too, doesn’t go to hell, the animal realm, and the ghost realm. They don’t go to places of loss, bad places, the underworld.*";
P_HTM[7713]="*Ime cepi, mahānāma, mahāsālā subhāsitaṃ dubbhāsitaṃ ājāneyyuṃ, ime cāhaṃ mahāsāle byākareyyaṃ: ‘sotāpannā avinipātadhammā niyatā sambodhiparāyaṇā’ti;**If these great sal trees could understand what was well said and poorly said, I’d declare them to be stream-enterers.*";
P_HTM[7714]="*kimaṅgaṃ pana saraṇāniṃ sakkaṃ.**Why can’t this apply to Sarakāni?*";
P_HTM[7715]="*Saraṇāni, mahānāma, sakko maraṇakāle sikkhaṃ samādiyī”ti.**Mahānāma, Sarakāni the Sakyan undertook the training at the time of his death.”*";
P_HTM[7716]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[7717]="*7. Mahānāmasuttaṃ**About Sarakāni the Sakyan (2nd)*";
P_HTM[7718]="*Kapilavatthunidānaṃ.**At Kapilavatthu.*";
P_HTM[7719]="*Tena kho pana samayena saraṇāni sakko kālaṅkato hoti.**Now at that time Sarakāni the Sakyan had passed away.*";
P_HTM[7720]="*So bhagavatā byākato:**The Buddha declared that he was*";
P_HTM[7721]="*“sotāpanno avinipātadhammo niyato sambodhiparāyaṇo”ti.**a stream-enterer, not liable to be reborn in the underworld, bound for awakening.*";
P_HTM[7722]="*Tatra sudaṃ sambahulā sakkā saṅgamma samāgamma ujjhāyanti khīyanti vipācenti:**At that, several Sakyans came together complaining, grumbling, and objecting,*";
P_HTM[7723]="*“acchariyaṃ vata bho, abbhutaṃ vata bho.**“It’s incredible, it’s amazing!*";
P_HTM[7724]="*Ettha dāni ko na sotāpanno bhavissati.**Who can’t become a stream-enterer these days?*";
P_HTM[7725]="*Yatra hi nāma saraṇāni sakko kālaṅkato.**For the Buddha even declared Sarakāni to be a stream-enterer after he passed away.*";
P_HTM[7726]="*So bhagavatā byākato:* **";
P_HTM[7727]="*‘sotāpanno avinipātadhammo niyato sambodhiparāyaṇo’ti.* **";
P_HTM[7728]="*Saraṇāni sakko sikkhāya aparipūrakārī ahosī”ti.**Sarakāni didn’t fulfill the training.”*";
P_HTM[7729]="*Atha kho mahānāmo sakko yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho mahānāmo sakko bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Mahānāma the Sakyan went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and told him what had happened. The Buddha said:*";
P_HTM[7730]="*“Idha, bhante, saraṇāni sakko kālaṅkato.* **";
P_HTM[7731]="*So bhagavatā byākato:* **";
P_HTM[7732]="*‘sotāpanno avinipātadhammo niyato sambodhiparāyaṇo’ti.* **";
P_HTM[7733]="*Tatra sudaṃ, bhante, sambahulā sakkā saṅgamma samāgamma ujjhāyanti khīyanti vipācenti:* **";
P_HTM[7734]="*‘acchariyaṃ vata bho, abbhutaṃ vata bho.* **";
P_HTM[7735]="*Ettha dāni ko na sotāpanno bhavissati.* **";
P_HTM[7736]="*Yatra hi nāma saraṇāni sakko kālaṅkato.* **";
P_HTM[7737]="*So bhagavatā byākato—* **";
P_HTM[7738]="*sotāpanno avinipātadhammo niyato sambodhiparāyaṇoti.* **";
P_HTM[7739]="*Saraṇāni sakko sikkhāya aparipūrakārī ahosī’”ti.* **";
P_HTM[7740]="*“Yo so, mahānāma, dīgharattaṃ upāsako buddhaṃ saraṇaṃ gato dhammaṃ saraṇaṃ gato saṅghaṃ saraṇaṃ gato, so kathaṃ vinipātaṃ gaccheyya.**“Mahānāma, when a lay follower has for a long time gone for refuge to the Buddha, the teaching, and the Saṅgha, how could they go to the underworld?*";
P_HTM[7741]="*Yañhi taṃ, mahānāma, sammā vadamāno vadeyya:**And if anyone should rightly be said to*";
P_HTM[7742]="*‘dīgharattaṃ upāsako buddhaṃ saraṇaṃ gato dhammaṃ saraṇaṃ gato saṅghaṃ saraṇaṃ gato’, saraṇāniṃ sakkaṃ sammā vadamāno vadeyya.**have for a long time gone for refuge to the Buddha, the teaching, and the Saṅgha, it’s Sarakāni the Sakyan.*";
P_HTM[7743]="*Saraṇāni, mahānāma, sakko dīgharattaṃ upāsako buddhaṃ saraṇaṃ gato dhammaṃ saraṇaṃ gato saṅghaṃ saraṇaṃ gato, so kathaṃ vinipātaṃ gaccheyya.**Sarakāni the Sakyan has for a long time gone for refuge to the Buddha, the teaching, and the Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[7744]="*Idha, mahānāma, ekacco puggalo buddhe ekantagato hoti abhippasanno—**Take a certain person who is sure and devoted to the Buddha …*";
P_HTM[7745]="*itipi so bhagavā … pe … satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavāti.* **";
P_HTM[7746]="*Dhamme … pe …**the teaching …*";
P_HTM[7747]="*saṅghe … pe …**the Saṅgha …*";
P_HTM[7748]="*hāsapañño javanapañño vimuttiyā ca samannāgato.**They have laughing wisdom and swift wisdom, and are endowed with freedom.*";
P_HTM[7749]="*So āsavānaṃ khayā anāsavaṃ cetovimuttiṃ paññāvimuttiṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharati.**They realize the undefiled freedom of heart and freedom by wisdom in this very life. And they live having realized it with their own insight due to the ending of defilements.*";
P_HTM[7750]="*Ayampi kho, mahānāma, puggalo parimutto nirayā parimutto tiracchānayoniyā parimutto pettivisayā parimutto apāyaduggativinipātā.**This person is exempt from hell, the animal realm, and the ghost realm. They’re exempt from places of loss, bad places, the underworld.*";
P_HTM[7751]="*Idha pana, mahānāma, ekacco puggalo buddhe ekantagato hoti abhippasanno—**Take another person who is sure and devoted to the Buddha …*";
P_HTM[7752]="*itipi so bhagavā … pe … satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavāti.* **";
P_HTM[7753]="*Dhamme … pe …**the teaching …*";
P_HTM[7754]="*saṅghe … pe …**the Saṅgha …*";
P_HTM[7755]="*hāsapañño javanapañño na ca vimuttiyā samannāgato.**They have laughing wisdom and swift wisdom, and are endowed with freedom.*";
P_HTM[7756]="*So pañcannaṃ orambhāgiyānaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ parikkhayā antarāparinibbāyī hoti, upahaccaparinibbāyī hoti, asaṅkhāraparinibbāyī hoti, sasaṅkhāraparinibbāyī hoti, uddhaṃsoto hoti akaniṭṭhagāmī.**With the ending of the five lower fetters, they’re extinguished between one life and the next … they’re extinguished upon landing … they’re extinguished without extra effort … they’re extinguished with extra effort … they head upstream, going to the Akaniṭṭha realm.*";
P_HTM[7757]="*Ayampi kho, mahānāma, puggalo parimutto nirayā parimutto tiracchānayoniyā parimutto pettivisayā parimutto apāyaduggativinipātā.**This person, too, is exempt from hell, the animal realm, and the ghost realm. They’re exempt from places of loss, bad places, the underworld.*";
P_HTM[7758]="*Idha pana, mahānāma, ekacco puggalo buddhe ekantagato hoti abhippasanno—**Take another person who is sure and devoted to the Buddha …*";
P_HTM[7759]="*itipi so bhagavā … pe … satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavāti.* **";
P_HTM[7760]="*Dhamme … pe …**the teaching …*";
P_HTM[7761]="*saṅghe … pe …**the Saṅgha …*";
P_HTM[7762]="*na hāsapañño na javanapañño na ca vimuttiyā samannāgato.**But they don’t have laughing wisdom or swift wisdom, nor are they endowed with freedom.*";
P_HTM[7763]="*So tiṇṇaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ parikkhayā rāgadosamohānaṃ tanuttā sakadāgāmī hoti, sakideva imaṃ lokaṃ āgantvā dukkhassantaṃ karoti.**With the ending of three fetters, and the weakening of greed, hate, and delusion, they’re a once-returner. They come back to this world once only, then make an end of suffering.*";
P_HTM[7764]="*Ayampi kho, mahānāma, puggalo parimutto nirayā parimutto tiracchānayoniyā parimutto pettivisayā parimutto apāyaduggativinipātā.**This person, too, is exempt from hell, the animal realm, and the ghost realm. They’re exempt from places of loss, bad places, the underworld.*";
P_HTM[7765]="*Idha pana, mahānāma, ekacco puggalo buddhe ekantagato hoti abhippasanno—**Take another person who is sure and devoted to the Buddha …*";
P_HTM[7766]="*itipi so bhagavā … pe … satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavāti.* **";
P_HTM[7767]="*Dhamme … pe …**the teaching …*";
P_HTM[7768]="*saṅghe … pe …**the Saṅgha …*";
P_HTM[7769]="*na hāsapañño na javanapañño na ca vimuttiyā samannāgato.**But they don’t have laughing wisdom or swift wisdom, nor are they endowed with freedom.*";
P_HTM[7770]="*So tiṇṇaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ parikkhayā sotāpanno hoti avinipātadhammo niyato sambodhiparāyaṇo.**With the ending of three fetters they’re a stream-enterer, not liable to be reborn in the underworld, bound for awakening.*";
P_HTM[7771]="*Ayampi kho, mahānāma, puggalo parimutto nirayā parimutto tiracchānayoniyā parimutto pettivisayā parimutto apāyaduggativinipātā.**This person, too, is exempt from hell, the animal realm, and the ghost realm. They’re exempt from places of loss, bad places, the underworld.*";
P_HTM[7772]="*Idha pana, mahānāma, ekacco puggalo na heva kho buddhe ekantagato hoti abhippasanno … pe …**Take another person who isn’t sure or devoted to the Buddha …*";
P_HTM[7773]="*na dhamme … pe …**the teaching …*";
P_HTM[7774]="*na saṅghe … pe …**the Saṅgha …*";
P_HTM[7775]="*na hāsapañño na javanapañño na ca vimuttiyā samannāgato;**They don’t have laughing wisdom or swift wisdom, nor are they endowed with freedom.*";
P_HTM[7776]="*api cassa ime dhammā honti—**Still, they have these qualities:*";
P_HTM[7777]="*saddhindriyaṃ … pe … paññindriyaṃ.**the faculties of faith, energy, mindfulness, immersion, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[7778]="*Tathāgatappaveditā cassa dhammā paññāya mattaso nijjhānaṃ khamanti.**And they accept the principles proclaimed by the Realized One after considering them with a degree of wisdom.*";
P_HTM[7779]="*Ayampi kho, mahānāma, puggalo agantā nirayaṃ agantā tiracchānayoniṃ agantā pettivisayaṃ agantā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ.**This person, too, doesn’t go to hell, the animal realm, and the ghost realm. They don’t go to places of loss, bad places, the underworld.*";
P_HTM[7780]="*Idha pana, mahānāma, ekacco puggalo na heva kho buddhe ekantagato hoti abhippasanno …**Take another person who isn’t sure or devoted to the Buddha …*";
P_HTM[7781]="*na dhamme … pe …**the teaching …*";
P_HTM[7782]="*na saṅghe … pe …**the Saṅgha …*";
P_HTM[7783]="*na hāsapañño na javanapañño na ca vimuttiyā samannāgato;**They don’t have laughing wisdom or swift wisdom, nor are they endowed with freedom.*";
P_HTM[7784]="*api cassa ime dhammā honti—**Still, they have these qualities:*";
P_HTM[7785]="*saddhindriyaṃ … pe … paññindriyaṃ.**the faculties of faith, energy, mindfulness, immersion, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[7786]="*Tathāgate cassa saddhāmattaṃ hoti pemamattaṃ.**And they have a degree of faith and love for the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[7787]="*Ayampi kho, mahānāma, puggalo agantā nirayaṃ agantā tiracchānayoniṃ agantā pettivisayaṃ agantā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ.**This person, too, doesn’t go to hell, the animal realm, and the ghost realm. They don’t go to places of loss, bad places, the underworld.*";
P_HTM[7788]="*Seyyathāpi, mahānāma, dukkhettaṃ dubbhūmaṃ avihatakhāṇukaṃ, bījāni cassu khaṇḍāni pūtīni vātātapahatāni asārādāni asukhasayitāni, devo ca na sammā dhāraṃ anuppaveccheyya.**Suppose there was a barren field, a barren ground, with uncleared stumps. And you had seeds that were broken, spoiled, weather-damaged, infertile, and ill kept. And the heavens didn’t provide enough rain.*";
P_HTM[7789]="*Api nu tāni bījāni vuddhiṃ virūḷhiṃ vepullaṃ āpajjeyyun”ti?**Would those seeds grow, increase, and mature?”*";
P_HTM[7790]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[7791]="*“Evameva kho, mahānāma, idha dhammo durakkhāto hoti duppavedito aniyyāniko anupasamasaṃvattaniko asammāsambuddhappavedito—**“In the same way, take a teaching that’s badly explained and badly propounded, not emancipating, not leading to peace, proclaimed by someone who is not a fully awakened Buddha.*";
P_HTM[7792]="*idamahaṃ dukkhettasmiṃ vadāmi.**This is what I call a barren field.*";
P_HTM[7793]="*Tasmiñca dhamme sāvako viharati dhammānudhammappaṭipanno sāmīcippaṭipanno anudhammacārī—**A disciple remains in such a teaching, practicing in line with that teaching, practicing it properly, living in line with that teaching.*";
P_HTM[7794]="*idamahaṃ dubbījasmiṃ vadāmi.**This is what I call a bad seed.*";
P_HTM[7795]="*Seyyathāpi, mahānāma, sukhettaṃ subhūmaṃ suvihatakhāṇukaṃ, bījāni cassu akhaṇḍāni apūtīni avātātapahatāni sārādāni sukhasayitāni;**Suppose there was a fertile field, a fertile ground, well-cleared of stumps. And you had seeds that were intact, unspoiled, not weather-damaged, fertile, and well-kept. And there’s plenty of rainfall.*";
P_HTM[7796]="*devo ca sammā dhāraṃ anuppaveccheyya.* **";
P_HTM[7797]="*Api nu tāni bījāni vuddhiṃ virūḷhiṃ vepullaṃ āpajjeyyun”ti?**Would those seeds grow, increase, and mature?”*";
P_HTM[7798]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”.**“Yes, sir.”*";
P_HTM[7799]="*“Evameva kho, mahānāma, idha dhammo svākkhāto hoti suppavedito niyyāniko upasamasaṃvattaniko sammāsambuddhappavedito—**“In the same way, take a teaching that’s well explained and well propounded, emancipating, leading to peace, proclaimed by someone who is a fully awakened Buddha.*";
P_HTM[7800]="*idamahaṃ sukhettasmiṃ vadāmi.**This is what I call a fertile field.*";
P_HTM[7801]="*Tasmiñca dhamme sāvako viharati dhammānudhammappaṭipanno sāmīcippaṭipanno anudhammacārī—**A disciple remains in such a teaching, practicing in line with that teaching, practicing it properly, living in line with that teaching.*";
P_HTM[7802]="*idamahaṃ subījasmiṃ vadāmi.**This is what I call a good seed.*";
P_HTM[7803]="*Kimaṅgaṃ pana saraṇāniṃ sakkaṃ.**Why can’t this apply to Sarakāni?*";
P_HTM[7804]="*Saraṇāni, mahānāma, sakko maraṇakāle sikkhāya paripūrakārī ahosī”ti.**Mahānāma, Sarakāni the Sakyan fulfilled the training at the time of his death.”*";
P_HTM[7805]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[7806]="*8. Vassasuttaṃ**Anāthapiṇḍika (1st)*";
P_HTM[7807]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[7808]="*Tena kho pana samayena anāthapiṇḍiko gahapati ābādhiko hoti dukkhito bāḷhagilāno.**Now at that time the householder Anāthapiṇḍika was sick, suffering, gravely ill.*";
P_HTM[7809]="*Atha kho anāthapiṇḍiko gahapati aññataraṃ purisaṃ āmantesi:**Then he addressed a man,*";
P_HTM[7810]="*“ehi tvaṃ, ambho purisa, yenāyasmā sāriputto tenupasaṅkama; upasaṅkamitvā mama vacanena āyasmato sāriputtassa pāde sirasā vanda:**“Please, mister, go to Venerable Sāriputta, and in my name bow with your head to his feet. Say to him:*";
P_HTM[7811]="*‘anāthapiṇḍiko, bhante, gahapati ābādhiko dukkhito bāḷhagilāno.**‘Sir, the householder Anāthapiṇḍika is sick, suffering, gravely ill.*";
P_HTM[7812]="*So āyasmato sāriputtassa pāde sirasā vandatī’ti.**He bows with his head to your feet.’*";
P_HTM[7813]="*Evañca vadehi:**And then say:*";
P_HTM[7814]="*‘sādhu kira, bhante, āyasmā sāriputto yena anāthapiṇḍikassa gahapatissa nivesanaṃ tenupasaṅkamatu anukampaṃ upādāyā’”ti.**‘Sir, please visit him at his home out of compassion.’”*";
P_HTM[7815]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho so puriso anāthapiṇḍikassa gahapatissa paṭissutvā yenāyasmā sāriputto tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmantaṃ sāriputtaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho so puriso āyasmantaṃ sāriputtaṃ etadavoca:**“Yes, sir,” that man replied. He did as Anāthapiṇḍika asked.*";
P_HTM[7816]="*“Anāthapiṇḍiko, bhante, gahapati ābādhiko dukkhito bāḷhagilāno.* **";
P_HTM[7817]="*So āyasmato sāriputtassa pāde sirasā vandati.* **";
P_HTM[7818]="*Evañca vadati:* **";
P_HTM[7819]="*‘sādhu kira, bhante, āyasmā sāriputto yena anāthapiṇḍikassa gahapatissa nivesanaṃ tenupasaṅkamatu anukampaṃ upādāyā’”ti.* **";
P_HTM[7820]="*Adhivāsesi kho āyasmā sāriputto tuṇhībhāvena.**Sāriputta consented in silence.*";
P_HTM[7821]="*Atha kho āyasmā sāriputto pubbaṇhasamayaṃ nivāsetvā pattacīvaramādāya āyasmatā ānandena pacchāsamaṇena yena anāthapiṇḍikassa gahapatissa nivesanaṃ tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā paññatte āsane nisīdi. Nisajja kho āyasmā sāriputto anāthapiṇḍikaṃ gahapatiṃ etadavoca:**Then Venerable Sāriputta robed up in the morning and, taking his bowl and robe, went with Venerable Ānanda as his second monk to Anāthapiṇḍika’s home. He sat down on the seat spread out, and said to Anāthapiṇḍika,*";
P_HTM[7822]="*“kacci te, gahapati, khamanīyaṃ kacci yāpanīyaṃ? Kacci dukkhā vedanā paṭikkamanti, no abhikkamanti; paṭikkamosānaṃ paññāyati, no abhikkamo”ti?**“Householder, I hope you’re coping; I hope you’re getting better. And I hope the pain is fading, not growing, that its fading is evident, not its growing.”*";
P_HTM[7823]="*“Na me, bhante, khamanīyaṃ, na yāpanīyaṃ. Bāḷhā me dukkhā vedanā abhikkamanti, no paṭikkamanti; abhikkamosānaṃ paññāyati, no paṭikkamo”ti.**“Sir, I’m not keeping well, I’m not alright. The pain is terrible and growing, not fading; its growing is evident, not its fading.”*";
P_HTM[7824]="*“Yathārūpena kho, gahapati, buddhe appasādena samannāgato assutavā puthujjano kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjati tathārūpo te buddhe appasādo natthi.**“Householder, you don’t have the distrust in the Buddha that causes an uneducated ordinary person to be reborn—when their body breaks up, after death—in a place of loss, a bad place, the underworld, hell.*";
P_HTM[7825]="*Atthi ca kho te, gahapati, buddhe aveccappasādo—**And you have experiential confidence in the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[7826]="*itipi so bhagavā … pe … satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavāti.**‘That Blessed One is perfected, a fully awakened Buddha, accomplished in knowledge and conduct, holy, knower of the world, supreme guide for those who wish to train, teacher of gods and humans, awakened, blessed.’*";
P_HTM[7827]="*Tañca pana te buddhe aveccappasādaṃ attani samanupassato ṭhānaso vedanā paṭippassambheyya.**Seeing in yourself that experiential confidence in the teaching, that pain may die down on the spot.*";
P_HTM[7828]="*Yathārūpena kho, gahapati, dhamme appasādena samannāgato assutavā puthujjano kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjati, tathārūpo te dhamme appasādo natthi.**You don’t have the distrust in the teaching that causes an uneducated ordinary person to be reborn—when their body breaks up, after death—in a place of loss, a bad place, the underworld, hell.*";
P_HTM[7829]="*Atthi ca kho te, gahapati, dhamme aveccappasādo—**And you have experiential confidence in the teaching:*";
P_HTM[7830]="*svākkhāto bhagavatā dhammo … pe … paccattaṃ veditabbo viññūhīti.**‘The teaching is well explained by the Buddha—visible in this very life, immediately effective, inviting inspection, relevant, so that sensible people can know it for themselves.’*";
P_HTM[7831]="*Tañca pana te dhamme aveccappasādaṃ attani samanupassato ṭhānaso vedanā paṭippassambheyya.**Seeing in yourself that experiential confidence in the teaching, that pain may die down on the spot.*";
P_HTM[7832]="*Yathārūpena kho, gahapati, saṅghe appasādena samannāgato assutavā puthujjano kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjati, tathārūpo te saṅghe appasādo natthi.**You don’t have the distrust in the Saṅgha that causes an uneducated ordinary person to be reborn—when their body breaks up, after death—in a place of loss, a bad place, the underworld, hell.*";
P_HTM[7833]="*Atthi ca kho te, gahapati, saṅghe aveccappasādo—**And you have experiential confidence in the Saṅgha:*";
P_HTM[7834]="*suppaṭipanno bhagavato sāvakasaṅgho … pe … anuttaraṃ puññakkhettaṃ lokassāti.**‘The Saṅgha of the Buddha’s disciples is practicing the way that’s good, straightforward, methodical, and proper. It consists of the four pairs, the eight individuals. This Saṅgha of the Buddha’s disciples is worthy of offerings dedicated to the gods, worthy of hospitality, worthy of a religious donation, and worthy of veneration with joined palms. It is the supreme field of merit for the world.’*";
P_HTM[7835]="*Tañca pana te saṅghe aveccappasādaṃ attani samanupassato ṭhānaso vedanā paṭippassambheyya.**Seeing in yourself that experiential confidence in the Saṅgha, that pain may die down on the spot.*";
P_HTM[7836]="*Yathārūpena kho, gahapati, dussīlyena samannāgato assutavā puthujjano kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjati, tathārūpaṃ te dussīlyaṃ natthi.**You don’t have the unethical conduct that causes an uneducated ordinary person to be reborn—when their body breaks up, after death—in a place of loss, a bad place, the underworld, hell.*";
P_HTM[7837]="*Atthi ca kho te, gahapati, ariyakantāni sīlāni … pe samādhisaṃvattanikāni.**Your ethical conduct is loved by the noble ones, unbroken, impeccable, spotless, and unmarred, liberating, praised by sensible people, not mistaken, and leading to immersion.*";
P_HTM[7838]="*Tāni ca pana te ariyakantāni sīlāni attani samanupassato ṭhānaso vedanā paṭippassambheyya.**Seeing in yourself that ethical conduct loved by the noble ones, that pain may die down on the spot.*";
P_HTM[7839]="*Yathārūpāya kho, gahapati, micchādiṭṭhiyā samannāgato assutavā puthujjano kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjati, tathārūpā te micchādiṭṭhi natthi.**You don’t have the wrong view that causes an uneducated ordinary person to be reborn—when their body breaks up, after death—in a place of loss, a bad place, the underworld, hell.*";
P_HTM[7840]="*Atthi ca kho te, gahapati, sammādiṭṭhi.**You have right view.*";
P_HTM[7841]="*Tañca pana te sammādiṭṭhiṃ attani samanupassato ṭhānaso vedanā paṭippassambheyya.**Seeing in yourself that right view, that pain may die down on the spot.*";
P_HTM[7842]="*Yathārūpena kho, gahapati, micchāsaṅkappena samannāgato assutavā puthujjano kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjati, tathārūpo te micchāsaṅkappo natthi.**You don’t have the wrong thought …*";
P_HTM[7843]="*Atthi ca kho te, gahapati, sammāsaṅkappo.* **";
P_HTM[7844]="*Tañca pana te sammāsaṅkappaṃ attani samanupassato ṭhānaso vedanā paṭippassambheyya.* **";
P_HTM[7845]="*Yathārūpāya kho, gahapati, micchāvācāya samannāgato assutavā puthujjano kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjati, tathārūpā te micchāvācā natthi.**wrong speech …*";
P_HTM[7846]="*Atthi ca kho te, gahapati, sammāvācā.* **";
P_HTM[7847]="*Tañca pana te sammāvācaṃ attani samanupassato ṭhānaso vedanā paṭippassambheyya.* **";
P_HTM[7848]="*Yathārūpena kho, gahapati, micchākammantena samannāgato assutavā puthujjano kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjati, tathārūpo te micchākammanto natthi.**wrong action …*";
P_HTM[7849]="*Atthi ca kho te, gahapati, sammākammanto.* **";
P_HTM[7850]="*Tañca pana te sammākammantaṃ attani samanupassato ṭhānaso vedanā paṭippassambheyya.* **";
P_HTM[7851]="*Yathārūpena kho, gahapati, micchāājīvena samannāgato assutavā puthujjano kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjati, tathārūpo te micchāājīvo natthi.**wrong livelihood …*";
P_HTM[7852]="*Atthi ca kho te, gahapati, sammāājīvo.* **";
P_HTM[7853]="*Tañca pana te sammāājīvaṃ attani samanupassato ṭhānaso vedanā paṭippassambheyya.* **";
P_HTM[7854]="*Yathārūpena kho, gahapati, micchāvāyāmena samannāgato assutavā puthujjano kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjati, tathārūpo te micchāvāyāmo natthi.**wrong effort …*";
P_HTM[7855]="*Atthi ca kho te, gahapati, sammāvāyāmo.* **";
P_HTM[7856]="*Tañca pana te sammāvāyāmaṃ attani samanupassato ṭhānaso vedanā paṭippassambheyya.* **";
P_HTM[7857]="*Yathārūpāya kho, gahapati, micchāsatiyā samannāgato assutavā puthujjano kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjati, tathārūpā te micchāsati natthi.**wrong mindfulness …*";
P_HTM[7858]="*Atthi ca kho te, gahapati, sammāsati.* **";
P_HTM[7859]="*Tañca pana te sammāsatiṃ attani samanupassato ṭhānaso vedanā paṭippassambheyya.* **";
P_HTM[7860]="*Yathārūpena kho, gahapati, micchāsamādhinā samannāgato assutavā puthujjano kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjati, tathārūpo te micchāsamādhi natthi.**wrong immersion …*";
P_HTM[7861]="*Atthi ca kho te, gahapati, sammāsamādhi.* **";
P_HTM[7862]="*Tañca pana te sammāsamādhiṃ attani samanupassato ṭhānaso vedanā paṭippassambheyya.* **";
P_HTM[7863]="*Yathārūpena kho, gahapati, micchāñāṇena samannāgato assutavā puthujjano kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjati, tathārūpaṃ te micchāñāṇaṃ natthi.**wrong knowledge …*";
P_HTM[7864]="*Atthi ca kho te, gahapati, sammāñāṇaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[7865]="*Tañca pana te sammāñāṇaṃ attani samanupassato ṭhānaso vedanā paṭippassambheyya.* **";
P_HTM[7866]="*Yathārūpāya kho, gahapati, micchāvimuttiyā samannāgato assutavā puthujjano kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjati, tathārūpā te micchāvimutti natthi.**wrong freedom …*";
P_HTM[7867]="*Atthi ca kho te, gahapati, sammāvimutti.**You have right freedom.*";
P_HTM[7868]="*Tañca pana te sammāvimuttiṃ attani samanupassato ṭhānaso vedanā paṭippassambheyyā”ti.**Seeing in yourself that right freedom, that pain may die down on the spot.”*";
P_HTM[7869]="*Atha kho anāthapiṇḍikassa gahapatissa ṭhānaso vedanā paṭippassambhiṃsu.**And then Anāthapiṇḍika’s pain died down on the spot.*";
P_HTM[7870]="*Atha kho anāthapiṇḍiko gahapati āyasmantañca sāriputtaṃ āyasmantañca ānandaṃ sakeneva thālipākena parivisi.**Then he served Sāriputta and Ānanda from his own dish.*";
P_HTM[7871]="*Atha kho anāthapiṇḍiko gahapati āyasmantaṃ sāriputtaṃ bhuttāviṃ onītapattapāṇiṃ aññataraṃ nīcāsanaṃ gahetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi.**When Sāriputta had eaten and washed his hand and bowl, Anāthapiṇḍika took a low seat and sat to one side.*";
P_HTM[7872]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinnaṃ kho anāthapiṇḍikaṃ gahapatiṃ āyasmā sāriputto imāhi gāthāhi anumodi:**Venerable Sāriputta expressed his appreciation to him with these verses.*";
P_HTM[7873]="*“Yassa saddhā tathāgate,**“Whoever has faith in the Realized One,*";
P_HTM[7874]="*acalā suppatiṭṭhitā;**unwavering and well grounded;*";
P_HTM[7875]="*Sīlañca yassa kalyāṇaṃ,**whose ethical conduct is good,*";
P_HTM[7876]="*ariyakantaṃ pasaṃsitaṃ.**praised and loved by the noble ones;*";
P_HTM[7877]="*Saṃghe pasādo yassatthi,**who has confidence in the Saṅgha,*";
P_HTM[7878]="*ujubhūtañca dassanaṃ;**and correct view:*";
P_HTM[7879]="*Adaliddoti taṃ āhu,**they’re said to be prosperous,*";
P_HTM[7880]="*amoghaṃ tassa jīvitaṃ.**their life is not in vain.*";
P_HTM[7881]="*Tasmā saddhañca sīlañca,**So let the wise devote themselves*";
P_HTM[7882]="*pasādaṃ dhammadassanaṃ;**to faith, ethical behaviour,*";
P_HTM[7883]="*Anuyuñjetha medhāvī,**confidence, and insight into the teaching,*";
P_HTM[7884]="*saraṃ buddhānasāsanan”ti.**remembering the instructions of the Buddhas.”*";
P_HTM[7885]="*Atha kho āyasmā sāriputto anāthapiṇḍikaṃ gahapatiṃ imāhi gāthāhi anumoditvā uṭṭhāyāsanā pakkāmi.**After expressing his appreciation to Anāthapiṇḍika with these verses, Sāriputta got up from his seat and left.*";
P_HTM[7886]="*Atha kho āyasmā ānando yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinnaṃ kho āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ bhagavā etadavoca:**Then Ānanda went up to the Buddha, bowed, and sat down to one side. The Buddha said to him,*";
P_HTM[7887]="*“handa kuto nu tvaṃ, ānanda, āgacchasi divādivassā”ti?**“So, Ānanda, where are you coming from in the middle of the day?”*";
P_HTM[7888]="*“Āyasmatā, bhante, sāriputtena anāthapiṇḍiko gahapati iminā ca iminā ca ovādena ovadito”ti.**“Sir, Venerable Sāriputta advised the householder Anāthapiṇḍika in this way and that.”*";
P_HTM[7889]="*“Paṇḍito, ānanda, sāriputto;**“Sāriputta is astute, Ānanda.*";
P_HTM[7890]="*mahāpañño, ānanda, sāriputto, yatra hi nāma cattāri sotāpattiyaṅgāni dasahākārehi vibhajissatī”ti.**He has great wisdom, since he can analyze the four factors of stream-entry in ten respects.”*";
P_HTM[7891]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[7892]="*9. Kāḷigodhasuttaṃ**With Anāthapiṇḍika (2nd)*";
P_HTM[7893]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[7894]="*Tena kho pana samayena anāthapiṇḍiko gahapati ābādhiko hoti dukkhito bāḷhagilāno.**Now at that time the householder Anāthapiṇḍika was sick, suffering, gravely ill.*";
P_HTM[7895]="*Atha kho anāthapiṇḍiko gahapati aññataraṃ purisaṃ āmantesi:**Then he addressed a man,*";
P_HTM[7896]="*“ehi tvaṃ, ambho purisa, yenāyasmā ānando tenupasaṅkama; upasaṅkamitvā mama vacanena āyasmato ānandassa pāde sirasā vanda:**“Please, mister, go to Venerable Ānanda, and in my name bow with your head to his feet. Say to him:*";
P_HTM[7897]="*‘anāthapiṇḍiko, bhante, gahapati ābādhiko dukkhito bāḷhagilāno.**‘Sir, the householder Anāthapiṇḍika is sick, suffering, gravely ill.*";
P_HTM[7898]="*So āyasmato ānandassa pāde sirasā vandatī’ti.**He bows with his head to your feet.’*";
P_HTM[7899]="*Evañca vadehi:**And then say:*";
P_HTM[7900]="*‘sādhu kira, bhante, āyasmā ānando yena anāthapiṇḍikassa gahapatissa nivesanaṃ tenupasaṅkamatu anukampaṃ upādāyā’”ti.**‘Sir, please visit him at his home out of compassion.’”*";
P_HTM[7901]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho so puriso anāthapiṇḍikassa gahapatissa paṭissutvā yenāyasmā ānando tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho so puriso āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ etadavoca:**“Yes, sir,” that man replied. He did as Anāthapiṇḍika asked.*";
P_HTM[7902]="*“anāthapiṇḍiko, bhante, gahapati ābādhiko dukkhito bāḷhagilāno.* **";
P_HTM[7903]="*So āyasmato ānandassa pāde sirasā vandati.* **";
P_HTM[7904]="*Evañca vadati:* **";
P_HTM[7905]="*‘sādhu kira, bhante, āyasmā ānando yena anāthapiṇḍikassa gahapatissa nivesanaṃ tenupasaṅkamatu anukampaṃ upādāyā’”ti.* **";
P_HTM[7906]="*Adhivāsesi kho āyasmā ānando tuṇhībhāvena.**Ānanda consented in silence.*";
P_HTM[7907]="*Atha kho āyasmā ānando pubbaṇhasamayaṃ nivāsetvā pattacīvaramādāya yena anāthapiṇḍikassa gahapatissa nivesanaṃ tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā paññatte āsane nisīdi. Nisajja kho āyasmā ānando anāthapiṇḍikaṃ gahapatiṃ etadavoca:**Then Venerable Ānanda robed up in the morning and, taking his bowl and robe, went to the home of the householder Anāthapiṇḍika. He sat down on the seat spread out and said to Anāthapiṇḍika,*";
P_HTM[7908]="*“kacci te, gahapati, khamanīyaṃ, kacci yāpanīyaṃ? Kacci dukkhā vedanā paṭikkamanti, no abhikkamanti; paṭikkamosānaṃ paññāyati, no abhikkamo”ti?**“Householder, I hope you’re coping; I hope you’re getting better. And I hope the pain is fading, not growing; that its fading, not its growing, is apparent.”*";
P_HTM[7909]="*“Na me, bhante, khamanīyaṃ na yāpanīyaṃ. Bāḷhā me dukkhā vedanā abhikkamanti, no paṭikkamanti; abhikkamosānaṃ paññāyati, no paṭikkamo”ti.**“Sir, I’m not keeping well, I’m not alright. The pain is terrible and growing, not fading; its growing is evident, not its fading.”*";
P_HTM[7910]="*“Catūhi kho, gahapati, dhammehi samannāgatassa assutavato puthujjanassa hoti uttāso, hoti chambhitattaṃ, hoti samparāyikaṃ maraṇabhayaṃ.**“Householder, when an uneducated ordinary person has four things, they’re frightened and terrified, and fear what awaits them after death.*";
P_HTM[7911]="*Katamehi catūhi?**What four?*";
P_HTM[7912]="*Idha, gahapati, assutavā puthujjano buddhe appasādena samannāgato hoti.**Firstly, an uneducated ordinary person distrusts the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[7913]="*Tañca panassa buddhe appasādaṃ attani samanupassato hoti uttāso, hoti chambhitattaṃ, hoti samparāyikaṃ maraṇabhayaṃ.**Seeing in themselves that distrust of the Buddha, they’re frightened and terrified, and fear what awaits them after death.*";
P_HTM[7914]="*Puna caparaṃ, gahapati, assutavā puthujjano dhamme appasādena samannāgato hoti.**Furthermore, an uneducated ordinary person distrusts the teaching …*";
P_HTM[7915]="*Tañca panassa dhamme appasādaṃ attani samanupassato hoti uttāso, hoti chambhitattaṃ, hoti samparāyikaṃ maraṇabhayaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[7916]="*Puna caparaṃ, gahapati, assutavā puthujjano saṅghe appasādena samannāgato hoti.**Furthermore, an uneducated ordinary person distrusts the Saṅgha …*";
P_HTM[7917]="*Tañca panassa saṅghe appasādaṃ attani samanupassato hoti uttāso, hoti chambhitattaṃ, hoti samparāyikaṃ maraṇabhayaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[7918]="*Puna caparaṃ, gahapati, assutavā puthujjano dussīlyena samannāgato hoti.**Furthermore, an uneducated ordinary person has unethical conduct.*";
P_HTM[7919]="*Tañca panassa dussīlyaṃ attani samanupassato hoti uttāso, hoti chambhitattaṃ, hoti samparāyikaṃ maraṇabhayaṃ.**Seeing in themselves that unethical conduct, they’re frightened and terrified, and fear what awaits them after death.*";
P_HTM[7920]="*Imehi kho, gahapati, catūhi dhammehi samannāgatassa assutavato puthujjanassa hoti uttāso, hoti chambhitattaṃ, hoti samparāyikaṃ maraṇabhayaṃ.**When an uneducated ordinary person has these four things, they’re frightened and terrified, and fear what awaits them after death.*";
P_HTM[7921]="*Catūhi kho, gahapati, dhammehi samannāgatassa sutavato ariyasāvakassa na hoti uttāso, na hoti chambhitattaṃ, na hoti samparāyikaṃ maraṇabhayaṃ.**When an educated noble disciple has four things, they’re not frightened or terrified, and don’t fear what awaits them after death.*";
P_HTM[7922]="*Katamehi catūhi?**What four?*";
P_HTM[7923]="*Idha, gahapati, sutavā ariyasāvako buddhe aveccappasādena samannāgato hoti—**Firstly, a noble disciple has experiential confidence in the Buddha …*";
P_HTM[7924]="*itipi so bhagavā … pe … satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavāti.* **";
P_HTM[7925]="*Tañca panassa buddhe aveccappasādaṃ attani samanupassato na hoti uttāso, na hoti chambhitattaṃ, na hoti samparāyikaṃ maraṇabhayaṃ.**Seeing in themselves that experiential confidence in the Buddha, they’re not frightened or terrified, and don’t fear what awaits them after death.*";
P_HTM[7926]="*Puna caparaṃ, gahapati, sutavā ariyasāvako dhamme aveccappasādena samannāgato hoti—**Furthermore, a noble disciple has experiential confidence in the teaching …*";
P_HTM[7927]="*svākkhāto bhagavatā dhammo … pe … paccattaṃ veditabbo viññūhīti.* **";
P_HTM[7928]="*Tañca panassa dhamme aveccappasādaṃ attani samanupassato na hoti uttāso, na hoti chambhitattaṃ, na hoti samparāyikaṃ maraṇabhayaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[7929]="*Puna caparaṃ, gahapati, sutavā ariyasāvako saṅghe aveccappasādena samannāgato hoti—**Furthermore, a noble disciple has experiential confidence in the Saṅgha …*";
P_HTM[7930]="*suppaṭipanno bhagavato sāvakasaṅgho … pe … anuttaraṃ puññakkhettaṃ lokassāti.* **";
P_HTM[7931]="*Tañca panassa saṅghe aveccappasādaṃ attani samanupassato na hoti uttāso, na hoti chambhitattaṃ, na hoti samparāyikaṃ maraṇabhayaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[7932]="*Puna caparaṃ, gahapati, sutavā ariyasāvako ariyakantehi sīlehi samannāgato hoti akhaṇḍehi … pe … samādhisaṃvattanikehi.**Furthermore, a noble disciple’s ethical conduct is loved by the noble ones, unbroken, impeccable, spotless, and unmarred, liberating, praised by sensible people, not mistaken, and leading to immersion.*";
P_HTM[7933]="*Tāni ca panassa ariyakantāni sīlāni attani samanupassato na hoti uttāso, na hoti chambhitattaṃ, na hoti samparāyikaṃ maraṇabhayaṃ.**Seeing in themselves that ethical conduct loved by the noble ones, they’re not frightened or terrified, and don’t fear what awaits them after death.*";
P_HTM[7934]="*Imehi kho, gahapati, catūhi dhammehi samannāgatassa sutavato ariyasāvakassa na hoti uttāso, na hoti chambhitattaṃ, na hoti samparāyikaṃ maraṇabhayan”ti.**When an educated noble disciple has these four things, they’re not frightened or terrified, and don’t fear what awaits them after death.”*";
P_HTM[7935]="*“Nāhaṃ, bhante ānanda, bhāyāmi.**“Sir, Ānanda, I am not afraid.*";
P_HTM[7936]="*Kyāhaṃ bhāyissāmi.**What have I to fear?*";
P_HTM[7937]="*Ahañhi, bhante, buddhe aveccappasādena samannāgato homi—**For I have experiential confidence in the Buddha …*";
P_HTM[7938]="*itipi so bhagavā … pe … satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavāti.* **";
P_HTM[7939]="*Dhamme … pe …**the teaching …*";
P_HTM[7940]="*saṅghe aveccappasādena samannāgato homi—**the Saṅgha …*";
P_HTM[7941]="*suppaṭipanno bhagavato sāvakasaṅgho … pe … anuttaraṃ puññakkhettaṃ lokassāti.* **";
P_HTM[7942]="*Yāni cimāni, bhante, bhagavatā gihisāmīcikāni sikkhāpadāni desitāni, nāhaṃ tesaṃ kiñci attani khaṇḍaṃ samanupassāmī”ti.**And of the training rules appropriate for laypeople taught by the Buddha, I don’t see any that I have broken.”*";
P_HTM[7943]="*“Lābhā te, gahapati, suladdhaṃ te, gahapati.**“You’re fortunate, householder, so very fortunate,*";
P_HTM[7944]="*Sotāpattiphalaṃ tayā, gahapati, byākatan”ti.**You have declared the fruit of stream-entry.”*";
P_HTM[7945]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[7946]="*10. Nandiyasakkasuttaṃ**Dangers and Threats (1st)*";
P_HTM[7947]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[7948]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinnaṃ kho anāthapiṇḍikaṃ gahapatiṃ bhagavā etadavoca:**Seated to one side, the Buddha said to the householder Anāthapiṇḍika:*";
P_HTM[7949]="*“yato kho, gahapati, ariyasāvakassa pañca bhayāni verāni vūpasantāni ca honti, catūhi ca sotāpattiyaṅgehi samannāgato hoti, ariyo cassa ñāyo paññāya sudiṭṭho hoti suppaṭividdho, so ākaṅkhamāno attanāva attānaṃ byākareyya:**“Householder, when a noble disciple has quelled five dangers and threats, has the four factors of stream-entry, and has clearly seen and comprehended the noble cycle with wisdom, they may, if they wish, declare of themselves:*";
P_HTM[7950]="*‘khīṇanirayomhi khīṇatiracchānayoni khīṇapettivisayo khīṇāpāyaduggativinipāto; sotāpannohamasmi avinipātadhammo niyato sambodhiparāyaṇo’.**‘I’ve finished with rebirth in hell, the animal realm, and the ghost realm. I’ve finished with all places of loss, bad places, the underworld. I am a stream-enterer! I’m not liable to be reborn in the underworld, and am bound for awakening.’*";
P_HTM[7951]="*Katamāni pañca bhayāni verāni vūpasantāni honti?**What are the five dangers and threats they have quelled?*";
P_HTM[7952]="*Yaṃ, gahapati, pāṇātipātī pāṇātipātappaccayā diṭṭhadhammikampi bhayaṃ veraṃ pasavati, samparāyikampi bhayaṃ veraṃ pasavati, cetasikampi dukkhaṃ domanassaṃ paṭisaṃvediyati.**Anyone who kills living creatures creates dangers and threats both in the present life and in lives to come, and experiences mental pain and sadness.*";
P_HTM[7953]="*Pāṇātipātā paṭiviratassa evaṃ taṃ bhayaṃ veraṃ vūpasantaṃ hoti.**So that danger and threat is quelled for anyone who refrains from killing living creatures.*";
P_HTM[7954]="*Yaṃ, gahapati, adinnādāyī … pe …**Anyone who steals …*";
P_HTM[7955]="*yaṃ, gahapati, kāmesumicchācārī … pe …**Anyone who commits sexual misconduct …*";
P_HTM[7956]="*yaṃ, gahapati, musāvādī … pe …**Anyone who lies …*";
P_HTM[7957]="*yaṃ, gahapati, surāmerayamajjappamādaṭṭhāyī surāmerayamajjappamādaṭṭhānappaccayā diṭṭhadhammikampi bhayaṃ veraṃ pasavati, samparāyikampi bhayaṃ veraṃ pasavati, cetasikampi dukkhaṃ domanassaṃ paṭisaṃvediyati.**Anyone who uses alcoholic drinks that cause negligence creates dangers and threats both in the present life and in lives to come, and experiences mental pain and sadness.*";
P_HTM[7958]="*Surāmerayamajjappamādaṭṭhānā paṭiviratassa evaṃ taṃ bhayaṃ veraṃ vūpasantaṃ hoti.**So that danger and threat is quelled for anyone who refrains from alcoholic drinks that cause negligence.*";
P_HTM[7959]="*Imāni pañca bhayāni verāni vūpasantāni honti.**These are the five dangers and threats they have quelled.*";
P_HTM[7960]="*Katamehi catūhi sotāpattiyaṅgehi samannāgato hoti?**What are the four factors of stream-entry that they have?*";
P_HTM[7961]="*Idha, gahapati, ariyasāvako buddhe aveccappasādena samannāgato hoti—**It’s when a noble disciple has experiential confidence in the Buddha …*";
P_HTM[7962]="*itipi so bhagavā … pe … satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavāti.* **";
P_HTM[7963]="*Dhamme … pe …**the teaching …*";
P_HTM[7964]="*saṅghe … pe …**the Saṅgha …*";
P_HTM[7965]="*ariyakantehi sīlehi samannāgato hoti akhaṇḍehi … pe … samādhisaṃvattanikehi.**And they have the ethical conduct loved by the noble ones … leading to immersion.*";
P_HTM[7966]="*Imehi catūhi sotāpattiyaṅgehi samannāgato hoti.**These are the four factors of stream-entry that they have.*";
P_HTM[7967]="*Katamo cassa ariyo ñāyo paññāya sudiṭṭho hoti suppaṭividdho?**And what is the noble cycle that they have clearly seen and comprehended with wisdom?*";
P_HTM[7968]="*Idha, gahapati, ariyasāvako paṭiccasamuppādaññeva sādhukaṃ yoniso manasi karoti—**A noble disciple properly attends to dependent origination itself:*";
P_HTM[7969]="*iti imasmiṃ sati idaṃ hoti, imassuppādā idaṃ uppajjati;**‘When this exists, that is; due to the arising of this, that arises.*";
P_HTM[7970]="*iti imasmiṃ asati idaṃ na hoti, imassa nirodhā idaṃ nirujjhati;**When this doesn’t exist, that is not; due to the cessation of this, that ceases.' That is:*";
P_HTM[7971]="*yadidaṃ avijjāpaccayā saṅkhārā, saṅkhārapaccayā viññāṇaṃ … pe …**Ignorance is a condition for choices. Choices are a condition for consciousness. Consciousness is a condition for name and form. Name and form are a condition for the six sense fields. The six sense fields are conditions for contact. Contact is a condition for feeling. Feeling is a condition for craving. Craving is a condition for grasping. Grasping is a condition for continued existence. Continued existence is a condition for rebirth. Rebirth is a condition that gives rise to old age and death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress.*";
P_HTM[7972]="*evametassa kevalassa dukkhakkhandhassa samudayo hoti.**That is how this entire mass of suffering originates.*";
P_HTM[7973]="*Avijjāya tveva asesavirāganirodhā saṅkhāranirodho … pe …**When ignorance fades away and ceases with nothing left over, choices cease. When choices cease, consciousness ceases. When consciousness ceases, name and form cease. When name and form cease, the six sense fields cease. When the six sense fields cease, contact ceases. When contact ceases, feeling ceases. When feeling ceases, craving ceases. When craving ceases, grasping ceases. When grasping ceases, continued existence ceases. When continued existence ceases, rebirth ceases. When rebirth ceases, old age and death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress cease.*";
P_HTM[7974]="*evametassa kevalassa dukkhakkhandhassa nirodho hoti.**That is how this entire mass of suffering ceases.*";
P_HTM[7975]="*Ayamassa ariyo ñāyo paññāya sudiṭṭho hoti suppaṭividdho.**This is the noble cycle that they have clearly seen and comprehended with wisdom.*";
P_HTM[7976]="*Yato kho, gahapati, ariyasāvakassa imāni pañca bhayāni verāni vūpasantāni honti, imehi catūhi sotāpattiyaṅgehi samannāgato hoti, ayañcassa ariyo ñāyo paññāya sudiṭṭho hoti suppaṭividdho. So ākaṅkhamāno attanāva attānaṃ byākareyya:**When a noble disciple has quelled five dangers and threats, has the four factors of stream-entry, and has clearly seen and comprehended the noble cycle with wisdom, they may, if they wish, declare of themselves:*";
P_HTM[7977]="*‘khīṇanirayomhi khīṇatiracchānayoni khīṇapettivisayo khīṇāpāyaduggativinipāto; sotāpannohamasmi avinipātadhammo niyato sambodhiparāyaṇo’”ti.**‘I’ve finished with rebirth in hell, the animal realm, and the ghost realm. I’ve finished with all places of loss, bad places, the underworld. I am a stream-enterer! I’m not liable to be reborn in the underworld, and am bound for awakening.’”*";
P_HTM[7978]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[7979]="*1. Samādhivaggo**About Sarakāni*";
P_HTM[7980]="*1. Paṭhamaabhisandasuttaṃ**Dangers and Threats (2nd)*";
P_HTM[7981]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ … pe …**At Sāvatthī. …*";
P_HTM[7982]="*“yato kho, bhikkhave, ariyasāvakassa imāni pañca bhayāni verāni vūpasantāni honti, imehi catūhi sotāpattiyaṅgehi samannāgato hoti, ayañcassa ariyo ñāyo paññāya sudiṭṭho hoti suppaṭividdho; so ākaṅkhamāno attanāva attānaṃ byākareyya:**“Mendicants, when a noble disciple has quelled five dangers and threats, has the four factors of stream-entry, and has clearly seen and comprehended the noble cycle with wisdom, they may, if they wish, declare of themselves:*";
P_HTM[7983]="*‘khīṇanirayomhi khīṇatiracchānayoni khīṇapettivisayo khīṇāpāyaduggativinipāto; sotāpannohamasmi avinipātadhammo niyato sambodhiparāyaṇo’”ti.**‘I’ve finished with rebirth in hell, the animal realm, and the ghost realm. I’ve finished with all places of loss, bad places, the underworld. I am a stream-enterer! I’m not liable to be reborn in the underworld, and am bound for awakening.’”*";
P_HTM[7984]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[7985]="*2. Dutiyaabhisandasuttaṃ**With Nandaka the Licchavi*";
P_HTM[7986]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā vesāliyaṃ viharati mahāvane kūṭāgārasālāyaṃ.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Vesālī, at the Great Wood, in the hall with the peaked roof.*";
P_HTM[7987]="*Atha kho nandako licchavimahāmatto yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinnaṃ kho nandakaṃ licchavimahāmattaṃ bhagavā etadavoca:**Then Nandaka the Licchavi minister went up to the Buddha, bowed, and sat down to one side. The Buddha said to him:*";
P_HTM[7988]="*“Catūhi kho, nandaka, dhammehi samannāgato ariyasāvako sotāpanno hoti avinipātadhammo niyato sambodhiparāyaṇo.**“Nandaka, a noble disciple who has four things is a stream-enterer, not liable to be reborn in the underworld, bound for awakening.*";
P_HTM[7989]="*Katamehi catūhi?**What four?*";
P_HTM[7990]="*Idha, nandaka, ariyasāvako buddhe aveccappasādena samannāgato hoti—**It’s when a noble disciple has experiential confidence in the Buddha …*";
P_HTM[7991]="*itipi so bhagavā … pe … satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavāti.* **";
P_HTM[7992]="*Dhamme … pe …**the teaching …*";
P_HTM[7993]="*saṅghe … pe …**the Saṅgha …*";
P_HTM[7994]="*ariyakantehi sīlehi samannāgato hoti akhaṇḍehi … pe … samādhisaṃvattanikehi.**And they have the ethical conduct loved by the noble ones … leading to immersion.*";
P_HTM[7995]="*Imehi kho, nandaka, catūhi dhammehi samannāgato ariyasāvako sotāpanno hoti avinipātadhammo niyato sambodhiparāyaṇo.**A noble disciple who has these four things is a stream-enterer, not liable to be reborn in the underworld, bound for awakening.*";
P_HTM[7996]="*Imehi ca pana, nandaka, catūhi dhammehi samannāgato ariyasāvako āyunā saṃyutto hoti dibbenapi mānusenapi;**A noble disciple who has these four things is guaranteed long life,*";
P_HTM[7997]="*vaṇṇena saṃyutto hoti dibbenapi mānusenapi;**beauty,*";
P_HTM[7998]="*sukhena saṃyutto hoti dibbenapi mānusenapi;**happiness,*";
P_HTM[7999]="*yasena saṃyutto hoti dibbenapi mānusenapi;**fame,*";
P_HTM[8000]="*ādhipateyyena saṃyutto hoti dibbenapi mānusenapi.**and sovereignty, both human and divine.*";
P_HTM[8001]="*Taṃ kho panāhaṃ, nandaka, nāññassa samaṇassa vā brāhmaṇassa vā sutvā vadāmi. Api ca yadeva mayā sāmaṃ ñātaṃ sāmaṃ diṭṭhaṃ sāmaṃ viditaṃ, tadevāhaṃ vadāmī”ti.**Now, I don’t say this because I’ve heard it from some other ascetic or brahmin. I only say it because I’ve known, seen, and realized it for myself.”*";
P_HTM[8002]="*Evaṃ vutte, aññataro puriso nandakaṃ licchavimahāmattaṃ etadavoca:**When he had spoken, a certain person said to Nandaka:*";
P_HTM[8003]="*“nahānakālo, bhante”ti.**“Sir, it is time to bathe.”*";
P_HTM[8004]="*“Alaṃ dāni, bhaṇe, etena bāhirena nahānena.**“Enough now, my man, with that exterior bath.*";
P_HTM[8005]="*Alamidaṃ ajjhattaṃ nahānaṃ bhavissati, yadidaṃ—**This interior bathing will do for me, that is,*";
P_HTM[8006]="*bhagavati pasādo”ti.**confidence in the Buddha.”*";
P_HTM[8007]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8008]="*Saraṇānivaggo tatiyo.* **";
P_HTM[8009]="*Mahānāmena dve vuttā,* **";
P_HTM[8010]="*godhā ca saraṇā duve;* **";
P_HTM[8011]="*Duve anāthapiṇḍikā,* **";
P_HTM[8012]="*duve verabhayena ca;* **";
P_HTM[8013]="*Licchavī dasamo vutto,* **";
P_HTM[8014]="*vaggo tena pavuccatīti.* **";
P_HTM[8015]="*3. Tatiyaabhisandasuttaṃ**Overflowing Merit (1st)*";
P_HTM[8016]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[8017]="*“Cattārome, bhikkhave, puññābhisandā kusalābhisandā sukhassāhārā.**“Mendicants, there are these four kinds of overflowing merit, overflowing goodness that nurture happiness.*";
P_HTM[8018]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[8019]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako buddhe aveccappasādena samannāgato hoti—**Firstly, a noble disciple has experiential confidence in the Buddha …*";
P_HTM[8020]="*itipi so bhagavā … pe … satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavāti.* **";
P_HTM[8021]="*Ayaṃ paṭhamo puññābhisando kusalābhisando sukhassāhāro.**This is the first kind of overflowing merit, overflowing goodness that nurtures happiness.*";
P_HTM[8022]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako dhamme aveccappasādena samannāgato hoti—**Furthermore, a noble disciple has experiential confidence in the teaching …*";
P_HTM[8023]="*svākkhāto bhagavatā dhammo … pe … paccattaṃ veditabbo viññūhīti.* **";
P_HTM[8024]="*Ayaṃ dutiyo puññābhisando kusalābhisando sukhassāhāro.**This is the second kind of overflowing merit, overflowing goodness that nurtures happiness.*";
P_HTM[8025]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako saṅghe aveccappasādena samannāgato hoti—**Furthermore, a noble disciple has experiential confidence in the Saṅgha …*";
P_HTM[8026]="*suppaṭipanno bhagavato sāvakasaṅgho … pe … anuttaraṃ puññakkhettaṃ lokassāti.* **";
P_HTM[8027]="*Ayaṃ tatiyo puññābhisando kusalābhisando sukhassāhāro.**This is the third kind of overflowing merit, overflowing goodness that nurtures happiness.*";
P_HTM[8028]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako ariyakantehi sīlehi samannāgato hoti akhaṇḍehi … pe … samādhisaṃvattanikehi.**Furthermore, a noble disciple’s ethical conduct is loved by the noble ones, unbroken, impeccable, spotless, and unmarred, liberating, praised by sensible people, not mistaken, and leading to immersion.*";
P_HTM[8029]="*Ayaṃ catuttho puññābhisando kusalābhisando sukhassāhāro.**This is the fourth kind of overflowing merit, overflowing goodness that nurtures happiness.*";
P_HTM[8030]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, cattāro puññābhisandā kusalābhisandā sukhassāhārā”ti.**These are the four kinds of overflowing merit, overflowing goodness that nurture happiness.”*";
P_HTM[8031]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8032]="*4. Paṭhamamahaddhanasuttaṃ**Overflowing Merit (2nd)*";
P_HTM[8033]="*“Cattārome, bhikkhave, puññābhisandā kusalābhisandā sukhassāhārā.**“Mendicants, there are these four kinds of overflowing merit, overflowing goodness that nurture happiness.*";
P_HTM[8034]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[8035]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako buddhe aveccappasādena samannāgato hoti—**It’s when a noble disciple has experiential confidence in the Buddha …*";
P_HTM[8036]="*itipi so bhagavā … pe … satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavāti.* **";
P_HTM[8037]="*Ayaṃ paṭhamo puññābhisando kusalābhisando sukhassāhāro.* **";
P_HTM[8038]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako dhamme … pe …**the teaching …*";
P_HTM[8039]="*saṅghe … pe ….**the Saṅgha …*";
P_HTM[8040]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako vigatamalamaccherena cetasā agāraṃ ajjhāvasati muttacāgo payatapāṇi vossaggarato yācayogo dānasaṃvibhāgarato.**Furthermore, a noble disciple lives at home rid of the stain of stinginess, freely generous, open-handed, loving to let go, committed to charity, loving to give and to share.*";
P_HTM[8041]="*Ayaṃ catuttho puññābhisando kusalābhisando sukhassāhāro.**This is the fourth kind of overflowing merit, overflowing goodness that nurtures happiness.*";
P_HTM[8042]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, cattāro puññābhisandā kusalābhisandā sukhassāhārā”ti.**These are the four kinds of overflowing merit, overflowing goodness that nurture happiness.”*";
P_HTM[8043]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8044]="*5. Dutiyamahaddhanasuttaṃ**Overflowing Merit (3rd)*";
P_HTM[8045]="*“Cattārome, bhikkhave, puññābhisandā kusalābhisandā sukhassāhārā.**“Mendicants, there are these four kinds of overflowing merit, overflowing goodness that nurture happiness.*";
P_HTM[8046]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[8047]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako buddhe aveccappasādena samannāgato hoti—**It’s when a noble disciple has experiential confidence in the Buddha …*";
P_HTM[8048]="*itipi so bhagavā … pe … satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavāti.* **";
P_HTM[8049]="*Ayaṃ paṭhamo puññābhisando kusalābhisando sukhassāhāro.* **";
P_HTM[8050]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako dhamme … pe …**the teaching …*";
P_HTM[8051]="*saṅghe … pe ….**the Saṅgha …*";
P_HTM[8052]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako paññavā hoti udayatthagāminiyā paññāya samannāgato ariyāya nibbedhikāya sammā dukkhakkhayagāminiyā.**Furthermore, a noble disciple is wise. They have the wisdom of arising and passing away which is noble, penetrative, and leads to the complete ending of suffering.*";
P_HTM[8053]="*Ayaṃ catuttho puññābhisando kusalābhisando sukhassāhāro.**This is the fourth kind of overflowing merit, overflowing goodness that nurtures happiness.*";
P_HTM[8054]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, cattāro puññābhisandā kusalābhisandā sukhassāhārā”ti.**These are the four kinds of overflowing merit, overflowing goodness that nurture happiness.”*";
P_HTM[8055]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8056]="*6. Suddhakasuttaṃ**Footprints of the Gods (1st)*";
P_HTM[8057]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[8058]="*“Cattārimāni, bhikkhave, devānaṃ devapadāni avisuddhānaṃ sattānaṃ visuddhiyā apariyodātānaṃ sattānaṃ pariyodapanāya.**“Mendicants, these four footprints of the gods are in order to purify unpurified beings and cleanse unclean beings.*";
P_HTM[8059]="*Katamāni cattāri?**What four?*";
P_HTM[8060]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako buddhe aveccappasādena samannāgato hoti—**Firstly, a noble disciple has experiential confidence in the Buddha …*";
P_HTM[8061]="*itipi so bhagavā … pe … satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavāti.* **";
P_HTM[8062]="*Idaṃ paṭhamaṃ devānaṃ devapadaṃ avisuddhānaṃ sattānaṃ visuddhiyā apariyodātānaṃ sattānaṃ pariyodapanāya.**This is the first footprint of the gods in order to purify unpurified beings and cleanse unclean beings.*";
P_HTM[8063]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako dhamme … pe …**Furthermore, a noble disciple has experiential confidence in the teaching …*";
P_HTM[8064]="*saṅghe … pe ….**the Saṅgha …*";
P_HTM[8065]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako ariyakantehi sīlehi samannāgato hoti akhaṇḍehi … pe … samādhisaṃvattanikehi.**Furthermore, a noble disciple’s ethical conduct is loved by the noble ones, unbroken, impeccable, spotless, and unmarred, liberating, praised by sensible people, not mistaken, and leading to immersion.*";
P_HTM[8066]="*Idaṃ catutthaṃ devānaṃ devapadaṃ avisuddhānaṃ sattānaṃ visuddhiyā apariyodātānaṃ sattānaṃ pariyodapanāya.**This is the fourth footprint of the gods in order to purify unpurified beings and cleanse unclean beings.*";
P_HTM[8067]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, cattāri devānaṃ devapadāni avisuddhānaṃ sattānaṃ visuddhiyā apariyodātānaṃ sattānaṃ pariyodapanāyā”ti.**These four footprints of the gods are in order to purify unpurified beings and cleanse unclean beings.”*";
P_HTM[8068]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8069]="*7. Nandiyasuttaṃ**Footprints of the Gods (2nd)*";
P_HTM[8070]="*“Cattārimāni, bhikkhave, devānaṃ devapadāni avisuddhānaṃ sattānaṃ visuddhiyā apariyodātānaṃ sattānaṃ pariyodapanāya.**“Mendicants, these four footprints of the gods are in order to purify unpurified beings and cleanse unclean beings.*";
P_HTM[8071]="*Katamāni cattāri?**What four?*";
P_HTM[8072]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako buddhe aveccappasādena samannāgato hoti—**Firstly, a noble disciple has experiential confidence in the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[8073]="*itipi so bhagavā … pe … satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavāti.**‘That Blessed One is perfected, a fully awakened Buddha, accomplished in knowledge and conduct, holy, knower of the world, supreme guide for those who wish to train, teacher of gods and humans, awakened, blessed.’*";
P_HTM[8074]="*So iti paṭisañcikkhati:**Then they reflect:*";
P_HTM[8075]="*‘kiṃ nu kho devānaṃ devapadan’ti?**‘What now is the footprint of the gods?’*";
P_HTM[8076]="*So evaṃ pajānāti:**They understand:*";
P_HTM[8077]="*‘abyābajjhaparame khvāhaṃ etarahi deve suṇāmi.**‘I hear that these days the gods consider non-harming to be supreme.*";
P_HTM[8078]="*Na ca kho panāhaṃ kiñci byābādhemi tasaṃ vā thāvaraṃ vā.**But I don’t hurt any creature firm or frail.*";
P_HTM[8079]="*Addhāhaṃ devapadadhammasamannāgato viharāmī’ti.**I definitely live in possession of a footprint of the gods.’*";
P_HTM[8080]="*Idaṃ paṭhamaṃ devānaṃ devapadaṃ avisuddhānaṃ sattānaṃ visuddhiyā apariyodātānaṃ sattānaṃ pariyodapanāya.**This is the first footprint of the gods in order to purify unpurified beings and cleanse unclean beings.*";
P_HTM[8081]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako dhamme … pe …**Furthermore, a noble disciple has experiential confidence in the teaching …*";
P_HTM[8082]="*saṅghe … pe ….**the Saṅgha …*";
P_HTM[8083]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako ariyakantehi sīlehi samannāgato hoti akhaṇḍehi … pe … samādhisaṃvattanikehi.**Furthermore, a noble disciple’s ethical conduct is loved by the noble ones, unbroken, impeccable, spotless, and unmarred, liberating, praised by sensible people, not mistaken, and leading to immersion.*";
P_HTM[8084]="*So iti paṭisañcikkhati:**Then they reflect:*";
P_HTM[8085]="*‘kiṃ nu kho devānaṃ devapadan’ti?**‘What now is the footprint of the gods?’*";
P_HTM[8086]="*So evaṃ pajānāti:**They understand:*";
P_HTM[8087]="*‘abyābajjhaparame khvāhaṃ etarahi deve suṇāmi.**‘I hear that these days the gods consider non-harming to be supreme.*";
P_HTM[8088]="*Na kho panāhaṃ kiñci byābādhemi tasaṃ vā thāvaraṃ vā.**But I don’t hurt any creature firm or frail.*";
P_HTM[8089]="*Addhāhaṃ devapadadhammasamannāgato viharāmī’ti.**I definitely live in possession of a footprint of the gods.’*";
P_HTM[8090]="*Idaṃ catutthaṃ devānaṃ devapadaṃ avisuddhānaṃ sattānaṃ visuddhiyā apariyodātānaṃ sattānaṃ pariyodapanāya.**This is the fourth footprint of the gods in order to purify unpurified beings and cleanse unclean beings.*";
P_HTM[8091]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, cattāri devānaṃ devapadāni avisuddhānaṃ sattānaṃ visuddhiyā apariyodātānaṃ sattānaṃ pariyodapanāyā”ti.**These four footprints of the gods are in order to purify unpurified beings and cleanse unclean beings.”*";
P_HTM[8092]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8093]="*8. Bhaddiyasuttaṃ**In Common With the Gods*";
P_HTM[8094]="*“Catūhi, bhikkhave, dhammehi samannāgataṃ attamanā devā sabhāgataṃ kathenti.**“Mendicants, when someone has four things the gods are pleased and speak of what they have in common.*";
P_HTM[8095]="*Katamehi catūhi?**What four?*";
P_HTM[8096]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako buddhe aveccappasādena samannāgato hoti—**Firstly, a noble disciple has experiential confidence in the Buddha …*";
P_HTM[8097]="*itipi so bhagavā … pe … satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavāti.* **";
P_HTM[8098]="*Yā tā devatā buddhe aveccappasādena samannāgatā ito cutā tatrūpapannā tāsaṃ evaṃ hoti:**There are deities with experiential confidence in the Buddha who passed away from here and were reborn there. They think:*";
P_HTM[8099]="*‘yathārūpena kho mayaṃ buddhe aveccappasādena samannāgatā tato cutā idhūpapannā, ariyasāvakopi tathārūpena buddhe aveccappasādena samannāgato ehīti devānaṃ santike’ti.**‘Having such experiential confidence in the Buddha, we passed away from there and were reborn here. That noble disciple has the same kind of experiential confidence in the Buddha, so they will come into the presence of the gods.’*";
P_HTM[8100]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako dhamme … pe …**Furthermore, a noble disciple has experiential confidence in the teaching …*";
P_HTM[8101]="*saṅghe … pe …**the Saṅgha …*";
P_HTM[8102]="*ariyakantehi sīlehi samannāgato hoti akhaṇḍehi … pe … samādhisaṃvattanikehi.**And they have the ethical conduct loved by the noble ones … leading to immersion.*";
P_HTM[8103]="*Yā tā devatā ariyakantehi sīlehi samannāgatā ito cutā tatrūpapannā tāsaṃ evaṃ hoti:**There are deities with the ethical conduct loved by the noble ones who passed away from here and were reborn there. They think:*";
P_HTM[8104]="*‘yathārūpehi kho mayaṃ ariyakantehi sīlehi samannāgatā tato cutā idhūpapannā, ariyasāvakopi tathārūpehi ariyakantehi sīlehi samannāgato ehīti devānaṃ santike’ti.**‘Having such ethical conduct loved by the noble ones, we passed away from there and were reborn here. That noble disciple has the same kind of ethical conduct loved by the noble ones, so they will come into the presence of the gods.’*";
P_HTM[8105]="*Imehi kho, bhikkhave, catūhi dhammehi samannāgataṃ attamanā devā sabhāgataṃ kathentī”ti.**When someone has four things the gods are pleased and speak of what they have in common.”*";
P_HTM[8106]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8107]="*9. Mahānāmasuttaṃ**With Mahānāma*";
P_HTM[8108]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sakkesu viharati kapilavatthusmiṃ nigrodhārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying in the land of the Sakyans, near Kapilavatthu in the Banyan Tree Monastery.*";
P_HTM[8109]="*Atha kho mahānāmo sakko yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho mahānāmo sakko bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Mahānāma the Sakyan went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him:*";
P_HTM[8110]="*“Kittāvatā nu kho, bhante, upāsako hotī”ti?**“Sir, how is a lay follower defined?”*";
P_HTM[8111]="*“Yato kho, mahānāma, buddhaṃ saraṇaṃ gato hoti, dhammaṃ saraṇaṃ gato hoti, saṅghaṃ saraṇaṃ gato hoti—**“Mahānāma, when you’ve gone for refuge to the Buddha, the teaching, and the Saṅgha,*";
P_HTM[8112]="*ettāvatā kho, mahānāma, upāsako hotī”ti.**you’re considered to be a lay follower.”*";
P_HTM[8113]="*“Kittāvatā pana, bhante, upāsako sīlasampanno hotī”ti?**“But how is an ethical lay follower defined?”*";
P_HTM[8114]="*“Yato kho, mahānāma, upāsako pāṇātipātā paṭivirato hoti, adinnādānā paṭivirato hoti, kāmesumicchācārā paṭivirato hoti, musāvādā paṭivirato hoti, surāmerayamajjappamādaṭṭhānā paṭivirato hoti—**“When a lay follower doesn’t kill living creatures, steal, commit sexual misconduct, lie, or consume alcoholic drinks that cause negligence,*";
P_HTM[8115]="*ettāvatā kho, mahānāma, upāsako sīlasampanno hotī”ti.**they’re considered to be an ethical lay follower.”*";
P_HTM[8116]="*“Kittāvatā pana, bhante, upāsako saddhāsampanno hotī”ti?**“But how is a faithful lay follower defined?”*";
P_HTM[8117]="*“Idha, mahānāma, upāsako saddho hoti, saddahati tathāgatassa bodhiṃ—**“It’s when a lay follower has faith in the Realized One’s awakening:*";
P_HTM[8118]="*itipi so bhagavā … pe … satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavāti.**‘That Blessed One is perfected, a fully awakened Buddha, accomplished in knowledge and conduct, holy, knower of the world, supreme guide for those who wish to train, teacher of gods and humans, awakened, blessed.’*";
P_HTM[8119]="*Ettāvatā kho, mahānāma, upāsako saddhāsampanno hotī”ti.**Then they’re considered to be a faithful lay follower.”*";
P_HTM[8120]="*“Kittāvatā pana, bhante, upāsako cāgasampanno hotī”ti?**“But how is a generous lay follower defined?”*";
P_HTM[8121]="*“Idha, mahānāma, upāsako vigatamalamaccherena cetasā agāraṃ ajjhāvasati muttacāgo payatapāṇi vossaggarato yācayogo dānasaṃvibhāgarato—**“It’s when a lay follower lives at home rid of the stain of stinginess, freely generous, open-handed, loving to let go, committed to charity, loving to give and to share.*";
P_HTM[8122]="*ettāvatā kho, mahānāma, upāsako cāgasampanno hotī”ti.**Then they’re considered to be a generous lay follower.”*";
P_HTM[8123]="*“Kittāvatā pana, bhante, upāsako paññāsampanno hotī”ti?**“But how is a wise lay follower defined?”*";
P_HTM[8124]="*“Idha, mahānāma, upāsako paññavā hoti udayatthagāminiyā paññāya samannāgato ariyāya nibbedhikāya sammā dukkhakkhayagāminiyā—**“It’s when a lay follower is wise. They have the wisdom of arising and passing away which is noble, penetrative, and leads to the complete ending of suffering.*";
P_HTM[8125]="*ettāvatā kho, mahānāma, upāsako paññāsampanno hotī”ti.**Then they’re considered to be a wise lay follower.”*";
P_HTM[8126]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8127]="*10. Aṅgasuttaṃ**Rain*";
P_HTM[8128]="*“Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, uparipabbate thullaphusitake deve vassante taṃ udakaṃ yathāninnaṃ pavattamānaṃ pabbatakandarapadarasākhā paripūreti, pabbatakandarapadarasākhā paripūrā kusobbhe paripūrenti, kusobbhā paripūrā mahāsobbhe paripūrenti, mahāsobbhā paripūrā kunnadiyo paripūrenti, kunnadiyo paripūrā mahānadiyo paripūrenti, mahānadiyo paripūrā mahāsamuddaṃ paripūrenti;**“Mendicants, suppose it rains heavily on a mountain top, and the water flows downhill to fill the hollows, crevices, and creeks. As they become full, they fill up the pools. The pools fill up the lakes, the lakes fill up the streams, and the streams fill up the rivers. And as the rivers become full, they fill up the ocean.*";
P_HTM[8129]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, ariyasāvakassa yo ca buddhe aveccappasādo, yo ca dhamme aveccappasādo, yo ca saṃghe aveccappasādo, yāni ca ariyakantāni sīlāni—**In the same way, a noble disciple has experiential confidence in the Buddha, the teaching, and the Saṅgha, and the ethics loved by the noble ones.*";
P_HTM[8130]="*ime dhammā sandamānā pāraṃ gantvā āsavānaṃ khayāya saṃvattantī”ti.**These things flow onwards; and, after crossing to the far shore, they lead to the ending of defilements.”*";
P_HTM[8131]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8132]="*2. Dhammacakkappavattanavaggo**Overflowing Merit*";
P_HTM[8133]="*1. Sagāthakasuttaṃ**With Kāḷigodhā*";
P_HTM[8134]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sakkesu viharati kapilavatthusmiṃ nigrodhārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying in the land of the Sakyans, near Kapilavatthu in the Banyan Tree Monastery.*";
P_HTM[8135]="*Atha kho bhagavā pubbaṇhasamayaṃ nivāsetvā pattacīvaramādāya yena kāḷigodhāya sākiyāniyā nivesanaṃ tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā paññatte āsane nisīdi.**Then the Buddha robed up in the morning and, taking his bowl and robe, went to the home of Kāḷigodhā the Sakyan lady, where he sat on the seat spread out.*";
P_HTM[8136]="*Atha kho kāḷigodhā sākiyānī yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinnaṃ kho kāḷigodhaṃ sākiyāniṃ bhagavā etadavoca:**Then Kāḷigodhā went up to the Buddha, bowed, and sat down to one side. The Buddha said to her:*";
P_HTM[8137]="*“Catūhi kho, godhe, dhammehi samannāgatā ariyasāvikā sotāpannā hoti avinipātadhammā niyatā sambodhiparāyaṇā.**“Godhā, a female noble disciple who has four things is a stream-enterer, not liable to be reborn in the underworld, bound for awakening.*";
P_HTM[8138]="*Katamehi catūhi?**What four?*";
P_HTM[8139]="*Idha, godhe, ariyasāvikā buddhe aveccappasādena samannāgatā hoti—**It’s when a noble disciple has experiential confidence in the Buddha …*";
P_HTM[8140]="*itipi so bhagavā … pe … satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavāti.* **";
P_HTM[8141]="*Dhamme … pe …**the teaching …*";
P_HTM[8142]="*saṃghe … pe …**the Saṅgha …*";
P_HTM[8143]="*vigatamalamaccherena cetasā agāraṃ ajjhāvasati muttacāgā payatapāṇinī vossaggaratā yācayogā dānasaṃvibhāgaratā.**And they live at home rid of the stain of stinginess, freely generous, open-handed, loving to let go, committed to charity, loving to give and to share.*";
P_HTM[8144]="*Imehi kho, godhe, catūhi dhammehi samannāgatā ariyasāvikā sotāpannā hoti avinipātadhammā niyatā sambodhiparāyaṇā”ti.**A female noble disciple who has these four things is a stream-enterer, not liable to be reborn in the underworld, bound for awakening.”*";
P_HTM[8145]="*“Yānimāni, bhante, bhagavatā cattāri sotāpattiyaṅgāni desitāni, saṃvijjante dhammā mayi, ahañca tesu dhammesu sandissāmi.**“Sir, these four factors of stream-entry that were taught by the Buddha are found in me, and I am seen in them.*";
P_HTM[8146]="*Ahañhi, bhante, buddhe aveccappasādena samannāgatā—**For I have experiential confidence in the Buddha …*";
P_HTM[8147]="*itipi so bhagavā … pe … satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavāti.* **";
P_HTM[8148]="*Dhamme … pe …**the teaching …*";
P_HTM[8149]="*saṅghe … pe …**the Saṅgha …*";
P_HTM[8150]="*yaṃ kho pana kiñci kule deyyadhammaṃ sabbaṃ taṃ appaṭivibhattaṃ sīlavantehi kalyāṇadhammehī”ti.**And I share without reservation all the gifts available to give in our family with those who are ethical and of good character.”*";
P_HTM[8151]="*“Lābhā te, godhe, suladdhaṃ te, godhe.**“You’re fortunate, Godhā, so very fortunate,*";
P_HTM[8152]="*Sotāpattiphalaṃ tayā, godhe, byākatan”ti.**You have declared the fruit of stream-entry.”*";
P_HTM[8153]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8154]="*2. Vassaṃvutthasuttaṃ**Nandiya the Sakyan*";
P_HTM[8155]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sakkesu viharati kapilavatthusmiṃ nigrodhārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying in the land of the Sakyans, near Kapilavatthu in the Banyan Tree Monastery.*";
P_HTM[8156]="*Atha kho nandiyo sakko yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho nandiyo sakko bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Nandiya the Sakyan went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him:*";
P_HTM[8157]="*“yasseva nu kho, bhante, ariyasāvakassa cattāri sotāpattiyaṅgāni sabbena sabbaṃ sabbathā sabbaṃ natthi sveva nu kho, bhante, ariyasāvako pamādavihārī”ti.**“Sir, if a noble disciple were to totally and utterly lack the four factors of stream-entry, would they live negligently?”*";
P_HTM[8158]="*“‘Yassa kho, nandiya, cattāri sotāpattiyaṅgāni sabbena sabbaṃ sabbathā sabbaṃ natthi tamahaṃ bāhiro puthujjanapakkhe ṭhito’ti vadāmi.**“Nandiya, someone who totally and utterly lacks these four factors of stream-entry is an outsider who belongs with the ordinary persons, I say.*";
P_HTM[8159]="*Api ca, nandiya, yathā ariyasāvako pamādavihārī ceva hoti, appamādavihārī ca**Neverthless, Nandiya, as to how a noble disciple lives negligently and how they live diligently,*";
P_HTM[8160]="*taṃ suṇāhi, sādhukaṃ manasi karohi; bhāsissāmī”ti.**listen and attend closely, I will speak.*";
P_HTM[8161]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho nandiyo sakko bhagavato paccassosi.**“Yes, sir,” Nandiya replied.*";
P_HTM[8162]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[8163]="*“Kathañca, nandiya, ariyasāvako pamādavihārī hoti?**“And how does a noble disciple live negligently?*";
P_HTM[8164]="*Idha, nandiya, ariyasāvako buddhe aveccappasādena samannāgato hoti—**Firstly, a noble disciple has experiential confidence in the Buddha …*";
P_HTM[8165]="*itipi so bhagavā … pe … satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavāti.* **";
P_HTM[8166]="*So tena buddhe aveccappasādena santuṭṭho na uttari vāyamati divā pavivekāya, rattiṃ paṭisallānāya.**They’re content with that confidence, and don’t make a further effort for solitude by day or retreat by night.*";
P_HTM[8167]="*Tassa evaṃ pamattassa viharato pāmojjaṃ na hoti.**When they live negligently, there’s no joy.*";
P_HTM[8168]="*Pāmojje asati, pīti na hoti.**When there’s no joy, there’s no rapture.*";
P_HTM[8169]="*Pītiyā asati, passaddhi na hoti.**When there’s no rapture, there’s no tranquility.*";
P_HTM[8170]="*Passaddhiyā asati, dukkhaṃ viharati.**When there’s no tranquility, there’s suffering.*";
P_HTM[8171]="*Dukkhino cittaṃ na samādhiyati.**When one is suffering, the mind does not become immersed in samādhi.*";
P_HTM[8172]="*Asamāhite citte dhammā na pātubhavanti.**When the mind is not immersed in samādhi, principles do not become clear.*";
P_HTM[8173]="*Dhammānaṃ apātubhāvā pamādavihārītveva saṅkhyaṃ gacchati.**Because principles have not become clear, they’re reckoned to live negligently.*";
P_HTM[8174]="*Puna caparaṃ, nandiya, ariyasāvako dhamme … pe …**Furthermore, a noble disciple has experiential confidence in the teaching …*";
P_HTM[8175]="*saṅghe … pe …**the Saṅgha …*";
P_HTM[8176]="*ariyakantehi sīlehi samannāgato hoti akhaṇḍehi … pe … samādhisaṃvattanikehi.**And they have the ethical conduct loved by the noble ones … leading to immersion.*";
P_HTM[8177]="*So tehi ariyakantehi sīlehi santuṭṭho na uttari vāyamati divā pavivekāya rattiṃ paṭisallānāya.**They’re content with that ethical conduct loved by the noble ones, and don’t make a further effort for solitude by day or retreat by night.*";
P_HTM[8178]="*Tassa evaṃ pamattassa viharato pāmojjaṃ na hoti.**When they live negligently, there’s no joy.*";
P_HTM[8179]="*Pāmojje asati, pīti na hoti.**When there’s no joy, there’s no rapture.*";
P_HTM[8180]="*Pītiyā asati, passaddhi na hoti.**When there’s no rapture, there’s no tranquility.*";
P_HTM[8181]="*Passaddhiyā asati, dukkhaṃ viharati.**When there’s no tranquility, there’s suffering.*";
P_HTM[8182]="*Dukkhino cittaṃ na samādhiyati.**When one is suffering, the mind does not become immersed in samādhi.*";
P_HTM[8183]="*Asamāhite citte dhammā na pātubhavanti.**When the mind is not immersed in samādhi, principles do not become clear.*";
P_HTM[8184]="*Dhammānaṃ apātubhāvā pamādavihārītveva saṅkhyaṃ gacchati.**Because principles have not become clear, they’re reckoned to live negligently.*";
P_HTM[8185]="*Evaṃ kho, nandiya, ariyasāvako pamādavihārī hoti.**That’s how a noble disciple lives negligently.*";
P_HTM[8186]="*Kathañca, nandiya, ariyasāvako appamādavihārī hoti?**And how does a noble disciple live diligently?*";
P_HTM[8187]="*Idha, nandiya, ariyasāvako buddhe aveccappasādena samannāgato hoti—**Firstly, a noble disciple has experiential confidence in the Buddha …*";
P_HTM[8188]="*itipi so bhagavā … pe … satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavāti.* **";
P_HTM[8189]="*So tena buddhe aveccappasādena asantuṭṭho uttari vāyamati divā pavivekāya rattiṃ paṭisallānāya.**But they’re not content with that confidence, and make a further effort for solitude by day and retreat by night.*";
P_HTM[8190]="*Tassa evaṃ appamattassa viharato pāmojjaṃ jāyati.**When they live diligently, joy springs up.*";
P_HTM[8191]="*Pamuditassa pīti jāyati.**Being joyful, rapture springs up.*";
P_HTM[8192]="*Pītimanassa kāyo passambhati.**When the mind is full of rapture, the body becomes tranquil.*";
P_HTM[8193]="*Passaddhakāyo sukhaṃ vediyati.**When the body is tranquil, they feel bliss.*";
P_HTM[8194]="*Sukhino cittaṃ samādhiyati.**And when blissful, the mind becomes immersed in samādhi.*";
P_HTM[8195]="*Samāhite citte dhammā pātubhavanti.**When the mind is immersed in samādhi, principles become clear.*";
P_HTM[8196]="*Dhammānaṃ pātubhāvā appamādavihārītveva saṅkhyaṃ gacchati.**Because principles have become clear, they’re reckoned to live diligently.*";
P_HTM[8197]="*Puna caparaṃ, nandiya, ariyasāvako dhamme … pe …**Furthermore, a noble disciple has experiential confidence in the teaching …*";
P_HTM[8198]="*saṅghe … pe …**the Saṅgha …*";
P_HTM[8199]="*ariyakantehi sīlehi samannāgato hoti akhaṇḍehi … pe … samādhisaṃvattanikehi.**And they have the ethical conduct loved by the noble ones … leading to immersion.*";
P_HTM[8200]="*So tehi ariyakantehi sīlehi asantuṭṭho uttari vāyamati divā pavivekāya rattiṃ paṭisallānāya.**But they’re not content with that ethical conduct loved by the noble ones, and make a further effort for solitude by day and retreat by night.*";
P_HTM[8201]="*Tassa evaṃ appamattassa viharato pāmojjaṃ jāyati.**When they live diligently, joy springs up.*";
P_HTM[8202]="*Pamuditassa pīti jāyati.**Being joyful, rapture springs up.*";
P_HTM[8203]="*Pītimanassa kāyo passambhati.**When the mind is full of rapture, the body becomes tranquil.*";
P_HTM[8204]="*Passaddhakāyo sukhaṃ vediyati.**When the body is tranquil, they feel bliss.*";
P_HTM[8205]="*Sukhino cittaṃ samādhiyati.**And when blissful, the mind becomes immersed in samādhi.*";
P_HTM[8206]="*Samāhite citte dhammā pātubhavanti.**When the mind is immersed in samādhi, principles become clear.*";
P_HTM[8207]="*Dhammānaṃ pātubhāvā appamādavihārītveva saṅkhyaṃ gacchati.**Because principles have become clear, they’re reckoned to live diligently.*";
P_HTM[8208]="*Evaṃ kho, nandiya, ariyasāvako appamādavihārī hotī”ti.**That’s how a noble disciple lives diligently.”*";
P_HTM[8209]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8210]="*Puññābhisandavaggo catuttho.* **";
P_HTM[8211]="*Abhisandā tayo vuttā,* **";
P_HTM[8212]="*duve devapadāni ca;* **";
P_HTM[8213]="*Sabhāgataṃ mahānāmo,* **";
P_HTM[8214]="*vassaṃ kāḷī ca nandiyāti.* **";
P_HTM[8215]="*3. Dhammadinnasuttaṃ**Overflowing Merit (1st)*";
P_HTM[8216]="*“Cattārome, bhikkhave, puññābhisandā, kusalābhisandā, sukhassāhārā.**“Mendicants, there are these four kinds of overflowing merit, overflowing goodness that nurture happiness.*";
P_HTM[8217]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[8218]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako buddhe aveccappasādena samannāgato hoti—**It’s when a noble disciple has experiential confidence in the Buddha …*";
P_HTM[8219]="*itipi so bhagavā … pe … satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavāti.* **";
P_HTM[8220]="*Ayaṃ paṭhamo puññābhisando, kusalābhisando, sukhassāhāro.* **";
P_HTM[8221]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako dhamme … pe …**the teaching …*";
P_HTM[8222]="*saṅghe … pe ….**the Saṅgha …*";
P_HTM[8223]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako ariyakantehi sīlehi samannāgato hoti akhaṇḍehi … pe … samādhisaṃvattanikehi.**Furthermore, they have the ethical conduct loved by the noble ones … leading to immersion. …*";
P_HTM[8224]="*Ayaṃ catuttho puññābhisando, kusalābhisando, sukhassāhāro.* **";
P_HTM[8225]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, cattāro puññābhisandā, kusalābhisandā, sukhassāhārā.**These are the four kinds of overflowing merit, overflowing goodness that nurture happiness.*";
P_HTM[8226]="*Imehi kho, bhikkhave, catūhi puññābhisandehi kusalābhisandehi samannāgatassa ariyasāvakassa na sukaraṃ puññassa pamāṇaṃ gaṇetuṃ:**When a noble disciple has these four kinds of overflowing merit and goodness, it’s not easy to measure how much merit they have by saying that*";
P_HTM[8227]="*‘ettako puññābhisando, kusalābhisando, sukhassāhāro’ti.**this is the extent of their overflowing merit, overflowing goodness that nurtures happiness.*";
P_HTM[8228]="*Atha kho asaṅkhyeyyo appameyyo mahāpuññakkhandhotveva saṅkhyaṃ gacchati.**It’s simply reckoned as an incalculable, immeasurable, great mass of merit.*";
P_HTM[8229]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, mahāsamudde na sukaraṃ udakassa pamāṇaṃ gaṇetuṃ:**It’s like trying to measure how much water is in the ocean. It’s not easy to say*";
P_HTM[8230]="*‘ettakāni udakāḷhakānī’ti vā ‘ettakāni udakāḷhakasatānī’ti vā ‘ettakāni udakāḷhakasahassānī’ti vā ‘ettakāni udakāḷhakasatasahassānī’ti vāti.**how many gallons, how many hundreds, thousands, hundreds of thousands of gallons there are.*";
P_HTM[8231]="*Atha kho asaṅkhyeyyo appameyyo mahāudakakkhandhotveva saṅkhyaṃ gacchati.**It’s simply reckoned as an incalculable, immeasurable, great mass of water.*";
P_HTM[8232]="*Evameva kho, bhikkhave, imehi catūhi puññābhisandehi kusalābhisandehi samannāgatassa ariyasāvakassa na sukaraṃ puññassa pamāṇaṃ gaṇetuṃ:**In the same way, when a noble disciple has these four kinds of overflowing merit and goodness, it’s not easy to measure how much merit they have by saying that*";
P_HTM[8233]="*‘ettako puññābhisando, kusalābhisando, sukhassāhāro’ti.**this is the extent of their overflowing merit, overflowing goodness that nurtures happiness.*";
P_HTM[8234]="*Atha kho asaṅkhyeyyo appameyyo mahāpuññakkhandhotveva saṅkhyaṃ gacchatī”ti.**It’s simply reckoned as an incalculable, immeasurable, great mass of merit.”*";
P_HTM[8235]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[8236]="*Idaṃ vatvāna sugato athāparaṃ etadavoca satthā:**Then the Holy One, the Teacher, went on to say:*";
P_HTM[8237]="*“Mahodadhiṃ aparimitaṃ mahāsaraṃ,**“Hosts of people use the rivers,*";
P_HTM[8238]="*Bahubheravaṃ ratanagaṇānamālayaṃ;**and though the rivers are many,*";
P_HTM[8239]="*Najjo yathā naragaṇasaṅghasevitā,**all reach the great deep, the boundless ocean,*";
P_HTM[8240]="*Puthū savantī upayanti sāgaraṃ.**the cruel sea that’s home to precious gems.*";
P_HTM[8241]="*Evaṃ naraṃ annapānavatthadadaṃ,**So too, when a person gives food, drink, and clothes;*";
P_HTM[8242]="*Seyyāni paccattharaṇassa dāyakaṃ;**and they’re a giver of beds, seats, and mats—*";
P_HTM[8243]="*Puññassa dhārā upayanti paṇḍitaṃ,**the streams of merit reach that astute person,*";
P_HTM[8244]="*Najjo yathā vārivahāva sāgaran”ti.**as the rivers bring their waters to the sea.”*";
P_HTM[8245]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8246]="*4. Gilānasuttaṃ**Overflowing Merit (2nd)*";
P_HTM[8247]="*“Cattārome, bhikkhave, puññābhisandā, kusalābhisandā, sukhassāhārā.**“Mendicants, there are these four kinds of overflowing merit, overflowing goodness that nurture happiness.*";
P_HTM[8248]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[8249]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako buddhe aveccappasādena samannāgato hoti—**It’s when a noble disciple has experiential confidence in the Buddha …*";
P_HTM[8250]="*itipi so bhagavā … pe … satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavāti.* **";
P_HTM[8251]="*Ayaṃ paṭhamo puññābhisando kusalābhisando sukhassāhāro.* **";
P_HTM[8252]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako dhamme … pe …**the teaching …*";
P_HTM[8253]="*saṅghe … pe ….**the Saṅgha …*";
P_HTM[8254]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako vigatamalamaccherena cetasā agāraṃ ajjhāvasati muttacāgo payatapāṇi vossaggarato yācayogo dānasaṃvibhāgarato.**Furthermore, a noble disciple lives at home rid of the stain of stinginess, freely generous, open-handed, loving to let go, committed to charity, loving to give and to share.*";
P_HTM[8255]="*Ayaṃ catuttho puññābhisando kusalābhisando sukhassāhāro.**This is the fourth kind of overflowing merit, overflowing goodness that nurtures happiness.*";
P_HTM[8256]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, cattāro puññābhisandā, kusalābhisandā, sukhassāhārā.**These are the four kinds of overflowing merit, overflowing goodness that nurture happiness.*";
P_HTM[8257]="*Imehi kho, bhikkhave, catūhi puññābhisandehi kusalābhisandehi samannāgatassa ariyasāvakassa na sukaraṃ puññassa pamāṇaṃ gaṇetuṃ:**When a noble disciple has these four kinds of overflowing merit and goodness, it’s not easy to measure how much merit they have by saying that*";
P_HTM[8258]="*‘ettako puññābhisando, kusalābhisando, sukhassāhāro’ti.**this is the extent of their overflowing merit, overflowing goodness that nurtures happiness.*";
P_HTM[8259]="*Atha kho asaṅkhyeyyo appameyyo mahāpuññakkhandhotveva saṅkhyaṃ gacchati.**It’s simply reckoned as an incalculable, immeasurable, great mass of merit.*";
P_HTM[8260]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, yatthimā mahānadiyo saṃsandanti samenti, seyyathidaṃ—**There are places where the great rivers—the Ganges, Yamuna, Aciravatī, Sarabhū, and Mahī—come together and converge.*";
P_HTM[8261]="*gaṅgā, yamunā, aciravatī, sarabhū, mahī, tattha na sukaraṃ udakassa pamāṇaṃ gaṇetuṃ:**It’s not easy measure how much water is in such places by saying*";
P_HTM[8262]="*‘ettakāni udakāḷhakānī’ti vā ‘ettakāni udakāḷhakasatānī’ti vā ‘ettakāni udakāḷhakasahassānī’ti vā ‘ettakāni udakāḷhakasatasahassānī’ti vāti.**how many gallons, how many hundreds, thousands, hundreds of thousands of gallons there are.*";
P_HTM[8263]="*Atha kho asaṅkhyeyyo appameyyo mahāudakakkhandhotveva saṅkhyaṃ gacchati.**It’s simply reckoned as an incalculable, immeasurable, great mass of water.*";
P_HTM[8264]="*Evameva kho, bhikkhave, imehi catūhi puññābhisandehi kusalābhisandehi samannāgatassa ariyasāvakassa na sukaraṃ puññassa pamāṇaṃ gaṇetuṃ:**In the same way, when a noble disciple has these four kinds of overflowing merit and goodness, it’s not easy to measure how much merit they have by saying that*";
P_HTM[8265]="*‘ettako puññābhisando, kusalābhisando, sukhassāhāro’ti.**this is the extent of their overflowing merit, overflowing goodness that nurtures happiness.*";
P_HTM[8266]="*Atha kho asaṅkhyeyyo appameyyo mahāpuññakkhandhotveva saṅkhyaṃ gacchatī”ti.**It’s simply reckoned as an incalculable, immeasurable, great mass of merit.”*";
P_HTM[8267]="*Idamavoca bhagavā … pe …**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[8268]="*satthā:**Then the Holy One, the Teacher, went on to say:*";
P_HTM[8269]="*“Mahodadhiṃ aparimitaṃ mahāsaraṃ,**“Hosts of people use the rivers,*";
P_HTM[8270]="*Bahubheravaṃ ratanagaṇānamālayaṃ;**and though the rivers are many,*";
P_HTM[8271]="*Najjo yathā naragaṇasaṅghasevitā,**all reach the great deep, the boundless ocean,*";
P_HTM[8272]="*Puthū savantī upayanti sāgaraṃ.**the cruel sea that’s home to precious gems.*";
P_HTM[8273]="*Evaṃ naraṃ annapānavatthadadaṃ,**So too, when a person gives food, drink, and clothes;*";
P_HTM[8274]="*Seyyāni paccattharaṇassa dāyakaṃ;**and they’re a giver of beds, seats, and mats—*";
P_HTM[8275]="*Puññassa dhārā upayanti paṇḍitaṃ,**the streams of merit reach that astute person,*";
P_HTM[8276]="*Najjo yathā vārivahāva sāgaran”ti.**as the rivers bring their waters to the sea.”*";
P_HTM[8277]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8278]="*5. Sotāpattiphalasuttaṃ**Overflowing Merit (3rd)*";
P_HTM[8279]="*“Cattārome, bhikkhave, puññābhisandā, kusalābhisandā, sukhassāhārā.**“Mendicants, there are these four kinds of overflowing merit, overflowing goodness that nurture happiness.*";
P_HTM[8280]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[8281]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako buddhe aveccappasādena samannāgato hoti—**It’s when a noble disciple has experiential confidence in the Buddha …*";
P_HTM[8282]="*itipi so bhagavā … pe … satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavāti.* **";
P_HTM[8283]="*Ayaṃ paṭhamo puññābhisando, kusalābhisando, sukhassāhāro.* **";
P_HTM[8284]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako dhamme … pe …**the teaching …*";
P_HTM[8285]="*saṅghe … pe ….**the Saṅgha …*";
P_HTM[8286]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako paññavā hoti udayatthagāminiyā paññāya samannāgato ariyāya nibbedhikāya sammā dukkhakkhayagāminiyā.**Furthermore, a noble disciple is wise. They have the wisdom of arising and passing away which is noble, penetrative, and leads to the complete ending of suffering.*";
P_HTM[8287]="*Ayaṃ catuttho puññābhisando kusalābhisando sukhassāhāro.**This is the fourth kind of overflowing merit, overflowing goodness that nurtures happiness.*";
P_HTM[8288]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, cattāro puññābhisandā kusalābhisandā sukhassāhārā.**These are the four kinds of overflowing merit, overflowing goodness that nurture happiness.*";
P_HTM[8289]="*Imehi kho, bhikkhave, catūhi puññābhisandehi kusalābhisandehi samannāgatassa ariyasāvakassa na sukaraṃ puññassa pamāṇaṃ gaṇetuṃ:**When a noble disciple has these four kinds of overflowing merit and goodness, it’s not easy to measure how much merit they have by saying that*";
P_HTM[8290]="*‘ettako puññābhisando, kusalābhisando, sukhassāhāro’ti.**this is the extent of their overflowing merit, overflowing goodness that nurtures happiness.*";
P_HTM[8291]="*Atha kho asaṅkhyeyyo appameyyo mahāpuññakkhandhotveva saṅkhyaṃ gacchatī”ti.**It’s simply reckoned as an incalculable, immeasurable, great mass of merit.”*";
P_HTM[8292]="*Idamavoca bhagavā … pe …**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[8293]="*satthā:**Then the Holy One, the Teacher, went on to say:*";
P_HTM[8294]="*“Yo puññakāmo kusale patiṭṭhito,**“One who desires merit, grounded in the skillful,*";
P_HTM[8295]="*Bhāveti maggaṃ amatassa pattiyā;**develops the eightfold path for realizing the deathless.*";
P_HTM[8296]="*So dhammasārādhigamo khaye rato,**Once they’ve reached the heart of the teaching, delighting in ending,*";
P_HTM[8297]="*Na vedhati maccurājāgamanasmin”ti.**they don’t tremble at the approach of the King of Death.”*";
P_HTM[8298]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8299]="*6. Sakadāgāmiphalasuttaṃ**Rich (1st)*";
P_HTM[8300]="*“Catūhi, bhikkhave, dhammehi samannāgato ariyasāvako ‘aḍḍho mahaddhano mahābhogo’ti vuccati.**“Mendicants, a noble disciple who has four things is said to be rich, affluent, and wealthy.*";
P_HTM[8301]="*Katamehi catūhi?**What four?*";
P_HTM[8302]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako buddhe aveccappasādena samannāgato hoti—**It’s when a noble disciple has experiential confidence in the Buddha …*";
P_HTM[8303]="*itipi so bhagavā … pe … satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavāti;* **";
P_HTM[8304]="*dhamme … pe …**the teaching …*";
P_HTM[8305]="*saṅghe … pe …**the Saṅgha …*";
P_HTM[8306]="*ariyakantehi sīlehi samannāgato hoti akhaṇḍehi … pe … samādhisaṃvattanikehi.**And they have the ethical conduct loved by the noble ones … leading to immersion.*";
P_HTM[8307]="*Imehi kho, bhikkhave, catūhi dhammehi samannāgato ariyasāvako ‘aḍḍho mahaddhano mahābhogo’ti vuccatī”ti.**A noble disciple who has these four things is said to be rich, affluent, and wealthy.”*";
P_HTM[8308]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8309]="*7. Anāgāmiphalasuttaṃ**Rich (2nd)*";
P_HTM[8310]="*“Catūhi, bhikkhave, dhammehi samannāgato ariyasāvako ‘aḍḍho mahaddhano mahābhogo mahāyaso’ti vuccati.**“Mendicants, a noble disciple who has four things is said to be rich, affluent, wealthy, and famous.*";
P_HTM[8311]="*Katamehi catūhi?**What four?*";
P_HTM[8312]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako buddhe aveccappasādena samannāgato hoti—**It’s when a noble disciple has experiential confidence in the Buddha …*";
P_HTM[8313]="*itipi so bhagavā … pe … satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavāti.* **";
P_HTM[8314]="*Dhamme … pe …**the teaching …*";
P_HTM[8315]="*saṅghe … pe …**the Saṅgha …*";
P_HTM[8316]="*ariyakantehi sīlehi samannāgato hoti akhaṇḍehi … pe … samādhisaṃvattanikehi.**And they have the ethical conduct loved by the noble ones … leading to immersion.*";
P_HTM[8317]="*Imehi kho, bhikkhave, catūhi dhammehi samannāgato ariyasāvako ‘aḍḍho mahaddhano mahābhogo mahāyaso’ti vuccatī”ti.**A noble disciple who has these four things is said to be rich, affluent, wealthy, and famous.”*";
P_HTM[8318]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8319]="*8. Arahattaphalasuttaṃ**Plain Version*";
P_HTM[8320]="*“Catūhi, bhikkhave, dhammehi samannāgato ariyasāvako sotāpanno hoti avinipātadhammo niyato sambodhiparāyaṇo.**“Mendicants, a noble disciple who has four things is a stream-enterer, not liable to be reborn in the underworld, bound for awakening.*";
P_HTM[8321]="*Katamehi catūhi?**What four?*";
P_HTM[8322]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako buddhe aveccappasādena samannāgato hoti—**It’s when a noble disciple has experiential confidence in the Buddha …*";
P_HTM[8323]="*itipi so bhagavā … pe … satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavāti.* **";
P_HTM[8324]="*Dhamme … pe …**the teaching …*";
P_HTM[8325]="*saṅghe … pe …**the Saṅgha …*";
P_HTM[8326]="*ariyakantehi sīlehi samannāgato hoti akhaṇḍehi … pe … samādhisaṃvattanikehi.**And they have the ethical conduct loved by the noble ones … leading to immersion.*";
P_HTM[8327]="*Imehi kho, bhikkhave, catūhi dhammehi samannāgato ariyasāvako sotāpanno hoti avinipātadhammo niyato sambodhiparāyaṇo”ti.**A noble disciple who has these four things is a stream-enterer, not liable to be reborn in the underworld, bound for awakening.”*";
P_HTM[8328]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8329]="*9. Paññāpaṭilābhasuttaṃ**With Nandiya*";
P_HTM[8330]="*Kapilavatthunidānaṃ.**At Kapilavatthu.*";
P_HTM[8331]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinnaṃ kho nandiyaṃ sakkaṃ bhagavā etadavoca:**Seated to one side, the Buddha said to Nandiya the Sakyan:*";
P_HTM[8332]="*“catūhi kho, nandiya, dhammehi samannāgato ariyasāvako sotāpanno hoti avinipātadhammo niyato sambodhiparāyaṇo.**“Nandiya, a noble disciple who has four things is a stream-enterer, not liable to be reborn in the underworld, bound for awakening.*";
P_HTM[8333]="*Katamehi catūhi?**What four?*";
P_HTM[8334]="*Idha, nandiya, ariyasāvako buddhe aveccappasādena samannāgato hoti—**It’s when a noble disciple has experiential confidence in the Buddha …*";
P_HTM[8335]="*itipi so bhagavā … pe … satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavāti.* **";
P_HTM[8336]="*Dhamme … pe …**the teaching …*";
P_HTM[8337]="*saṅghe … pe …**the Saṅgha …*";
P_HTM[8338]="*ariyakantehi sīlehi samannāgato hoti akhaṇḍehi … pe … samādhisaṃvattanikehi.**And they have the ethical conduct loved by the noble ones … leading to immersion.*";
P_HTM[8339]="*Imehi kho, nandiya, catūhi dhammehi samannāgato ariyasāvako sotāpanno hoti avinipātadhammo niyato sambodhiparāyaṇo”ti.**A noble disciple who has these four things is a stream-enterer, not liable to be reborn in the underworld, bound for awakening.”*";
P_HTM[8340]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8341]="*10. Paññāvuddhisuttaṃ**With Bhaddiya*";
P_HTM[8342]="*Kapilavatthunidānaṃ.**At Kapilavatthu.*";
P_HTM[8343]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinnaṃ kho bhaddiyaṃ sakkaṃ bhagavā etadavoca:**Seated to one side, the Buddha said to Bhaddiya the Sakyan:*";
P_HTM[8344]="*“catūhi kho, bhaddiya, dhammehi samannāgato ariyasāvako sotāpanno hoti avinipātadhammo niyato sambodhiparāyaṇo.**“Bhaddiya, a noble disciple who has four things is a stream-enterer …”*";
P_HTM[8345]="*Katamehi catūhi?* **";
P_HTM[8346]="*Idha, bhaddiya, ariyasāvako buddhe … pe …* **";
P_HTM[8347]="*dhamme … pe …* **";
P_HTM[8348]="*saṅghe … pe …* **";
P_HTM[8349]="*ariyakantehi sīlehi samannāgato hoti akhaṇḍehi … pe … samādhisaṃvattanikehi.* **";
P_HTM[8350]="*Imehi kho, bhaddiya, catūhi dhammehi samannāgato ariyasāvako sotāpanno hoti avinipātadhammo niyato sambodhiparāyaṇo”ti.* **";
P_HTM[8351]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8352]="*11. Paññāvepullasuttaṃ**With Mahānāma*";
P_HTM[8353]="*Kapilavatthunidānaṃ.**At Kapilavatthu.*";
P_HTM[8354]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinnaṃ kho mahānāmaṃ sakkaṃ bhagavā etadavoca:**Seated to one side, the Buddha said to Mahānāma the Sakyan:*";
P_HTM[8355]="*“catūhi kho, mahānāma, dhammehi samannāgato ariyasāvako sotāpanno hoti … pe … sambodhiparāyaṇo.**“Mahānāma, a noble disciple who has four things is a stream-enterer …”*";
P_HTM[8356]="*Katamehi catūhi?* **";
P_HTM[8357]="*Idha, mahānāma, ariyasāvako buddhe … pe …* **";
P_HTM[8358]="*dhamme … pe …* **";
P_HTM[8359]="*saṅghe … pe …* **";
P_HTM[8360]="*ariyakantehi sīlehi samannāgato hoti akhaṇḍehi … pe … samādhisaṃvattanikehi.* **";
P_HTM[8361]="*Imehi kho, mahānāma, catūhi dhammehi samannāgato ariyasāvako sotāpanno hoti avinipātadhammo niyato sambodhiparāyaṇo”ti.* **";
P_HTM[8362]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8363]="*3. Koṭigāmavaggo**Overflowing Merit, With Verses*";
P_HTM[8364]="*1. Mahāpaññāsuttaṃ**Factors*";
P_HTM[8365]="*“Cattārimāni, bhikkhave, sotāpattiyaṅgāni.**“Mendicants, there are these four factors of stream-entry.*";
P_HTM[8366]="*Katamāni cattāri?**What four?*";
P_HTM[8367]="*Sappurisasaṃsevo, saddhammassavanaṃ, yonisomanasikāro, dhammānudhammappaṭipatti—**Associating with good people, listening to the true teaching, proper attention, and practicing in line with the teaching.*";
P_HTM[8368]="*imāni kho, bhikkhave, cattāri sotāpattiyaṅgānī”ti.**These are the four factors of stream-entry.”*";
P_HTM[8369]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8370]="*Sagāthakapuññābhisandavaggo pañcamo.* **";
P_HTM[8371]="*Abhisandā tayo vuttā,* **";
P_HTM[8372]="*Duve mahaddhanena ca;* **";
P_HTM[8373]="*Suddhaṃ nandiyaṃ bhaddiyaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[8374]="*Mahānāmaṅgena te dasāti.* **";
P_HTM[8375]="*2. Puthupaññāsuttaṃ**With Verses*";
P_HTM[8376]="*“Catūhi, bhikkhave, dhammehi samannāgato ariyasāvako sotāpanno hoti avinipātadhammo niyato sambodhiparāyaṇo.**“Mendicants, a noble disciple who has four things is a stream-enterer, not liable to be reborn in the underworld, bound for awakening.*";
P_HTM[8377]="*Katamehi catūhi?**What four?*";
P_HTM[8378]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako buddhe aveccappasādena samannāgato hoti—**It’s when a noble disciple has experiential confidence in the Buddha …*";
P_HTM[8379]="*itipi so bhagavā … pe … satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavāti.* **";
P_HTM[8380]="*Dhamme … pe …**the teaching …*";
P_HTM[8381]="*saṅghe … pe …**the Saṅgha …*";
P_HTM[8382]="*ariyakantehi sīlehi samannāgato hoti akhaṇḍehi … pe … samādhisaṃvattanikehi.**And they have the ethical conduct loved by the noble ones … leading to immersion.*";
P_HTM[8383]="*Imehi kho, bhikkhave, catūhi dhammehi samannāgato ariyasāvako sotāpanno hoti avinipātadhammo niyato sambodhiparāyaṇo”ti.**A noble disciple who has these four things is a stream-enterer, not liable to be reborn in the underworld, bound for awakening.”*";
P_HTM[8384]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[8385]="*Idaṃ vatvāna sugato athāparaṃ etadavoca satthā:**Then the Holy One, the Teacher, went on to say:*";
P_HTM[8386]="*“Yassa saddhā tathāgate,**“Whoever has faith in the Realized One,*";
P_HTM[8387]="*acalā suppatiṭṭhitā;**unwavering and well grounded;*";
P_HTM[8388]="*Sīlañca yassa kalyāṇaṃ,**whose ethical conduct is good,*";
P_HTM[8389]="*ariyakantaṃ pasaṃsitaṃ.**praised and loved by the noble ones;*";
P_HTM[8390]="*Saṅghe pasādo yassatthi,**who has confidence in the Saṅgha,*";
P_HTM[8391]="*ujubhūtañca dassanaṃ;**and correct view:*";
P_HTM[8392]="*Adaliddoti taṃ āhu,**they’re said to be prosperous,*";
P_HTM[8393]="*amoghaṃ tassa jīvitaṃ.**their life is not in vain.*";
P_HTM[8394]="*Tasmā saddhañca sīlañca,**So let the wise devote themselves*";
P_HTM[8395]="*pasādaṃ dhammadassanaṃ;**to faith, ethical behaviour,*";
P_HTM[8396]="*Anuyuñjetha medhāvī,**confidence, and insight into the teaching,*";
P_HTM[8397]="*saraṃ buddhānasāsanan”ti.**remembering the instructions of the Buddhas.”*";
P_HTM[8398]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8399]="*3. Vipulapaññāsuttaṃ**One Who Completed the Rains*";
P_HTM[8400]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati jetavane anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery.*";
P_HTM[8401]="*Tena kho pana samayena aññataro bhikkhu sāvatthiyaṃ vassaṃvuttho kapilavatthuṃ anuppatto hoti kenacideva karaṇīyena.**Now at that time a certain mendicant who had completed the rainy season residence in Sāvatthī arrived at Kapilavatthu on some business.*";
P_HTM[8402]="*Assosuṃ kho kāpilavatthavā sakyā: “aññataro kira bhikkhu sāvatthiyaṃ vassaṃvuttho kapilavatthuṃ anuppatto”ti.**The Sakyans of Kapilavatthu heard about this.*";
P_HTM[8403]="*Atha kho kāpilavatthavā sakyā yena so bhikkhu tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā taṃ bhikkhuṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu. Ekamantaṃ nisinnā kho kāpilavatthavā sakyā taṃ bhikkhuṃ etadavocuṃ:**They went to that mendicant, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him,*";
P_HTM[8404]="*“kacci, bhante, bhagavā arogo ceva balavā cā”ti?**“Sir, we hope that you’re healthy and well.”*";
P_HTM[8405]="*“Arogo cāvuso, bhagavā balavā cā”ti.**“I am, good sirs.”*";
P_HTM[8406]="*“Kacci pana, bhante, sāriputtamoggallānā arogā ceva balavanto cā”ti?**“And we hope that Sāriputta and Moggallāna are healthy and well.”*";
P_HTM[8407]="*“Sāriputtamoggallānāpi kho, āvuso, arogā ceva balavanto cā”ti.**“They are.”*";
P_HTM[8408]="*“Kacci pana, bhante, bhikkhusaṅgho arogo ca balavā cā”ti.**“And we hope that the mendicant Saṅgha is healthy and well.”*";
P_HTM[8409]="*“Bhikkhusaṅghopi kho, āvuso, arogo ca balavā cā”ti.**“It is.”*";
P_HTM[8410]="*“Atthi pana te, bhante, kiñci iminā antaravassena bhagavato sammukhā sutaṃ sammukhā paṭiggahitan”ti?**“But sir, during this rains residence did you hear and learn anything in the presence of the Buddha?”*";
P_HTM[8411]="*“Sammukhā metaṃ, āvuso, bhagavato sutaṃ sammukhā paṭiggahitaṃ:**“Good sirs, I heard and learned this in the presence of the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[8412]="*‘appakā te, bhikkhave, bhikkhū ye āsavānaṃ khayā anāsavaṃ cetovimuttiṃ paññāvimuttiṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharanti.**‘There are fewer mendicants who realize the undefiled freedom of heart and freedom by wisdom in this very life, and live having realized it with their own insight due to the ending of defilements.*";
P_HTM[8413]="*Atha kho eteva bahutarā bhikkhū ye pañcannaṃ orambhāgiyānaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ parikkhayā opapātikā tattha parinibbāyino anāvattidhammā tasmā lokā’ti.**There are more mendicants who, having ended the five lower fetters, are reborn spontaneously, and will be extinguished there, not liable to return from that world.’*";
P_HTM[8414]="*Aparampi kho me, āvuso, bhagavato sammukhā sutaṃ sammukhā paṭiggahitaṃ:**In addition, I heard and learned this in the presence of the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[8415]="*‘appakā te, bhikkhave, bhikkhū ye pañcannaṃ orambhāgiyānaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ parikkhayā opapātikā tattha parinibbāyino anāvattidhammā tasmā lokā.**‘There are fewer mendicants who, having ended the five lower fetters, are reborn spontaneously, and will be extinguished there, not liable to return from that world.*";
P_HTM[8416]="*Atha kho eteva bahutarā bhikkhū ye tiṇṇaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ parikkhayā rāgadosamohānaṃ tanuttā sakadāgāmino, sakideva imaṃ lokaṃ āgantvā dukkhassantaṃ karissantī’ti.**There are more mendicants who, with the ending of three fetters, and the weakening of greed, hate, and delusion, are once-returners, who come back to this world once only, then make an end of suffering.’*";
P_HTM[8417]="*Aparampi kho me, āvuso, bhagavato sammukhā sutaṃ sammukhā paṭiggahitaṃ:**In addition, I heard and learned this in the presence of the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[8418]="*‘appakā te, bhikkhave, bhikkhū ye tiṇṇaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ parikkhayā rāgadosamohānaṃ tanuttā sakadāgāmino, sakideva imaṃ lokaṃ āgantvā dukkhassantaṃ karissanti.**‘There are fewer mendicants who, with the ending of three fetters, and the weakening of greed, hate, and delusion, are once-returners, who come back to this world once only, then make an end of suffering.*";
P_HTM[8419]="*Atha kho eteva bahutarā bhikkhū ye tiṇṇaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ parikkhayā sotāpannā avinipātadhammā niyatā sambodhiparāyaṇā’”ti.**There are more mendicants who, with the ending of three fetters are stream-enterers, not liable to be reborn in the underworld, bound for awakening.’”*";
P_HTM[8420]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8421]="*4. Gambhīrapaññāsuttaṃ**With Dhammadinna*";
P_HTM[8422]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā bārāṇasiyaṃ viharati isipatane migadāye.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Benares, in the deer park at Isipatana.*";
P_HTM[8423]="*Atha kho dhammadinno upāsako pañcahi upāsakasatehi saddhiṃ yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho dhammadinno upāsako bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then the lay follower Dhammadinna, together with five hundred lay followers, went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him:*";
P_HTM[8424]="*“ovadatu no, bhante, bhagavā;**“May the Buddha please advise*";
P_HTM[8425]="*anusāsatu no, bhante, bhagavā yaṃ amhākaṃ assa dīgharattaṃ hitāya sukhāyā”ti.**and instruct us. It will be for our lasting welfare and happiness.”*";
P_HTM[8426]="*“Tasmātiha vo, dhammadinna, evaṃ sikkhitabbaṃ:**“So, Dhammadinna, you should train like this:*";
P_HTM[8427]="*‘ye te suttantā tathāgatabhāsitā gambhīrā gambhīratthā lokuttarā suññatapaṭisaṃyuttā te kālena kālaṃ upasampajja viharissāmā’ti.**‘From time to time we will undertake and dwell upon the discourses spoken by the Realized One that are deep, profound, transcendent, dealing with emptiness.’*";
P_HTM[8428]="*Evañhi vo, dhammadinna, sikkhitabban”ti.**That’s how you should train yourselves.”*";
P_HTM[8429]="*“Na kho netaṃ, bhante, sukaraṃ amhehi puttasambādhasayanaṃ ajjhāvasantehi kāsikacandanaṃ paccanubhontehi mālāgandhavilepanaṃ dhārayantehi jātarūparajataṃ sādiyantehi—**“Sir, we live at home with our children, using sandalwood imported from Kāsi, wearing garlands, perfumes, and makeup, and accepting gold and money.*";
P_HTM[8430]="*ye te suttantā tathāgatabhāsitā gambhīrā gambhīratthā lokuttarā suññatapaṭisaṃyuttā te kālena kālaṃ upasampajja viharituṃ.**It’s not easy for us to undertake and dwell from time to time upon the discourses spoken by the Realized One that are deep, profound, transcendent, dealing with emptiness.*";
P_HTM[8431]="*Tesaṃ no, bhante, bhagavā amhākaṃ pañcasu sikkhāpadesu ṭhitānaṃ uttaridhammaṃ desetū”ti.**Since we are established in the five training rules, please teach us further.”*";
P_HTM[8432]="*“Tasmātiha vo, dhammadinna, evaṃ sikkhitabbaṃ:**“So, Dhammadinna, you should train like this:*";
P_HTM[8433]="*‘buddhe aveccappasādena samannāgatā bhavissāma—**‘We will have experiential confidence in the Buddha …*";
P_HTM[8434]="*itipi so bhagavā … pe … satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavāti.* **";
P_HTM[8435]="*Dhamme … pe …**the teaching …*";
P_HTM[8436]="*saṅghe … pe …**the Saṅgha …*";
P_HTM[8437]="*ariyakantehi sīlehi samannāgatā bhavissāma akhaṇḍehi … pe … samādhisaṃvattanikehī’ti.**And we will have the ethical conduct loved by the noble ones … leading to immersion.’*";
P_HTM[8438]="*Evañhi vo, dhammadinna, sikkhitabban”ti.**That’s how you should train yourselves.”*";
P_HTM[8439]="*“Yānimāni, bhante, bhagavatā cattāri sotāpattiyaṅgāni desitāni, saṃvijjante dhammā amhesu, mayañca tesu dhammesu sandissāma.**“Sir, these four factors of stream-entry that were taught by the Buddha are found in us, and we embody them.*";
P_HTM[8440]="*Mayañhi, bhante, buddhe aveccappasādena samannāgatā—**For we have experiential confidence in the Buddha …*";
P_HTM[8441]="*itipi so bhagavā … pe … satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavāti.* **";
P_HTM[8442]="*Dhamme … pe …**the teaching …*";
P_HTM[8443]="*saṅghe … pe …**the Saṅgha …*";
P_HTM[8444]="*ariyakantehi sīlehi samannāgatā akhaṇḍehi … pe … samādhisaṃvattanikehī”ti.**And we have the ethical conduct loved by the noble ones … leading to immersion.”*";
P_HTM[8445]="*“Lābhā vo, dhammadinna, suladdhaṃ vo, dhammadinna.**“You’re fortunate, Dhammadinna, so very fortunate!*";
P_HTM[8446]="*Sotāpattiphalaṃ tumhehi byākatan”ti.**You have all declared the fruit of stream-entry.”*";
P_HTM[8447]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8448]="*5. Appamattapaññāsuttaṃ**Sick*";
P_HTM[8449]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sakkesu viharati kapilavatthusmiṃ nigrodhārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying in the land of the Sakyans, near Kapilavatthu in the Banyan Tree Monastery.*";
P_HTM[8450]="*Tena kho pana samayena sambahulā bhikkhū bhagavato cīvarakammaṃ karonti:**At that time several mendicants were making a robe for the Buddha, thinking that*";
P_HTM[8451]="*“niṭṭhitacīvaro bhagavā temāsaccayena cārikaṃ pakkamissatī”ti.**when his robe was finished and the three months of the rains residence had passed the Buddha would set out wandering.*";
P_HTM[8452]="*Assosi kho mahānāmo sakko:**Mahānāma the Sakyan heard about this.*";
P_HTM[8453]="*“sambahulā kira bhikkhū bhagavato cīvarakammaṃ karonti:* **";
P_HTM[8454]="*‘niṭṭhitacīvaro bhagavā temāsaccayena cārikaṃ pakkamissatī’”ti.* **";
P_HTM[8455]="*Atha kho mahānāmo sakko yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho mahānāmo sakko bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then he went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and told him that he had heard that the Buddha was leaving. He added,*";
P_HTM[8456]="*“sutametaṃ, bhante:* **";
P_HTM[8457]="*‘sambahulā kira bhikkhū bhagavato cīvarakammaṃ karonti—* **";
P_HTM[8458]="*niṭṭhitacīvaro bhagavā temāsaccayena cārikaṃ pakkamissatī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[8459]="*Na kho netaṃ, bhante, bhagavato sammukhā sutaṃ sammukhā paṭiggahitaṃ**“Sir, I haven’t heard and learned it in the presence of the Buddha*";
P_HTM[8460]="*sappaññena upāsakena sappañño upāsako ābādhiko dukkhito bāḷhagilāno ovaditabbo”ti.**how a wise lay follower should advise another wise lay follower who is sick, suffering, gravely ill.”*";
P_HTM[8461]="*“Sappaññena, mahānāma, upāsakena sappañño upāsako ābādhiko dukkhito bāḷhagilāno catūhi assāsanīyehi dhammehi assāsetabbo:**“Mahānāma, a wise lay follower should put at ease another wise lay follower who is sick, suffering, gravely ill with four consolations.*";
P_HTM[8462]="*‘assāsatāyasmā—**‘Be at ease, sir.*";
P_HTM[8463]="*atthāyasmato buddhe aveccappasādo itipi so bhagavā … pe … satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavāti.**You have experiential confidence in the Buddha …*";
P_HTM[8464]="*Assāsatāyasmā—* **";
P_HTM[8465]="*atthāyasmato dhamme … pe …**the teaching …*";
P_HTM[8466]="*saṅghe … pe …**the Saṅgha …*";
P_HTM[8467]="*ariyakantāni sīlāni akhaṇḍāni … pe … samādhisaṃvattanikānī’ti.**And you have the ethical conduct loved by the noble ones … leading to immersion.’*";
P_HTM[8468]="*Sappaññena, mahānāma, upāsakena sappañño upāsako ābādhiko dukkhito bāḷhagilāno imehi catūhi assāsanīyehi dhammehi assāsetvā evamassa vacanīyo:**When a wise lay follower has put at ease another wise lay follower who is sick, suffering, gravely ill with these four consolations, they should say:*";
P_HTM[8469]="*‘atthāyasmato mātāpitūsu apekkhā’ti?**‘Are you concerned for your mother and father?’*";
P_HTM[8470]="*So ce evaṃ vadeyya:**If they reply,*";
P_HTM[8471]="*‘atthi me mātāpitūsu apekkhā’ti, so evamassa vacanīyo:**‘I am,’ they should say:*";
P_HTM[8472]="*‘āyasmā kho māriso maraṇadhammo.**‘But sir, it’s your nature to die.*";
P_HTM[8473]="*Sacepāyasmā mātāpitūsu apekkhaṃ karissati, marissateva;**Whether or not you are concerned for your mother and father,*";
P_HTM[8474]="*no cepāyasmā mātāpitūsu apekkhaṃ karissati, marissateva.**you will die anyway.*";
P_HTM[8475]="*Sādhāyasmā, yā te mātāpitūsu apekkhā taṃ pajahā’ti.**It would be good to give up concern for your mother and father.’*";
P_HTM[8476]="*So ce evaṃ vadeyya:**If they reply,*";
P_HTM[8477]="*‘yā me mātāpitūsu apekkhā sā pahīnā’ti, so evamassa vacanīyo:**‘I have given up concern for my mother and father,’ they should say:*";
P_HTM[8478]="*‘atthi panāyasmato puttadāresu apekkhā’ti?**‘But are you concerned for your partners and children?’*";
P_HTM[8479]="*So ce evaṃ vadeyya:**If they reply,*";
P_HTM[8480]="*‘atthi me puttadāresu apekkhā’ti, so evamassa vacanīyo:**‘I am,’ they should say:*";
P_HTM[8481]="*‘āyasmā kho māriso maraṇadhammo.**‘But sir, it’s your nature to die.*";
P_HTM[8482]="*Sacepāyasmā puttadāresu apekkhaṃ karissati, marissateva;**Whether or not you are concerned for your partners and children,*";
P_HTM[8483]="*no cepāyasmā puttadāresu apekkhaṃ karissati, marissateva.**you will die anyway.*";
P_HTM[8484]="*Sādhāyasmā, yā te puttadāresu apekkhā taṃ pajahā’ti.**It would be good to give up concern for your partners and children.’*";
P_HTM[8485]="*So ce evaṃ vadeyya:**If they reply,*";
P_HTM[8486]="*‘yā me puttadāresu apekkhā sā pahīnā’ti, so evamassa vacanīyo:**‘I have given up concern for my partners and children,’ they should say:*";
P_HTM[8487]="*‘atthi panāyasmato mānusakesu pañcasu kāmaguṇesu apekkhā’ti?**‘But are you concerned for the five kinds of human sensual stimulation?’*";
P_HTM[8488]="*So ce evaṃ vadeyya:**If they reply,*";
P_HTM[8489]="*‘atthi me mānusakesu pañcasu kāmaguṇesu apekkhā’ti, so evamassa vacanīyo:**‘I am,’ they should say:*";
P_HTM[8490]="*‘mānusakehi kho, āvuso, kāmehi dibbā kāmā abhikkantatarā ca paṇītatarā ca.**‘Good sir, heavenly sensual pleasures are better than human sensual pleasures.*";
P_HTM[8491]="*Sādhāyasmā, mānusakehi kāmehi cittaṃ vuṭṭhāpetvā cātumahārājikesu devesu cittaṃ adhimocehī’ti.**It would be good to turn your mind away from human sensual pleasures and fix it on the gods of the Four Great Kings.’*";
P_HTM[8492]="*So ce evaṃ vadeyya:**If they reply,*";
P_HTM[8493]="*‘mānusakehi me kāmehi cittaṃ vuṭṭhitaṃ, cātumahārājikesu devesu cittaṃ adhimocitan’ti, so evamassa vacanīyo:**‘I have done so,’ they should say:*";
P_HTM[8494]="*‘cātumahārājikehi kho, āvuso, devehi tāvatiṃsā devā abhikkantatarā ca paṇītatarā ca.**‘Good sir, the gods of the Thirty Three are better than the gods of the Four Great Kings …*";
P_HTM[8495]="*Sādhāyasmā, cātumahārājikehi devehi cittaṃ vuṭṭhāpetvā tāvatiṃsesu devesu cittaṃ adhimocehī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[8496]="*So ce evaṃ vadeyya:* **";
P_HTM[8497]="*‘cātumahārājikehi me devehi cittaṃ vuṭṭhitaṃ, tāvatiṃsesu devesu cittaṃ adhimocitan’ti, so evamassa vacanīyo:* **";
P_HTM[8498]="*‘tāvatiṃsehi kho, āvuso, devehi yāmā devā … pe …**Good sir, the gods of Yama …*";
P_HTM[8499]="*tusitā devā … pe …**the Joyful Gods …*";
P_HTM[8500]="*nimmānaratī devā … pe …**the Gods Who Love to Create …*";
P_HTM[8501]="*paranimmitavasavattī devā … pe …**the Gods Who Control the Creations of Others …*";
P_HTM[8502]="*paranimmitavasavattīhi kho, āvuso, devehi brahmaloko abhikkantataro ca paṇītataro ca.**the Gods of the Brahmā realm are better than the Gods Who Control the Creations of Others.*";
P_HTM[8503]="*Sādhāyasmā, paranimmitavasavattīhi devehi cittaṃ vuṭṭhāpetvā brahmaloke cittaṃ adhimocehī’ti.**It would be good to turn your mind away from the Gods Who Control the Creations of Others and fix it on the Gods of the Brahmā realm.’*";
P_HTM[8504]="*So ce evaṃ vadeyya:**If they reply,*";
P_HTM[8505]="*‘paranimmitavasavattīhi me devehi cittaṃ vuṭṭhitaṃ, brahmaloke cittaṃ adhimocitan’ti, so evamassa vacanīyo:**‘I have done so,’ they should say:*";
P_HTM[8506]="*‘brahmalokopi kho, āvuso, anicco addhuvo sakkāyapariyāpanno.**‘Good sir, the Brahmā realm is impermanent, not lasting, and included within identity.*";
P_HTM[8507]="*Sādhāyasmā, brahmalokā cittaṃ vuṭṭhāpetvā sakkāyanirodhe cittaṃ upasaṃharāhī’ti.**It would be good to turn your mind away from the Brahmā realm and apply it to the cessation of identity.’*";
P_HTM[8508]="*So ce evaṃ vadeyya:**If they reply,*";
P_HTM[8509]="*‘brahmalokā me cittaṃ vuṭṭhitaṃ, sakkāyanirodhe cittaṃ upasaṃharāmī’ti;**‘I have done so,’*";
P_HTM[8510]="*evaṃ vimuttacittassa kho, mahānāma, upāsakassa āsavā vimuttacittena bhikkhunā na kiñci nānākaraṇaṃ vadāmi, yadidaṃ—**then there is no difference between a lay follower whose mind is freed in this way and a mendicant whose mind is freed from defilements; that is,*";
P_HTM[8511]="*vimuttiyā vimuttan”ti.**between the freedom of one and the other.”*";
P_HTM[8512]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8513]="*6. Bhūripaññāsuttaṃ**The Fruit of Stream*";
P_HTM[8514]="*“Cattārome, bhikkhave, dhammā bhāvitā bahulīkatā sotāpattiphalasacchikiriyāya saṃvattanti.**“Mendicants, when four things are developed and cultivated they lead to the realization of the fruit of stream-entry.*";
P_HTM[8515]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[8516]="*Sappurisasaṃsevo, saddhammassavanaṃ, yonisomanasikāro, dhammānudhammappaṭipatti—**Associating with good people, listening to the true teaching, proper attention, and practicing in line with the teaching.*";
P_HTM[8517]="*ime kho, bhikkhave, cattāro dhammā bhāvitā bahulīkatā sotāpattiphalasacchikiriyāya saṃvattantī”ti.**When these four things are developed and cultivated they lead to the realization of the fruit of stream-entry.”*";
P_HTM[8518]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8519]="*7. Paññābāhullasuttaṃ**The Fruit of Once*";
P_HTM[8520]="*“Cattārome, bhikkhave, dhammā bhāvitā bahulīkatā sakadāgāmiphalasacchikiriyāya saṃvattanti.**“Mendicants, when four things are developed and cultivated they lead to the realization of the fruit of once-return. …”*";
P_HTM[8521]="*Katame cattāro?* **";
P_HTM[8522]="*… pe Saṃvattantī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[8523]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8524]="*8. Sīghapaññāsuttaṃ**The Fruit of Non*";
P_HTM[8525]="*“… Anāgāmiphalasacchikiriyāya saṃvattantī”ti.**“Mendicants, when four things are developed and cultivated they lead to the realization of the fruit of non-return. …”*";
P_HTM[8526]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8527]="*9. Lahupaññāsuttaṃ**The Fruit of Perfection*";
P_HTM[8528]="*“… Arahattaphalasacchikiriyāya saṃvattantī”ti.**“Mendicants, when four things are developed and cultivated they lead to the realization of the fruit of perfection. …”*";
P_HTM[8529]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8530]="*10. Hāsapaññāsuttaṃ**The Getting of Wisdom*";
P_HTM[8531]="*“… Paññāpaṭilābhāya saṃvattantī”ti.**“Mendicants, when four things are developed and cultivated they lead to the getting of wisdom. …”*";
P_HTM[8532]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8533]="*11. Javanapaññāsuttaṃ**The Growth of Wisdom*";
P_HTM[8534]="*“… Paññāvuddhiyā saṃvattantī”ti.**“Mendicants, when four things are developed and cultivated they lead to the growth of wisdom. …”*";
P_HTM[8535]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8536]="*12. Tikkhapaññāsuttaṃ**The Increase of Wisdom*";
P_HTM[8537]="*“…. Paññāvepullāya … saṃvattantī”ti.**“Mendicants, when four things are developed and cultivated they lead to the increase of wisdom. …”*";
P_HTM[8538]="*Ekādasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8539]="*Sappaññavaggo chaṭṭho.* **";
P_HTM[8540]="*Sagāthakaṃ vassaṃvutthaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[8541]="*dhammadinnañca gilānaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[8542]="*Caturo phalā paṭilābho,* **";
P_HTM[8543]="*vuddhi vepullatāya cāti.* **";
P_HTM[8544]="*13. Nibbedhikapaññāsuttaṃ**Great Wisdom*";
P_HTM[8545]="*“Cattārome, bhikkhave, dhammā bhāvitā bahulīkatā mahāpaññatāya saṃvattanti.**“Mendicants, when four things are developed and cultivated they lead to great wisdom.*";
P_HTM[8546]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[8547]="*Sappurisasaṃsevo, saddhammassavanaṃ, yonisomanasikāro, dhammānudhammappaṭipatti—**Associating with good people, listening to the true teaching, proper attention, and practicing in line with the teaching.*";
P_HTM[8548]="*ime kho, bhikkhave, cattāro dhammā bhāvitā bahulīkatā mahāpaññatāya saṃvattantī”ti.**When these four things are developed and cultivated they lead to great wisdom.”*";
P_HTM[8549]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8550]="*4. Sīsapāvanavaggo**Great Wisdom*";
P_HTM[8551]="*1. Samādhisuttaṃ**Widespread Wisdom*";
P_HTM[8552]="*“… Puthupaññatāya saṃvattantī”ti.**“Mendicants, when four things are developed and cultivated they lead to widespread wisdom …”*";
P_HTM[8553]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8554]="*2. Paṭisallānasuttaṃ**Abundant Wisdom*";
P_HTM[8555]="*“… Vipulapaññatāya saṃvattantī”ti.**“Mendicants, when four things are developed and cultivated they lead to abundant wisdom …”*";
P_HTM[8556]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8557]="*3. Paṭhamakulaputtasuttaṃ**Deep Wisdom*";
P_HTM[8558]="*“… Gambhīrapaññatāya saṃvattantī”ti.**“Mendicants, when four things are developed and cultivated they lead to deep wisdom …”*";
P_HTM[8559]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8560]="*4. Dutiyakulaputtasuttaṃ**Extraordinary Wisdom*";
P_HTM[8561]="*“… Appamattapaññatāya saṃvattantī”ti.**“Mendicants, when four things are developed and cultivated they lead to extraordinary wisdom …”*";
P_HTM[8562]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8563]="*5. Paṭhamasamaṇabrāhmaṇasuttaṃ**Vast Wisdom*";
P_HTM[8564]="*“… Bhūripaññatāya saṃvattantī”ti.**“Mendicants, when four things are developed and cultivated they lead to vast wisdom …”*";
P_HTM[8565]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8566]="*6. Dutiyasamaṇabrāhmaṇasuttaṃ**Much Wisdom*";
P_HTM[8567]="*“… Paññābāhullāya saṃvattantī”ti.**“Mendicants, when four things are developed and cultivated they lead to much wisdom …”*";
P_HTM[8568]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8569]="*7. Vitakkasuttaṃ**Fast Wisdom*";
P_HTM[8570]="*“… Sīghapaññatāya saṃvattantī”ti.**“Mendicants, when four things are developed and cultivated they lead to fast wisdom …”*";
P_HTM[8571]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8572]="*8. Cintasuttaṃ**Light Wisdom*";
P_HTM[8573]="*“… Lahupaññatāya saṃvattantī”ti.**“Mendicants, when four things are developed and cultivated they lead to light wisdom …”*";
P_HTM[8574]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8575]="*9. Viggāhikakathāsuttaṃ**Laughing Wisdom*";
P_HTM[8576]="*“… Hāsapaññatāya saṃvattantī”ti.**“Mendicants, when four things are developed and cultivated they lead to laughing wisdom …”*";
P_HTM[8577]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8578]="*10. Tiracchānakathāsuttaṃ**Swift Wisdom*";
P_HTM[8579]="*“… Javanapaññatāya saṃvattantī”ti.**“Mendicants, when four things are developed and cultivated they lead to swift wisdom …”*";
P_HTM[8580]="*Ekādasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8581]="*5. Papātavaggo**Great Wisdom*";
P_HTM[8582]="*1. Dhammacakkappavattanasuttaṃ**Sharp Wisdom*";
P_HTM[8583]="*“… Tikkhapaññatāya saṃvattantī”ti.**“Mendicants, when four things are developed and cultivated they lead to sharp wisdom …”*";
P_HTM[8584]="*Dvādasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8585]="*2. Tathāgatasuttaṃ**Penetrating Wisdom*";
P_HTM[8586]="*“… Nibbedhikapaññatāya saṃvattanti.**“Mendicants, when four things are developed and cultivated they lead to penetrating wisdom.*";
P_HTM[8587]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[8588]="*Sappurisasaṃsevo, saddhammassavanaṃ, yonisomanasikāro, dhammānudhammappaṭipatti—**Associating with good people, listening to the true teaching, proper attention, and practicing in line with the teaching.*";
P_HTM[8589]="*ime kho, bhikkhave, cattāro dhammā bhāvitā bahulīkatā nibbedhikapaññatāya saṃvattantī”ti.**When these four things are developed and cultivated they lead to penetrating wisdom.”*";
P_HTM[8590]="*Terasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8591]="*Mahāpaññavaggo sattamo.* **";
P_HTM[8592]="*Mahā puthu vipula gambhīraṃ,* **";
P_HTM[8593]="*Appamatta bhūri bāhullaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[8594]="*Sīgha lahu hāsa javana,* **";
P_HTM[8595]="*Tikkha nibbedhikāya cāti.* **";
P_HTM[8596]="*Sotāpattisaṃyuttaṃ ekādasamaṃ.**The Linked Discourses on Stream-Entry, the eleventh section.*";
P_HTM[8597]="*56. Saccasaṃyuttaṃ* **";
P_HTM[8598]="*3. Khandhasuttaṃ**Immersion*";
P_HTM[8599]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[8600]="*… pe …* **";
P_HTM[8601]="*“Samādhiṃ, bhikkhave, bhāvetha.**“Mendicants, develop immersion.*";
P_HTM[8602]="*Samāhito, bhikkhave, bhikkhu yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.**A mendicant who has immersion truly understands.*";
P_HTM[8603]="*Kiñca yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti?**What do they truly understand?*";
P_HTM[8604]="*‘Idaṃ dukkhan’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti, ‘ayaṃ dukkhasamudayo’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti, ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodho’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti, ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.**They truly understand: ‘This is suffering’ … ‘This is the origin of suffering’ … ‘This is the cessation of suffering’ … ‘This is the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering’.*";
P_HTM[8605]="*Samādhiṃ, bhikkhave, bhāvetha.**Develop immersion.*";
P_HTM[8606]="*Samāhito, bhikkhave, bhikkhu yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.**A mendicant who has immersion truly understands.*";
P_HTM[8607]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yogo karaṇīyo, ‘ayaṃ dukkhasamudayo’ti yogo karaṇīyo, ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodho’ti yogo karaṇīyo, ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation to understand: ‘This is suffering’ … ‘This is the origin of suffering’ … ‘This is the cessation of suffering’ … ‘This is the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering’.”*";
P_HTM[8608]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8609]="*4. Ajjhattikāyatanasuttaṃ**Retreat*";
P_HTM[8610]="*“Paṭisallāne, bhikkhave, yogamāpajjatha.**“Mendicants, meditate in retreat.*";
P_HTM[8611]="*Paṭisallīno, bhikkhave, bhikkhu yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.**A mendicant in retreat truly understands.*";
P_HTM[8612]="*Kiñca yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti?**What do they truly understand?*";
P_HTM[8613]="*‘Idaṃ dukkhan’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti, ‘ayaṃ dukkhasamudayo’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti, ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodho’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti, ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.**They truly understand: ‘This is suffering’ … ‘This is the origin of suffering’ … ‘This is the cessation of suffering’ … ‘This is the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering’.*";
P_HTM[8614]="*Paṭisallāne, bhikkhave, yogamāpajjatha.**Meditate in retreat.*";
P_HTM[8615]="*Paṭisallīno, bhikkhave, bhikkhu yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.**A mendicant in retreat truly understands.*";
P_HTM[8616]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yogo karaṇīyo, ‘ayaṃ dukkhasamudayo’ti yogo karaṇīyo, ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodho’ti yogo karaṇīyo, ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation to understand: ‘This is suffering’ … ‘This is the origin of suffering’ … ‘This is the cessation of suffering’ … ‘This is the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering’.”*";
P_HTM[8617]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8618]="*5. Paṭhamadhāraṇasuttaṃ**A Gentleman (1st)*";
P_HTM[8619]="*“Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, atītamaddhānaṃ kulaputtā sammā agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajiṃsu, sabbe te catunnaṃ ariyasaccānaṃ yathābhūtaṃ abhisamayāya.**“Mendicants, whatever gentlemen—past,*";
P_HTM[8620]="*Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, anāgatamaddhānaṃ kulaputtā sammā agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajissanti, sabbe te catunnaṃ ariyasaccānaṃ yathābhūtaṃ abhisamayāya.**future,*";
P_HTM[8621]="*Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, etarahi kulaputtā sammā agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajanti, sabbe te catunnaṃ ariyasaccānaṃ yathābhūtaṃ abhisamayāya.**or present—rightly go forth from the lay life to homelessness, all of them do so in order to truly comprehend the four noble truths.*";
P_HTM[8622]="*Katamesaṃ catunnaṃ?**What four?*";
P_HTM[8623]="*Dukkhassa ariyasaccassa dukkhasamudayassa ariyasaccassa dukkhanirodhassa ariyasaccassa dukkhanirodhagāminiyā paṭipadāya ariyasaccassa.**The noble truths of suffering, the origin of suffering, the cessation of suffering, and the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering.*";
P_HTM[8624]="*Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, atītamaddhānaṃ kulaputtā sammā agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajiṃsu … pe …**Whatever gentlemen—past,*";
P_HTM[8625]="*pabbajissanti … pe …**future,*";
P_HTM[8626]="*pabbajanti, sabbe te imesaṃyeva catunnaṃ ariyasaccānaṃ yathābhūtaṃ abhisamayāya.**or present—rightly go forth from the lay life to homelessness, all of them do so in order to truly comprehend the four noble truths.*";
P_HTM[8627]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yogo karaṇīyo, ‘ayaṃ dukkhasamudayo’ti yogo karaṇīyo, ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodho’ti yogo karaṇīyo, ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation to understand: ‘This is suffering’ … ‘This is the origin of suffering’ … ‘This is the cessation of suffering’ … ‘This is the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering’.”*";
P_HTM[8628]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8629]="*6. Dutiyadhāraṇasuttaṃ**A Gentleman (2nd)*";
P_HTM[8630]="*“Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, atītamaddhānaṃ kulaputtā sammā agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajitā yathābhūtaṃ abhisamesuṃ, sabbe te cattāri ariyasaccāni yathābhūtaṃ abhisamesuṃ.**“Mendicants, whatever gentlemen—past,*";
P_HTM[8631]="*Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, anāgatamaddhānaṃ kulaputtā sammā agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajitā yathābhūtaṃ abhisamessanti, sabbe te cattāri ariyasaccāni yathābhūtaṃ abhisamessanti.**future,*";
P_HTM[8632]="*Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, etarahi kulaputtā sammā agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajitā yathābhūtaṃ abhisamenti, sabbe te cattāri ariyasaccāni yathābhūtaṃ abhisamenti.**or present—truly comprehend after rightly going forth from the lay life to homelessness, all of them truly comprehend the four noble truths.*";
P_HTM[8633]="*Katamāni cattāri?**What four?*";
P_HTM[8634]="*Dukkhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ, dukkhasamudayaṃ ariyasaccaṃ, dukkhanirodhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ, dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā ariyasaccaṃ.**The noble truths of suffering, the origin of suffering, the cessation of suffering, and the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering. …*";
P_HTM[8635]="*Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, atītamaddhānaṃ kulaputtā sammā agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajitā yathābhūtaṃ abhisamesuṃ … pe …* **";
P_HTM[8636]="*abhisamessanti … pe …* **";
P_HTM[8637]="*abhisamenti, sabbe te imāni cattāri ariyasaccāni yathābhūtaṃ abhisamenti.* **";
P_HTM[8638]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yogo karaṇīyo … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation …”*";
P_HTM[8639]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8640]="*7. Avijjāsuttaṃ**Ascetics and Brahmins (1st)*";
P_HTM[8641]="*“Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, atītamaddhānaṃ samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā yathābhūtaṃ abhisambojjhiṃsu, sabbe te cattāri ariyasaccāni yathābhūtaṃ abhisambojjhiṃsu.**“Mendicants, whatever ascetics and brahmins truly wake up—in the past,*";
P_HTM[8642]="*Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, anāgatamaddhānaṃ samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā yathābhūtaṃ abhisambojjhissanti, sabbe te cattāri ariyasaccāni yathābhūtaṃ abhisambojjhissanti.**future,*";
P_HTM[8643]="*Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, etarahi samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā yathābhūtaṃ abhisambojjhanti, sabbe te cattāri ariyasaccāni yathābhūtaṃ abhisambojjhanti.**or present—all of them truly wake up to the four noble truths.*";
P_HTM[8644]="*Katamāni cattāri?**What four?*";
P_HTM[8645]="*Dukkhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ … pe … dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā ariyasaccaṃ.**The noble truths of suffering, the origin of suffering, the cessation of suffering, and the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering. …*";
P_HTM[8646]="*Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, atītamaddhānaṃ samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā yathābhūtaṃ abhisambojjhiṃsu … pe …* **";
P_HTM[8647]="*abhisambojjhissanti … pe …* **";
P_HTM[8648]="*abhisambojjhanti, sabbe te imāni cattāri ariyasaccāni yathābhūtaṃ abhisambojjhanti.* **";
P_HTM[8649]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yogo karaṇīyo … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation …”*";
P_HTM[8650]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8651]="*8. Vijjāsuttaṃ**Ascetics and Brahmins (2nd)*";
P_HTM[8652]="*“Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, atītamaddhānaṃ samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā yathābhūtaṃ abhisambuddhaṃ pakāsesuṃ, sabbe te cattāri ariyasaccāni yathābhūtaṃ abhisambuddhaṃ pakāsesuṃ.**“Mendicants, whatever ascetics and brahmins—past,*";
P_HTM[8653]="*Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, anāgatamaddhānaṃ samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā yathābhūtaṃ abhisambuddhaṃ pakāsessanti, sabbe te cattāri ariyasaccāni yathābhūtaṃ abhisambuddhaṃ pakāsessanti.**future,*";
P_HTM[8654]="*Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, etarahi samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā yathābhūtaṃ abhisambuddhaṃ pakāsenti, sabbe te cattāri ariyasaccāni yathābhūtaṃ abhisambuddhaṃ pakāsenti.**or present—reveal that they are awakened, all of them reveal that they truly awakened to the four noble truths.*";
P_HTM[8655]="*Katamāni cattāri?**What four?*";
P_HTM[8656]="*Dukkhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ … pe … dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā ariyasaccaṃ.**The noble truths of suffering, the origin of suffering, the cessation of suffering, and the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering. …*";
P_HTM[8657]="*Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, atītamaddhānaṃ samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā yathābhūtaṃ abhisambuddhaṃ pakāsesuṃ … pe …* **";
P_HTM[8658]="*pakāsessanti … pe …* **";
P_HTM[8659]="*pakāsenti, sabbe te imāni cattāri ariyasaccāni yathābhūtaṃ abhisambuddhaṃ pakāsenti.* **";
P_HTM[8660]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yogo karaṇīyo … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation …”*";
P_HTM[8661]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8662]="*9. Saṅkāsanasuttaṃ**Thoughts*";
P_HTM[8663]="*“Mā, bhikkhave, pāpake akusale vitakke vitakkeyyātha, seyyathidaṃ—**“Mendicants, don’t think bad, unskillful thoughts, such as*";
P_HTM[8664]="*kāmavitakkaṃ, byāpādavitakkaṃ, vihiṃsāvitakkaṃ.**sensual, malicious, and cruel thoughts.*";
P_HTM[8665]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[8666]="*Nete, bhikkhave, vitakkā atthasaṃhitā nādibrahmacariyakā na nibbidāya na virāgāya na nirodhāya na upasamāya na abhiññāya na sambodhāya na nibbānāya saṃvattanti.**Because those thoughts aren’t beneficial or relevant to the fundamentals of the spiritual life. They don’t lead to disillusionment, dispassion, cessation, peace, insight, awakening, and extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[8667]="*Vitakkentā ca kho tumhe, bhikkhave, ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti vitakkeyyātha, ‘ayaṃ dukkhasamudayo’ti vitakkeyyātha, ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodho’ti vitakkeyyātha, ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti vitakkeyyātha.**When you think, you should think: ‘This is suffering’ … ‘This is the origin of suffering’ … ‘This is the cessation of suffering’ … ‘This is the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering’.*";
P_HTM[8668]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[8669]="*Ete, bhikkhave, vitakkā atthasaṃhitā ete ādibrahmacariyakā ete nibbidāya virāgāya nirodhāya upasamāya abhiññāya sambodhāya nibbānāya saṃvattanti.**Because those thoughts are beneficial and relevant to the fundamentals of the spiritual life. They lead to disillusionment, dispassion, cessation, peace, insight, awakening, and extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[8670]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yogo karaṇīyo … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation …”*";
P_HTM[8671]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8672]="*10. Tathasuttaṃ**Thought*";
P_HTM[8673]="*“Mā, bhikkhave, pāpakaṃ akusalaṃ cittaṃ cinteyyātha:**“Mendicants, don’t think up a bad, unskillful idea.*";
P_HTM[8674]="*‘sassato loko’ti vā ‘asassato loko’ti vā, ‘antavā loko’ti vā ‘anantavā loko’ti vā, ‘taṃ jīvaṃ taṃ sarīran’ti vā ‘aññaṃ jīvaṃ aññaṃ sarīran’ti vā, ‘hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā’ti vā ‘na hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā’ti vā, ‘hoti ca na ca hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā’ti vā, ‘neva hoti na na hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā’ti vā.**For example: the world is eternal, or not eternal, or finite, or infinite; the soul and the body are the same thing, or they are different things; after death, a Realized One exists, or doesn’t exist, or both exists and doesn’t exist, or neither exists nor doesn’t exist.*";
P_HTM[8675]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[8676]="*Nesā, bhikkhave, cintā atthasaṃhitā nādibrahmacariyakā na nibbidāya na virāgāya na nirodhāya na upasamāya na abhiññāya na sambodhāya na nibbānāya saṃvattati.**Because those thoughts aren’t beneficial or relevant to the fundamentals of the spiritual life. They don’t lead to disillusionment, dispassion, cessation, peace, insight, awakening, and extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[8677]="*Cintentā ca kho tumhe, bhikkhave, ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti cinteyyātha, ‘ayaṃ dukkhasamudayo’ti cinteyyātha, ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodho’ti cinteyyātha, ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti cinteyyātha.**When you think something up, you should think: ‘This is suffering’ … ‘This is the origin of suffering’ … ‘This is the cessation of suffering’ … ‘This is the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering’.*";
P_HTM[8678]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[8679]="*Esā, bhikkhave, cintā atthasaṃhitā, esā ādibrahmacariyakā, esā nibbidāya virāgāya nirodhāya upasamāya abhiññāya sambodhāya nibbānāya saṃvattati.**Because those thoughts are beneficial and relevant to the fundamentals of the spiritual life. They lead to disillusionment, dispassion, cessation, peace, insight, awakening, and extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[8680]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yogo karaṇīyo … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation …”*";
P_HTM[8681]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8682]="*6. Abhisamayavaggo**Immersion*";
P_HTM[8683]="*1. Paṭhamakoṭigāmasuttaṃ**Arguments*";
P_HTM[8684]="*“Mā, bhikkhave, viggāhikakathaṃ katheyyātha:**“Mendicants, don’t get into arguments, such as:*";
P_HTM[8685]="*‘na tvaṃ imaṃ dhammavinayaṃ ājānāsi, ahaṃ imaṃ dhammavinayaṃ ājānāmi. Kiṃ tvaṃ imaṃ dhammavinayaṃ ājānissasi. Micchāpaṭipanno tvamasi, ahamasmi sammāpaṭipanno. Sahitaṃ me, asahitaṃ te. Purevacanīyaṃ pacchā avaca, pacchāvacanīyaṃ pure avaca. Adhiciṇṇaṃ te viparāvattaṃ. Āropito te vādo, cara vādappamokkhāya. Niggahitosi, nibbeṭhehi vā sace pahosī’ti.**‘You don’t understand this teaching and training. I understand this teaching and training. What, you understand this teaching and training? You’re practicing wrong. I’m practicing right. I stay on topic, you don’t. You said last what you should have said first. You said first what you should have said last. What you’ve thought so much about has been disproved. Your doctrine is refuted. Go on, save your doctrine! You’re trapped; get yourself out of this—if you can!’*";
P_HTM[8686]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[8687]="*Nesā, bhikkhave, kathā atthasaṃhitā nādibrahmacariyakā na nibbidāya na virāgāya na nirodhāya na upasamāya na abhiññāya na sambodhāya na nibbānāya saṃvattati.**Because those discussions aren’t beneficial or relevant to the fundamentals of the spiritual life. They don’t lead to disillusionment, dispassion, cessation, peace, insight, awakening, and extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[8688]="*Kathentā ca kho tumhe, bhikkhave, ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti katheyyātha, ‘ayaṃ dukkhasamudayo’ti katheyyātha, ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodho’ti katheyyātha, ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti katheyyātha … pe …**When you discuss, you should discuss: ‘This is suffering’ … ‘This is the origin of suffering’ … ‘This is the cessation of suffering’ … ‘This is the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering’. …*";
P_HTM[8689]="*yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation …”*";
P_HTM[8690]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8691]="*2. Dutiyakoṭigāmasuttaṃ**Unworthy Talk*";
P_HTM[8692]="*“Mā, bhikkhave, anekavihitaṃ tiracchānakathaṃ katheyyātha, seyyathidaṃ—**“Mendicants, don’t engage in all kinds of unworthy talk, such as*";
P_HTM[8693]="*rājakathaṃ corakathaṃ mahāmattakathaṃ senākathaṃ, bhayakathaṃ yuddhakathaṃ, annakathaṃ pānakathaṃ vatthakathaṃ sayanakathaṃ mālākathaṃ gandhakathaṃ, ñātikathaṃ yānakathaṃ gāmakathaṃ nigamakathaṃ nagarakathaṃ janapadakathaṃ itthikathaṃ sūrakathaṃ visikhākathaṃ kumbhaṭṭhānakathaṃ, pubbapetakathaṃ nānattakathaṃ, lokakkhāyikaṃ samuddakkhāyikaṃ itibhavābhavakathaṃ iti vā.**talk about kings, bandits, and ministers; talk about armies, threats, and wars; talk about food, drink, clothes, and beds; talk about garlands and fragrances; talk about family, vehicles, villages, towns, cities, and countries; talk about women and heroes; street talk and talk at the well; talk about the departed; motley talk; tales of land and sea; and talk about being reborn in this or that state of existence.*";
P_HTM[8694]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[8695]="*Nesā, bhikkhave, kathā atthasaṃhitā nādibrahmacariyakā na nibbidāya na virāgāya na nirodhāya na upasamāya na abhiññāya na sambodhāya na nibbānāya saṃvattati.**Because those discussions aren’t beneficial or relevant to the fundamentals of the spiritual life. They don’t lead to disillusionment, dispassion, cessation, peace, insight, awakening, and extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[8696]="*Kathentā ca kho tumhe, bhikkhave, ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti katheyyātha, ‘ayaṃ dukkhasamudayo’ti katheyyātha, ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodho’ti katheyyātha, ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti katheyyātha.**When you discuss, you should discuss: ‘This is suffering’ … ‘This is the origin of suffering’ … ‘This is the cessation of suffering’ … ‘This is the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering’. …*";
P_HTM[8697]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?* **";
P_HTM[8698]="*Esā, bhikkhave, kathā atthasaṃhitā, esā ādibrahmacariyakā, esā nibbidāya virāgāya nirodhāya upasamāya abhiññāya sambodhāya nibbānāya saṃvattati.* **";
P_HTM[8699]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yogo karaṇīyo … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation …”*";
P_HTM[8700]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8701]="*Samādhivaggo paṭhamo.* **";
P_HTM[8702]="*Samādhi paṭisallānā,* **";
P_HTM[8703]="*kulaputtā apare duve;* **";
P_HTM[8704]="*Samaṇabrāhmaṇā vitakkaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[8705]="*cintā viggāhikā kathāti.* **";
P_HTM[8706]="*3. Sammāsambuddhasuttaṃ**Rolling Forth the Wheel of Dhamma*";
P_HTM[8707]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā bārāṇasiyaṃ viharati isipatane migadāye.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Benares, in the deer park at Isipatana.*";
P_HTM[8708]="*Tatra kho bhagavā pañcavaggiye bhikkhū āmantesi:**There the Buddha addressed the group of five mendicants:*";
P_HTM[8709]="*“Dveme, bhikkhave, antā pabbajitena na sevitabbā.**“Mendicants, these two extremes should not be cultivated by one who has gone forth.*";
P_HTM[8710]="*Katame dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[8711]="*Yo cāyaṃ kāmesu kāmasukhallikānuyogo hīno gammo pothujjaniko anariyo anatthasaṃhito, yo cāyaṃ attakilamathānuyogo dukkho anariyo anatthasaṃhito.**Indulgence in sensual pleasures, which is low, crude, ordinary, ignoble, and pointless. And indulgence in self-mortification, which is painful, ignoble, and pointless.*";
P_HTM[8712]="*Ete kho, bhikkhave, ubho ante anupagamma majjhimā paṭipadā tathāgatena abhisambuddhā cakkhukaraṇī ñāṇakaraṇī upasamāya abhiññāya sambodhāya nibbānāya saṃvattati.**Avoiding these two extremes, the Realized One woke up by understanding the middle way, which gives vision and knowledge, and leads to peace, direct knowledge, awakening, and extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[8713]="*Katamā ca sā, bhikkhave, majjhimā paṭipadā tathāgatena abhisambuddhā cakkhukaraṇī ñāṇakaraṇī upasamāya abhiññāya sambodhāya nibbānāya saṃvattati?**And what is that middle way?*";
P_HTM[8714]="*Ayameva ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo, seyyathidaṃ—**It is simply this noble eightfold path, that is:*";
P_HTM[8715]="*sammādiṭṭhi sammāsaṅkappo sammāvācā sammākammanto sammāājīvo sammāvāyāmo sammāsati sammāsamādhi.**right view, right thought, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, and right immersion.*";
P_HTM[8716]="*Ayaṃ kho sā, bhikkhave, majjhimā paṭipadā tathāgatena abhisambuddhā cakkhukaraṇī ñāṇakaraṇī upasamāya abhiññāya sambodhāya nibbānāya saṃvattati.**This is that middle way, which gives vision and knowledge, and leads to peace, direct knowledge, awakening, and extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[8717]="*Idaṃ kho pana, bhikkhave, dukkhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ—**Now this is the noble truth of suffering.*";
P_HTM[8718]="*jātipi dukkhā, jarāpi dukkhā, byādhipi dukkho, maraṇampi dukkhaṃ, appiyehi sampayogo dukkho, piyehi vippayogo dukkho, yampicchaṃ na labhati tampi dukkhaṃ—saṃkhittena pañcupādānakkhandhā dukkhā.**Rebirth is suffering; old age is suffering; illness is suffering; death is suffering; association with the disliked is suffering; separation from the liked is suffering; not getting what you wish for is suffering. In brief, the five grasping aggregates are suffering.*";
P_HTM[8719]="*Idaṃ kho pana, bhikkhave, dukkhasamudayaṃ ariyasaccaṃ—**Now this is the noble truth of the origin of suffering.*";
P_HTM[8720]="*yāyaṃ taṇhā ponobbhavikā nandirāgasahagatā tatratatrābhinandinī, seyyathidaṃ—**It’s the craving that leads to future rebirth, mixed up with relishing and greed, taking pleasure in various different realms. That is,*";
P_HTM[8721]="*kāmataṇhā, bhavataṇhā, vibhavataṇhā.**craving for sensual pleasures, craving to continue existence, and craving to end existence.*";
P_HTM[8722]="*Idaṃ kho pana, bhikkhave, dukkhanirodhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ—**Now this is the noble truth of the cessation of suffering.*";
P_HTM[8723]="*yo tassāyeva taṇhāya asesavirāganirodho cāgo paṭinissaggo mutti anālayo.**It’s the fading away and cessation of that very same craving with nothing left over; giving it away, letting it go, releasing it, and not adhering to it.*";
P_HTM[8724]="*Idaṃ kho pana, bhikkhave, dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā ariyasaccaṃ—**Now this is the noble truth of the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering.*";
P_HTM[8725]="*ayameva ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo, seyyathidaṃ—**It is simply this noble eightfold path, that is:*";
P_HTM[8726]="*sammādiṭṭhi … pe … sammāsamādhi.**right view, right thought, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, and right immersion.*";
P_HTM[8727]="*‘Idaṃ dukkhaṃ ariyasaccan’ti me, bhikkhave, pubbe ananussutesu dhammesu cakkhuṃ udapādi, ñāṇaṃ udapādi, paññā udapādi, vijjā udapādi, āloko udapādi.**‘This is the noble truth of suffering.’ Such was the vision, knowledge, wisdom, realization, and light that arose in me regarding teachings not learned before from another.*";
P_HTM[8728]="*‘Taṃ kho panidaṃ dukkhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ pariññeyyan’ti me, bhikkhave, pubbe … pe … udapādi.**‘This noble truth of suffering should be completely understood.’ Such was the vision that arose in me …*";
P_HTM[8729]="*‘Taṃ kho panidaṃ dukkhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ pariññātan’ti me, bhikkhave, pubbe ananussutesu dhammesu cakkhuṃ udapādi, ñāṇaṃ udapādi, paññā udapādi, vijjā udapādi, āloko udapādi.**‘This noble truth of suffering has been completely understood.’ Such was the vision that arose in me …*";
P_HTM[8730]="*‘Idaṃ dukkhasamudayaṃ ariyasaccan’ti me, bhikkhave, pubbe ananussutesu dhammesu cakkhuṃ udapādi, ñāṇaṃ udapādi, paññā udapādi, vijjā udapādi, āloko udapādi.**‘This is the noble truth of the origin of suffering.’ Such was the vision that arose in me …*";
P_HTM[8731]="*‘Taṃ kho panidaṃ dukkhasamudayaṃ ariyasaccaṃ pahātabban’ti me, bhikkhave, pubbe … pe … udapādi.**‘This noble truth of the origin of suffering should be given up.’ Such was the vision that arose in me …*";
P_HTM[8732]="*‘Taṃ kho panidaṃ dukkhasamudayaṃ ariyasaccaṃ pahīnan’ti me, bhikkhave, pubbe ananussutesu dhammesu cakkhuṃ udapādi, ñāṇaṃ udapādi, paññā udapādi, vijjā udapādi, āloko udapādi.**‘This noble truth of the origin of suffering has been given up.’ Such was the vision that arose in me …*";
P_HTM[8733]="*‘Idaṃ dukkhanirodhaṃ ariyasaccan’ti me, bhikkhave, pubbe ananussutesu dhammesu cakkhuṃ udapādi, ñāṇaṃ udapādi, paññā udapādi, vijjā udapādi, āloko udapādi.**‘This is the noble truth of the cessation of suffering.’ Such was the vision that arose in me …*";
P_HTM[8734]="*‘Taṃ kho panidaṃ dukkhanirodhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ sacchikātabban’ti me, bhikkhave, pubbe … pe … udapādi.**‘This noble truth of the cessation of suffering should be realized.’ Such was the vision that arose in me …*";
P_HTM[8735]="*‘Taṃ kho panidaṃ dukkhanirodhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ sacchikatan’ti me, bhikkhave, pubbe ananussutesu dhammesu cakkhuṃ udapādi, ñāṇaṃ udapādi, paññā udapādi, vijjā udapādi, āloko udapādi.**‘This noble truth of the cessation of suffering has been realized.’ Such was the vision that arose in me …*";
P_HTM[8736]="*‘Idaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā ariyasaccan’ti me, bhikkhave, pubbe ananussutesu dhammesu cakkhuṃ udapādi, ñāṇaṃ udapādi, paññā udapādi, vijjā udapādi, āloko udapādi.**‘This is the noble truth of the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering.’ Such was the vision that arose in me …*";
P_HTM[8737]="*‘Taṃ kho panidaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā ariyasaccaṃ bhāvetabban’ti me, bhikkhave, pubbe … pe … udapādi.**‘This noble truth of the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering should be developed.’ Such was the vision that arose in me …*";
P_HTM[8738]="*‘Taṃ kho panidaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā ariyasaccaṃ bhāvitan’ti me, bhikkhave, pubbe ananussutesu dhammesu cakkhuṃ udapādi, ñāṇaṃ udapādi, paññā udapādi, vijjā udapādi, āloko udapādi.**‘This noble truth of the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering has been developed.’ Such was the vision, knowledge, wisdom, realization, and light that arose in me regarding teachings not learned before from another.*";
P_HTM[8739]="*Yāvakīvañca me, bhikkhave, imesu catūsu ariyasaccesu evaṃ tiparivaṭṭaṃ dvādasākāraṃ yathābhūtaṃ ñāṇadassanaṃ na suvisuddhaṃ ahosi, neva tāvāhaṃ, bhikkhave, sadevake loke samārake sabrahmake sassamaṇabrāhmaṇiyā pajāya sadevamanussāya ‘anuttaraṃ sammāsambodhiṃ abhisambuddho’ti paccaññāsiṃ.**As long as my true knowledge and vision about these four noble truths was not fully purified in these three perspectives and twelve respects, I didn’t announce my supreme perfect awakening in this world with its gods, Māras, and Brahmās, this population with its ascetics and brahmins, its gods and humans.*";
P_HTM[8740]="*Yato ca kho me, bhikkhave, imesu catūsu ariyasaccesu evaṃ tiparivaṭṭaṃ dvādasākāraṃ yathābhūtaṃ ñāṇadassanaṃ suvisuddhaṃ ahosi, athāhaṃ, bhikkhave, sadevake loke samārake sabrahmake sassamaṇabrāhmaṇiyā pajāya sadevamanussāya ‘anuttaraṃ sammāsambodhiṃ abhisambuddho’ti paccaññāsiṃ.**But when my true knowledge and vision about these four noble truths was fully purified in these three perspectives and twelve respects, I announced my supreme perfect awakening in this world with its gods, Māras, and Brahmās, this population with its ascetics and brahmins, its gods and humans.*";
P_HTM[8741]="*Ñāṇañca pana me dassanaṃ udapādi:**Knowledge and vision arose in me:*";
P_HTM[8742]="*‘akuppā me vimutti, ayamantimā jāti, natthi dāni punabbhavo’”ti.**‘My freedom is unshakable; this is my last rebirth; now there are no more future lives.’”*";
P_HTM[8743]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[8744]="*Attamanā pañcavaggiyā bhikkhū bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandunti.**Satisfied, the group of five mendicants was happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[8745]="*Imasmiñca pana veyyākaraṇasmiṃ bhaññamāne āyasmato koṇḍaññassa virajaṃ vītamalaṃ dhammacakkhuṃ udapādi:**And while this discourse was being spoken, the stainless, immaculate vision of the Dhamma arose in Venerable Koṇḍañña:*";
P_HTM[8746]="*“yaṃ kiñci samudayadhammaṃ sabbaṃ taṃ nirodhadhamman”ti.**“Everything that has a beginning has an end.”*";
P_HTM[8747]="*Pavattite ca pana bhagavatā dhammacakke bhummā devā saddamanussāvesuṃ:**And when the Buddha rolled forth the Wheel of Dhamma, the earth gods raised the cry:*";
P_HTM[8748]="*“etaṃ bhagavatā bārāṇasiyaṃ isipatane migadāye anuttaraṃ dhammacakkaṃ pavattitaṃ appaṭivattiyaṃ samaṇena vā brāhmaṇena vā devena vā mārena vā brahmunā vā kenaci vā lokasmin”ti.**“Near Benares, in the deer park at Isipatana, the Buddha has rolled forth the supreme Wheel of Dhamma. And that wheel cannot be rolled back by any ascetic or brahmin or god or Māra or Brahmā or by anyone in the world.”*";
P_HTM[8749]="*Bhummānaṃ devānaṃ saddaṃ sutvā cātumahārājikā devā saddamanussāvesuṃ:**Hearing the cry of the Earth Gods, the Gods of the Four Great Kings …*";
P_HTM[8750]="*“etaṃ bhagavatā bārāṇasiyaṃ isipatane migadāye anuttaraṃ dhammacakkaṃ pavattitaṃ, appaṭivattiyaṃ samaṇena vā brāhmaṇena vā devena vā mārena vā brahmunā vā kenaci vā lokasmin”ti.* **";
P_HTM[8751]="*Cātumahārājikānaṃ devānaṃ saddaṃ sutvā tāvatiṃsā devā … pe …**the Gods of the Thirty-Three …*";
P_HTM[8752]="*yāmā devā … pe …**the Gods of Yama …*";
P_HTM[8753]="*tusitā devā … pe …**the Joyful Gods …*";
P_HTM[8754]="*nimmānaratī devā … pe …**the Gods Who Love to Create …*";
P_HTM[8755]="*paranimmitavasavattī devā … pe …**the Gods Who Control the Creations of Others …*";
P_HTM[8756]="*brahmakāyikā devā saddamanussāvesuṃ:**the Gods of Brahmā’s Host raised the cry:*";
P_HTM[8757]="*“etaṃ bhagavatā bārāṇasiyaṃ isipatane migadāye anuttaraṃ dhammacakkaṃ pavattitaṃ appaṭivattiyaṃ samaṇena vā brāhmaṇena vā devena vā mārena vā brahmunā vā kenaci vā lokasmin”ti.**“Near Benares, in the deer park at Isipatana, the Buddha has rolled forth the supreme Wheel of Dhamma. And that wheel cannot be rolled back by any ascetic or brahmin or god or Māra or Brahmā or by anyone in the world.”*";
P_HTM[8758]="*Itiha tena khaṇena tena layena tena muhuttena yāva brahmalokā saddo abbhuggacchi.**And so at that moment, in that instant, the cry soared up to the Brahmā realm.*";
P_HTM[8759]="*Ayañca dasasahassilokadhātu saṅkampi sampakampi sampavedhi, appamāṇo ca uḷāro obhāso loke pāturahosi atikkamma devānaṃ devānubhāvanti.**And this galaxy shook and rocked and trembled. And an immeasurable, magnificent light appeared in the world, surpassing the glory of the gods.*";
P_HTM[8760]="*Atha kho bhagavā imaṃ udānaṃ udānesi:**Then the Buddha was inspired to exclaim:*";
P_HTM[8761]="*“aññāsi vata bho, koṇḍañño, aññāsi vata bho, koṇḍañño”ti.**“Koṇḍañña has really understood! Koṇḍañña has really understood!”*";
P_HTM[8762]="*Iti hidaṃ āyasmato koṇḍaññassa “aññāsikoṇḍañño” tveva nāmaṃ ahosīti.**And that’s how Venerable Koṇḍañña came to be known as “Koṇḍañña Who Understood”.*";
P_HTM[8763]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8764]="*4. Arahantasuttaṃ**The Realized Ones*";
P_HTM[8765]="*“‘Idaṃ dukkhaṃ ariyasaccan’ti, bhikkhave, tathāgatānaṃ pubbe ananussutesu dhammesu cakkhuṃ udapādi, ñāṇaṃ udapādi, paññā udapādi, vijjā udapādi, āloko udapādi.**“‘This is the noble truth of suffering.’ Such was the vision, knowledge, wisdom, realization, and light that arose in the Realized Ones regarding teachings not learned before from another.*";
P_HTM[8766]="*‘Taṃ kho panidaṃ dukkhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ pariññeyyan’ti, bhikkhave, tathāgatānaṃ pubbe … pe … udapādi.**‘This noble truth of suffering should be completely understood.’ …*";
P_HTM[8767]="*‘Taṃ kho panidaṃ dukkhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ pariññātan’ti, bhikkhave, tathāgatānaṃ pubbe ananussutesu dhammesu cakkhuṃ udapādi, ñāṇaṃ udapādi, paññā udapādi, vijjā udapādi, āloko udapādi.**‘This noble truth of suffering has been completely understood.’ …*";
P_HTM[8768]="*‘Idaṃ dukkhasamudayaṃ ariyasaccan’ti bhikkhave, tathāgatānaṃ pubbe ananussutesu dhammesu cakkhuṃ udapādi, ñāṇaṃ udapādi, paññā udapādi, vijjā udapādi, āloko udapādi.**‘This is the noble truth of the origin of suffering.’ …*";
P_HTM[8769]="*‘Taṃ kho panidaṃ dukkhasamudayaṃ ariyasaccaṃ pahātabban’ti, bhikkhave, tathāgatānaṃ pubbe … pe … udapādi.**‘This noble truth of the origin of suffering should be given up.’ …*";
P_HTM[8770]="*‘Taṃ kho panidaṃ dukkhasamudayaṃ ariyasaccaṃ pahīnan’ti, bhikkhave, tathāgatānaṃ pubbe ananussutesu dhammesu cakkhuṃ udapādi, ñāṇaṃ udapādi, paññā udapādi, vijjā udapādi, āloko udapādi.**‘This noble truth of the origin of suffering has been given up.’ …*";
P_HTM[8771]="*‘Idaṃ dukkhanirodhaṃ ariyasaccan’ti, bhikkhave, tathāgatānaṃ pubbe ananussutesu dhammesu cakkhuṃ udapādi, ñāṇaṃ udapādi, paññā udapādi, vijjā udapādi, āloko udapādi.**‘This is the noble truth of the cessation of suffering.’ …*";
P_HTM[8772]="*‘Taṃ kho panidaṃ dukkhanirodhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ sacchikātabban’ti, bhikkhave, tathāgatānaṃ pubbe … pe … udapādi.**‘This noble truth of the cessation of suffering should be realized.’ …*";
P_HTM[8773]="*‘Taṃ kho panidaṃ dukkhanirodhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ sacchikatan’ti, bhikkhave, tathāgatānaṃ pubbe ananussutesu dhammesu cakkhuṃ udapādi, ñāṇaṃ udapādi, paññā udapādi, vijjā udapādi, āloko udapādi.**‘This noble truth of the cessation of suffering has been realized.’ …*";
P_HTM[8774]="*‘Idaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā ariyasaccan’ti, bhikkhave, tathāgatānaṃ pubbe ananussutesu dhammesu cakkhuṃ udapādi, ñāṇaṃ udapādi, paññā udapādi, vijjā udapādi, āloko udapādi.**‘This is the noble truth of the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering.’ …*";
P_HTM[8775]="*‘Taṃ kho panidaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā ariyasaccaṃ bhāvetabban’ti, bhikkhave, tathāgatānaṃ pubbe … pe … udapādi.**‘This noble truth of the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering should be developed.’ …*";
P_HTM[8776]="*‘Taṃ kho panidaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā ariyasaccaṃ bhāvitan’ti, bhikkhave, tathāgatānaṃ pubbe ananussutesu dhammesu cakkhuṃ udapādi, ñāṇaṃ udapādi, paññā udapādi, vijjā udapādi, āloko udapādī”ti.**‘This noble truth of the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering has been developed.’ Such was the vision, knowledge, wisdom, realization, and light that arose in the Realized Ones regarding teachings not learned before from another.”*";
P_HTM[8777]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8778]="*5. Āsavakkhayasuttaṃ**Aggregates*";
P_HTM[8779]="*“Cattārimāni, bhikkhave, ariyasaccāni.**“Mendicants, there are these four noble truths.*";
P_HTM[8780]="*Katamāni cattāri?**What four?*";
P_HTM[8781]="*Dukkhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ, dukkhasamudayaṃ ariyasaccaṃ, dukkhanirodhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā ariyasaccaṃ.**The noble truths of suffering, the origin of suffering, the cessation of suffering, and the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering.*";
P_HTM[8782]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, dukkhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ?**And what is the noble truth of suffering?*";
P_HTM[8783]="*‘Pañcupādānakkhandhā’ tissa vacanīyaṃ, seyyathidaṃ—**You should say: ‘The five grasping aggregates’.*";
P_HTM[8784]="*rūpupādānakkhandho … pe … viññāṇupādānakkhandho.**That is: form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness.*";
P_HTM[8785]="*Idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, dukkhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ.**This is called the noble truth of suffering.*";
P_HTM[8786]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, dukkhasamudayaṃ ariyasaccaṃ?**And what is the noble truth of the origin of suffering?*";
P_HTM[8787]="*Yāyaṃ taṇhā ponobbhavikā nandirāgasahagatā tatratatrābhinandinī, seyyathidaṃ—**It’s the craving that leads to future rebirth, mixed up with relishing and greed, taking pleasure in various different realms. That is,*";
P_HTM[8788]="*kāmataṇhā, bhavataṇhā, vibhavataṇhā.**craving for sensual pleasures, craving to continue existence, and craving to end existence.*";
P_HTM[8789]="*Idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, dukkhasamudayaṃ ariyasaccaṃ.**This is called the noble truth of the origin of suffering.*";
P_HTM[8790]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, dukkhanirodhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ?**And what is the noble truth of the cessation of suffering?*";
P_HTM[8791]="*Yo tassāyeva taṇhāya asesavirāganirodho cāgo paṭinissaggo mutti anālayo—**It’s the fading away and cessation of that very same craving with nothing left over; giving it away, letting it go, releasing it, and not adhering to it.*";
P_HTM[8792]="*idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, dukkhanirodhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ.**This is called the noble truth of the cessation of suffering.*";
P_HTM[8793]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā ariyasaccaṃ?**And what is the noble truth of the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering?*";
P_HTM[8794]="*Ayameva ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo, seyyathidaṃ—**It is simply this noble eightfold path, that is:*";
P_HTM[8795]="*sammādiṭṭhi … pe … sammāsamādhi—**right view, right thought, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, and right immersion.*";
P_HTM[8796]="*idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā ariyasaccaṃ.**This is called the noble truth of the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering.*";
P_HTM[8797]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, cattāri ariyasaccāni.**These are the four noble truths.*";
P_HTM[8798]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yogo karaṇīyo … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation …”*";
P_HTM[8799]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8800]="*6. Mittasuttaṃ**Interior Sense Fields*";
P_HTM[8801]="*“Cattārimāni, bhikkhave, ariyasaccāni.**“Mendicants, there are these four noble truths.*";
P_HTM[8802]="*Katamāni cattāri?**What four?*";
P_HTM[8803]="*Dukkhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ, dukkhasamudayaṃ ariyasaccaṃ, dukkhanirodhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ, dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā ariyasaccaṃ.**The noble truths of suffering, the origin of suffering, the cessation of suffering, and the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering.*";
P_HTM[8804]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, dukkhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ?**And what is the noble truth of suffering?*";
P_HTM[8805]="*‘Cha ajjhattikāni āyatanānī’tissa vacanīyaṃ.**You should say: ‘The six interior sense fields’.*";
P_HTM[8806]="*Katamāni cha?**What six?*";
P_HTM[8807]="*Cakkhāyatanaṃ … pe … manāyatanaṃ—**The sense fields of the eye, ear, nose, tongue, body, and mind.*";
P_HTM[8808]="*idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, dukkhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ.**This is called the noble truth of suffering. …”*";
P_HTM[8809]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, dukkhasamudayaṃ ariyasaccaṃ?* **";
P_HTM[8810]="*Yāyaṃ taṇhā ponobbhavikā nandirāgasahagatā tatratatrābhinandinī, seyyathidaṃ—kāmataṇhā, bhavataṇhā, vibhavataṇhā—* **";
P_HTM[8811]="*idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, dukkhasamudayaṃ ariyasaccaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8812]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, dukkhanirodhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ?* **";
P_HTM[8813]="*Yo tassāyeva taṇhāya asesavirāganirodho cāgo paṭinissaggo mutti anālayo—* **";
P_HTM[8814]="*idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, dukkhanirodhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8815]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā ariyasaccaṃ?* **";
P_HTM[8816]="*Ayameva ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo, seyyathidaṃ—* **";
P_HTM[8817]="*sammādiṭṭhi … pe … sammāsamādhi—* **";
P_HTM[8818]="*idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā ariyasaccaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8819]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, cattāri ariyasaccāni.* **";
P_HTM[8820]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yogo karaṇīyo … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yogo karaṇīyo”ti.* **";
P_HTM[8821]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8822]="*7. Tathasuttaṃ**Remembering (1st)*";
P_HTM[8823]="*“Dhāretha no tumhe, bhikkhave, mayā cattāri ariyasaccāni desitānī”ti?**“Mendicants, do you remember the four noble truths that I taught?”*";
P_HTM[8824]="*Evaṃ vutte, aññataro bhikkhu bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When he said this, one of the mendicants said to the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[8825]="*“ahaṃ kho, bhante, dhāremi bhagavatā cattāri ariyasaccāni desitānī”ti.**“I do, sir.”*";
P_HTM[8826]="*“Yathā kathaṃ pana tvaṃ, bhikkhu, dhāresi mayā cattāri ariyasaccāni desitānī”ti?**“How so, mendicant?”*";
P_HTM[8827]="*“Dukkhaṃ khvāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavatā paṭhamaṃ ariyasaccaṃ desitaṃ dhāremi;**“Sir, I remember that suffering is the first noble truth you’ve taught;*";
P_HTM[8828]="*dukkhasamudayaṃ khvāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavatā dutiyaṃ ariyasaccaṃ desitaṃ dhāremi;**the origin of suffering is the second;*";
P_HTM[8829]="*dukkhanirodhaṃ khvāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavatā tatiyaṃ ariyasaccaṃ desitaṃ dhāremi;**the cessation of suffering is the third;*";
P_HTM[8830]="*dukkhanirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ khvāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavatā catutthaṃ ariyasaccaṃ desitaṃ dhāremi.**and the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering is the fourth.*";
P_HTM[8831]="*Evaṃ khvāhaṃ, bhante, dhāremi bhagavatā cattāri ariyasaccāni desitānī”ti.**That’s how I remember the four noble truths as you’ve taught them.”*";
P_HTM[8832]="*“Sādhu sādhu, bhikkhu.**“Good, good, mendicant!*";
P_HTM[8833]="*Sādhu kho tvaṃ, bhikkhu, dhāresi mayā cattāri ariyasaccāni desitānīti.**It’s good that you remember the four noble truths as I’ve taught them.*";
P_HTM[8834]="*Dukkhaṃ kho, bhikkhu, mayā paṭhamaṃ ariyasaccaṃ desitaṃ, tathā naṃ dhārehi;**Suffering is the first noble truth I’ve taught, and that’s how you should remember it.*";
P_HTM[8835]="*dukkhasamudayaṃ kho, bhikkhu, mayā dutiyaṃ ariyasaccaṃ desitaṃ, tathā naṃ dhārehi;**The origin of suffering is the second;*";
P_HTM[8836]="*dukkhanirodhaṃ kho, bhikkhu, mayā tatiyaṃ ariyasaccaṃ desitaṃ, tathā naṃ dhārehi;**the cessation of suffering is the third;*";
P_HTM[8837]="*dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā kho, bhikkhu, mayā catutthaṃ ariyasaccaṃ desitaṃ, tathā naṃ dhārehi.**and the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering is the fourth.*";
P_HTM[8838]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhu, dhārehi mayā cattāri ariyasaccāni desitānīti.**That’s how you should remember the four noble truths as I’ve taught them.*";
P_HTM[8839]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhu, ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yogo karaṇīyo … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation …”*";
P_HTM[8840]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8841]="*8. Lokasuttaṃ**Remembering (2nd)*";
P_HTM[8842]="*“Dhāretha no tumhe, bhikkhave, mayā cattāri ariyasaccāni desitānī”ti?**“Mendicants, do you remember the four noble truths that I taught?”*";
P_HTM[8843]="*Evaṃ vutte, aññataro bhikkhu bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When he said this, one of the mendicants said to the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[8844]="*“ahaṃ kho, bhante, dhāremi bhagavatā cattāri ariyasaccāni desitānī”ti.**“I do, sir.”*";
P_HTM[8845]="*“Yathā kathaṃ pana tvaṃ, bhikkhu, dhāresi mayā cattāri ariyasaccāni desitānī”ti?**“How so, mendicant?”*";
P_HTM[8846]="*“Dukkhaṃ khvāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavatā paṭhamaṃ ariyasaccaṃ desitaṃ dhāremi.**“Sir, I remember that suffering is the first noble truth you’ve taught.*";
P_HTM[8847]="*Yo hi koci, bhante, samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā evaṃ vadeyya:**For if any ascetic or brahmin should say this:*";
P_HTM[8848]="*‘netaṃ dukkhaṃ paṭhamaṃ ariyasaccaṃ yaṃ samaṇena gotamena desitaṃ.**‘What the ascetic Gotama teaches is not the first noble truth of suffering.*";
P_HTM[8849]="*Ahametaṃ dukkhaṃ paṭhamaṃ ariyasaccaṃ paccakkhāya aññaṃ dukkhaṃ paṭhamaṃ ariyasaccaṃ paññapessāmī’ti—**I’ll reject this first noble truth of suffering and describe another first noble truth of suffering.’*";
P_HTM[8850]="*netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**That is not possible.*";
P_HTM[8851]="*Dukkhasamudayaṃ khvāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavatā … pe …**The origin of suffering … The cessation of suffering …*";
P_HTM[8852]="*dukkhanirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ khvāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavatā catutthaṃ ariyasaccaṃ desitaṃ dhāremi.**The practice that leads to the cessation of suffering is the fourth noble truth you’ve taught.*";
P_HTM[8853]="*Yo hi koci, bhante, samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā evaṃ vadeyya:**For if any ascetic or brahmin should say this:*";
P_HTM[8854]="*‘netaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā catutthaṃ ariyasaccaṃ yaṃ samaṇena gotamena desitaṃ.**‘What the ascetic Gotama teaches is not the fourth noble truth of the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering.*";
P_HTM[8855]="*Ahametaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ catutthaṃ ariyasaccaṃ paccakkhāya aññaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ catutthaṃ ariyasaccaṃ paññapessāmī’ti—**I’ll reject this fourth noble truth of the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering and describe another fourth noble truth of the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering.’*";
P_HTM[8856]="*netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**That is not possible.*";
P_HTM[8857]="*Evaṃ khvāhaṃ, bhante, dhāremi bhagavatā cattāri ariyasaccāni desitānī”ti.**That’s how I remember the four noble truths as you’ve taught them.”*";
P_HTM[8858]="*“Sādhu sādhu, bhikkhu.**“Good, good, mendicant!*";
P_HTM[8859]="*Sādhu kho tvaṃ, bhikkhu, dhāresi mayā cattāri ariyasaccāni desitānīti.**It’s good that you remember the four noble truths as I’ve taught them.*";
P_HTM[8860]="*Dukkhaṃ kho, bhikkhu, mayā paṭhamaṃ ariyasaccaṃ desitaṃ, tathā naṃ dhārehi.**Suffering is the first noble truth I’ve taught, and that’s how you should remember it.*";
P_HTM[8861]="*Yo hi koci, bhikkhu, samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā evaṃ vadeyya:**For if any ascetic or brahmin should say this:*";
P_HTM[8862]="*‘netaṃ dukkhaṃ paṭhamaṃ ariyasaccaṃ yaṃ samaṇena gotamena desitaṃ.**‘What the ascetic Gotama teaches is not the first noble truth of suffering.*";
P_HTM[8863]="*Ahametaṃ dukkhaṃ paṭhamaṃ ariyasaccaṃ paccakkhāya aññaṃ dukkhaṃ paṭhamaṃ ariyasaccaṃ paññapessāmī’ti—**I’ll reject this first noble truth of suffering and describe another first noble truth of suffering.’*";
P_HTM[8864]="*netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**That is not possible.*";
P_HTM[8865]="*Dukkhasamudayaṃ kho, bhikkhu … pe …**The origin of suffering …*";
P_HTM[8866]="*dukkhanirodhaṃ kho, bhikkhu … pe …**The cessation of suffering …*";
P_HTM[8867]="*dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā kho, bhikkhu, mayā catutthaṃ ariyasaccaṃ desitaṃ, tathā naṃ dhārehi.**The practice that leads to the cessation of suffering is the fourth noble truth I’ve taught, and that’s how you should remember it.*";
P_HTM[8868]="*Yo hi koci, bhikkhu, samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā evaṃ vadeyya:**For if any ascetic or brahmin should say this:*";
P_HTM[8869]="*‘netaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā catutthaṃ ariyasaccaṃ yaṃ samaṇena gotamena desitaṃ.**‘What the ascetic Gotama teaches is not the fourth noble truth of the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering.*";
P_HTM[8870]="*Ahametaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ catutthaṃ ariyasaccaṃ paccakkhāya aññaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ catutthaṃ ariyasaccaṃ paññapessāmī’ti—**I’ll reject this fourth noble truth of the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering and describe another fourth noble truth of the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering.’*";
P_HTM[8871]="*netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**That is not possible.*";
P_HTM[8872]="*Evaṃ kho tvaṃ, bhikkhu, dhārehi mayā cattāri ariyasaccāni desitānīti.**That’s how you should remember the four noble truths as I’ve taught them.*";
P_HTM[8873]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhu, ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yogo karaṇīyo … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation …”*";
P_HTM[8874]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8875]="*9. Pariññeyyasuttaṃ**Ignorance*";
P_HTM[8876]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho so bhikkhu bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Seated to one side, that mendicant said to the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[8877]="*“‘avijjā, avijjā’ti, bhante, vuccati.**“Sir, they speak of this thing called ‘ignorance’.*";
P_HTM[8878]="*Katamā nu kho, bhante, avijjā;**What is ignorance?*";
P_HTM[8879]="*kittāvatā ca avijjāgato hotī”ti?**And how is an ignorant person defined?”*";
P_HTM[8880]="*“Yaṃ kho, bhikkhu, dukkhe aññāṇaṃ, dukkhasamudaye aññāṇaṃ, dukkhanirodhe aññāṇaṃ, dukkhanirodhagāminiyā paṭipadāya aññāṇaṃ—**“Not knowing about suffering, the origin of suffering, the cessation of suffering, and the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering.*";
P_HTM[8881]="*ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhu, avijjā;**This is called ignorance.*";
P_HTM[8882]="*ettāvatā ca avijjāgato hotīti.**And this is how an ignorant person is defined.*";
P_HTM[8883]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhu, ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yogo karaṇīyo … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation …”*";
P_HTM[8884]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8885]="*10. Gavampatisuttaṃ**Knowledge*";
P_HTM[8886]="*Atha kho aññataro bhikkhu yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho so bhikkhu bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then a mendicant went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him:*";
P_HTM[8887]="*“‘vijjā, vijjā’ti, bhante, vuccati.**“Sir, they speak of this thing called ‘knowledge’.*";
P_HTM[8888]="*Katamā nu kho, bhante, vijjā;**What is knowledge?*";
P_HTM[8889]="*kittāvatā ca vijjāgato hotī”ti?**And how is a knowledgeable person defined?”*";
P_HTM[8890]="*“Yaṃ kho, bhikkhu, dukkhe ñāṇaṃ, dukkhasamudaye ñāṇaṃ, dukkhanirodhe ñāṇaṃ, dukkhanirodhagāminiyā paṭipadāya ñāṇaṃ—**“Knowing about suffering, the origin of suffering, the cessation of suffering, and the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering.*";
P_HTM[8891]="*ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhu, vijjā;**This is called knowledge.*";
P_HTM[8892]="*ettāvatā ca vijjāgato hotīti.**And this is how a knowledgeable person is defined.*";
P_HTM[8893]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhu, ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yogo karaṇīyo … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation …”*";
P_HTM[8894]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8895]="*7. Paṭhamaāmakadhaññapeyyālavaggo**Rolling Forth the Wheel of Dhamma*";
P_HTM[8896]="*1. Sīsapāvanasuttaṃ**Expressions*";
P_HTM[8897]="*“‘Idaṃ dukkhaṃ ariyasaccan’ti, bhikkhave, mayā paññattaṃ.**“Mendicants, I’ve declared: ‘This is the noble truth of suffering.’*";
P_HTM[8898]="*Tattha aparimāṇā vaṇṇā aparimāṇā byañjanā aparimāṇā saṅkāsanā:**And there are limitless explanations, phrases, and expressions about that:*";
P_HTM[8899]="*‘itipidaṃ dukkhaṃ ariyasaccan’ti;**‘This is another way of saying that this is the noble truth of suffering.’*";
P_HTM[8900]="*idaṃ dukkhasamudayaṃ … pe …**I’ve declared: ‘This is the noble truth of the origin of suffering.’ …*";
P_HTM[8901]="*idaṃ dukkhanirodhaṃ … pe …**I’ve declared: ‘This is the noble truth of the cessation of suffering.’ …*";
P_HTM[8902]="*‘idaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā ariyasaccan’ti, bhikkhave, mayā paññattaṃ.**I’ve declared: ‘This is the noble truth of the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering.’*";
P_HTM[8903]="*Tattha aparimāṇā vaṇṇā aparimāṇā byañjanā aparimāṇā saṅkāsanā:**And there are limitless explanations, phrases, and expressions about that:*";
P_HTM[8904]="*‘itipidaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā ariyasaccan’ti.**‘This is another way of saying that this is the noble truth of the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering.’*";
P_HTM[8905]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yogo karaṇīyo … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation …”*";
P_HTM[8906]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8907]="*2. Khadirapattasuttaṃ**Real*";
P_HTM[8908]="*“Cattārimāni, bhikkhave, tathāni avitathāni anaññathāni.**“Mendicants, these four things are real, not unreal, not otherwise.*";
P_HTM[8909]="*Katamāni cattāri?**What four?*";
P_HTM[8910]="*‘Idaṃ dukkhan’ti, bhikkhave, tathametaṃ avitathametaṃ anaññathametaṃ;**‘This is suffering’ …*";
P_HTM[8911]="*‘ayaṃ dukkhasamudayo’ti tathametaṃ avitathametaṃ anaññathametaṃ;**‘This is the origin of suffering’ …*";
P_HTM[8912]="*‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodho’ti tathametaṃ avitathametaṃ anaññathametaṃ;**‘This is the cessation of suffering’ …*";
P_HTM[8913]="*‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti tathametaṃ avitathametaṃ anaññathametaṃ—**‘This is the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering’ …*";
P_HTM[8914]="*imāni kho, bhikkhave, cattāri tathāni avitathāni anaññathāni.**These four things are real, not unreal, not otherwise.*";
P_HTM[8915]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yogo karaṇīyo … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation …”*";
P_HTM[8916]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8917]="*Dhammacakkappavattanavaggo dutiyo.* **";
P_HTM[8918]="*Dhammacakkaṃ tathāgataṃ,* **";
P_HTM[8919]="*khandhā āyatanena ca;* **";
P_HTM[8920]="*Dhāraṇā ca dve avijjā,* **";
P_HTM[8921]="*vijjā saṅkāsanā tathāti.* **";
P_HTM[8922]="*3. Daṇḍasuttaṃ**At the Village of Koṭi (1st)*";
P_HTM[8923]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā vajjīsu viharati koṭigāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying in the land of the Vajjis at the village of Koṭi.*";
P_HTM[8924]="*Tatra kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**There the Buddha addressed the mendicants:*";
P_HTM[8925]="*“catunnaṃ, bhikkhave, ariyasaccānaṃ ananubodhā appaṭivedhā evamidaṃ dīghamaddhānaṃ sandhāvitaṃ saṃsaritaṃ mamañceva tumhākañca.**“Mendicants, not understanding and not penetrating four noble truths, both you and I have wandered and transmigrated for such a very long time.*";
P_HTM[8926]="*Katamesaṃ catunnaṃ?**What four?*";
P_HTM[8927]="*Dukkhassa, bhikkhave, ariyasaccassa ananubodhā appaṭivedhā evamidaṃ dīghamaddhānaṃ sandhāvitaṃ saṃsaritaṃ mamañceva tumhākañca.**The noble truths of suffering,*";
P_HTM[8928]="*Dukkhasamudayassa ariyasaccassa … pe …**the origin of suffering,*";
P_HTM[8929]="*dukkhanirodhassa ariyasaccassa … pe …**the cessation of suffering,*";
P_HTM[8930]="*dukkhanirodhagāminiyā paṭipadāya ariyasaccassa ananubodhā appaṭivedhā evamidaṃ dīghamaddhānaṃ sandhāvitaṃ saṃsaritaṃ mamañceva tumhākañca.**and the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering.*";
P_HTM[8931]="*Tayidaṃ, bhikkhave, dukkhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ anubuddhaṃ paṭividdhaṃ, dukkhasamudayaṃ ariyasaccaṃ anubuddhaṃ paṭividdhaṃ, dukkhanirodhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ anubuddhaṃ paṭividdhaṃ, dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā ariyasaccaṃ anubuddhaṃ paṭividdhaṃ; ucchinnā bhavataṇhā, khīṇā bhavanetti; natthi dāni punabbhavo”ti.**These noble truths of suffering, origin, cessation, and the path have been understood and comprehended. Craving for continued existence has been cut off; the attachment to continued existence is ended; now there are no more future lives.”*";
P_HTM[8932]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[8933]="*Idaṃ vatvāna sugato athāparaṃ etadavoca satthā:**Then the Holy One, the Teacher, went on to say:*";
P_HTM[8934]="*“Catunnaṃ ariyasaccānaṃ,**“Because of not truly seeing*";
P_HTM[8935]="*Yathābhūtaṃ adassanā;**the four noble truths,*";
P_HTM[8936]="*Saṃsitaṃ dīghamaddhānaṃ,**we have transmigrated for a long time*";
P_HTM[8937]="*Tāsu tāsveva jātisu.**from one rebirth to the next.*";
P_HTM[8938]="*Tāni etāni diṭṭhāni,**But now that these truths have been seen,*";
P_HTM[8939]="*bhavanetti samūhatā;**the attachment to rebirth is eradicated.*";
P_HTM[8940]="*Ucchinnaṃ mūlaṃ dukkhassa,**The root of suffering is cut off,*";
P_HTM[8941]="*natthi dāni punabbhavo”ti.**now there are no more future lives.”*";
P_HTM[8942]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8943]="*4. Celasuttaṃ**At the Village of Koṭi (2nd)*";
P_HTM[8944]="*“Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānanti, ‘ayaṃ dukkhasamudayo’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānanti, ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodho’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānanti, ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānanti,**“Mendicants, there are ascetics and brahmins who don’t truly understand about suffering, its origin, its cessation, and the path.*";
P_HTM[8945]="*na me te, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā samaṇesu vā samaṇasammatā brāhmaṇesu vā brāhmaṇasammatā, na ca pana te āyasmanto sāmaññatthaṃ vā brahmaññatthaṃ vā diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharanti.**I don’t regard them as true ascetics and brahmins. Those venerables don’t realize the goal of life as an ascetic or brahmin, and don’t live having realized it with their own insight.*";
P_HTM[8946]="*Ye ca kho keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānanti, ‘ayaṃ dukkhasamudayo’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānanti, ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodho’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānanti, ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānanti,**There are ascetics and brahmins who do truly understand about suffering, its origin, its cessation, and the path.*";
P_HTM[8947]="*te kho me, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā samaṇesu ceva samaṇasammatā brāhmaṇesu ca brāhmaṇasammatā, te ca panāyasmanto sāmaññatthañca brahmaññatthañca diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharantī”ti.**I regard them as true ascetics and brahmins. Those venerables realize the goal of life as an ascetic or brahmin, and live having realized it with their own insight.”*";
P_HTM[8948]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[8949]="*Idaṃ vatvāna sugato athāparaṃ etadavoca satthā:**Then the Holy One, the Teacher, went on to say:*";
P_HTM[8950]="*“Ye dukkhaṃ nappajānanti,**“There are those who don’t understand suffering*";
P_HTM[8951]="*atho dukkhassa sambhavaṃ;**and suffering’s cause,*";
P_HTM[8952]="*Yattha ca sabbaso dukkhaṃ,**and where all suffering*";
P_HTM[8953]="*asesaṃ uparujjhati.**ceases with nothing left over.*";
P_HTM[8954]="*Tañca maggaṃ na jānanti,**And they don’t know the path*";
P_HTM[8955]="*Dukkhūpasamagāminaṃ;**that leads to the stilling of suffering.*";
P_HTM[8956]="*Cetovimuttihīnā te,**They lack the heart’s release,*";
P_HTM[8957]="*Atho paññāvimuttiyā;**as well as the release by wisdom.*";
P_HTM[8958]="*Abhabbā te antakiriyāya,**Unable to make an end,*";
P_HTM[8959]="*Te ve jātijarūpagā.**they continue to be reborn and get old.*";
P_HTM[8960]="*Ye ca dukkhaṃ pajānanti,**But there are those who understand suffering*";
P_HTM[8961]="*atho dukkhassa sambhavaṃ;**and suffering’s cause,*";
P_HTM[8962]="*Yattha ca sabbaso dukkhaṃ,**and where all suffering*";
P_HTM[8963]="*asesaṃ uparujjhati.**ceases with nothing left over.*";
P_HTM[8964]="*Tañca maggaṃ pajānanti,**And they understand the path*";
P_HTM[8965]="*dukkhūpasamagāminaṃ;**that leads to the stilling of suffering.*";
P_HTM[8966]="*Cetovimuttisampannā,**They’re endowed with the heart’s release,*";
P_HTM[8967]="*atho paññāvimuttiyā;**as well as the release by wisdom.*";
P_HTM[8968]="*Bhabbā te antakiriyāya,**Able to make an end,*";
P_HTM[8969]="*na te jātijarūpagā”ti.**they don’t continue to be reborn and get old.”*";
P_HTM[8970]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8971]="*5. Sattisatasuttaṃ**The Fully Awakened Buddha*";
P_HTM[8972]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[8973]="*Cattārimāni, bhikkhave, ariyasaccāni.**“Mendicants, there are these four noble truths.*";
P_HTM[8974]="*Katamāni cattāri?**What four?*";
P_HTM[8975]="*Dukkhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ … pe … dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā ariyasaccaṃ—**The noble truths of suffering, the origin of suffering, the cessation of suffering, and the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering.*";
P_HTM[8976]="*imāni kho, bhikkhave, cattāri ariyasaccāni.**These are the four noble truths.*";
P_HTM[8977]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, catunnaṃ ariyasaccānaṃ yathābhūtaṃ abhisambuddhattā tathāgato ‘arahaṃ sammāsambuddho’ti vuccati.**It is because he has truly woken up to these four noble truths that the Realized One is called ‘the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha’.*";
P_HTM[8978]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yogo karaṇīyo … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation …”*";
P_HTM[8979]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8980]="*6. Pāṇasuttaṃ**The Perfected Ones*";
P_HTM[8981]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[8982]="*“Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, atītamaddhānaṃ arahanto sammāsambuddhā yathābhūtaṃ abhisambujjhiṃsu, sabbe te cattāri ariyasaccāni yathābhūtaṃ abhisambujjhiṃsu.**“Mendicants, whatever perfected ones, fully awakened Buddhas truly wake up—in the past,*";
P_HTM[8983]="*Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, anāgatamaddhānaṃ arahanto sammāsambuddhā yathābhūtaṃ abhisambujjhissanti, sabbe te cattāri ariyasaccāni yathābhūtaṃ abhisambujjhissanti.**future,*";
P_HTM[8984]="*Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, etarahi arahanto sammāsambuddhā yathābhūtaṃ abhisambujjhanti, sabbe te cattāri ariyasaccāni yathābhūtaṃ abhisambujjhanti.**or present—all of them truly wake up to the four noble truths.*";
P_HTM[8985]="*Katamāni cattāri?**What four?*";
P_HTM[8986]="*Dukkhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ, dukkhasamudayaṃ ariyasaccaṃ, dukkhanirodhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ, dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā ariyasaccaṃ.**The noble truths of suffering, the origin of suffering, the cessation of suffering, and the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering.*";
P_HTM[8987]="*Ye hi, keci, bhikkhave, atītamaddhānaṃ arahanto sammāsambuddhā yathābhūtaṃ abhisambujjhiṃsu … pe …**Whatever perfected ones, fully awakened Buddhas truly wake up—in the past,*";
P_HTM[8988]="*abhisambujjhissanti …**future,*";
P_HTM[8989]="*abhisambujjhanti, sabbe te imāni cattāri ariyasaccāni yathābhūtaṃ abhisambujjhanti.**or present—all of them truly wake up to the four noble truths.*";
P_HTM[8990]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yogo karaṇīyo … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation …”*";
P_HTM[8991]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8992]="*7. Paṭhamasūriyasuttaṃ**The Ending of Defilements*";
P_HTM[8993]="*“Jānatohaṃ, bhikkhave, passato āsavānaṃ khayaṃ vadāmi, no ajānato apassato.**“Mendicants, I say that the ending of defilements is for one who knows and sees, not for one who does not know or see.*";
P_HTM[8994]="*Kiñca, bhikkhave, jānato passato āsavānaṃ khayo hoti?**For one who knows and sees what?*";
P_HTM[8995]="*‘Idaṃ dukkhan’ti, bhikkhave, jānato passato āsavānaṃ khayo hoti, ‘ayaṃ dukkhasamudayo’ti jānato passato āsavānaṃ khayo hoti, ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodho’ti jānato passato āsavānaṃ khayo hoti, ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti jānato passato āsavānaṃ khayo hoti.**The ending of defilements is for one who knows and sees suffering, its origin, its cessation, and the path.*";
P_HTM[8996]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, jānato evaṃ passato āsavānaṃ khayo hoti.**The ending of the defilements is for one who knows and sees this.*";
P_HTM[8997]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yogo karaṇīyo … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation …”*";
P_HTM[8998]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[8999]="*8. Dutiyasūriyasuttaṃ**Friends*";
P_HTM[9000]="*“Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, anukampeyyātha, ye ca sotabbaṃ maññeyyuṃ—mittā vā amaccā vā ñātī vā sālohitā vā—te vo, bhikkhave, catunnaṃ ariyasaccānaṃ yathābhūtaṃ abhisamayāya samādapetabbā nivesetabbā patiṭṭhāpetabbā.**“Mendicants, those who you have sympathy for, and those worth listening to—friends and colleagues, relatives and family—should be encouraged, supported, and established in the true comprehension of the four noble truths.*";
P_HTM[9001]="*Katamesaṃ catunnaṃ?**What four?*";
P_HTM[9002]="*Dukkhassa ariyasaccassa, dukkhasamudayassa ariyasaccassa, dukkhanirodhassa ariyasaccassa, dukkhanirodhagāminiyā paṭipadāya ariyasaccassa.**The noble truths of suffering, the origin of suffering, the cessation of suffering, and the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering.*";
P_HTM[9003]="*Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, anukampeyyātha, ye ca sotabbaṃ maññeyyuṃ—mittā vā amaccā vā ñātī vā sālohitā vā—te vo, bhikkhave, imesaṃ catunnaṃ ariyasaccānaṃ yathābhūtaṃ abhisamayāya samādapetabbā nivesetabbā patiṭṭhāpetabbā.**Those who you have sympathy for, and those worth listening to—friends and colleagues, relatives and family—should be encouraged, supported, and established in the true comprehension of these four noble truths.*";
P_HTM[9004]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yogo karaṇīyo … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation …”*";
P_HTM[9005]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9006]="*9. Indakhīlasuttaṃ**Real*";
P_HTM[9007]="*“Cattārimāni, bhikkhave, ariyasaccāni.**“Mendicants, there are these four noble truths.*";
P_HTM[9008]="*Katamāni cattāri?**What four?*";
P_HTM[9009]="*Dukkhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ, dukkhasamudayaṃ ariyasaccaṃ, dukkhanirodhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ, dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā ariyasaccaṃ—**The noble truths of suffering, the origin of suffering, the cessation of suffering, and the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering.*";
P_HTM[9010]="*imāni kho, bhikkhave, cattāri ariyasaccāni tathāni avitathāni anaññathāni;**These four things are real, not unreal, not otherwise.*";
P_HTM[9011]="*tasmā ‘ariyasaccānī’ti vuccanti.**That’s why they’re called ‘noble truths’.*";
P_HTM[9012]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yogo karaṇīyo … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation …”*";
P_HTM[9013]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9014]="*10. Vādatthikasuttaṃ**The World*";
P_HTM[9015]="*“Cattārimāni, bhikkhave, ariyasaccāni.**“Mendicants, there are these four noble truths.*";
P_HTM[9016]="*Katamāni cattāri?**What four?*";
P_HTM[9017]="*Dukkhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ, dukkhasamudayaṃ ariyasaccaṃ, dukkhanirodhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ, dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā ariyasaccaṃ.**The noble truths of suffering, the origin of suffering, the cessation of suffering, and the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering.*";
P_HTM[9018]="*Sadevake loke samārake sabrahmake sassamaṇabrāhmaṇiyā pajāya sadevamanussāya tathāgato ariyo;**In this world with its gods, Māras, and Brahmās, this population with its ascetics and brahmins, its gods and humans, the Realized One is the Noble One.*";
P_HTM[9019]="*tasmā ‘ariyasaccānī’ti vuccanti.**That’s why they’re called ‘noble truths’.*";
P_HTM[9020]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yogo karaṇīyo … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation …”*";
P_HTM[9021]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9022]="*8. Dutiyaāmakadhaññapeyyālavaggo**At the Village of Koṭi*";
P_HTM[9023]="*1. Lokacintāsuttaṃ**Should Be Completely Understood*";
P_HTM[9024]="*“Cattārimāni, bhikkhave, ariyasaccāni.**“Mendicants, there are these four noble truths.*";
P_HTM[9025]="*Katamāni cattāri?**What four?*";
P_HTM[9026]="*Dukkhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ, dukkhasamudayaṃ ariyasaccaṃ, dukkhanirodhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ, dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā ariyasaccaṃ—**The noble truths of suffering, the origin of suffering, the cessation of suffering, and the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering.*";
P_HTM[9027]="*imāni kho, bhikkhave, cattāri ariyasaccāni.**These are the four noble truths.*";
P_HTM[9028]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, catunnaṃ ariyasaccānaṃ atthi ariyasaccaṃ pariññeyyaṃ, atthi ariyasaccaṃ pahātabbaṃ, atthi ariyasaccaṃ sacchikātabbaṃ, atthi ariyasaccaṃ bhāvetabbaṃ.**Of these four noble truths, there is one to be completely understood, one to be given up, one to be realized, and one to be developed.*";
P_HTM[9029]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, ariyasaccaṃ pariññeyyaṃ?**And which noble truth should be completely understood?*";
P_HTM[9030]="*Dukkhaṃ, bhikkhave, ariyasaccaṃ pariññeyyaṃ, dukkhasamudayaṃ ariyasaccaṃ pahātabbaṃ, dukkhanirodhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ sacchikātabbaṃ, dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā ariyasaccaṃ bhāvetabbaṃ.**The noble truth of suffering should be completely understood. The noble truth of the origin of suffering should be given up. The noble truth of the cessation of suffering should be realized. The noble truth of the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering should be developed.*";
P_HTM[9031]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yogo karaṇīyo … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation …”*";
P_HTM[9032]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9033]="*2. Papātasuttaṃ**With Gavampati*";
P_HTM[9034]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ sambahulā therā bhikkhū cetesu viharanti sahañcanike.**At one time several mendicants were staying in the land of the Cetis at Sahajāti.*";
P_HTM[9035]="*Tena kho pana samayena sambahulānaṃ therānaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ pacchābhattaṃ piṇḍapātapaṭikkantānaṃ maṇḍalamāḷe sannisinnānaṃ sannipatitānaṃ ayamantarākathā udapādi:**Now at that time, after the meal, on return from alms-round, several senior mendicants sat together in the pavilion and this discussion came up among them:*";
P_HTM[9036]="*“yo nu kho, āvuso, dukkhaṃ passati dukkhasamudayampi so passati, dukkhanirodhampi passati, dukkhanirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadampi passatī”ti.**“Reverends, does someone who sees suffering also see the origin of suffering, the cessation of suffering, and the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering?”*";
P_HTM[9037]="*Evaṃ vutte, āyasmā gavampati thero bhikkhū etadavoca:**When they said this, Venerable Gavampati said to those senior mendicants:*";
P_HTM[9038]="*“sammukhā metaṃ, āvuso, bhagavato sutaṃ, sammukhā paṭiggahitaṃ:**“Reverends, I have heard and learned this in the presence of the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[9039]="*‘yo, bhikkhave, dukkhaṃ passati dukkhasamudayampi so passati, dukkhanirodhampi passati, dukkhanirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadampi passati.**‘Someone who sees suffering also sees the origin of suffering, the cessation of suffering, and the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering.*";
P_HTM[9040]="*Yo dukkhasamudayaṃ passati dukkhampi so passati, dukkhanirodhampi passati, dukkhanirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadampi passati.**Someone who sees the origin of suffering also sees suffering, the cessation of suffering, and the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering.*";
P_HTM[9041]="*Yo dukkhanirodhaṃ passati dukkhampi so passati, dukkhasamudayampi passati, dukkhanirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadampi passati.**Someone who sees the cessation of suffering also sees suffering, the origin of suffering, and the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering.*";
P_HTM[9042]="*Yo dukkhanirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ passati dukkhampi so passati, dukkhasamudayampi passati, dukkhanirodhampi passatī’”ti.**Someone who sees the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering also sees suffering, the origin of suffering, and the cessation of suffering.’”*";
P_HTM[9043]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9044]="*Koṭigāmavaggo tatiyo.* **";
P_HTM[9045]="*Dve vajjī sammāsambuddho,* **";
P_HTM[9046]="*arahaṃ āsavakkhayo;* **";
P_HTM[9047]="*Mittaṃ tathā ca loko ca,* **";
P_HTM[9048]="*pariññeyyaṃ gavampatīti.* **";
P_HTM[9049]="*3. Mahāpariḷāhasuttaṃ**In a Rosewood Forest*";
P_HTM[9050]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā kosambiyaṃ viharati sīsapāvane.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Kosambī in a rosewood forest.*";
P_HTM[9051]="*Atha kho bhagavā parittāni sīsapāpaṇṇāni pāṇinā gahetvā bhikkhū āmantesi:**Then the Buddha picked up a few rosewood leaves in his hand and addressed the mendicants:*";
P_HTM[9052]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhikkhave,**“What do you think, mendicants?*";
P_HTM[9053]="*katamaṃ nu kho bahutaraṃ—**Which is more:*";
P_HTM[9054]="*yāni vā mayā parittāni sīsapāpaṇṇāni pāṇinā gahitāni yadidaṃ upari sīsapāvane”ti?**the few leaves in my hand, or those in the forest above me?”*";
P_HTM[9055]="*“Appamattakāni, bhante, bhagavatā parittāni sīsapāpaṇṇāni pāṇinā gahitāni;**“Sir, the few leaves in your hand are a tiny amount.*";
P_HTM[9056]="*atha kho etāneva bahutarāni yadidaṃ upari sīsapāvane”ti.**There are far more leaves in the forest above.”*";
P_HTM[9057]="*“Evameva kho, bhikkhave, etadeva bahutaraṃ yaṃ vo mayā abhiññāya anakkhātaṃ.**“In the same way, there is much more that I have directly known but have not explained to you. What I have explained is a tiny amount.*";
P_HTM[9058]="*Kasmā cetaṃ, bhikkhave, mayā anakkhātaṃ?**And why haven’t I explained it?*";
P_HTM[9059]="*Na hetaṃ, bhikkhave, atthasaṃhitaṃ nādibrahmacariyakaṃ na nibbidāya na virāgāya na nirodhāya na upasamāya na abhiññāya na sambodhāya na nibbānāya saṃvattati;**Because it’s not beneficial or relevant to the fundamentals of the spiritual life. It doesn’t lead to disillusionment, dispassion, cessation, peace, insight, awakening, and extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[9060]="*tasmā taṃ mayā anakkhātaṃ.**That’s why I haven’t explained it.*";
P_HTM[9061]="*Kiñca, bhikkhave, mayā akkhātaṃ?**And what have I explained?*";
P_HTM[9062]="*‘Idaṃ dukkhan’ti, bhikkhave, mayā akkhātaṃ, ‘ayaṃ dukkhasamudayo’ti mayā akkhātaṃ, ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodho’ti mayā akkhātaṃ, ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti mayā akkhātaṃ.**I have explained: ‘This is suffering’ … ‘This is the origin of suffering’ … ‘This is the cessation of suffering’ … ‘This is the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering’.*";
P_HTM[9063]="*Kasmā cetaṃ, bhikkhave, mayā akkhātaṃ?**And why have I explained this?*";
P_HTM[9064]="*Etañhi, bhikkhave, atthasaṃhitaṃ etaṃ ādibrahmacariyakaṃ etaṃ nibbidāya virāgāya nirodhāya upasamāya abhiññāya sambodhāya nibbānāya saṃvattati;**Because it’s beneficial and relevant to the fundamentals of the spiritual life. It leads to disillusionment, dispassion, cessation, peace, insight, awakening, and extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[9065]="*tasmā taṃ mayā akkhātaṃ.**That’s why I’ve explained it.*";
P_HTM[9066]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yogo karaṇīyo … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation …”*";
P_HTM[9067]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9068]="*4. Kūṭāgārasuttaṃ**Acacia Leaves*";
P_HTM[9069]="*“Yo, bhikkhave, evaṃ vadeyya:**“Mendicants, suppose someone were to say:*";
P_HTM[9070]="*‘ahaṃ dukkhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ yathābhūtaṃ anabhisamecca, dukkhasamudayaṃ ariyasaccaṃ yathābhūtaṃ anabhisamecca, dukkhanirodhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ yathābhūtaṃ anabhisamecca, dukkhanirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ ariyasaccaṃ yathābhūtaṃ anabhisamecca sammā dukkhassantaṃ karissāmī’ti—**‘Without truly comprehending the noble truths of suffering, its origin, its cessation, and the path, I will completely make an end of suffering.’*";
P_HTM[9071]="*netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**That is not possible.*";
P_HTM[9072]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, yo evaṃ vadeyya:**It’s as if someone were to say:*";
P_HTM[9073]="*‘ahaṃ khadirapattānaṃ vā saralapattānaṃ vā āmalakapattānaṃ vā puṭaṃ karitvā udakaṃ vā tālapattaṃ vā āharissāmī’ti—**‘I’ll make a basket out of acacia leaves or pine needles or myrobalan leaves, and use it to carry water or a palm frond.’*";
P_HTM[9074]="*netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati;**That is not possible.*";
P_HTM[9075]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, yo evaṃ vadeyya:**In the same way, suppose someone were to say:*";
P_HTM[9076]="*‘ahaṃ dukkhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ yathābhūtaṃ anabhisamecca … pe … dukkhanirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ ariyasaccaṃ yathābhūtaṃ anabhisamecca sammā dukkhassantaṃ karissāmī’ti—**‘Without truly comprehending the noble truths of suffering, its origin, its cessation, and the path, I will completely make an end of suffering.’*";
P_HTM[9077]="*netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**That is not possible.*";
P_HTM[9078]="*Yo ca kho, bhikkhave, evaṃ vadeyya:**But suppose someone were to say:*";
P_HTM[9079]="*‘ahaṃ dukkhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ yathābhūtaṃ abhisamecca, dukkhasamudayaṃ ariyasaccaṃ yathābhūtaṃ abhisamecca, dukkhanirodhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ yathābhūtaṃ abhisamecca, dukkhanirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ ariyasaccaṃ yathābhūtaṃ abhisamecca sammā dukkhassantaṃ karissāmī’ti—**‘After truly comprehending the noble truths of suffering, its origin, its cessation, and the path, I will completely make an end of suffering.’*";
P_HTM[9080]="*ṭhānametaṃ vijjati.**That is possible.*";
P_HTM[9081]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, yo evaṃ vadeyya:**It’s as if someone were to say:*";
P_HTM[9082]="*‘ahaṃ padumapattānaṃ vā palāsapattānaṃ vā māluvapattānaṃ vā puṭaṃ karitvā udakaṃ vā tālapattaṃ vā āharissāmī’ti—**‘I’ll make a basket out of lotus leaves or flame-of-the-forest leaves or camel’s foot creeper leaves, and use it to carry water or a palm frond.’*";
P_HTM[9083]="*ṭhānametaṃ vijjati;**That is possible.*";
P_HTM[9084]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, yo evaṃ vadeyya:**In the same way, suppose someone were to say:*";
P_HTM[9085]="*‘ahaṃ dukkhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ yathābhūtaṃ abhisamecca … pe … dukkhanirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ ariyasaccaṃ yathābhūtaṃ abhisamecca sammā dukkhassantaṃ karissāmī’ti—**‘After truly comprehending the noble truths of suffering, its origin, its cessation, and the path, I will completely make an end of suffering.’*";
P_HTM[9086]="*ṭhānametaṃ vijjati.**That is possible.*";
P_HTM[9087]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yogo karaṇīyo … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation …”*";
P_HTM[9088]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9089]="*5. Vālasuttaṃ**A Stick*";
P_HTM[9090]="*“Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, daṇḍo uparivehāsaṃ khitto sakimpi mūlena nipatati, sakimpi aggena nipatati;**“Mendicants, suppose a stick was tossed up in the air. Sometimes it’d fall on its bottom, sometimes the middle, and sometimes the top.*";
P_HTM[9091]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, avijjānīvaraṇā sattā taṇhāsaṃyojanā sandhāvantā saṃsarantā sakimpi asmā lokā paraṃ lokaṃ gacchanti, sakimpi parasmā lokā imaṃ lokaṃ āgacchanti.**It’s the same for sentient beings roaming and transmigrating, hindered by ignorance and fettered by craving. Sometimes they go from this world to the other world, and sometimes they come from the other world to this world.*";
P_HTM[9092]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[9093]="*Adiṭṭhattā, bhikkhave, catunnaṃ ariyasaccānaṃ.**It’s because they haven’t seen the four noble truths.*";
P_HTM[9094]="*Katamesaṃ catunnaṃ?**What four?*";
P_HTM[9095]="*Dukkhassa ariyasaccassa … pe … dukkhanirodhagāminiyā paṭipadāya ariyasaccassa.**The noble truths of suffering, its origin, its cessation, and the path.*";
P_HTM[9096]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yogo karaṇīyo … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation …”*";
P_HTM[9097]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9098]="*6. Andhakārasuttaṃ**Clothes*";
P_HTM[9099]="*“Āditte, bhikkhave, cele vā sīse vā kimassa karaṇīyan”ti?**“Mendicants, if your clothes or head were on fire, what would you do about it?”*";
P_HTM[9100]="*“Āditte, bhante, cele vā sīse vā, tasseva celassa vā sīsassa vā nibbāpanāya adhimatto chando ca vāyāmo ca ussāho ca ussoḷhī ca appaṭivānī ca sati ca sampajaññañca karaṇīyan”ti.**“Sir, if our clothes or head were on fire, we’d apply intense enthusiasm, effort, zeal, vigor, perseverance, mindfulness, and situational awareness in order to extinguish it.”*";
P_HTM[9101]="*“Ādittaṃ, bhikkhave, celaṃ vā sīsaṃ vā ajjhupekkhitvā amanasikaritvā anabhisametānaṃ catunnaṃ ariyasaccānaṃ yathābhūtaṃ abhisamayāya adhimatto chando ca vāyāmo ca ussāho ca ussoḷhī ca appaṭivānī ca sati ca sampajaññañca karaṇīyaṃ.**“Mendicants, regarding your burning head or clothes with equanimity, not paying attention to them, you should apply intense enthusiasm, effort, zeal, vigor, perseverance, mindfulness, and situational awareness to truly comprehending the four noble truths.*";
P_HTM[9102]="*Katamesaṃ catunnaṃ?**What four?*";
P_HTM[9103]="*Dukkhassa ariyasaccassa … pe … dukkhanirodhagāminiyā paṭipadāya ariyasaccassa.**The noble truths of suffering, its origin, its cessation, and the path.*";
P_HTM[9104]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yogo karaṇīyo … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation …”*";
P_HTM[9105]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9106]="*7. Paṭhamachiggaḷayugasuttaṃ**A Hundred Spears*";
P_HTM[9107]="*“Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, puriso vassasatāyuko vassasatajīvī.**“Mendicants, suppose there was a man with a lifespan of a hundred years.*";
P_HTM[9108]="*Tamenaṃ evaṃ vadeyya:**And someone might say to him:*";
P_HTM[9109]="*‘ehambho purisa, pubbaṇhasamayaṃ taṃ sattisatena hanissanti, majjhanhikasamayaṃ sattisatena hanissanti, sāyanhasamayaṃ sattisatena hanissanti.**‘Come now, my good man, they’ll strike you with a hundred spears in the morning, at midday, and in the late afternoon.*";
P_HTM[9110]="*So kho tvaṃ, ambho purisa, divase divase tīhi tīhi sattisatehi haññamāno vassasatāyuko vassasatajīvī vassasatassa accayena anabhisametāni cattāri ariyasaccāni abhisamessasī’ti.**And you’ll live for a hundred years being struck with three hundred spears every day. But when a hundred years have passed, you will comprehend the four noble truths for the first time.’*";
P_HTM[9111]="*Atthavasikena, bhikkhave, kulaputtena alaṃ upagantuṃ.**For an earnest and gentleman this is sufficient reason to submit.*";
P_HTM[9112]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[9113]="*Anamataggoyaṃ, bhikkhave, saṃsāro;**Transmigration has no known beginning.*";
P_HTM[9114]="*pubbā koṭi nappaññāyati sattippahārānaṃ asippahārānaṃ usuppahārānaṃ pharasuppahārānaṃ.**No first point is found of blows by spears, swords, arrows, and axes.*";
P_HTM[9115]="*Evañcetaṃ, bhikkhave, assa.**Now this may be so.*";
P_HTM[9116]="*Na kho panāhaṃ, bhikkhave, saha dukkhena, saha domanassena catunnaṃ ariyasaccānaṃ abhisamayaṃ vadāmi;**But the comprehension of the four noble truths doesn’t come with pain or sadness, I say.*";
P_HTM[9117]="*api cāhaṃ, bhikkhave, sahāva sukhena, sahāva somanassena catunnaṃ ariyasaccānaṃ abhisamayaṃ vadāmi.**Rather, the comprehension of the four noble truths comes only with pleasure and happiness, I say.*";
P_HTM[9118]="*Katamesaṃ catunnaṃ?**What four?*";
P_HTM[9119]="*Dukkhassa ariyasaccassa … pe … dukkhanirodhagāminiyā paṭipadāya ariyasaccassa.**The noble truths of suffering, its origin, its cessation, and the path.*";
P_HTM[9120]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yogo karaṇīyo … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation …”*";
P_HTM[9121]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9122]="*8. Dutiyachiggaḷayugasuttaṃ**Living Creatures*";
P_HTM[9123]="*“Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, puriso yaṃ imasmiṃ jambudīpe tiṇakaṭṭhasākhāpalāsaṃ tacchetvā ekajjhaṃ saṃhareyya;**Suppose a person was to strip all the grass, sticks, branches, and leaves in India, gather them together into one pile,*";
P_HTM[9124]="*ekajjhaṃ saṃharitvā sūlaṃ kareyya.**and make them into stakes.*";
P_HTM[9125]="*Sūlaṃ karitvā ye mahāsamudde mahantakā pāṇā te mahantakesu sūlesu āvuneyya, ye mahāsamudde majjhimakā pāṇā te majjhimakesu sūlesu āvuneyya, ye mahāsamudde sukhumakā pāṇā te sukhumakesu sūlesu āvuneyya.**Then they’d impale the large creatures in the ocean on large stakes; the medium-sized creatures on medium-sized stakes; and the small creatures on small stakes.*";
P_HTM[9126]="*Apariyādinnā ca, bhikkhave, mahāsamudde oḷārikā pāṇā assu.**They wouldn’t run out of sizable creatures in the ocean before*";
P_HTM[9127]="*Atha imasmiṃ jambudīpe tiṇakaṭṭhasākhāpalāsaṃ parikkhayaṃ pariyādānaṃ gaccheyya.**using up all the grass, sticks, branches, and leaves in India.*";
P_HTM[9128]="*Ito bahutarā kho, bhikkhave, mahāsamudde sukhumakā pāṇā, ye na sukarā sūlesu āvunituṃ.**There are far more small creatures in the ocean than this, so it wouldn’t be feasible to impale them on stakes.*";
P_HTM[9129]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[9130]="*Sukhumattā, bhikkhave, attabhāvassa.**Because of the small size of those life-forms.*";
P_HTM[9131]="*Evaṃ mahā kho, bhikkhave, apāyo.**That’s how big the plane of loss is.*";
P_HTM[9132]="*Evaṃ mahantasmā kho, bhikkhave, apāyasmā parimutto diṭṭhisampanno puggalo ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.**A person accomplished in view, exempt from that vast plane of loss, truly understands: ‘This is suffering’ … ‘This is the origin of suffering’ … ‘This is the cessation of suffering’ … ‘This is the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering’.*";
P_HTM[9133]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yogo karaṇīyo … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation …”*";
P_HTM[9134]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9135]="*9. Paṭhamasinerupabbatarājasuttaṃ**The Simile of the Sun (1st)*";
P_HTM[9136]="*“Sūriyassa, bhikkhave, udayato etaṃ pubbaṅgamaṃ etaṃ pubbanimittaṃ, yadidaṃ—aruṇuggaṃ.**“Mendicants, the dawn is the forerunner and precursor of the sunrise.*";
P_HTM[9137]="*Evameva kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno catunnaṃ ariyasaccānaṃ yathābhūtaṃ abhisamayāya etaṃ pubbaṅgamaṃ etaṃ pubbanimittaṃ, yadidaṃ—sammādiṭṭhi.**In the same way, right view is the forerunner and precursor of truly comprehending the four noble truths.*";
P_HTM[9138]="*Tassetaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno pāṭikaṅkhaṃ:**A mendicant with right view can expect to truly understand:*";
P_HTM[9139]="*‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānissati … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānissati.**‘This is suffering’ … ‘This is the origin of suffering’ … ‘This is the cessation of suffering’ … ‘This is the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering’.*";
P_HTM[9140]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yogo karaṇīyo … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation …”*";
P_HTM[9141]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9142]="*10. Dutiyasinerupabbatarājasuttaṃ**The Simile of the Sun (2nd)*";
P_HTM[9143]="*“Yāvakīvañca, bhikkhave, candimasūriyā loke nuppajjanti, neva tāva mahato ālokassa pātubhāvo hoti mahato obhāsassa.**“Mendicants, as long as the moon and the sun don’t arise in the world, no great light or great radiance appears.*";
P_HTM[9144]="*Andhatamaṃ tadā hoti andhakāratimisā.**Darkness prevails then, utter darkness.*";
P_HTM[9145]="*Neva tāva rattindivā paññāyanti, na māsaddhamāsā paññāyanti, na utusaṃvaccharā paññāyanti.**Day and night aren’t found, nor months and fortnights, nor seasons and years.*";
P_HTM[9146]="*Yato ca kho, bhikkhave, candimasūriyā loke uppajjanti, atha mahato ālokassa pātubhāvo hoti mahato obhāsassa.**But when the moon and the sun arise in the world, a great light, a great radiance appears.*";
P_HTM[9147]="*Neva andhakāratamaṃ tadā hoti na andhakāratimisā.**Darkness no longer prevails.*";
P_HTM[9148]="*Atha rattindivā paññāyanti, māsaddhamāsā paññāyanti, utusaṃvaccharā paññāyanti.**Day and night are found, and months and fortnights, and seasons and years.*";
P_HTM[9149]="*Evameva kho, bhikkhave, yāvakīvañca tathāgato loke nuppajjati arahaṃ sammāsambuddho, neva tāva mahato ālokassa pātubhāvo hoti mahato obhāsassa.**In the same way, as long as the Realized One doesn’t arise in the world, no great light or great radiance appears.*";
P_HTM[9150]="*Andhatamaṃ tadā hoti andhakāratimisā.**Darkness prevails then, utter darkness.*";
P_HTM[9151]="*Neva tāva catunnaṃ ariyasaccānaṃ ācikkhaṇā hoti desanā paññāpanā paṭṭhapanā vivaraṇā vibhajanā uttānīkammaṃ.**There’s no explanation of the four noble truths, no teaching, advocating, establishing, clarifying, analyzing, and revealing of them.*";
P_HTM[9152]="*Yato ca kho, bhikkhave, tathāgato loke uppajjati arahaṃ sammāsambuddho, atha mahato ālokassa pātubhāvo hoti mahato obhāsassa.**But when the Realized One arises in the world, a great light, a great radiance appears.*";
P_HTM[9153]="*Neva andhatamaṃ tadā hoti na andhakāratimisā.**Darkness no longer prevails.*";
P_HTM[9154]="*Atha kho catunnaṃ ariyasaccānaṃ ācikkhaṇā hoti desanā paññāpanā paṭṭhapanā vivaraṇā vibhajanā uttānīkammaṃ.**Then there’s the explanation of the four noble truths, the teaching, advocating, establishing, clarifying, analyzing, and revealing of them.*";
P_HTM[9155]="*Katamesaṃ catunnaṃ?**What four?*";
P_HTM[9156]="*Dukkhassa ariyasaccassa … pe … dukkhanirodhagāminiyā paṭipadāya ariyasaccassa.**The noble truths of suffering, its origin, its cessation, and the path.*";
P_HTM[9157]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yogo karaṇīyo … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation …”*";
P_HTM[9158]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9159]="*9. Tatiyaāmakadhaññapeyyālavaggo**In a Rosewood Forest*";
P_HTM[9160]="*1. Nakhasikhasuttaṃ**A Boundary Pillar*";
P_HTM[9161]="*“Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānanti … pe …**“Mendicants, there are ascetics and brahmins who don’t truly understand about suffering, its origin, its cessation, and the path.*";
P_HTM[9162]="*‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānanti, te aññassa samaṇassa vā brāhmaṇassa vā mukhaṃ ullokenti:**They gaze up at the face of another ascetic or brahmin, thinking:*";
P_HTM[9163]="*‘ayaṃ nūna bhavaṃ jānaṃ jānāti, passaṃ passatī’ti.**‘Surely this worthy one knows and sees.’*";
P_HTM[9164]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, tūlapicu vā kappāsapicu vā lahuko vātūpādāno same bhūmibhāge nikkhitto.**Suppose there was a light tuft of cotton-wool or kapok which was taken up by the wind and landed on level ground.*";
P_HTM[9165]="*Tamenaṃ puratthimo vāto pacchimena saṃhareyya, pacchimo vāto puratthimena saṃhareyya, uttaro vāto dakkhiṇena saṃhareyya, dakkhiṇo vāto uttarena saṃhareyya.**The east wind wafts it west; the west wind wafts it east; the north wind wafts it south; and the south wind wafts it north.*";
P_HTM[9166]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[9167]="*Lahukattā, bhikkhave, kappāsapicuno.**It’s because the tuft of cotton-wool is so light.*";
P_HTM[9168]="*Evameva kho, bhikkhave, ye hi keci samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānanti … pe …**In the same way, there are ascetics and brahmins who don’t truly understand about suffering, its origin, its cessation, and the path.*";
P_HTM[9169]="*‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānanti, te aññassa samaṇassa vā brāhmaṇassa vā mukhaṃ ullokenti:**They gaze up at the face of another ascetic or brahmin, thinking:*";
P_HTM[9170]="*‘ayaṃ nūna bhavaṃ jānaṃ jānāti, passaṃ passatī’ti.**‘Surely this worthy one knows and sees.’*";
P_HTM[9171]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[9172]="*Adiṭṭhattā, bhikkhave, catunnaṃ ariyasaccānaṃ.**It’s because they haven’t seen the four noble truths.*";
P_HTM[9173]="*Ye ca kho keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānanti … pe …**There are ascetics and brahmins who truly understand about suffering, its origin, its cessation, and the path.*";
P_HTM[9174]="*‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānanti, te na aññassa samaṇassa vā brāhmaṇassa vā mukhaṃ ullokenti:**They don’t gaze up at the face of another ascetic or brahmin, thinking:*";
P_HTM[9175]="*‘ayaṃ nūna bhavaṃ jānaṃ jānāti, passaṃ passatī’ti.**‘Surely this worthy one knows and sees.’*";
P_HTM[9176]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, ayokhīlo vā indakhīlo vā gambhīranemo sunikhāto acalo asampakampī.**Suppose there was an iron pillar or a boundary pillar with deep foundations, firmly embedded, imperturbable and unshakable.*";
P_HTM[9177]="*Puratthimāya cepi disāya āgaccheyya bhusā vātavuṭṭhi, neva saṅkampeyya na sampakampeyya na sampacāleyya; pacchimāya cepi disāya … pe … uttarāya cepi disāya … pe … dakkhiṇāya cepi disāya āgaccheyya bhusā vātavuṭṭhi, neva saṅkampeyya na sampakampeyya na sampacāleyya.**Even if violent storms were to blow up out of the east, the west, the north, and the south, they couldn’t make it shake or rock or tremble.*";
P_HTM[9178]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[9179]="*Gambhīrattā, bhikkhave, nemassa sunikhātattā indakhīlassa.**It’s because that boundary pillar is firmly embedded, with deep foundations.*";
P_HTM[9180]="*Evameva kho, bhikkhave, ye ca kho keci samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānanti … pe …**In the same way, there are ascetics and brahmins who truly understand about suffering, its origin, its cessation, and the path.*";
P_HTM[9181]="*ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānanti, te na aññassa samaṇassa vā brāhmaṇassa vā mukhaṃ ullokenti:**They don’t gaze up at the face of another ascetic or brahmin, thinking:*";
P_HTM[9182]="*‘ayaṃ nūna bhavaṃ jānaṃ jānāti, passaṃ passatī’ti.**‘Surely this worthy one knows and sees.’*";
P_HTM[9183]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[9184]="*Sudiṭṭhattā, bhikkhave, catunnaṃ ariyasaccānaṃ.**It’s because they have clearly seen the four noble truths.*";
P_HTM[9185]="*Katamesaṃ catunnaṃ?**What four?*";
P_HTM[9186]="*Dukkhassa ariyasaccassa … pe … dukkhanirodhagāminiyā paṭipadāya ariyasaccassa.**The noble truths of suffering, its origin, its cessation, and the path.*";
P_HTM[9187]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yogo karaṇīyo … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation …”*";
P_HTM[9188]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9189]="*2. Pokkharaṇīsuttaṃ**Looking For a Debate*";
P_HTM[9190]="*“Yo hi koci, bhikkhave, bhikkhu ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti … pe …**“Mendicants, take any mendicant who truly understands: ‘This is suffering’ … ‘This is the origin of suffering’ … ‘This is the cessation of suffering’ … ‘This is the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering’.*";
P_HTM[9191]="*‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti, puratthimāya cepi disāya āgaccheyya samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā vādatthiko vādagavesī:**An ascetic or brahmin might come from the east, west, north, or south wanting to debate, seeking a debate, thinking:*";
P_HTM[9192]="*‘vādamassa āropessāmī’ti, taṃ vata sahadhammena saṅkampessati vā sampakampessati vā sampacālessati vāti—netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**‘I’ll refute their doctrine!’ It’s simply impossible for them to legitimately make that mendicant shake or rock or tremble.*";
P_HTM[9193]="*Pacchimāya cepi disāya … pe …* **";
P_HTM[9194]="*uttarāya cepi disāya … pe …* **";
P_HTM[9195]="*dakkhiṇāya cepi disāya āgaccheyya samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā vādatthiko vādagavesī:* **";
P_HTM[9196]="*‘vādamassa āropessāmī’ti, taṃ vata sahadhammena saṅkampessati vā sampakampessati vā sampacālessati vāti—netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.* **";
P_HTM[9197]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, silāyūpo soḷasa kukkuko.**Suppose there was a stone pillar, sixteen feet long.*";
P_HTM[9198]="*Tassassu aṭṭha kukku heṭṭhā nemaṅgamā, aṭṭha kukku uparinemassa.**Eight feet were buried underground, and eight above ground.*";
P_HTM[9199]="*Puratthimāya cepi disāya āgaccheyya bhusā vātavuṭṭhi, neva saṅkampeyya na sampakampeyya na sampacāleyya; pacchimāya cepi disāya … pe … uttarāya cepi disāya … pe … dakkhiṇāya cepi disāya āgaccheyya bhusā vātavuṭṭhi, neva saṅkampeyya na sampakampeyya na sampacāleyya.**Even if violent storms were to blow up out of the east, the west, the north, and the south, they couldn’t make it shake or rock or tremble.*";
P_HTM[9200]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[9201]="*Gambhīrattā, bhikkhave, nemassa sunikhātattā silāyūpassa.**It’s because that boundary pillar is firmly embedded, with deep foundations.*";
P_HTM[9202]="*Evameva kho, bhikkhave, yo hi koci bhikkhu ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti;**In the same way, take any mendicant who truly understands: ‘This is suffering’ … ‘This is the origin of suffering’ … ‘This is the cessation of suffering’ … ‘This is the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering’.*";
P_HTM[9203]="*puratthimāya cepi disāya āgaccheyya samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā vādatthiko vādagavesī ‘vādamassa āropessāmī’ti, taṃ vata sahadhammena saṅkampessati vā sampakampessati vā sampacālessati vāti—netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**An ascetic or brahmin might come from the east, west, north, or south wanting to debate, seeking a debate, thinking: ‘I’ll refute their doctrine!’ It’s simply impossible for them to legitimately make that mendicant shake or rock or tremble.*";
P_HTM[9204]="*Pacchimāya cepi disāya … pe …* **";
P_HTM[9205]="*uttarāya cepi disāya … pe …* **";
P_HTM[9206]="*dakkhiṇāya cepi disāya āgaccheyya samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā vādatthiko vādagavesī: ‘vādamassa āropessāmī’ti, taṃ vata sahadhammena saṅkampessati vā sampakampessati vā sampacālessati vāti—netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.* **";
P_HTM[9207]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[9208]="*Sudiṭṭhattā, bhikkhave, catunnaṃ ariyasaccānaṃ.**It’s because they have clearly seen the four noble truths.*";
P_HTM[9209]="*Katamesaṃ catunnaṃ?**What four?*";
P_HTM[9210]="*Dukkhassa ariyasaccassa … pe … dukkhanirodhagāminiyā paṭipadāya ariyasaccassa.**The noble truths of suffering, its origin, its cessation, and the path.*";
P_HTM[9211]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yogo karaṇīyo … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation …”*";
P_HTM[9212]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9213]="*Sīsapāvanavaggo catuttho.* **";
P_HTM[9214]="*Sīsapā khadiro daṇḍo,* **";
P_HTM[9215]="*celā sattisatena ca;* **";
P_HTM[9216]="*Pāṇā sūriyūpamā dvedhā,* **";
P_HTM[9217]="*indakhīlo ca vādinoti.* **";
P_HTM[9218]="*3. Paṭhamasaṃbhejjasuttaṃ**Speculation About the World*";
P_HTM[9219]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā rājagahe viharati veḷuvane kalandakanivāpe.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Rājagaha, in the Bamboo Grove, the squirrels’ feeding ground.*";
P_HTM[9220]="*Tatra kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**There the Buddha addressed the mendicants:*";
P_HTM[9221]="*“bhūtapubbaṃ, bhikkhave, aññataro puriso rājagahā nikkhamitvā ‘lokacintaṃ cintessāmī’ti yena sumāgadhā pokkharaṇī tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā sumāgadhāya pokkharaṇiyā tīre nisīdi lokacintaṃ cintento.**“Once upon a time, mendicants, a certain person left Rājagaha, thinking ‘I’ll speculate about the world.’ They went to the Sumāgadhā lotus pond and sat down on the bank speculating about the world.*";
P_HTM[9222]="*Addasā kho, bhikkhave, so puriso sumāgadhāya pokkharaṇiyā tīre caturaṅginiṃ senaṃ bhisamuḷālaṃ pavisantaṃ.**Then that person saw an army of four divisions enter a lotus stalk.*";
P_HTM[9223]="*Disvānassa etadahosi:**When he saw this he thought,*";
P_HTM[9224]="*‘ummattosmi nāmāhaṃ, vicetosmi nāmāhaṃ.**‘I’ve gone mad, really, I’ve lost my mind!*";
P_HTM[9225]="*Yaṃ loke natthi taṃ mayā diṭṭhan’ti.**I’m seeing things that don’t exist in the world.’*";
P_HTM[9226]="*Atha kho so, bhikkhave, puriso nagaraṃ pavisitvā mahājanakāyassa ārocesi:**Then that person entered the city and informed a large crowd,*";
P_HTM[9227]="*‘ummattosmi nāmāhaṃ, bhante, vicetosmi nāmāhaṃ, bhante.**‘I’ve gone mad, really, I’ve lost my mind!*";
P_HTM[9228]="*Yaṃ loke natthi taṃ mayā diṭṭhan’ti.**I’m seeing things that don’t exist in the world.’*";
P_HTM[9229]="*‘Kathaṃ pana tvaṃ, ambho purisa, ummatto kathaṃ viceto?**‘But how is it that you’re mad? How have you lost your mind?*";
P_HTM[9230]="*Kiñca loke natthi yaṃ tayā diṭṭhan’ti?**And what have you seen that doesn’t exist in the world?’*";
P_HTM[9231]="*‘Idhāhaṃ, bhante, rājagahā nikkhamitvā “lokacintaṃ cintessāmī”ti yena sumāgadhā pokkharaṇī tenupasaṅkamiṃ; upasaṅkamitvā sumāgadhāya pokkharaṇiyā tīre nisīdiṃ lokacintaṃ cintento.**‘Sirs, I left Rājagaha, thinking “I’ll speculate about the world.” I went to the Sumāgadhā lotus pond and sat down on the bank speculating about the world.*";
P_HTM[9232]="*Addasaṃ khvāhaṃ, bhante, sumāgadhāya pokkharaṇiyā tīre caturaṅginiṃ senaṃ bhisamuḷālaṃ pavisantaṃ.**Then I saw an army of four divisions enter a lotus stalk.*";
P_HTM[9233]="*Evaṃ khvāhaṃ, bhante, ummatto evaṃ viceto.**That’s why I’m mad, that’s why I’ve lost my mind.*";
P_HTM[9234]="*Idañca loke natthi yaṃ mayā diṭṭhan’ti.**And that’s what I’ve seen that doesn’t exist in the world.’*";
P_HTM[9235]="*‘Taggha tvaṃ, ambho purisa, ummatto taggha viceto.**‘Well, mister, you’re definitely mad, you’ve definitely lost your mind.*";
P_HTM[9236]="*Idañca loke natthi yaṃ tayā diṭṭhan’ti.**And you’re seeing things that don’t exist in the world.’*";
P_HTM[9237]="*Taṃ kho pana, bhikkhave, so puriso bhūtaṃyeva addasa, no abhūtaṃ.**But what that person saw was in fact real, not unreal.*";
P_HTM[9238]="*Bhūtapubbaṃ, bhikkhave, devāsurasaṅgāmo samupabyūḷho ahosi.**Once upon a time, a battle was fought between the gods and the demons.*";
P_HTM[9239]="*Tasmiṃ kho pana, bhikkhave, saṅgāme devā jiniṃsu, asurā parājiniṃsu.**In that battle the gods won and the demons lost.*";
P_HTM[9240]="*Parājitā ca kho, bhikkhave, asurā bhītā bhisamuḷālena asurapuraṃ pavisiṃsu devānaṃyeva mohayamānā.**The defeated and terrified demons entered the demon city through the lotus stalk only to confuse the gods.*";
P_HTM[9241]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, mā lokacintaṃ cintetha:**So mendicants, don’t speculate about the world.*";
P_HTM[9242]="*‘sassato loko’ti vā ‘asassato loko’ti vā, ‘antavā loko’ti vā ‘anantavā loko’ti vā, ‘taṃ jīvaṃ taṃ sarīran’ti vā ‘aññaṃ jīvaṃ aññaṃ sarīran’ti vā, ‘hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā’ti vā ‘na hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā’ti vā, ‘hoti ca na ca hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā’ti vā, ‘neva hoti na na hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā’ti vā.**For example: the world is eternal, or not eternal, or finite, or infinite; the soul and the body are the same thing, or they are different things; after death, a Realized One exists, or doesn’t exist, or both exists and doesn’t exist, or neither exists nor doesn’t exist.*";
P_HTM[9243]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[9244]="*Nesā, bhikkhave, cintā atthasaṃhitā nādibrahmacariyakā na nibbidāya na virāgāya na nirodhāya na upasamāya na abhiññāya na sambodhāya na nibbānāya saṃvattati.**Because those thoughts aren’t beneficial or relevant to the fundamentals of the spiritual life. They don’t lead to disillusionment, dispassion, cessation, peace, insight, awakening, and extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[9245]="*Cintentā kho tumhe, bhikkhave, ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti cinteyyātha … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti cinteyyātha.**When you think something up, you should think: ‘This is suffering’ … ‘This is the origin of suffering’ … ‘This is the cessation of suffering’ … ‘This is the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering’.*";
P_HTM[9246]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[9247]="*Esā, bhikkhave, cintā atthasaṃhitā esā ādibrahmacariyakā esā nibbidāya virāgāya nirodhāya upasamāya abhiññāya sambodhāya nibbānāya saṃvattati.**Because those thoughts are beneficial and relevant to the fundamentals of the spiritual life. They lead to disillusionment, dispassion, cessation, peace, insight, awakening, and extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[9248]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yogo karaṇīyo … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation …”*";
P_HTM[9249]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9250]="*4. Dutiyasaṃbhejjasuttaṃ**A Cliff*";
P_HTM[9251]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā rājagahe viharati gijjhakūṭe pabbate.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Rājagaha, on the Vulture’s Peak Mountain.*";
P_HTM[9252]="*Atha kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**Then the Buddha said to the mendicants,*";
P_HTM[9253]="*“āyāma, bhikkhave, yena paṭibhānakūṭo tenupasaṅkamissāma divāvihārāyā”ti.**“Come, mendicants, let’s go to Inspiration Peak for the day’s meditation.*";
P_HTM[9254]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Yes, sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[9255]="*Atha kho bhagavā sambahulehi bhikkhūhi saddhiṃ yena paṭibhānakūṭo tenupasaṅkami.**Then the Buddha together with several mendicants went to Inspiration Peak.*";
P_HTM[9256]="*Addasā kho aññataro bhikkhu paṭibhānakūṭe mahantaṃ papātaṃ.**A certain mendicant saw the big cliff there*";
P_HTM[9257]="*Disvāna bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**and said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[9258]="*“mahā vatāyaṃ, bhante, papāto subhayānako, bhante, papāto.**“Sir, that big cliff is really huge and scary.*";
P_HTM[9259]="*Atthi nu kho, bhante, imamhā papātā añño papāto mahantataro ca bhayānakataro cā”ti?**Is there any other cliff bigger and scarier than this one?”*";
P_HTM[9260]="*“Atthi kho, bhikkhu, imamhā papātā añño papāto mahantataro ca bhayānakataro cā”ti.**“There is, mendicant.”*";
P_HTM[9261]="*“Katamo pana, bhante, imamhā papātā añño papāto mahantataro ca bhayānakataro cā”ti?**“But sir, what is it?”*";
P_HTM[9262]="*“Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānanti, ‘ayaṃ dukkhasamudayo’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānanti, ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodho’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānanti, ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānanti,**“Mendicant, there are ascetics and brahmins who don’t truly understand about suffering, its origin, its cessation, and the path.*";
P_HTM[9263]="*te jātisaṃvattanikesu saṅkhāresu abhiramanti, jarāsaṃvattanikesu saṅkhāresu abhiramanti, maraṇasaṃvattanikesu saṅkhāresu abhiramanti, sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsasaṃvattanikesu saṅkhāresu abhiramanti.**They take pleasure in choices that lead to rebirth, old age, and death, to sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress.*";
P_HTM[9264]="*Te jātisaṃvattanikesu saṅkhāresu abhiratā jarāsaṃvattanikesu saṅkhāresu abhiratā maraṇasaṃvattanikesu saṅkhāresu abhiratā sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsasaṃvattanikesu saṅkhāresu abhiratā jātisaṃvattanikepi saṅkhāre abhisaṅkharonti, jarāsaṃvattanikepi saṅkhāre abhisaṅkharonti, maraṇasaṃvattanikepi saṅkhāre abhisaṅkharonti, sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsasaṃvattanikepi saṅkhāre abhisaṅkharonti.**Since they take pleasure in such choices, they continue to make them.*";
P_HTM[9265]="*Te jātisaṃvattanikepi saṅkhāre abhisaṅkharitvā jarāsaṃvattanikepi saṅkhāre abhisaṅkharitvā maraṇasaṃvattanikepi saṅkhāre abhisaṅkharitvā sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsasaṃvattanikepi saṅkhāre abhisaṅkharitvā jātipapātampi papatanti, jarāpapātampi papatanti, maraṇapapātampi papatanti, sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsapapātampi papatanti.**Having made choices that lead to rebirth, old age, and death, to sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress, they fall down the cliff of rebirth, old age, and death, of sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress.*";
P_HTM[9266]="*Te na parimuccanti jātiyā jarāya maraṇena sokehi paridevehi dukkhehi domanassehi upāyāsehi.**They’re not freed from rebirth, old age, and death, from sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress.*";
P_HTM[9267]="*‘Na parimuccanti dukkhasmā’ti vadāmi.**They’re not freed from suffering, I say.*";
P_HTM[9268]="*Ye ca kho keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānanti … pe …**There are ascetics and brahmins who truly understand about suffering, its origin, its cessation, and the path.*";
P_HTM[9269]="*‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānanti, te jātisaṃvattanikesu saṅkhāresu nābhiramanti, jarāsaṃvattanikesu saṅkhāresu nābhiramanti, maraṇasaṃvattanikesu saṅkhāresu nābhiramanti, sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsasaṃvattanikesu saṅkhāresu nābhiramanti.**They don’t take pleasure in choices that lead to rebirth, old age, and death, to sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress.*";
P_HTM[9270]="*Te jātisaṃvattanikesu saṅkhāresu anabhiratā, jarāsaṃvattanikesu saṅkhāresu anabhiratā, maraṇasaṃvattanikesu saṅkhāresu anabhiratā, sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsasaṃvattanikesu saṅkhāresu anabhiratā, jātisaṃvattanikepi saṅkhāre nābhisaṅkharonti, jarāsaṃvattanikepi saṅkhāre nābhisaṅkharonti, maraṇasaṃvattanikepi saṅkhāre nābhisaṅkharonti, sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsasaṃvattanikepi saṅkhāre nābhisaṅkharonti.**Since they don’t take pleasure in such choices, they stop making them.*";
P_HTM[9271]="*Te jātisaṃvattanikepi saṅkhāre anabhisaṅkharitvā, jarāsaṃvattanikepi saṅkhāre anabhisaṅkharitvā, maraṇasaṃvattanikepi saṅkhāre anabhisaṅkharitvā, sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsasaṃvattanikepi saṅkhāre anabhisaṅkharitvā, jātipapātampi nappapatanti, jarāpapātampi nappapatanti, maraṇapapātampi nappapatanti, sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsapapātampi nappapatanti.**Having stopped making choices that lead to rebirth, old age, and death, to sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress, they don’t fall down the cliff of rebirth, old age, and death, of sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress.*";
P_HTM[9272]="*Te parimuccanti jātiyā jarāya maraṇena sokehi paridevehi dukkhehi domanassehi upāyāsehi.**They’re freed from rebirth, old age, and death, from sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress.*";
P_HTM[9273]="*‘Parimuccanti dukkhasmā’ti vadāmi.**They’re freed from suffering, I say.*";
P_HTM[9274]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yogo karaṇīyo … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation …”*";
P_HTM[9275]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9276]="*5. Paṭhamamahāpathavīsuttaṃ**The Mighty Fever*";
P_HTM[9277]="*“Atthi, bhikkhave, mahāpariḷāho nāma nirayo.**“Mendicants, there is a hell called ‘The Mighty Fever’.*";
P_HTM[9278]="*Tattha yaṃ kiñci cakkhunā rūpaṃ passati, aniṭṭharūpaññeva passati no iṭṭharūpaṃ; akantarūpaññeva passati no kantarūpaṃ; amanāparūpaññeva passati no manāparūpaṃ.**There, whatever sight you see with your eye is unlikable, not likable; undesirable, not desirable; unpleasant, not pleasant.*";
P_HTM[9279]="*Yaṃ kiñci sotena saddaṃ suṇāti … pe …**Whatever sound you hear … Whatever odor you smell … Whatever flavor you taste …*";
P_HTM[9280]="*yaṃ kiñci kāyena phoṭṭhabbaṃ phusati … pe …**Whatever touch you feel …*";
P_HTM[9281]="*yaṃ kiñci manasā dhammaṃ vijānāti, aniṭṭharūpaññeva vijānāti no iṭṭharūpaṃ; akantarūpaññeva vijānāti no kantarūpaṃ; amanāparūpaññeva vijānāti no manāparūpan”ti.**Whatever thought you know with your mind is unlikable, not likable; undesirable, not desirable; unpleasant, not pleasant.”*";
P_HTM[9282]="*Evaṃ vutte, aññataro bhikkhu bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When he said this, one of the mendicants said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[9283]="*“mahā vata so, bhante, pariḷāho, sumahā vata so, bhante, pariḷāho.**“Sir, that fever really is mighty, so very mighty.*";
P_HTM[9284]="*Atthi nu kho, bhante, etamhā pariḷāhā añño pariḷāho mahantataro ceva bhayānakataro cā”ti?**Is there any other fever more mighty and terrifying than this one?”*";
P_HTM[9285]="*“Atthi kho, bhikkhu, etamhā pariḷāhā añño pariḷāho mahantataro ca bhayānakataro cā”ti.**“There is, mendicant.”*";
P_HTM[9286]="*“Katamo pana, bhante, etamhā pariḷāhā añño pariḷāho mahantataro ca bhayānakataro cā”ti?**“But sir, what is it?”*";
P_HTM[9287]="*“Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānanti … pe …**“Mendicants, there are ascetics and brahmins who don’t truly understand about suffering, its origin, its cessation, and the path.*";
P_HTM[9288]="*‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānanti, te jātisaṃvattanikesu saṅkhāresu abhiramanti … pe …**They take pleasure in choices that lead to rebirth …*";
P_HTM[9289]="*abhiratā … pe … abhisaṅkharonti … pe …**They continue to make such choices …*";
P_HTM[9290]="*abhisaṅkharitvā jātipariḷāhenapi pariḍayhanti, jarāpariḷāhenapi pariḍayhanti, maraṇapariḷāhenapi pariḍayhanti, sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsapariḷāhenapi pariḍayhanti.**Having made such choices, they burn with the fever of rebirth, old age, and death, of sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress.*";
P_HTM[9291]="*Te na parimuccanti jātiyā jarāya maraṇena sokehi paridevehi dukkhehi domanassehi upāyāsehi.**They’re not freed from rebirth, old age, and death, from sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress.*";
P_HTM[9292]="*‘Na parimuccanti dukkhasmā’ti vadāmi.**They’re not freed from suffering, I say.*";
P_HTM[9293]="*Ye ca kho keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānanti … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānanti.**There are ascetics and brahmins who truly understand about suffering, its origin, its cessation, and the path.*";
P_HTM[9294]="*Te jātisaṃvattanikesu saṅkhāresu nābhiramanti … pe …**They don’t take pleasure in choices that lead to rebirth …*";
P_HTM[9295]="*anabhiratā … pe … nābhisaṅkharonti … pe …**They stop making such choices …*";
P_HTM[9296]="*anabhisaṅkharitvā jātipariḷāhenapi na pariḍayhanti, jarāpariḷāhenapi na pariḍayhanti, maraṇapariḷāhenapi na pariḍayhanti, sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsapariḷāhenapi na pariḍayhanti.**Having stopped making such choices, they don’t burn with the fever of rebirth, old age, and death, of sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress.*";
P_HTM[9297]="*Te parimuccanti jātiyā jarāya maraṇena sokehi paridevehi dukkhehi domanassehi upāyāsehi.**They’re freed from rebirth, old age, and death, from sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress.*";
P_HTM[9298]="*‘Parimuccanti dukkhasmā’ti vadāmi.**They’re freed from suffering, I say.*";
P_HTM[9299]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yogo karaṇīyo … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation …”*";
P_HTM[9300]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9301]="*6. Dutiyamahāpathavīsuttaṃ**A Bungalow*";
P_HTM[9302]="*“Yo hi, bhikkhave, evaṃ vadeyya:**“Mendicants, suppose someone were to say:*";
P_HTM[9303]="*‘ahaṃ dukkhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ yathābhūtaṃ anabhisamecca … pe … dukkhanirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ ariyasaccaṃ yathābhūtaṃ anabhisamecca sammā dukkhassantaṃ karissāmī’ti—**‘Without truly comprehending the noble truths of suffering, its origin, its cessation, and the path, I will completely make an end of suffering.’*";
P_HTM[9304]="*netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**That is not possible.*";
P_HTM[9305]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, yo evaṃ vadeyya:**It’s as if someone were to say:*";
P_HTM[9306]="*‘ahaṃ kūṭāgārassa heṭṭhimaṃ gharaṃ akaritvā uparimaṃ gharaṃ āropessāmī’ti—**‘Before the lower story of a bungalow is built, I will climb up to the upper story.’*";
P_HTM[9307]="*netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati;**That is not possible.*";
P_HTM[9308]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, yo evaṃ vadeyya:**In the same way, suppose someone were to say:*";
P_HTM[9309]="*‘ahaṃ dukkhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ yathābhūtaṃ anabhisamecca … pe … dukkhanirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ ariyasaccaṃ yathābhūtaṃ anabhisamecca sammā dukkhassantaṃ karissāmī’ti—**‘Without truly comprehending the noble truths of suffering, its origin, its cessation, and the path, I will completely make an end of suffering.’*";
P_HTM[9310]="*netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**That is not possible.*";
P_HTM[9311]="*Yo ca kho, bhikkhave, evaṃ vadeyya:**But suppose someone were to say:*";
P_HTM[9312]="*‘ahaṃ dukkhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ yathābhūtaṃ abhisamecca … pe … dukkhanirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ ariyasaccaṃ yathābhūtaṃ abhisamecca sammā dukkhassantaṃ karissāmī’ti—**‘After truly comprehending the noble truths of suffering, its origin, its cessation, and the path, I will completely make an end of suffering.’*";
P_HTM[9313]="*ṭhānametaṃ vijjati.**That is possible.*";
P_HTM[9314]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, yo evaṃ vadeyya:**It’s as if someone were to say:*";
P_HTM[9315]="*‘ahaṃ kūṭāgārassa heṭṭhimaṃ gharaṃ karitvā uparimaṃ gharaṃ āropessāmī’ti—**‘After the lower story of a bungalow is built, I will climb up to the upper story.’*";
P_HTM[9316]="*ṭhānametaṃ vijjati;**That is possible.*";
P_HTM[9317]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, yo evaṃ vadeyya:**In the same way, suppose someone were to say:*";
P_HTM[9318]="*‘ahaṃ dukkhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ yathābhūtaṃ abhisamecca … pe … dukkhanirodhagāminiṃ paṭipadaṃ ariyasaccaṃ yathābhūtaṃ abhisamecca sammā dukkhassantaṃ karissāmī’ti—**‘After truly comprehending the noble truths of suffering, its origin, its cessation, and the path, I will completely make an end of suffering.’*";
P_HTM[9319]="*ṭhānametaṃ vijjati.**That is possible.*";
P_HTM[9320]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yogo karaṇīyo … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation …”*";
P_HTM[9321]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9322]="*7. Paṭhamamahāsamuddasuttaṃ**Splitting Hairs*";
P_HTM[9323]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā vesāliyaṃ viharati mahāvane kūṭāgārasālāyaṃ.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Vesālī, at the Great Wood, in the hall with the peaked roof.*";
P_HTM[9324]="*Atha kho āyasmā ānando pubbaṇhasamayaṃ nivāsetvā pattacīvaramādāya vesāliṃ piṇḍāya pāvisi.**Then Venerable Ānanda robed up in the morning and, taking his bowl and robe, entered Vesālī for alms.*";
P_HTM[9325]="*Addasā kho āyasmā ānando sambahule licchavikumārake santhāgāre upāsanaṃ karonte, dūratova sukhumena tāḷacchiggaḷena asanaṃ atipātente, poṅkhānupoṅkhaṃ avirādhitaṃ.**He saw several Licchavi youths practicing archery. They were shooting arrows from a distance through a small keyhole, shot after shot without missing.*";
P_HTM[9326]="*Disvānassa etadahosi:**When he saw this he thought,*";
P_HTM[9327]="*“sikkhitā vatime licchavikumārakā, susikkhitā vatime licchavikumārakā;**“These Licchavi youths really are trained, so well trained,*";
P_HTM[9328]="*yatra hi nāma dūratova sukhumena tāḷacchiggaḷena asanaṃ atipātessanti poṅkhānupoṅkhaṃ avirādhitan”ti.**in that they shoot arrows from a distance through a small keyhole, shot after shot without missing.”*";
P_HTM[9329]="*Atha kho āyasmā ānando vesāliṃ piṇḍāya caritvā pacchābhattaṃ piṇḍapātapaṭikkanto yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā ānando bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Ānanda wandered for alms in Vesālī. After the meal, on his return from alms-round, he went to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and told him what had happened.*";
P_HTM[9330]="*“idhāhaṃ, bhante, pubbaṇhasamayaṃ nivāsetvā pattacīvaramādāya vesāliṃ piṇḍāya pāvisiṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9331]="*Addasaṃ khvāhaṃ, bhante, sambahule licchavikumārake santhāgāre upāsanaṃ karonte dūratova sukhumena tāḷacchiggaḷena asanaṃ atipātente poṅkhānupoṅkhaṃ avirādhitaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9332]="*Disvāna me etadahosi:* **";
P_HTM[9333]="*‘sikkhitā vatime licchavikumārakā, susikkhitā vatime licchavikumārakā;* **";
P_HTM[9334]="*yatra hi nāma dūratova sukhumena tāḷacchiggaḷena asanaṃ atipātessanti poṅkhānupoṅkhaṃ avirādhitan’”ti.* **";
P_HTM[9335]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, ānanda,**“What do you think, Ānanda?*";
P_HTM[9336]="*katamaṃ nu kho dukkarataraṃ vā durabhisambhavataraṃ vā—**Which is harder and more challenging:*";
P_HTM[9337]="*yo dūratova sukhumena tāḷacchiggaḷena asanaṃ atipāteyya poṅkhānupoṅkhaṃ avirādhitaṃ, yo vā sattadhā bhinnassa vālassa koṭiyā koṭiṃ paṭivijjheyyā”ti?**to shoot arrows from a distance through a small keyhole, shot after shot without missing? Or to take a horsehair split into seven strands and penetrate one tip with another tip?”*";
P_HTM[9338]="*“Etadeva, bhante, dukkaratarañceva durabhisambhavatarañca yo vā sattadhā bhinnassa vālassa koṭiyā koṭiṃ paṭivijjheyyā”ti.**“It’s more difficult and challenging, sir, to take a horsehair split into seven strands and penetrate one tip with another tip.”*";
P_HTM[9339]="*“Atha kho, ānanda, duppaṭivijjhataraṃ paṭivijjhanti, ye ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yathābhūtaṃ paṭivijjhanti … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yathābhūtaṃ paṭivijjhanti.**“Still, Ānanda, those who truly penetrate suffering, its origin, its cessation, and the path penetrate something tougher than that.*";
P_HTM[9340]="*Tasmātihānanda, ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yogo karaṇīyo … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation …”*";
P_HTM[9341]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9342]="*8. Dutiyamahāsamuddasuttaṃ**Darkness*";
P_HTM[9343]="*“Atthi, bhikkhave, lokantarikā aghā asaṃvutā andhakārā andhakāratimisā, yatthamimesaṃ candimasūriyānaṃ evaṃmahiddhikānaṃ evaṃ mahānubhāvānaṃ ābhāya nānubhontī”ti.**“Mendicants, the boundless desolation of interstellar space is so utterly dark that even the light of the moon and the sun, so mighty and powerful, makes no impression.”*";
P_HTM[9344]="*Evaṃ vutte, aññataro bhikkhu bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When he said this, one of the mendicants asked the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[9345]="*“mahā vata so, bhante, andhakāro, sumahā vata so, bhante, andhakāro.**“Sir, that darkness really is mighty, so very mighty.*";
P_HTM[9346]="*Atthi nu kho, bhante, etamhā andhakārā añño andhakāro mahantataro ca bhayānakataro cā”ti?**Is there any other darkness more mighty and terrifying than this one?”*";
P_HTM[9347]="*“Atthi kho, bhikkhu, etamhā andhakārā añño andhakāro mahantataro ca bhayānakataro cā”ti.**“There is, mendicant.”*";
P_HTM[9348]="*“Katamo pana, bhante, etamhā andhakārā añño andhakāro mahantataro ca bhayānakataro cā”ti?**“But sir, what is it?”*";
P_HTM[9349]="*“Ye hi keci, bhikkhu, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānanti … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānanti,**“There are ascetics and brahmins who don’t truly understand about suffering, its origin, its cessation, and the path.*";
P_HTM[9350]="*te jātisaṃvattanikesu saṅkhāresu abhiramanti … pe …**They take pleasure in choices that lead to rebirth …*";
P_HTM[9351]="*abhiratā … pe … abhisaṅkharonti … pe …**They continue to make such choices …*";
P_HTM[9352]="*abhisaṅkharitvā jātandhakārampi papatanti, jarandhakārampi papatanti, maraṇandhakārampi papatanti, sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsandhakārampi papatanti.**Having made such choices, they fall into the darkness of rebirth, old age, and death, of sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress.*";
P_HTM[9353]="*Te na parimuccanti jātiyā jarāya maraṇena sokehi paridevehi dukkhehi domanassehi upāyāsehi.**They’re not freed from rebirth, old age, and death, from sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress.*";
P_HTM[9354]="*‘Na parimuccanti dukkhasmā’ti vadāmi.**They’re not freed from suffering, I say.*";
P_HTM[9355]="*Ye ca kho keci, bhikkhu, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānanti … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānanti,**There are ascetics and brahmins who truly understand about suffering, its origin, its cessation, and the path.*";
P_HTM[9356]="*te jātisaṃvattanikesu saṅkhāresu nābhiramanti … pe …**They don’t take pleasure in choices that lead to rebirth …*";
P_HTM[9357]="*anabhiratā … pe … nābhisaṅkharonti … pe …**They stop making such choices …*";
P_HTM[9358]="*anabhisaṅkharitvā jātandhakārampi nappapatanti, jarandhakārampi nappapatanti, maraṇandhakārampi nappapatanti, sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsandhakārampi nappapatanti.**Having stopped making such choices, they don’t fall into the darkness of rebirth, old age, and death, of sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress.*";
P_HTM[9359]="*Te parimuccanti jātiyā jarāya maraṇena sokehi paridevehi dukkhehi domanassehi upāyāsehi.**They’re freed from rebirth, old age, and death, from sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress.*";
P_HTM[9360]="*‘Parimuccanti dukkhasmā’ti vadāmi.**They’re freed from suffering, I say.*";
P_HTM[9361]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yogo karaṇīyo … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation …”*";
P_HTM[9362]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9363]="*9. Paṭhamapabbatūpamasuttaṃ**A Yoke With a Hole (1st)*";
P_HTM[9364]="*“Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, puriso mahāsamudde ekacchiggaḷaṃ yugaṃ pakkhipeyya. Tatrāpissa kāṇo kacchapo. So vassasatassa vassasatassa accayena sakiṃ sakiṃ ummujjeyya.**“Mendicants, suppose a person was to throw a yoke with a single hole into the ocean. And there was a one-eyed turtle who popped up once every hundred years.*";
P_HTM[9365]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhikkhave,**What do you think, mendicants?*";
P_HTM[9366]="*api nu kho kāṇo kacchapo vassasatassa vassasatassa accayena sakiṃ sakiṃ ummujjanto amusmiṃ ekacchiggaḷe yuge gīvaṃ paveseyyā”ti?**Would that one-eyed turtle, popping up once every hundred years, still poke its neck through the hole in that yoke?”*";
P_HTM[9367]="*“Yadi nūna, bhante, kadāci karahaci dīghassa addhuno accayenā”ti.**“Only after a very long time, sir, if ever.”*";
P_HTM[9368]="*“Khippataraṃ kho so, bhikkhave, kāṇo kacchapo vassasatassa vassasatassa accayena sakiṃ sakiṃ ummujjanto amusmiṃ ekacchiggaḷe yuge gīvaṃ paveseyya, na tvevāhaṃ, bhikkhave, sakiṃ vinipātagatena bālena manussattaṃ vadāmi.**“That one-eyed turtle would poke its neck through the hole in that yoke sooner than a fool who has fallen to the underworld would be reborn as a human being, I say.*";
P_HTM[9369]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[9370]="*Na hettha, bhikkhave, atthi dhammacariyā, samacariyā, kusalakiriyā, puññakiriyā.**Because there there’s no principled or moral conduct, and no doing what is good and skillful.*";
P_HTM[9371]="*Aññamaññakhādikā ettha, bhikkhave, vattati dubbalakhādikā.**There they just prey on each other, preying on the weak.*";
P_HTM[9372]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[9373]="*Adiṭṭhattā, bhikkhave, catunnaṃ ariyasaccānaṃ.**It’s because they haven’t seen the four noble truths.*";
P_HTM[9374]="*Katamesaṃ catunnaṃ?**What four?*";
P_HTM[9375]="*Dukkhassa ariyasaccassa … pe … dukkhanirodhagāminiyā paṭipadāya ariyasaccassa.**The noble truths of suffering, its origin, its cessation, and the path.*";
P_HTM[9376]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yogo karaṇīyo … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation …”*";
P_HTM[9377]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9378]="*10. Dutiyapabbatūpamasuttaṃ**A Yoke With a Hole (2nd)*";
P_HTM[9379]="*“Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, ayaṃ mahāpathavī ekodakā assa.**“Mendicants, suppose the earth was entirely covered with water.*";
P_HTM[9380]="*Tatra puriso ekacchiggaḷaṃ yugaṃ pakkhipeyya.**And a person threw a yoke with a single hole into it.*";
P_HTM[9381]="*Tamenaṃ puratthimo vāto pacchimena saṃhareyya, pacchimo vāto puratthimena saṃhareyya, uttaro vāto dakkhiṇena saṃhareyya, dakkhiṇo vāto uttarena saṃhareyya.**The east wind wafts it west; the west wind wafts it east; the north wind wafts it south; and the south wind wafts it north.*";
P_HTM[9382]="*Tatrassa kāṇo kacchapo. So vassasatassa vassasatassa accayena sakiṃ sakiṃ ummujjeyya.**And there was a one-eyed turtle who popped up once every hundred years.*";
P_HTM[9383]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhikkhave,**What do you think, mendicants?*";
P_HTM[9384]="*api nu kho kāṇo kacchapo vassasatassa vassasatassa accayena sakiṃ sakiṃ ummujjanto amusmiṃ ekacchiggaḷe yuge gīvaṃ paveseyyā”ti?**Would that one-eyed turtle, popping up once every hundred years, still poke its neck through the hole in that yoke?”*";
P_HTM[9385]="*“Adhiccamidaṃ, bhante, yaṃ so kāṇo kacchapo vassasatassa vassasatassa accayena sakiṃ sakiṃ ummujjanto amusmiṃ ekacchiggaḷe yuge gīvaṃ paveseyyā”ti.**“It’s unlikely, sir.”*";
P_HTM[9386]="*“Evaṃ adhiccamidaṃ, bhikkhave, yaṃ manussattaṃ labhati.**“That’s how unlikely it is to get reborn as a human being.*";
P_HTM[9387]="*Evaṃ adhiccamidaṃ, bhikkhave, yaṃ tathāgato loke uppajjati arahaṃ sammāsambuddho.**And that’s how unlikely it is for a Realized One to arise in the world, a perfected one, a fully awakened Buddha.*";
P_HTM[9388]="*Evaṃ adhiccamidaṃ, bhikkhave, yaṃ tathāgatappavedito dhammavinayo loke dibbati.**And that’s how unlikely it is for the teaching and training proclaimed by a Realized One to shine in the world.*";
P_HTM[9389]="*Tassidaṃ, bhikkhave, manussattaṃ laddhaṃ, tathāgato loke uppanno arahaṃ sammāsambuddho, tathāgatappavedito ca dhammavinayo loke dibbati.**And now, mendicants, you have been reborn as a human being. A Realized One has arisen in the world, a perfected one, a fully awakened Buddha. And the teaching and training proclaimed by a Realized One shines in the world.*";
P_HTM[9390]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yogo karaṇīyo … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation …”*";
P_HTM[9391]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9392]="*10. Catutthaāmakadhaññapeyyālavaggo**A Cliff*";
P_HTM[9393]="*1. Aññatrasuttaṃ**Sineru, King of Mountains (1st)*";
P_HTM[9394]="*“Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, puriso sinerussa pabbatarājassa satta muggamattiyo pāsāṇasakkharā upanikkhipeyya.**“Mendicants, suppose a person was to place down on Sineru, the king of mountains, seven pebbles the size of mung beans.*";
P_HTM[9395]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhikkhave,**What do you think, mendicants?*";
P_HTM[9396]="*katamaṃ nu kho bahutaraṃ—yā vā satta muggamattiyo pāsāṇasakkharā upanikkhittā, yo vā sinerupabbatarājā”ti?**Which is more: the seven pebbles the size of mung beans? Or Sineru, the king of mountains?”*";
P_HTM[9397]="*“Etadeva, bhante, bahutaraṃ, yadidaṃ—sinerupabbatarājā;**“Sir, Sineru, the king of mountains, is certainly more.*";
P_HTM[9398]="*appamattikā satta muggamattiyo pāsāṇasakkharā upanikkhittā.**The seven pebbles the size of mung beans are tiny.*";
P_HTM[9399]="*Saṅkhampi na upenti, upanidhampi na upenti, kalabhāgampi na upenti sinerupabbatarājānaṃ upanidhāya satta muggamattiyo pāsāṇasakkharā upanikkhittā”ti.**Compared to Sineru, they can’t be reckoned or compared, they’re not even a fraction.”*";
P_HTM[9400]="*“Evameva kho, bhikkhave, ariyasāvakassa diṭṭhisampannassa puggalassa abhisametāvino etadeva bahutaraṃ dukkhaṃ yadidaṃ parikkhīṇaṃ pariyādinnaṃ; appamattakaṃ avasiṭṭhaṃ.**“In the same way, for a person with comprehension, a noble disciple accomplished in view, the suffering that’s over and done with is more, what’s left is tiny.*";
P_HTM[9401]="*Saṅkhampi na upeti, upanidhampi na upeti, kalabhāgampi na upeti, purimaṃ dukkhakkhandhaṃ parikkhīṇaṃ pariyādinnaṃ upanidhāya yadidaṃ sattakkhattuparamatā;**Compared to the mass of suffering in the past that’s over and done with, it can’t be reckoned or compared, it’s not even a fraction, since there are at most seven more lives.*";
P_HTM[9402]="*yo ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.**Such a person truly understands about suffering, its origin, its cessation, and the path.*";
P_HTM[9403]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yogo karaṇīyo … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation …”*";
P_HTM[9404]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9405]="*2. Paccantasuttaṃ**Sineru, King of Mountains (2nd)*";
P_HTM[9406]="*“Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, sinerupabbatarājāyaṃ parikkhayaṃ pariyādānaṃ gaccheyya, ṭhapetvā satta muggamattiyo pāsāṇasakkharā.**“Mendicants, suppose Sineru, the king of mountains, was worn away and eroded except for seven pebbles the size of mustard seeds.*";
P_HTM[9407]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhikkhave,**What do you think, mendicants?*";
P_HTM[9408]="*katamaṃ nu kho bahutaraṃ—yaṃ vā sinerussa pabbatarājassa parikkhīṇaṃ pariyādinnaṃ, yā vā satta muggamattiyo pāsāṇasakkharā avasiṭṭhā”ti?**Which is more: the portion of Sineru, the king of mountains, that has been worn away and eroded? Or the seven pebbles the size of mustard seeds that are left?”*";
P_HTM[9409]="*“Etadeva, bhante, bahutaraṃ sinerussa pabbatarājassa yadidaṃ parikkhīṇaṃ pariyādinnaṃ;**“Sir, the portion of Sineru, the king of mountains, that has been worn away and eroded is certainly more.*";
P_HTM[9410]="*appamattikā satta muggamattiyo pāsāṇasakkharā avasiṭṭhā.**The seven pebbles the size of mustard seeds are tiny.*";
P_HTM[9411]="*Saṅkhampi na upenti, upanidhampi na upenti, kalabhāgampi na upenti sinerussa pabbatarājassa parikkhīṇaṃ pariyādinnaṃ upanidhāya satta muggamattiyo pāsāṇasakkharā avasiṭṭhā”ti.**Compared to Sineru, they can’t be reckoned or compared, they’re not even a fraction.”*";
P_HTM[9412]="*“Evameva kho, bhikkhave, ariyasāvakassa diṭṭhisampannassa puggalassa abhisametāvino etadeva bahutaraṃ dukkhaṃ yadidaṃ parikkhīṇaṃ pariyādinnaṃ; appamattakaṃ avasiṭṭhaṃ.**“In the same way, for a person with comprehension, a noble disciple accomplished in view, the suffering that’s over and done with is more, what’s left is tiny.*";
P_HTM[9413]="*Saṅkhampi na upeti, upanidhampi na upeti, kalabhāgampi na upeti, purimaṃ dukkhakkhandhaṃ parikkhīṇaṃ pariyādinnaṃ upanidhāya yadidaṃ sattakkhattuparamatā;**Compared to the mass of suffering in the past that’s over and done with, it can’t be reckoned or compared, it’s not even a fraction, since there are at most seven more lives.*";
P_HTM[9414]="*yo ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.**Such a person truly understands about suffering, its origin, its cessation, and the path.*";
P_HTM[9415]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yogo karaṇīyo … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation …”*";
P_HTM[9416]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9417]="*Papātavaggo pañcamo.* **";
P_HTM[9418]="*Cintā papāto pariḷāho,* **";
P_HTM[9419]="*kūṭaṃ vālandhakāro ca;* **";
P_HTM[9420]="*Chiggaḷena ca dve vuttā,* **";
P_HTM[9421]="*sineru apare duveti.* **";
P_HTM[9422]="*3. Paññāsuttaṃ**A Fingernail*";
P_HTM[9423]="*Atha kho bhagavā parittaṃ nakhasikhāyaṃ paṃsuṃ āropetvā bhikkhū āmantesi:**Then the Buddha, picking up a little bit of dirt under his fingernail, addressed the mendicants:*";
P_HTM[9424]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhikkhave,**“What do you think, mendicants?*";
P_HTM[9425]="*katamaṃ nu kho bahutaraṃ—yo vāyaṃ mayā paritto nakhasikhāyaṃ paṃsu āropito, ayaṃ vā mahāpathavī”ti?**Which is more: the little bit of dirt under my fingernail, or this great earth?”*";
P_HTM[9426]="*“Etadeva, bhante, bahutaraṃ yadidaṃ—mahāpathavī; appamattakāyaṃ bhagavatā paritto nakhasikhāyaṃ paṃsu āropito.**“Sir, the great earth is certainly more. The little bit of dirt under your fingernail is tiny.*";
P_HTM[9427]="*Saṅkhampi na upeti, upanidhampi na upeti, kalabhāgampi na upeti mahāpathaviṃ upanidhāya bhagavatā paritto nakhasikhāyaṃ paṃsu āropito”ti.**Compared to the great earth, it can’t be reckoned or compared, it’s not even a fraction.”*";
P_HTM[9428]="*“Evameva kho, bhikkhave, ariyasāvakassa diṭṭhisampannassa puggalassa abhisametāvino etadeva bahutaraṃ dukkhaṃ yadidaṃ parikkhīṇaṃ pariyādinnaṃ; appamattakaṃ avasiṭṭhaṃ.**“In the same way, for a person with comprehension, a noble disciple accomplished in view, the suffering that’s over and done with is more, what’s left is tiny.*";
P_HTM[9429]="*Saṅkhampi na upeti, upanidhampi na upeti, kalabhāgampi na upeti purimaṃ dukkhakkhandhaṃ parikkhīṇaṃ pariyādinnaṃ upanidhāya yadidaṃ sattakkhattuparamatā;**Compared to the mass of suffering in the past that’s over and done with, it can’t be reckoned or compared, it’s not even a fraction, since there are at most seven more lives.*";
P_HTM[9430]="*yo ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.**Such a person truly understands about suffering, its origin, its cessation, and the path.*";
P_HTM[9431]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yogo karaṇīyo … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation …”*";
P_HTM[9432]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9433]="*4. Surāmerayasuttaṃ**A Lotus Pond*";
P_HTM[9434]="*“Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, pokkharaṇī paññāsayojanāni āyāmena, paññāsayojanāni vitthārena, paññāsayojanāni ubbedhena, puṇṇā udakassa samatittikā kākapeyyā.**“Mendicants, suppose there was a lotus pond that was fifty leagues long, fifty leagues wide, and fifty leagues deep, full to the brim so a crow could drink from it.*";
P_HTM[9435]="*Tato puriso kusaggena udakaṃ uddhareyya.**Then a person would pick up some water on the tip of a blade of grass.*";
P_HTM[9436]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhikkhave,**What do you think, mendicants?*";
P_HTM[9437]="*katamaṃ nu kho bahutaraṃ—yaṃ vā kusaggena ubbhataṃ, yaṃ vā pokkharaṇiyā udakan”ti?**Which is more: the water on the tip of the blade of grass, or the water in the lotus pond?”*";
P_HTM[9438]="*“Etadeva, bhante, bahutaraṃ, yadidaṃ—pokkharaṇiyā udakaṃ; appamattakaṃ kusaggena udakaṃ ubbhataṃ.**“Sir, the water in the lotus pond is certainly more. The water on the tip of a blade of grass is tiny.*";
P_HTM[9439]="*Saṅkhampi na upeti, upanidhampi na upeti, kalabhāgampi na upeti pokkharaṇiyā udakaṃ upanidhāya kusaggena udakaṃ ubbhatan”ti.**Compared to the water in the lotus pond, it can’t be reckoned or compared, it’s not even a fraction.”*";
P_HTM[9440]="*“Evameva kho, bhikkhave, ariyasāvakassa … pe …**“In the same way, for a noble disciple …*";
P_HTM[9441]="*yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation …”*";
P_HTM[9442]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9443]="*5. Odakasuttaṃ**Where the Waters Flow Together (1st)*";
P_HTM[9444]="*“Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, yatthimā mahānadiyo saṃsandanti samenti, seyyathidaṃ—**“Mendicants, there are places where the great rivers—the Ganges, Yamuna, Aciravatī, Sarabhū, and Mahī—come together and converge.*";
P_HTM[9445]="*gaṅgā, yamunā, aciravatī, sarabhū, mahī, tato puriso dve vā tīṇi vā udakaphusitāni uddhareyya.**Suppose a person was to draw two or three drops of water from such a place.*";
P_HTM[9446]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhikkhave,**What do you think, mendicants?*";
P_HTM[9447]="*katamaṃ nu kho bahutaraṃ—yāni dve vā tīṇi vā udakaphusitāni ubbhatāni, yaṃ vā sambhejjaudakan”ti?**Which is more: the two or three drops drawn out or the water in the confluence?”*";
P_HTM[9448]="*“Etadeva, bhante, bahutaraṃ, yadidaṃ—saṃbhejjaudakaṃ; appamattakāni dve vā tīṇi vā udakaphusitāni ubbhatāni.**“Sir, the water in the confluence is certainly more. The two or three drops drawn out are tiny.*";
P_HTM[9449]="*Saṅkhampi na upenti, upanidhampi na upenti, kalabhāgampi na upenti saṃbhejjaudakaṃ upanidhāya dve vā tīṇi vā udakaphusitāni ubbhatānī”ti.**Compared to the water in the confluence, it can’t be reckoned or compared, it’s not even a fraction.”*";
P_HTM[9450]="*“Evameva kho, bhikkhave, ariyasāvakassa … pe …**“In the same way, for a noble disciple …*";
P_HTM[9451]="*yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation …”*";
P_HTM[9452]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9453]="*6. Matteyyasuttaṃ**Where the Waters Flow Together (2nd)*";
P_HTM[9454]="*“Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, yatthimā mahānadiyo saṃsandanti samenti, seyyathidaṃ—**“Mendicants, there are places where the great rivers—the Ganges, Yamuna, Aciravatī, Sarabhū, and Mahī—come together and converge.*";
P_HTM[9455]="*gaṅgā, yamunā, aciravatī, sarabhū, mahī, taṃ udakaṃ parikkhayaṃ pariyādānaṃ gaccheyya, ṭhapetvā dve vā tīṇi vā udakaphusitāni.**Suppose that water dried up and evaporated except for two or three drops.*";
P_HTM[9456]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhikkhave,**What do you think, mendicants?*";
P_HTM[9457]="*katamaṃ nu kho bahutaraṃ—yaṃ vā saṃbhejjaudakaṃ parikkhīṇaṃ pariyādinnaṃ, yāni dve vā tīṇi vā udakaphusitāni avasiṭṭhānī”ti?**Which is more: the water in the confluence that has dried up and evaporated, or the two or three drops left?”*";
P_HTM[9458]="*“Etadeva, bhante, bahutaraṃ saṃbhejjaudakaṃ yadidaṃ parikkhīṇaṃ pariyādinnaṃ; appamattakāni dve vā tīṇi vā udakaphusitāni avasiṭṭhāni.**“Sir, the water in the confluence that has dried up and evaporated is certainly more. The two or three drops left are tiny.*";
P_HTM[9459]="*Saṅkhampi na upenti, upanidhampi na upenti, kalabhāgampi na upenti saṃbhejjaudakaṃ parikkhīṇaṃ pariyādinnaṃ upanidhāya dve vā tīṇi vā udakaphusitāni avasiṭṭhānī”ti.**Compared to the water in the confluence that has dried up and evaporated, it can’t be reckoned or compared, it’s not even a fraction.”*";
P_HTM[9460]="*“Evameva kho, bhikkhave, ariyasāvakassa … pe …**“In the same way, for a noble disciple …*";
P_HTM[9461]="*yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation …”*";
P_HTM[9462]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9463]="*7. Petteyyasuttaṃ**The Earth (1st)*";
P_HTM[9464]="*“Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, puriso mahāpathaviyā satta kolaṭṭhimattiyo guḷikā upanikkhipeyya.**“Mendicants, suppose a person was to place seven clay balls the size of jujube seeds on the great earth.*";
P_HTM[9465]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhikkhave,**What do you think, mendicants?*";
P_HTM[9466]="*katamaṃ nu kho bahutaraṃ—yā vā satta kolaṭṭhimattiyo guḷikā upanikkhittā, ayaṃ vā mahāpathavī”ti?**Which is more: the seven clay balls the size of jujube seeds, or the great earth?”*";
P_HTM[9467]="*“Etadeva, bhante, bahutaraṃ, yadidaṃ—mahāpathavī; appamattikā satta kolaṭṭhimattiyo guḷikā upanikkhittā.**“Sir, the great earth is certainly more. The seven clay balls the size of jujube seeds are tiny.*";
P_HTM[9468]="*Saṅkhampi na upenti, upanidhampi na upenti, kalabhāgampi na upenti mahāpathaviṃ upanidhāya satta kolaṭṭhimattiyo guḷikā upanikkhittā”ti.**Compared to the great earth, they can’t be reckoned or compared, they’re not even a fraction.”*";
P_HTM[9469]="*“Evameva kho, bhikkhave, ariyasāvakassa … pe …**“In the same way, for a noble disciple …*";
P_HTM[9470]="*yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation …”*";
P_HTM[9471]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9472]="*8. Sāmaññasuttaṃ**The Earth (2nd)*";
P_HTM[9473]="*“Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, mahāpathavī parikkhayaṃ pariyādānaṃ gaccheyya ṭhapetvā satta kolaṭṭhimattiyo guḷikā.**“Mendicants, suppose the great earth was worn away and eroded except for seven clay balls the size of jujube seeds.*";
P_HTM[9474]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhikkhave,**What do you think, mendicants?*";
P_HTM[9475]="*katamaṃ nu kho bahutaraṃ—yaṃ vā mahāpathaviyā parikkhīṇaṃ pariyādinnaṃ, yā vā satta kolaṭṭhimattiyo guḷikā avasiṭṭhā”ti?**Which is more: the great earth that has been worn away and eroded, or the seven clay balls the size of jujube seeds that are left?”*";
P_HTM[9476]="*“Etadeva, bhante, bahutaraṃ mahāpathaviyā yadidaṃ parikkhīṇaṃ pariyādinnaṃ; appamattikā satta kolaṭṭhimattiyo guḷikā avasiṭṭhā.**“Sir, the great earth that has been worn away and eroded is certainly more. The seven clay balls the size of jujube seeds are tiny.*";
P_HTM[9477]="*Saṅkhampi na upenti, upanidhampi na upenti, kalabhāgampi na upenti mahāpathaviyā parikkhīṇaṃ pariyādinnaṃ upanidhāya satta kolaṭṭhimattiyo guḷikā avasiṭṭhā”ti.**Compared to the great earth that has been worn away and eroded, they can’t be reckoned or compared, they’re not even a fraction.”*";
P_HTM[9478]="*“Evameva kho, bhikkhave, ariyasāvakassa … pe …**“In the same way, for a noble disciple …*";
P_HTM[9479]="*yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation …”*";
P_HTM[9480]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9481]="*9. Brahmaññasuttaṃ**The Ocean (1st)*";
P_HTM[9482]="*“Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, puriso mahāsamuddato dve vā tīṇi vā udakaphusitāni uddharitāni.**“Mendicants, suppose a man was to draw up two or three drops of water from the ocean.*";
P_HTM[9483]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhikkhave,**What do you think, mendicants?*";
P_HTM[9484]="*katamaṃ nu kho bahutaraṃ—yāni dve vā tīṇi vā udakaphusitāni ubbhatāni, yaṃ vā mahāsamudde udakan”ti?**Which is more: the two or three drops drawn out or the water in the ocean?”*";
P_HTM[9485]="*“Etadeva, bhante, bahutaraṃ, yadidaṃ—mahāsamudde udakaṃ; appamattakāni dve vā tīṇi vā udakaphusitāni ubbhatāni.**“Sir, the water in the ocean is certainly more. The two or three drops drawn out are tiny.*";
P_HTM[9486]="*Saṅkhampi na upenti, upanidhampi na upenti, kalabhāgampi na upenti mahāsamudde udakaṃ upanidhāya dve vā tīṇi vā udakaphusitāni ubbhatānī”ti.**Compared to the water in the ocean, it can’t be reckoned or compared, it’s not even a fraction.”*";
P_HTM[9487]="*“Evameva kho, bhikkhave, ariyasāvakassa … pe …**“In the same way, for a noble disciple …*";
P_HTM[9488]="*yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation …”*";
P_HTM[9489]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9490]="*10. Pacāyikasuttaṃ**The Ocean (2nd)*";
P_HTM[9491]="*“Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, mahāsamudde udakaṃ parikkhayaṃ pariyādānaṃ gaccheyya ṭhapetvā dve vā tīṇi vā udakaphusitāni.**“Mendicants, suppose the water in the ocean dried up and evaporated except for two or three drops.*";
P_HTM[9492]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhikkhave,**What do you think, mendicants?*";
P_HTM[9493]="*katamaṃ nu kho bahutaraṃ—yaṃ vā mahāsamudde udakaṃ parikkhīṇaṃ pariyādinnaṃ, yāni dve vā tīṇi vā udakaphusitāni avasiṭṭhānī”ti?**Which is more: the water in the ocean that has dried up and evaporated, or the two or three drops left?”*";
P_HTM[9494]="*“Etadeva, bhante, bahutaraṃ mahāsamudde udakaṃ yadidaṃ parikkhīṇaṃ pariyādinnaṃ; appamattakāni dve vā tīṇi vā udakaphusitāni avasiṭṭhāni.**“Sir, the water in the ocean that has dried up and evaporated is certainly more. The two or three drops left are tiny.*";
P_HTM[9495]="*Saṅkhampi na upenti, upanidhampi na upenti, kalabhāgampi na upenti mahāsamudde udakaṃ parikkhīṇaṃ pariyādinnaṃ upanidhāya dve vā tīṇi vā udakaphusitāni avasiṭṭhānī”ti.**Compared to the water in the ocean that has dried up and evaporated, it can’t be reckoned or compared, it’s not even a fraction.”*";
P_HTM[9496]="*“Evameva kho, bhikkhave, ariyasāvakassa … pe …**“In the same way, for a noble disciple …*";
P_HTM[9497]="*yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation …”*";
P_HTM[9498]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9499]="*11. Pañcagatipeyyālavaggo**Comprehension*";
P_HTM[9500]="*1. Pāṇātipātasuttaṃ**A Mountain (1st)*";
P_HTM[9501]="*“Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, puriso himavato pabbatarājassa satta sāsapamattiyo pāsāṇasakkharā upanikkhipeyya.**“Mendicants, suppose a person was to place seven pebbles the size of mustard seeds on the Himalayas, the king of mountains.*";
P_HTM[9502]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhikkhave,**What do you think, mendicants?*";
P_HTM[9503]="*katamaṃ nu kho bahutaraṃ—yā vā satta sāsapamattiyo pāsāṇasakkharā upanikkhittā, ayaṃ vā himavā pabbatarājā”ti?**Which is more: the seven pebbles the size of mustard seeds, or the Himalayas, the king of mountains?”*";
P_HTM[9504]="*“Etadeva, bhante, bahutaraṃ, yadidaṃ—himavā pabbatarājā; appamattikā satta sāsapamattiyo pāsāṇasakkharā upanikkhittā.**“Sir, the Himalayas, the king of mountains, is certainly more. The seven pebbles the size of mustard seeds are tiny.*";
P_HTM[9505]="*Saṅkhampi na upenti, upanidhampi na upenti, kalabhāgampi na upenti himavantaṃ pabbatarājānaṃ upanidhāya satta sāsapamattiyo pāsāṇasakkharā upanikkhittā”ti.**Compared to the Himalayas, they can’t be reckoned or compared, they’re not even a fraction.”*";
P_HTM[9506]="*“Evameva kho, bhikkhave, ariyasāvakassa … pe …**“In the same way, for a noble disciple …*";
P_HTM[9507]="*yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation …”*";
P_HTM[9508]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9509]="*2. Adinnādānasuttaṃ**A Mountain (2nd)*";
P_HTM[9510]="*“Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, himavā pabbatarājā parikkhayaṃ pariyādānaṃ gaccheyya, ṭhapetvā satta sāsapamattiyo pāsāṇasakkharā.**“Mendicants, suppose the Himalayas, the king of mountains, was worn away and eroded except for seven pebbles the size of mustard seeds.*";
P_HTM[9511]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhikkhave,**What do you think, mendicants?*";
P_HTM[9512]="*katamaṃ nu kho bahutaraṃ—yaṃ vā himavato pabbatarājassa parikkhīṇaṃ pariyādinnaṃ, yā vā satta sāsapamattiyo pāsāṇasakkharā avasiṭṭhā”ti?**Which is more: the portion of the Himalayas, the king of mountains, that has been worn away and eroded, or the seven pebbles the size of mustard seeds that are left?”*";
P_HTM[9513]="*“Etadeva, bhante, bahutaraṃ himavato pabbatarājassa yadidaṃ parikkhīṇaṃ pariyādinnaṃ; appamattikā satta sāsapamattiyo pāsāṇasakkharā avasiṭṭhā.**“Sir, the portion of the Himalayas, the king of mountains, that has been worn away and eroded is certainly more. The seven pebbles the size of mustard seeds are tiny.*";
P_HTM[9514]="*Saṅkhampi na upenti, upanidhampi na upenti, kalabhāgampi na upenti himavato pabbatarājassa parikkhīṇaṃ pariyādinnaṃ upanidhāya satta sāsapamattiyo pāsāṇasakkharā avasiṭṭhā”ti.**Compared to the Himalayas, they can’t be reckoned or compared, they’re not even a fraction.”*";
P_HTM[9515]="*“Evameva kho, bhikkhave, ariyasāvakassa diṭṭhisampannassa puggalassa abhisametāvino etadeva bahutaraṃ dukkhaṃ yadidaṃ parikkhīṇaṃ pariyādinnaṃ; appamattakaṃ avasiṭṭhaṃ.**“In the same way, for a person with comprehension, a noble disciple accomplished in view, the suffering that’s over and done with is more, what’s left is tiny.*";
P_HTM[9516]="*Saṅkhampi na upeti, upanidhampi na upeti, kalabhāgampi na upeti, purimaṃ dukkhakkhandhaṃ parikkhīṇaṃ pariyādinnaṃ upanidhāya yadidaṃ sattakkhattuparamatā;**Compared to the mass of suffering in the past that’s over and done with, it can’t be reckoned or compared, it’s not even a fraction, since there are at most seven more lives.*";
P_HTM[9517]="*yo ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.**Such a person truly understands about suffering, its origin, its cessation, and the path.*";
P_HTM[9518]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yogo karaṇīyo … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation …”*";
P_HTM[9519]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9520]="*Abhisamayavaggo chaṭṭho.* **";
P_HTM[9521]="*Nakhasikhā pokkharaṇī,* **";
P_HTM[9522]="*sambhejja apare duve;* **";
P_HTM[9523]="*Pathavī dve samuddā dve,* **";
P_HTM[9524]="*dvemā ca pabbatūpamāti.* **";
P_HTM[9525]="*3. Kāmesumicchācārasuttaṃ**Not Human*";
P_HTM[9526]="*Atha kho bhagavā parittaṃ nakhasikhāyaṃ paṃsuṃ āropetvā bhikkhū āmantesi:**Then the Buddha, picking up a little bit of dirt under his fingernail, addressed the mendicants:*";
P_HTM[9527]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhikkhave,**“What do you think, mendicants?*";
P_HTM[9528]="*katamaṃ nu kho bahutaraṃ—yo vāyaṃ mayā paritto nakhasikhāyaṃ paṃsu āropito, ayaṃ vā mahāpathavī”ti?**Which is more: the little bit of dirt under my fingernail, or this great earth?”*";
P_HTM[9529]="*“Etadeva, bhante, bahutaraṃ, yadidaṃ—mahāpathavī; appamattakāyaṃ bhagavatā paritto nakhasikhāyaṃ paṃsu āropito.**“Sir, the great earth is certainly more. The little bit of dirt under your fingernail is tiny.*";
P_HTM[9530]="*Saṅkhampi na upeti, upanidhampi na upeti, kalabhāgampi na upeti mahāpathaviṃ upanidhāya bhagavatā paritto nakhasikhāyaṃ paṃsu āropito”ti.**Compared to the great earth, it can’t be reckoned or compared, it’s not even a fraction.”*";
P_HTM[9531]="*“Evameva kho, bhikkhave, appamattakā te sattā ye manussesu paccājāyanti; atha kho eteva bahutarā sattā ye aññatra manussehi paccājāyanti.**“In the same way, the sentient beings reborn as humans are few, while those not reborn as humans are many.*";
P_HTM[9532]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[9533]="*Adiṭṭhattā, bhikkhave, catunnaṃ ariyasaccānaṃ.**It’s because they haven’t seen the four noble truths.*";
P_HTM[9534]="*Katamesaṃ catunnaṃ?**What four?*";
P_HTM[9535]="*Dukkhassa ariyasaccassa … pe … dukkhanirodhagāminiyā paṭipadāya ariyasaccassa.**The noble truths of suffering, its origin, its cessation, and the path.*";
P_HTM[9536]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yogo karaṇīyo … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation …”*";
P_HTM[9537]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9538]="*4. Musāvādasuttaṃ**In the Borderlands*";
P_HTM[9539]="*Atha kho bhagavā parittaṃ nakhasikhāyaṃ paṃsuṃ āropetvā bhikkhū āmantesi:**Then the Buddha, picking up a little bit of dirt under his fingernail, addressed the mendicants:*";
P_HTM[9540]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhikkhave,**“What do you think, mendicants?*";
P_HTM[9541]="*katamaṃ nu kho bahutaraṃ—yo vāyaṃ mayā paritto nakhasikhāyaṃ paṃsu āropito, ayaṃ vā mahāpathavī”ti?**Which is more: the little bit of dirt under my fingernail, or this great earth?”*";
P_HTM[9542]="*“Etadeva, bhante, bahutaraṃ, yadidaṃ—mahāpathavī; appamattakāyaṃ bhagavatā paritto nakhasikhāyaṃ paṃsu āropito.**“Sir, the great earth is certainly more. The little bit of dirt under your fingernail is tiny.*";
P_HTM[9543]="*Saṅkhampi na upeti, upanidhampi na upeti, kalabhāgampi na upeti mahāpathaviṃ upanidhāya bhagavatā paritto nakhasikhāyaṃ paṃsu āropito”ti.**Compared to the great earth, it can’t be reckoned or compared, it’s not even a fraction.”*";
P_HTM[9544]="*“Evameva kho, bhikkhave, appamattakā te sattā ye majjhimesu janapadesu paccājāyanti; atha kho eteva bahutarā sattā ye paccantimesu janapadesu paccājāyanti aviññātāresu milakkhesu … pe ….**“In the same way, the sentient beings reborn in central countries are few, while those reborn in the borderlands, among barbarian tribes, are many. …”*";
P_HTM[9545]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9546]="*5. Pesuññasuttaṃ**Wisdom*";
P_HTM[9547]="*… “Evameva kho, bhikkhave, appakā te sattā ye pana ariyena paññācakkhunā samannāgatā; atha kho eteva bahutarā sattā ye avijjāgatā sammuḷhā … pe ….**“… the sentient beings who have the noble eye of wisdom are few, while those who are ignorant and confused are many. …”*";
P_HTM[9548]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9549]="*6. Pharusavācāsuttaṃ**Alcohol and Drugs*";
P_HTM[9550]="*… “Evameva kho, bhikkhave, appakā te sattā ye surāmerayamajjappamādaṭṭhānā paṭiviratā; atha kho eteva bahutarā sattā ye surāmerayamajjappamādaṭṭhānā apaṭiviratā … pe ….**“… the sentient beings who refrain from alcoholic drinks that cause negligence, are few, while those who don’t refrain are many. …”*";
P_HTM[9551]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9552]="*7. Samphappalāpasuttaṃ**Born in Water*";
P_HTM[9553]="*… “Evameva kho, bhikkhave, appakā te sattā ye thalajā; atha kho eteva bahutarā sattā ye udakajā. Taṃ kissa hetu … pe ….**“… the sentient beings born on land are few, while those born in water are many. …”*";
P_HTM[9554]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9555]="*8. Bījagāmasuttaṃ**Respect Mother*";
P_HTM[9556]="*… “Evameva kho, bhikkhave, appakā te sattā ye matteyyā; atha kho eteva bahutarā sattā ye amatteyyā … pe ….**“… the sentient beings who respect their mothers are few, while those who don’t are many. …”*";
P_HTM[9557]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9558]="*9. Vikālabhojanasuttaṃ**Respect Father*";
P_HTM[9559]="*… “Evameva kho, bhikkhave, appakā te sattā ye petteyyā; atha kho eteva bahutarā sattā ye apetteyyā … pe ….**“… the sentient beings who respect their fathers are few, while those who don’t are many. …”*";
P_HTM[9560]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9561]="*10. Gandhavilepanasuttaṃ**Respect Ascetics*";
P_HTM[9562]="*… “Evameva kho, bhikkhave, appakā te sattā ye sāmaññā; atha kho eteva bahutarā sattā ye asāmaññā … pe ….**“… the sentient beings who respect ascetics are few, while those who don’t are many. …”*";
P_HTM[9563]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9564]="*3____30. Pettidevapettivisayasuttaṃ**Abbreviated Texts on Raw Grain*";
P_HTM[9565]="*1. Naccagītasuttaṃ**Respect Brahmins*";
P_HTM[9566]="*… “Evameva kho, bhikkhave, appakā te sattā ye brahmaññā; atha kho eteva bahutarā sattā ye abrahmaññā … pe ….**“… the sentient beings who respect brahmins are few, while those who don’t are many. …”*";
P_HTM[9567]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9568]="*2. Uccāsayanasuttaṃ**Honor the Elders*";
P_HTM[9569]="*… “Evameva kho, bhikkhave, appakā te sattā ye kule jeṭṭhāpacāyino; atha kho eteva bahutarā sattā ye kule ajeṭṭhāpacāyinoti … pe ….**“… the sentient beings who honor the elders in the family are few, while those who don’t are many. …”*";
P_HTM[9570]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9571]="*Paṭhamaāmakadhaññapeyyālavaggo sattamo.* **";
P_HTM[9572]="*Aññatra paccantaṃ paññā,* **";
P_HTM[9573]="*Surāmerayaodakā;* **";
P_HTM[9574]="*Matteyya petteyyā cāpi,* **";
P_HTM[9575]="*Sāmaññaṃ brahmapacāyikanti.* **";
P_HTM[9576]="*3. Jātarūparajatasuttaṃ**Killing Living Creatures*";
P_HTM[9577]="*… “Evameva kho, bhikkhave, appakā te sattā ye pāṇātipātā paṭiviratā; atha kho eteva bahutarā sattā ye pāṇātipātā appaṭiviratā.**“… the sentient beings who refrain from killing living creatures are few, while those who don’t refrain are many. …”*";
P_HTM[9578]="*Taṃ kissa hetu? … pe ….* **";
P_HTM[9579]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9580]="*4. Āmakadhaññasuttaṃ**Stealing*";
P_HTM[9581]="*… “Evameva kho, bhikkhave, appakā te sattā ye adinnādānā paṭiviratā; atha kho eteva bahutarā sattā ye adinnādānā appaṭiviratā … pe ….**“… the sentient beings who refrain from stealing are few, while those who don’t refrain are many. …”*";
P_HTM[9582]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9583]="*5. Āmakamaṃsasuttaṃ**Sexual Misconduct*";
P_HTM[9584]="*… “Evameva kho, bhikkhave, appakā te sattā ye kāmesumicchācārā paṭiviratā; atha kho eteva bahutarā sattā ye kāmesumicchācārā appaṭiviratā … pe ….**“… the sentient beings who refrain from sexual misconduct are few, while those who don’t refrain are many. …”*";
P_HTM[9585]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9586]="*6. Kumārikasuttaṃ**Lying*";
P_HTM[9587]="*… “Evameva kho, bhikkhave, appakā te sattā ye musāvādā paṭiviratā; atha kho eteva bahutarā sattā ye musāvādā appaṭiviratā … pe ….**“… the sentient beings who refrain from lying are few, while those who don’t refrain are many. …”*";
P_HTM[9588]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9589]="*7. Dāsidāsasuttaṃ**Divisive Speech*";
P_HTM[9590]="*… “Evameva kho, bhikkhave, appakā te sattā ye pisuṇāya vācāya paṭiviratā; atha kho eteva bahutarā sattā ye pisuṇāya vācāya appaṭiviratā … pe ….**“… the sentient beings who refrain from divisive speech are few, while those who don’t refrain are many. …”*";
P_HTM[9591]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9592]="*8. Ajeḷakasuttaṃ**Harsh Speech*";
P_HTM[9593]="*… “Evameva kho, bhikkhave, appakā te sattā ye pharusāya vācāya paṭiviratā; atha kho eteva bahutarā sattā ye pharusāya vācāya appaṭiviratā … pe ….**“… the sentient beings who refrain from harsh speech are few, while those who don’t refrain are many. …”*";
P_HTM[9594]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9595]="*9. Kukkuṭasūkarasuttaṃ**Nonsense*";
P_HTM[9596]="*… “Evameva kho, bhikkhave, appakā te sattā ye samphappalāpā paṭiviratā; atha kho eteva bahutarā sattā ye samphappalāpā appaṭiviratā … pe ….**“… the sentient beings who refrain from talking nonsense are few, while those who don’t refrain are many. …”*";
P_HTM[9597]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9598]="*10. Hatthigavassasuttaṃ**Plants*";
P_HTM[9599]="*… “Evameva kho, bhikkhave, appakā te sattā ye bījagāmabhūtagāmasamārambhā paṭiviratā; atha kho eteva bahutarā sattā ye bījagāmabhūtagāmasamārambhā appaṭiviratā … pe ….**“… the sentient beings who refrain from injuring plants and seeds are few, while those who don’t refrain are many. …”*";
P_HTM[9600]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9601]="*3____30. Pettidevapettivisayasuttaṃ**Abbreviated Texts on Raw Grain*";
P_HTM[9602]="*1. Khettavatthusuttaṃ**Food at the Wrong Time*";
P_HTM[9603]="*… “Evameva kho, bhikkhave, appakā te sattā ye vikālabhojanā paṭiviratā; atha kho eteva bahutarā sattā ye vikālabhojanā appaṭiviratā … pe ….**“… the sentient beings who refrain from food at the wrong time are few, while those who don’t refrain are many. …”*";
P_HTM[9604]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9605]="*2. Kayavikkayasuttaṃ**Perfumes and Makeup*";
P_HTM[9606]="*… “Evameva kho, bhikkhave, appakā te sattā ye mālāgandhavilepanadhāraṇamaṇḍanavibhūsanaṭṭhānā paṭiviratā; atha kho eteva bahutarā sattā ye mālāgandhavilepanadhāraṇamaṇḍanavibhūsanaṭṭhānā appaṭiviratā … pe ….**“… the sentient beings who refrain from beautifying and adorning themselves with garlands, perfumes, and makeup are few, while those who don’t refrain are many …”*";
P_HTM[9607]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9608]="*Dutiyaāmakadhaññapeyyālavaggo aṭṭhamo.* **";
P_HTM[9609]="*Pāṇaṃ adinnaṃ kāmesu,* **";
P_HTM[9610]="*musāvādañca pesuññaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[9611]="*Pharusaṃ samphappalāpaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[9612]="*bījañca vikālaṃ gandhanti.* **";
P_HTM[9613]="*3. Dūteyyasuttaṃ**Dancing and Singing*";
P_HTM[9614]="*….**….*";
P_HTM[9615]="*“Evameva kho, bhikkhave, appakā te sattā ye naccagītavāditavisūkadassanā paṭiviratā; atha kho eteva bahutarā sattā ye naccagītavāditavisūkadassanā appaṭiviratā. Taṃ kissa hetu … pe ….**“… the sentient beings who refrain from dancing, singing, music, and seeing shows are few, while those who don’t refrain are many …”*";
P_HTM[9616]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9617]="*4. Tulākūṭasuttaṃ**High Beds*";
P_HTM[9618]="*… “Evameva kho, bhikkhave, appakā te sattā ye uccāsayanamahāsayanā paṭiviratā; atha kho eteva bahutarā sattā ye uccāsayanamahāsayanā appaṭiviratā … pe ….**“… the sentient beings who refrain from high and luxurious beds are few, while those who don’t refrain are many. …”*";
P_HTM[9619]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9620]="*5. Ukkoṭanasuttaṃ**Gold and Money*";
P_HTM[9621]="*… “Evameva kho, bhikkhave, appakā te sattā ye jātarūparajatapaṭiggahaṇā paṭiviratā; atha kho eteva bahutarā sattā ye jātarūparajatapaṭiggahaṇā appaṭiviratā … pe ….**“… the sentient beings who refrain from receiving gold and money are few, while those who don’t refrain are many. …”*";
P_HTM[9622]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9623]="*6-11. Chedanādisuttaṃ**Raw Grain*";
P_HTM[9624]="*… “Evameva kho, bhikkhave, appakā te sattā ye āmakadhaññapaṭiggahaṇā paṭiviratā; atha kho eteva bahutarā sattā ye āmakadhaññapaṭiggahaṇā appaṭiviratā … pe ….**“… the sentient beings who refrain from receiving raw grain are few, while those who don’t refrain are many. …”*";
P_HTM[9625]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9626]="*3____30. Pettidevapettivisayasuttaṃ**Abbreviated Texts on Raw Grain*";
P_HTM[9627]="*1. Manussacutinirayasuttaṃ**Raw Meat*";
P_HTM[9628]="*… “Evameva kho, bhikkhave, appakā te sattā ye āmakamaṃsapaṭiggahaṇā paṭiviratā; atha kho eteva bahutarā sattā ye āmakamaṃsapaṭiggahaṇā appaṭiviratā … pe ….**“… the sentient beings who refrain from receiving raw meat are few, while those who don’t refrain are many. …”*";
P_HTM[9629]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9630]="*2. Manussacutitiracchānasuttaṃ**Women and Girls*";
P_HTM[9631]="*… “Evameva kho, bhikkhave, appakā te sattā ye itthikumārikapaṭiggahaṇā paṭiviratā; atha kho eteva bahutarā sattā ye itthikumārikapaṭiggahaṇā appaṭiviratā … pe ….**“… the sentient beings who refrain from receiving women and girls are few, while those who don’t refrain are many. …”*";
P_HTM[9632]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9633]="*3. Manussacutipettivisayasuttaṃ**Bondservants*";
P_HTM[9634]="*… “Evameva kho, bhikkhave, appakā te sattā ye dāsidāsapaṭiggahaṇā paṭiviratā; atha kho eteva bahutarā sattā ye dāsidāsapaṭiggahaṇā appaṭiviratā … pe ….**“… the sentient beings who refrain from receiving male and female bondservants are few, while those who don’t refrain are many. …”*";
P_HTM[9635]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9636]="*4-5-6. Manussacutidevanirayādisuttaṃ**Goats and Sheep*";
P_HTM[9637]="*… “Evameva kho, bhikkhave, appakā te sattā ye ajeḷakapaṭiggahaṇā paṭiviratā; atha kho eteva bahutarā sattā ye ajeḷakapaṭiggahaṇā appaṭiviratā … pe ….**“… the sentient beings who refrain from receiving goats and sheep are few, while those who don’t refrain are many. …”*";
P_HTM[9638]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9639]="*7-9. Devacutinirayādisuttaṃ**Chickens and Pigs*";
P_HTM[9640]="*… “Evameva kho, bhikkhave, appakā te sattā ye kukkuṭasūkarapaṭiggahaṇā paṭiviratā; atha kho eteva bahutarā sattā ye kukkuṭasūkarapaṭiggahaṇā appaṭiviratā … pe ….**“… the sentient beings who refrain from receiving chickens and pigs are few, while those who don’t refrain are many. …”*";
P_HTM[9641]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9642]="*10-12. Devamanussanirayādisuttaṃ**Elephants and Cows*";
P_HTM[9643]="*… “Evameva kho, bhikkhave, appakā te sattā ye hatthigavassavaḷavapaṭiggahaṇā paṭiviratā; atha kho eteva bahutarā sattā ye hatthigavassavaḷavapaṭiggahaṇā appaṭiviratā … pe ….**“… the sentient beings who refrain from receiving elephants, cows, horses, and mares are few, while those who don’t refrain are many. …”*";
P_HTM[9644]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9645]="*Tatiyaāmakadhaññapeyyālavaggo navamo.* **";
P_HTM[9646]="*Naccaṃ sayanaṃ rajataṃ,* **";
P_HTM[9647]="*dhaññaṃ maṃsaṃ kumārikā;* **";
P_HTM[9648]="*Dāsī ajeḷakañceva,* **";
P_HTM[9649]="*kukkuṭasūkarahatthīti.* **";
P_HTM[9650]="*13-15. Nirayamanussanirayādisuttaṃ**Fields and Land*";
P_HTM[9651]="*… “Evameva kho, bhikkhave, appakā te sattā ye khettavatthupaṭiggahaṇā paṭiviratā; atha kho eteva bahutarā sattā ye khettavatthupaṭiggahaṇā appaṭiviratā … pe ….**“… the sentient beings who refrain from receiving fields and land are few, while those who don’t refrain are many. …”*";
P_HTM[9652]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9653]="*16-18. Nirayadevanirayādisuttaṃ**Buying and Selling*";
P_HTM[9654]="*… “Evameva kho, bhikkhave, appakā te sattā ye kayavikkayā paṭiviratā; atha kho eteva bahutarā sattā ye kayavikkayā appaṭiviratā … pe ….**“… the sentient beings who refrain from buying and selling are few, while those who don’t refrain are many. …”*";
P_HTM[9655]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9656]="*19-21. Tiracchānamanussanirayādisuttaṃ**Errands*";
P_HTM[9657]="*… “Evameva kho, bhikkhave, appakā te sattā ye dūteyyapahiṇagamanānuyogā paṭiviratā; atha kho eteva bahutarā sattā ye dūteyyapahiṇagamanānuyogā appaṭiviratā … pe ….**“… the sentient beings who refrain from running errands and messages are few, while those who don’t refrain are many. …”*";
P_HTM[9658]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9659]="*22-24. Tiracchānadevanirayādisuttaṃ**False Weights*";
P_HTM[9660]="*… “Evameva kho, bhikkhave, appakā te sattā ye tulākūṭakaṃsakūṭamānakūṭā paṭiviratā; atha kho eteva bahutarā sattā ye tulākūṭakaṃsakūṭamānakūṭā appaṭiviratā … pe ….**“… the sentient beings who refrain from falsifying weights, metals, or measures are few, while those who don’t refrain are many. …”*";
P_HTM[9661]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9662]="*25-27. Pettimanussanirayādisuttaṃ**Bribery*";
P_HTM[9663]="*… “Evameva kho, bhikkhave, appakā te sattā ye ukkoṭanavañcananikatisāciyogā paṭiviratā; atha kho eteva bahutarā sattā ye ukkoṭanavañcananikatisāciyogā appaṭiviratā … pe ….**“… the sentient beings who refrain from bribery, fraud, cheating, and duplicity are few, while those who don’t refrain are many. …”*";
P_HTM[9664]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9665]="*28-29. Pettidevanirayādisuttaṃ**96–101. Chedanādisutta*";
P_HTM[9666]="*… “Evameva kho, bhikkhave, appakā te sattā ye chedanavadhabandhanaviparāmosaālopasahasākārā paṭiviratā; atha kho eteva bahutarā sattā ye chedanavadhabandhanaviparāmosaālopasahasākārā appaṭiviratā.**“… the sentient beings who refrain from mutilation, murder, abduction, banditry, plunder, and violence are few, while those who don’t refrain are many.*";
P_HTM[9667]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[9668]="*Adiṭṭhattā bhikkhave, catunnaṃ ariyasaccānaṃ.**It’s because they haven’t seen the four noble truths.*";
P_HTM[9669]="*Katamesaṃ catunnaṃ?**What four?*";
P_HTM[9670]="*Dukkhassa ariyasaccassa … pe … dukkhanirodhagāminiyā paṭipadāya ariyasaccassa.**The noble truths of suffering, its origin, its cessation, and the path.*";
P_HTM[9671]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yogo karaṇīyo … pe … ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation …”*";
P_HTM[9672]="*Ekādasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9673]="*Catutthaāmakadhaññapeyyālavaggo dasamo.* **";
P_HTM[9674]="*Khettaṃ kāyaṃ dūteyyañca,* **";
P_HTM[9675]="*tulākūṭaṃ ukkoṭanaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[9676]="*Chedanaṃ vadhabandhanaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[9677]="*viparālopaṃ sāhasanti.* **";
P_HTM[9678]="*30. Pettidevapettivisayasuttaṃ**Passing Away as Humans and Reborn in Hell*";
P_HTM[9679]="*Atha kho bhagavā parittaṃ nakhasikhāyaṃ paṃsuṃ āropetvā bhikkhū āmantesi:* **";
P_HTM[9680]="*“taṃ kiṃ maññatha, bhikkhave, katamaṃ nu kho bahutaraṃ—* **";
P_HTM[9681]="*yo vāyaṃ mayā paritto nakhasikhāyaṃ paṃsu āropito, ayaṃ vā mahāpathavī”ti?* **";
P_HTM[9682]="*“Etadeva, bhante, bahutaraṃ, yadidaṃ—* **";
P_HTM[9683]="*mahāpathavī;* **";
P_HTM[9684]="*appamattakāyaṃ bhagavatā paritto nakhasikhāyaṃ paṃsu āropito.* **";
P_HTM[9685]="*Saṅkhampi na upeti, upanidhampi na upeti, kalabhāgampi na upeti mahāpathaviṃ upanidhāya bhagavatā paritto nakhasikhāyaṃ paṃsu āropito”ti.* **";
P_HTM[9686]="*“Evameva kho, bhikkhave, appakā te sattā ye manussā cutā manussesu paccājāyanti; atha kho eteva bahutarā sattā ye manussā cutā niraye paccājāyanti … pe ….**“… the sentient beings who die as humans and are reborn as humans are few, while those who die as humans and are reborn in hell are many …”*";
P_HTM[9687]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9688]="*3____30. Pettidevapettivisayasuttaṃ**Passing Away as Humans and Reborn as Animals*";
P_HTM[9689]="*… “Evameva kho, bhikkhave, appakā te sattā ye manussā cutā manussesu paccājāyanti; atha kho eteva bahutarā sattā ye manussā cutā tiracchānayoniyā paccājāyanti … pe ….**“… the sentient beings who die as humans and are reborn as humans are few, while those who die as humans and are reborn in the animal realm are many …”*";
P_HTM[9690]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9691]="*3____30. Pettidevapettivisayasuttaṃ**Passing Away as Humans and Reborn as Ghosts*";
P_HTM[9692]="*… “Evameva kho, bhikkhave, appakā te sattā ye manussā cutā manussesu paccājāyanti; atha kho eteva bahutarā sattā ye manussā cutā pettivisaye paccājāyanti … pe ….**“… the sentient beings who die as humans and are reborn as humans are few, while those who die as humans and are reborn in the ghost realm are many …”*";
P_HTM[9693]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9694]="*3____30. Pettidevapettivisayasuttaṃ**105–107. Manussacutidevanirayādisutta*";
P_HTM[9695]="*… “Evameva kho, bhikkhave, appakā te sattā ye manussā cutā devesu paccājāyanti; atha kho eteva bahutarā sattā ye manussā cutā niraye paccājāyanti … pe … tiracchānayoniyā paccājāyanti … pe … pettivisaye paccājāyanti … pe ….**“… the sentient beings who die as humans and are reborn as gods are few, while those who die as humans and are reborn in hell, or the animal realm, or the ghost realm are many.”*";
P_HTM[9696]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9697]="*3____30. Pettidevapettivisayasuttaṃ**108–110. Devacutinirayādisutta*";
P_HTM[9698]="*… “Evameva kho, bhikkhave, appakā te sattā ye devā cutā devesu paccājāyanti; atha kho eteva bahutarā sattā ye devā cutā niraye paccājāyanti … pe … tiracchānayoniyā paccājāyanti … pe … pettivisaye paccājāyanti … pe ….**“… the sentient beings who die as gods and are reborn as gods are few, while those who die as gods and are reborn in hell, or the animal realm, or the ghost realm are many.”*";
P_HTM[9699]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9700]="*3____30. Pettidevapettivisayasuttaṃ**111–113. Devamanussanirayādisutta*";
P_HTM[9701]="*… “Evameva kho, bhikkhave, appakā te sattā ye devā cutā manussesu paccājāyanti; atha kho eteva bahutarā sattā ye devā cutā niraye paccājāyanti … pe … tiracchānayoniyā paccājāyanti … pe … pettivisaye paccājāyanti … pe ….**“… the sentient beings who die as gods and are reborn as humans are few, while those who die as gods and are reborn in hell, or the animal realm, or the ghost realm are many.”*";
P_HTM[9702]="*Dvādasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9703]="*3____30. Pettidevapettivisayasuttaṃ**114–116. Nirayamanussanirayādisutta*";
P_HTM[9704]="*… “Evameva kho, bhikkhave, appakā te sattā ye nirayā cutā manussesu paccājāyanti; atha kho eteva bahutarā sattā ye nirayā cutā niraye paccājāyanti … pe … tiracchānayoniyā paccājāyanti … pe … pettivisaye paccājāyanti … pe ….**“… the sentient beings who die in hell and are reborn as humans are few, while those who die in hell and are reborn in hell, or the animal realm, or the ghost realm are many.”*";
P_HTM[9705]="*Pannarasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9706]="*3____30. Pettidevapettivisayasuttaṃ**117–119. Nirayadevanirayādisutta*";
P_HTM[9707]="*… “Evameva kho, bhikkhave, appakā te sattā ye nirayā cutā devesu paccājāyanti; atha kho eteva bahutarā sattā ye nirayā cutā niraye paccājāyanti … pe … tiracchānayoniyā paccājāyanti … pe … pettivisaye paccājāyanti … pe ….**“… the sentient beings who die in hell and are reborn as gods are few, while those who die in hell and are reborn in hell, or the animal realm, or the ghost realm are many.”*";
P_HTM[9708]="*Aṭṭhārasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9709]="*3____30. Pettidevapettivisayasuttaṃ**120–122. Tiracchānamanussanirayādisutta*";
P_HTM[9710]="*… “Evameva kho, bhikkhave, appakā te sattā ye tiracchānayoniyā cutā manussesu paccājāyanti; atha kho eteva bahutarā sattā ye tiracchānayoniyā cutā niraye paccājāyanti … pe … tiracchānayoniyā paccājāyanti … pe … pettivisaye paccājāyanti … pe ….**“… the sentient beings who die as animals and are reborn as humans are few, while those who die as animals and are reborn in hell, or the animal realm, or the ghost realm are many.”*";
P_HTM[9711]="*Ekavīsatimaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9712]="*3____30. Pettidevapettivisayasuttaṃ**123–125. Tiracchānadevanirayādisutta*";
P_HTM[9713]="*… “Evameva kho, bhikkhave, appakā te sattā ye tiracchānayoniyā cutā devesu paccājāyanti; atha kho eteva bahutarā sattā ye tiracchānayoniyā cutā niraye paccājāyanti … pe … tiracchānayoniyā paccājāyanti … pe … pettivisaye paccājāyanti … pe ….**“… the sentient beings who die as animals and are reborn as gods are few, while those who die as animals and are reborn in hell, or the animal realm, or the ghost realm are many.”*";
P_HTM[9714]="*Catuvīsatimaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9715]="*3____30. Pettidevapettivisayasuttaṃ**126–128. Pettimanussanirayādisutta*";
P_HTM[9716]="*… “Evameva kho, bhikkhave, appakā te sattā ye pettivisayā cutā manussesu paccājāyanti; atha kho eteva bahutarā sattā ye pettivisayā cutā niraye paccājāyanti … pe … tiracchānayoniyā paccājāyanti … pe … pettivisaye paccājāyanti … pe ….**“… the sentient beings who die as ghosts and are reborn as humans are few, while those who die as ghosts and are reborn in hell, or the animal realm, or the ghost realm are many.”*";
P_HTM[9717]="*Sattavīsatimaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9718]="*3____30. Pettidevapettivisayasuttaṃ**129–130. Pettidevanirayādisutta*";
P_HTM[9719]="*… “Evameva kho, bhikkhave, appakā te sattā ye pettivisayā cutā devesu paccājāyanti; atha kho eteva bahutarā sattā ye pettivisayā cutā niraye paccājāyanti … pe …**“… the sentient beings who die as ghosts and are reborn as gods are few, while those who die as ghosts and are reborn in hell are many.”*";
P_HTM[9720]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, appakā te sattā ye pettivisayā cutā devesu paccājāyanti; atha kho eteva bahutarā sattā ye pettivisayā cutā tiracchānayoniyā paccājāyanti … pe ….**“… the sentient beings who die as ghosts and are reborn as gods are few, while those who die as ghosts and are reborn in the animal realm are many.”*";
P_HTM[9721]="*Ekūnatiṃsatimaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[9722]="*3____30. Pettidevapettivisayasuttaṃ**Dying as Ghosts and Reborn as Ghosts*";
P_HTM[9723]="*… “Evameva kho, bhikkhave, appakā te sattā ye pettivisayā cutā devesu paccājāyanti; atha kho eteva bahutarā sattā ye pettivisayā cutā pettivisaye paccājāyanti.**“… the sentient beings who die as ghosts and are reborn as gods are few, while those who die as ghosts and are reborn in the ghost realm are many.*";
P_HTM[9724]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[9725]="*Adiṭṭhattā, bhikkhave, catunnaṃ ariyasaccānaṃ.**It’s because they haven’t seen the four noble truths.*";
P_HTM[9726]="*Katamesaṃ catunnaṃ?**What four?*";
P_HTM[9727]="*Dukkhassa ariyasaccassa, dukkhasamudayassa ariyasaccassa, dukkhanirodhassa ariyasaccassa, dukkhanirodhagāminiyā paṭipadāya ariyasaccassa.**The noble truths of suffering, the origin of suffering, the cessation of suffering, and the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering.*";
P_HTM[9728]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yogo karaṇīyo, ‘ayaṃ dukkhasamudayo’ti yogo karaṇīyo, ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodho’ti yogo karaṇīyo, ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yogo karaṇīyo”ti.**That’s why you should practice meditation to understand: ‘This is suffering’ … ‘This is the origin of suffering’ … ‘This is the cessation of suffering’ … ‘This is the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering’.”*";
P_HTM[9729]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[9730]="*Attamanā te bhikkhū bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandunti.**Satisfied, the mendicants were happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[9731]="*Tiṃsatimaṃ.* **";
